For example, a gap in full-time employment longer than six months can lead to automatic exclusion by almost half of the tools used by executives Fuller’s team surveyed, even though a work gap has nothing to do with whether a candidate is qualified for a job.

该团队在报告中写道：“招聘人员永远不会看到候选人的申请，即使它可能满足雇主的所有要求。” 16

“A recruiter will never see that candidate’s application, even though it might fulfill all of the employer’s requirements,” the team wrote in their report.16

这些申请人暂时离开职场的原因对该工具来说并不重要。他们可能是配偶或子女生病、身心健康问题、怀孕困难、因军人配偶调职而搬迁、被监禁，或者正在照顾年幼的孩子或其父母。所有这些原因都不重要：一次失败，你就会被淘汰。

The reason why these applicants temporarily left the workforce doesn’t matter to the tool. They could be applicants whose spouse or child was ill, who had physical or mental health needs, who had a difficult pregnancy, who relocated due to a new posting as a military spouse, who were incarcerated, or who were taking care of young children or their parents. None of these reasons matter: one strike and you’re out.

人类招聘人员可能更能理解人们不得不暂时离开职场的原因。例如，在疫情爆发的最初几个月，美国约有350万有学龄儿童的母亲离开了工作岗位。17即使申请人失业时间超过六个月，人类招聘人员也可能会记住这一点，并将简历放入“可以”的筛选框中。

A human recruiter might be more understanding of the reasons someone would have to leave the workforce for a while. During the early months of the pandemic, for example, roughly 3.5 million mothers with school-age children left active work in the US.17 A human recruiter might remember that and put a résumé on the yes pile even though the applicant was out of work for longer than six months.

富勒说，这六个月的间隔是一个“相当隐蔽的过滤器”。即使你是最有资格的候选人，算法也是无情的。它们按照程序运行：“最大限度地减少招聘人员寻找求职者所花费的时间和成本，”富勒说。

This six-month gap is a “pretty insidious filter,” Fuller said. It doesn’t matter if you are the most qualified candidate; algorithms are unforgiving. They do what they are programmed to do: “Minimize the time and costs recruiters spend in finding job candidates,” Fuller said.

这些系统必须改变。人力资源经理需要调查他们使用的工具，了解这些选拔标准是否有意义，是否能够聘用到能够长期取得成功的人才。

These systems must change. HR managers need to investigate the tools they use and understand whether the selection criteria are meaningful and lead to hiring people that are successful long term.

“我如何将我的绩效管理系统结果与人事档案关联起来，这样我就能查看‘过去五年内，该职位上表现最好的五名员工’？”富勒问道。人力资源经理需要开始挖掘和真正理解这些人成功的原因：“他们有哪些共同点？绩效评估中是如何体现的？我们如何衡量效率，比如说生产力？谁留下来了？”人力资源经理还需要考虑可能已经潜入系统的偏见。

“How do I link my performance management system results with the personnel files, so I can see ‘here are the five best performers in this job hired in the last five years’?” Fuller asked. HR managers need to start digging and really understand why these folks have been successful: “What are their common attributes? What does it say in the performance reviews? How are we measuring effectiveness, let’s say, productivity? Who stayed?” HR managers also need to account for bias that may have crept into the system.

这些问题和步骤将帮助公司构建更好的工具，并了解机器学习软件拒绝候选人的理由。

These are the questions and steps that will help companies build better tools and also understand on what grounds the machine learning software rejects candidates.

但当一位申请人被拒绝数百次时，我们很难抑制内心深处的疑问：也许他们只是不够资格。我们怎么知道，如果申请人没有被选中，那不是他们的错呢？乔·富勒认为，如果候选人具备该职位的合理资格，那么被拒绝可能与他无关。

But when it comes to an applicant getting hundreds of rejections, it’s hard to turn off the little voice asking if maybe they just aren’t qualified. How do we know that it is not the applicant’s fault when they don’t get chosen? Joe Fuller believes that if a candidate is reasonably qualified for the position, a rejection is probably not on them.

他认为，人工智能系统非常擅长拒绝合格的求职者，以至于当公司开始使用人工智能程序来招聘那些之前被“隐藏”的人——那些被自动化工具从人才库中拒之门外的人——时，公司会惊讶地发现，这些求职者最终都取得了优异的成绩。他们比通过传统招聘渠道招聘的人更高效、更有动力、更投入。“我认为这是相当有说服力的证据，”富勒说。

He argues that AI systems are so good at rejecting qualified applicants that when companies start using programs that hire people who have previously been “hidden”—they were rejected from the talent pool by automated tools—the companies are surprised that these job seekers turn out to be overachievers. They are more productive, more motivated, more engaged than folks recruited through more traditional hiring channels. “I think it’s pretty compelling evidence,” Fuller said.

那么，为什么招聘系统仍然运转不畅？这是因为许多公司关注的是错误的指标：他们的首要任务是降低成本和缩短填补职位所需的时间。招聘人员的评估标准通常是招聘速度。该团队在报告中写道：“急于以尽可能低的成本快速填补职位空缺的招聘人员不会花时间去思考非传统背景候选人的潜力。” 18

So, why is recruiting still broken? It’s because many companies are focused on the wrong metrics: their first priority is to reduce costs and the time it takes to fill a position. Most often recruiters are evaluated by how fast someone is hired. “A recruiter eager to fill a position as cheaply and as quickly as possible will not spend time contemplating the potential of candidates from nontraditional backgrounds,” wrote the team in their report.18

乔·富勒的报告称，讽刺的是，公司领导层不断抱怨没有足够的合格候选人，而他们却知道自己的招聘流程存在问题，并且主动排除了那些他们声称迫切需要的申请人：“雇主几乎普遍承认，这些负面筛选条件会导致他们在某些时候（如果不是大多数时候）无意中排除合格的候选人。” 19

Joe Fuller’s report calls it ironic that company leaders keep complaining about not having enough qualified candidates for jobs, when they know that their own hiring processes are broken and actively excluding the very applicants they claim to so desperately want: “Employers almost universally acknowledge that these negative filters cause them to inadvertently exclude qualified candidates some, if not most of the time.”19

打击招聘工具中的歧视

FIGHTING DISCRIMINATION IN HIRING TOOLS

招聘流程需要改变，但传统上，招聘和人力资源被视为不会直接影响公司盈利的成本因素，尽管可以说，招聘顶尖人才可能是许多公司为其盈利所能做的最重要的任务。

The hiring process needs to change, but traditionally, hiring and human resources have been seen as cost factors that don’t directly contribute to the company’s bottom line, although, arguably, hiring top talent might be the most important task many companies can do for their bottom line.

随着人工智能的进步，或许可以了解哪些新员工是成功的，但我在现实世界中还没有看到过这种情况，或许是因为建立系统需要很长时间，而且需要多年的员工追踪。公司还必须了解是什么让一个人高效或成功，而这很难做到。

With the progress of AI, it might be possible to understand which new hires are successful, but I have not seen this done in the real world, maybe because it would take a long time to set up and years of tracking employees. Companies would also have to understand what makes someone productive or successful, which is a pretty hard thing to do.

我希望公司能从中吸取教训，变得更加谨慎，首先分析和测试申请人跟踪系统，然后再将其用于求职者，并就谁被录用、谁被拒绝做出重大决定。

I am hoping that companies learn from this and become more cautious, first analyzing and testing applicant tracking systems before they use them on job seekers and make material decisions about who gets hired and who gets rejected.

乔·富勒发现的一些关于招聘行业的信息，或许对正在找工作的索菲有所启发。我们聊过之后，索菲开始深入挖掘，想找出自己屡遭拒绝的原因。于是，她开始了一项小小的研究项目。

Some of what Joe Fuller found about the hiring industry might have affected Sophie as she was searching for a job. After we chatted, Sophie dug deeper to see if she could find out why she had been rejected so many times. She embarked on a little research project.

她将职位描述和简历上传到一个在线工具，该工具可以帮助求职者了解他们的简历在自动简历筛选器中的评分情况。根据结果，她推断，如果她的简历仅由人工智能进行分析，“无论我的技能如何，我都无法入职，因为我的简历只有40%会被机器阅读，”她解释说。

She uploaded a job description and her résumé to an online tool that helps applicants understand how their résumé will likely be scored by an automated résumé screener. From the results, she deduced that if her résumé was being analyzed only by AI, “I would never make it regardless of my skill set because my résumé is only 40 percent read by the machine,” she explained.

职位描述匹配率只有 40% 已经相当低了。一些在线服务建议求职者应该争取达到 60% 到 80% 的匹配率。但对索菲来说，这解释了她将简历上传到公司招聘系统时的一些经历。招聘系统会将数据整理成电子表格。软件经常会显示，某些字段（例如经验、教育背景或技能）要么是空的，要么是从简历中复制过来的错误信息。

A 40 percent match for a job description is pretty low. A 60 percent to 80 percent match rate score is what some online services suggest applicants should aim for. But for Sophie, this explained some of her experiences when she uploaded her résumé into companies’ hiring systems that sorted the data into a spreadsheet. Often, the software would show her that some fields such as experience, education, or skills either were empty or had the wrong information copied into them from her résumé.

“我总是必须填写其余内容以符合我的简历，”索菲说。

“I always had to fill in the rest of the stuff to match what my résumé says,” Sophie said.

她申请了近 150 个职位，但只有通过 LinkedIn 直接联系招聘人员才得以进入下一轮，这基本上绕过了申请人跟踪系统。

She applied to nearly 150 jobs and only ever advanced to the next round when she contacted recruiters directly on LinkedIn, essentially circumventing the applicant tracking systems.

现在，索菲认为她的部分使命是发现并消除工具中的歧视：“进入科技领域，我很兴奋，但我知道，在消除算法偏见方面，我们还有很多工作要做。这只是一个开始，因为历史总是会重演。我们正在摆脱人类身上的种族歧视。但现在，我们又要面对一场与机器人相关的战斗。”

Now Sophie sees part of her mission to detect and take down discrimination in tools: “Getting into tech, I’m excited, but I know we have a lot of work to do as far as getting rid of algorithmic biases. And this is only the beginning because history repeats itself. We’re getting away from the whole racist discrimination with us people. But now we have a whole other battle having to do with robots.”

未来，人类绕过机器的可能性或许会降低，因为企业很可能会更多地（而非更少地）使用人工智能和自动化技术。但新的人工智能工具也在帮助求职者。许多求职者正在使用 ChatGPT 撰写简历、求职信以及潜在面试问题的答案。

In the future, there might be less possibility for a human workaround to avoid the machines because it is likely companies will employ more AI and automation, not less. But new AI tools are helping job seekers as well. Many applicants are using ChatGPT to write their résumés, cover letters, and answers to potential interview questions.

一位社交媒体用户为某人使用 ChatGPT 撰写简历和求职信后获得面试机会而欣喜：“简历筛选机器人竟然最喜欢用 ChatGPT 写的简历，真是可笑。” 其他人则评论说，HR 一直在使用 AI 工具，现在却不得不处理 AI 撰写的简历和求职信，真是讽刺。AI 对决 AI——愿最好的工具获胜！

One social media user rejoiced that someone had gotten a job interview after using ChatGPT to write their résumé and cover letter: “I’m just laughing at the notion of the résumé screening bots liking the ChatGPT-written ones the best.” Others commented how ironic it was that HR has been using AI tools that now have to deal with résumés and cover letters written by AI. AI versus AI—may the best tool win!

*索菲是一位黑人女性，她的名字很独特，正试图进入科技行业。由于她批评潜在雇主的招聘方式，她请求我不要使用她的真名。索菲是她自己选择的笔名。

* Sophie is a Black woman with a unique name trying to break into the tech industry. Because she is criticizing the hiring methods of potential employers, she has asked me not to use her real name. Sophie is a pseudonym she chose.

第二章

CHAPTER 2

剑桥分析公司的工作

Cambridge Analytica for Work

扫描你的网络生活

On Scanning Your Online Life

米耳朵嗡嗡响。我简直不敢相信自己听到的消息：一家公司竟然在出售类似剑桥分析公司（Cambridge Analytica）的招聘个性档案。

My ears were ringing. I couldn’t believe what I had just heard: a company was selling Cambridge Analytica–like personality profiles for hiring.

如果你不记得这桩丑闻，政治咨询公司剑桥分析公司（Cambridge Analytica）利用Facebook提供的社交媒体数据，构建了用户的个性档案，然后将其出售给政治团体，用于定向传播信息和兜售影响力。这些丑闻于2018年被曝光。人们普遍认为该公司已经越界了。1

If you don’t recall this scandal, Cambridge Analytica, a political consulting firm, used social media data provided by Facebook to build personality profiles of people that it then sold to political groups to target messages and peddle influence. They were exposed in 2018. The consensus was that the firm had crossed the line.1

我在与一家人工智能招聘初创公司的首席执行官交谈时，从社交媒体动态中了解到了这个可以预测求职者性格特征的工具。我们聊了聊他们眼中该领域最新的产品以及一些不靠谱的算法。我问了我最喜欢的问题：“是什么让你夜不能寐？”他们犹豫了一下。我理解。在自己的行业里，很难指出缺点。

I found out about this tool predicting job applicants’ personality profiles from social media feeds during a conversation with a CEO of an AI-based hiring start-up. We were chatting about the newest products and some of the dodgy algorithms that they saw emerging in the field. I asked my favorite question: “What keeps you up at night?” They hesitated. I understood. It’s hard to point out flaws in your own industry.

他们不情愿地告诉我，有一家公司可以根据用户的社交媒体信息预测性格特征——无论是否征得用户的同意。

They reluctantly shared with me that there is a company that predicts personality traits based on users’ social media feeds—with or without users’ consent.

“一家公司根据某人的 Twitter 或 LinkedIn 动态预测性格特征？有点像剑桥分析公司对 Facebook 用户所做的那样？”我问道。

“A company is predicting personality traits based on someone’s Twitter or LinkedIn feed? Kind of what Cambridge Analytica did for Facebook users?” I asked.

“它们有点令人毛骨悚然，”首席执行官说道。

“They are a little creepy,” the CEO said.

当我查看这家公司的网站时，连我自己都感到震惊：它的创意甚至超越了我发现的其他“科幻”工具；DeepSense（现在的Humantic AI）宣称，只需一个电子邮件地址，该公司的算法就可以扫描求职者的社交动态，并为招聘经理提供关于求职者的隐藏信息：“了解他们真实的个性，而不仅仅是他们希望你看到的个性。让DeepSense为你预测他们的文化契合度、个性和行为。”

When I checked the company’s website, even I got a bit of a jolt: its idea topped even the other “science fiction” tools I had discovered; DeepSense, now Humantic AI, advertised that with just an email address the company’s algorithm can scan social feeds of job candidates and give hiring managers hidden insights into job candidates: “Get to know their real persona, not just the persona that they want you to see. Let DeepSense predict their culture fit, personality and behavior for you.”

扫描候选人的社交媒体历史记录是人工智能招聘程序使用的四种策略中的第二种，也是我们本章探讨的内容。但与简历筛选器不同，这种策略并非那么简单，尽管听起来像是一种神奇的算法，但或许也有点令人担忧。Humantic 的人工智能声称它可以预测候选人的真实身份。它可以判断我是否认真负责，是否善于团队合作，我的开放程度如何，我的情绪是否稳定，我需要多少监督。它可能比我自己更了解我。而这些信息就藏在我的社交媒体动态中，显而易见。

Scanning candidates’ social media history is the second of the four strategies AI hiring programs use and what we explore in this chapter. But unlike résumé screeners, this strategy is less straightforward and perhaps a bit troubling despite sounding like a magic algorithm. Humantic’s AI claims it can predict who a candidate really is. It can tell if I am conscientious, a team player, how open I am, if I am emotionally stable, how much supervision I need. It probably knows more about me than I do. And that information is just there hiding in plain sight—in my social feeds.

这种性格预测软件是新兴人工智能工具的一部分，这些工具正在向职场迈进。我们已经讨论过简历筛选器的优缺点（目前为止主要是缺点）。预测工具的作用不仅仅是对人们提供的信息进行分类。它们使用我们的数据越多越好，包括我们在工作中和社交媒体上写的文字，以分析我们的个性并预测我们的行为。

This kind of personality prediction software is part of new AI-based tools that are pushing into the world of work. We already covered the pros and cons (mostly cons so far) of résumé screeners. Predictive tools attempt to do more than sort the information people provide. They use our data—the more the better, including text we write at work and on our social media feeds—to analyze our personality and predict our behavior.

随着我对这个世界的深入了解，我发现我们的数字足迹会影响我们作为求职者的吸引力，以及我们能否保住现有的工作，因为公司可以持续不断地对我们进行社交媒体背景调查。我还发现，很多这类工具并不需要被调查者的同意。

As I dug deeper into this world, I discovered that our digital breadcrumb trails can affect how attractive we are as job candidates and whether we keep the jobs we already have as companies can run continuous social media background checks on us. I also found that many of these tools don’t require the consent of the person investigated.

而且，也许最令人震惊的是，它们甚至可能无法很好地完成它们声称要做的两件事——分析我们的社交信息和预测我们的性格。

And, perhaps most shocking, they may not even work very well at the two things they claim to do—analyze our social feeds and predict our personalities.

需要深入了解

A NEED TO LOOK UNDER THE HOOD

我理解，对于招聘经理来说，了解求职者“隐藏的”性格特征和软技能会很有帮助，尤其是通过即时社交媒体分析。（下一章我们将再次探讨求职者参与的人工智能游戏，这些游戏可能决定他们是被拒还是进入下一轮招聘，我们将再次看到对性格洞察日益增长的需求。）

I understand that for hiring managers insight into the “hidden” personality traits and soft skills of applicants would be helpful information to have, especially through an instant social media analysis. (We see this growing need for personality insights again in the next chapter on AI games that applicants play that may decide if they get rejected or move to the next round of hiring.)

由于具体工作技能的保质期越来越短，软技能和个性特质在招聘中的重要性日益凸显。2快速的技术变革和包括最近疫情在内的异常事件，迫使企业及其员工迅速适应新的工作方式。3在充满不确定性的时期，帮助企业的不是那些只拥有单一特定专业知识或技能的员工，而是那些能够轻松适应不断变化的世界并自学新技能和知识的员工。首席创新官托马斯·查莫罗-普雷穆齐克表示，在不久的将来，对软技能评估的需求将会加速增长。他是万宝盛华集团 (ManpowerGroup) 的高管，也是伦敦大学学院的商业心理学教授。

Soft skills and personality traits are growing in importance in hiring since concrete job skills have shorter and shorter shelf lives.2 Rapid technological change and unusual events, including the most recent pandemic, forced companies and their employees to quickly adjust to new ways of working.3 Instead of employees who have just one specific expertise or skill set, what’s helping companies in uncertain times are employees who can easily adjust to a changing world and teach themselves new skills and knowledge. This need for soft skills assessments will accelerate in the near future, said Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic, chief innovation officer at ManpowerGroup and a professor of business psychology at University College London.

查莫罗-普雷穆齐克表示：“如果我们接受工作岗位将被颠覆和取代的现实，到2030年或2040年，50%的工作岗位将不复存在，专业知识和知识的价值也将降低，那么我们就必须把赌注押在好奇心、学习能力、人际交往能力和积极性等方面。”

“If we accept the fact that jobs are going to be disrupted and replaced, and 50 percent of the jobs you will find in 2030 or 2040 don’t exist today, and there is a devaluation of expertise and knowledge, then you have to bet on things like curiosity, learning ability, people skills, and motivation,” Chamorro-Premuzic said.

其基本理念是，我们每个人都拥有一些稳定的性格特质，这些特质驱动着我们的行为，因此在招聘决策中应该被考虑。分析社交媒体动态的算法似乎也是获取候选人关键性格特质的更好方法，而不是基于简历或面试的假设。例如，大多数人可能不会承认自己在团队合作方面存在困难。

The underlying idea is that we all have somewhat stable personality traits that drive our behavior and should therefore be considered in hiring decisions. Algorithms that analyze social media feeds also seem like a much better way to access candidates’ key personality traits instead of assumptions based on their résumés or job interviews. Most people probably wouldn’t admit that they struggle to work well in teams, for example.

查莫罗-普雷穆齐克在 2023 年接受《纽约时报》采访时表示：“性格测试的产业规模大约为 20 亿美元”，而 2019 年的预估规模为 5 亿美元。4

“Personality testing is roughly a $2 billion industry,” Chamorro-Premuzic told the New York Times in 2023, up from an estimated $500 million in 2019.4

包括哈雷戴维森在内的一些公司要求员工进行性格测试，并在电子邮件签名中列出他们最大的优势。5据《纽约时报》报道，在其他一些公司，性格测试的结果被用来诊断办公室问题。（“莎莉真的很挣扎，因为她是蓝调，所以每次在电话里被拒绝，她都会为此耿耿于怀。”）6

Some companies, including Harley-Davidson, asked their employees to take a personality test and include their top strengths in their email signature.5 In others, the results of personality tests were used to diagnose office problems, wrote the New York Times. (“Sally is really struggling because she’s a blue, so every time she gets rejected on the phone, she stews about it.”)6

传统性格测试的开发商声称，他们的产品可以帮助雇主轻松判断求职者是否具备他们所青睐的特质，但填写这些测试耗时长，管理成本高昂，并且不可避免地会导致雇主在此过程中失去求职者。此外，求职者为了展现自己更优秀的求职能力，在传统性格测试中作弊的风险始终存在。

Traditional personality test makers say that their products help employers easily find whether candidates have sought-after traits, but they take a lot of time to fill out, are costly to administer, and cause employers inevitably to lose candidates in the process. And there is always a risk that candidates might be dishonest on a traditional personality test because they want to come off as more employable.

包括 IBM、Humantic AI 和 Crystal 在内的多家科技公司已经开发出一些工具，利用人工智能和算法根据任何人的社交媒体动态创建即时性格分析——甚至可能在候选人不知情的情况下进行评估。*

Several tech companies, including IBM, Humantic AI, and Crystal, have developed tools that use artificial intelligence and algorithms to create an instant personality analysis from anyone’s social media feed—­possibly without the candidate even knowing they are being assessed.*

我们的调查始于社交媒体背景调查，然后测试性格预测工具——两者都是通过检查员工和申请人的社交媒体信息来组装的。

We start our investigation by looking into social media background checks and then test out personality prediction tools—both are assembled by checking employees’ and applicants’ social media feeds.

打破权力平衡

TIPPING THE POWER BALANCE

当然，在基于人工智能的持续背景调查出现之前，招聘经理能够查看我的社交媒体动态，但这是一项繁琐的任务——谁愿意花几个小时阅读我多年前发的所有无聊推文呢？招聘经理如何有效、公平地比较不同候选人的多个社交媒体动态？用Excel表格给他们打分？招聘人员如何根据我的推文判断我的性格？这似乎不切实际，也是不可能的。

Of course, hiring managers were able to check my social media feeds before AI-based continuous background checks emerged, but that was a cumbersome task—who wants to spend hours reading all of my boring tweets from years ago? And how can hiring managers effectively and fairly compare multiple social media feeds of different candidates? Score them in an Excel sheet? How would a recruiter know what my personality is based on my tweets? Seems impractical and impossible.

这些新工具通过未经授权的监控和心理评估，为雇主提供了前所未有的视角来观察——或者更确切地说，洞察——我们。它们正在从根本上改变职场和招聘中本已脆弱的权力平衡。

These new tools offer employers an unparalleled look at—or, better, into—us through unauthorized surveillance and psychological assessment. They are fundamentally changing an already fragile power balance at work and in hiring.

传统上，招聘是基于求职者向其申请的机构披露的信息，而且通常会精心包装。当然，求职者和雇主之间从未真正实现过权力平衡，因为公司拥有最终决定权，决定谁能获得这份工作。但我过去可以决定我的申请材料。我负责挑选过去我把经验和技能写在简历上。我负责撰写求职信，并突出显示或删除任何我认为不相关的经验或技能。在求职面试中，我可以决定哪些信息需要保留或分享，甚至我还会建议进行背景调查。

Traditionally, hiring is based on information job candidates disclose to, and usually carefully package for, the organization they are applying to. There has never been a true balance of power between applicants and employers, of course, because companies get to make the final decision about who gets a job. But I used to be able to decide what went into my application. I was in charge of curating which past experiences and skills I put on my résumé or CV. I was in charge of writing my cover letter and highlighting or leaving out any experiences or skills I did not think were relevant. In job interviews, I could decide which information I wanted to withhold or share and even reference checks were suggested by me.

但人工智能从根本上改变了这种本已不平衡的权力平衡，赋予雇主（几乎）所有的权力：算法现在可以找到并拒绝一些人，其中一些人甚至可能不知道他们正在被考虑录用。

But AI fundamentally changes this already uneven power balance to give employers (almost) all power: algorithms can now find and reject people, some of whom may not even know they were being considered for a job.

这不仅仅局限于招聘决策。一些公司使用人工智能对现有员工进行持续的背景调查，以检查员工是否有暴力倾向、发布色情图片、欺凌、发表政治言论、可能引发丑闻或有自残倾向。

This is not limited to just hiring decisions. Some companies use AI to run continuous background checks on their existing employees to check whether their workers are exhibiting violent tendencies, post racy images, are bullies, post about politics, may cause a scandal, or are prone to self-harm.

我不清楚这些工具是否真的能衡量它们声称能够衡量的东西：机器如何从我的推特信息中推断出我是否有自残倾向？什么是恶意言语？如果我完全不使用社交媒体，会不会损害我的工作前景？这些人工智能工具如何在分析结束时给出简洁易懂的推荐或排名——将一个人丰富的内心世界浓缩成一个确定的数字？许多这些显而易见的问题都没有得到供应商的解答。

It’s not clear to me that these tools measure what they say they can measure: How does a machine deduce from my Twitter feed whether I am prone to self-harm? What exactly constitutes toxic language? Will it harm my job prospects if I’m not on social media at all? How do these AI tools come up with a neat and easy recommendation or ranking at the end of the analysis—boiling down a person’s rich inner life into one definite number? Many of these obvious questions go unanswered by vendors.

但他们确实向我们保证他们的产品有效——几乎所有网站都提供准确率在 90% 到 95% 之间的统计数据。供应商在其网站上分享白皮书和案例研究，以说服雇主这些工具有效。但事实真的如此吗？

But they do assure us their products work—almost all websites feature stats in the 90 to 95 percent accuracy range. Vendors share white papers and case studies on their websites to convince employers that these tools work. But do they?

极端审查

EXTREME VETTING

据Vox/Recode报道，凯·摩尔 (Kai Moore) 瞥见了通过算法进行持续监控的新黑暗世界。7

Kai Moore glimpsed the new and dark world of continuous surveillance by algorithm, according to Vox/Recode.7

2020年，摩尔所在的公司更换了工资系统，并要求对每位员工进行新的背景调查。摩尔的雇主与一家名为Fama的公司合作，进行了这些背景调查，其中包括人工智能社交媒体检查。

In 2020, the company Moore worked for switched payroll systems and required a new background check for every employee. Moore’s employer worked with a company called Fama to run these background checks, which included an AI social media check.

Fama、Good Egg、Ferretly 和 Intelligo 等供应商宣称，他们可以在社交媒体上发现求职者和现有员工的负面性格特征和可疑行为。

Vendors including Fama, Good Egg, Ferretly, and Intelligo advertise that they can find negative personality traits and questionable behavior of job applicants and current employees on social media.

该公司在其网站上写道：“Fama 帮助发现那些危及品牌和名人安全的行为，并揭露那些通常隐藏在大量公开数据中的不良内容。” Fama 还向政府机构推销其背景调查服务，声称其人工智能可以预测谁会泄露信息：“这些公开的电子信息 (PAEI) 可以为个人的认知、计划、联想和行动提供线索。”

“Fama helps highlight behaviors that put brands and celebrities at risk and surfaces bad content that is often hidden in reams of publicly available data,” the company wrote on their website. Fama also marketed its background checks to government institutions, claiming its AI can predict who will leak information: “This publicly available electronic information (PAEI) can offer clues into an individual’s perceptions, plans, associations, and actions.”

2019 年初，法玛向 CNN 商业频道透露，该公司拥有 120 多名客户，每月筛查 2 万人。8

In early 2019, Fama shared with CNN Business that the company had more than 120 clients and screened twenty thousand people a month.8

人力资源经理可以自己检查社交媒体账户，有些人确实会这么做，但这很耗时（而且处于法律的灰色地带）。将这项不切实际的任务外包给算法要容易得多，算法可以在几秒钟内对人们的在线行为进行评分和排名，并给出明确的建议。

Human resources managers could check social media accounts themselves, and some do, but it’s time-consuming (and in a legal gray zone). It’s much easier to outsource this impractical task to an algorithm that scores and ranks people’s online behavior in seconds and comes up with one clear recommendation.

Fama 首席执行官 Ben Mones 声称，Fama 报告对就业或招聘决策的影响率约为 12% 到 15%。9他还表示，根据求职者的反馈，这些报告的准确率高达 99.98% 。10

The CEO of Fama, Ben Mones, claimed that a Fama report affects an employment or hiring decision about 12 to 15 percent of the time.9 He also said that the reports are 99.98 percent accurate based on feedback from candidates.10

这些公司不仅提供一次性的个人快照——这些背景调查还可以持续进行。

These companies offer not only a onetime snapshot of a person—these background checks can be run continuously.

仅仅回顾一个人的过去是不够的。人是会变的，有好有坏。他们最近犯罪了吗？他们吸毒了吗？“在网上欺凌他人，或分享种族主义表情包？”Good Egg 在其网站上声称。Good Egg 宣称，其人工智能社交媒体背景报告能够标记侮辱和欺凌、仇恨言论、淫秽和恶意语言、暴力威胁、暴力和色情图片以及有自残倾向的人。

“Looking at a person’s past isn’t enough. People change, for better or worse. Have they recently committed a crime? Do they abuse drugs, bully others online, or share racist memes?” asserts Good Egg on its website. Good Egg advertises that its AI social media background report flags insults and bullying, hate speech, obscene and toxic language, threats of violence, violent and racy images, and people who are prone to self-harm.

至少这些公司是这么承诺的。凯·摩尔（Kai Moore，使用代词“他们”）不相信他们接受的背景调查真的会标记出这种行为。据Vox/Recode报道，Fama 的算法扫描了摩尔的社交媒体动态，并将其标记为“考虑”，而不是直接的“无误”。摩尔看到了这份报告。它包含三百多页，分析了他们所有的推文、转发和点赞。他们对所看到的内容感到不悦。

That’s at least what the companies promise. Kai Moore, who uses the pronoun they, didn’t believe the background check they were subjected to actually flagged this kind of behavior. Fama’s algorithms scanned Moore’s social media feeds and labeled them a “consider” rather than an outright “clear,” wrote Vox/Recode. Moore was able to see the report. It contained more than three hundred pages analyzing all their tweets, retweets, and likes. They were not amused by what they saw.

Moore 点赞的一条推文被标记为语言不当，因为推文中提到了“一个很酷的烛台”。他们点赞的提及酒精的推文也被标记为“不当”，包括这条：“我看到一个小孩拿着一大瓶薄荷伏特加跑过 Trader Joe's，妈妈在后面追着他说‘不不不不不不’，祝他圣诞快乐。” 一条在讨论 LGBTQ 身份时提到“地狱”的推文也被标记为“语言不当”。记住，Moore 并没有写这些推文；他们只是“点赞”了它们，但这一切都表明该公司应该更谨慎地审查 Moore。

A tweet Moore liked was flagged “bad” for language because the person mentioned “a cool ass candle holder.” Tweets they liked that mentioned alcohol were flagged as “bad,” including this one: “Merry christmas to the toddler I saw running across trader joe’s with a giant bottle of peppermint vodka and mom running after him ‘no no no no no no’ only.” One tweet mentioning “hell” in discussing LGBTQ identity was labeled “bad” for “language.” Remember, Moore did not write these tweets; they merely “liked” them, but this all added up to suggesting the company screen Moore more carefully.

甚至在自己的营销材料中，有一家供应商也毫不避讳地展示可疑的通话。背景调查公司 Ferretly 发布了一张其报告的截图，并将该帖子标记为“政治言论”：“我们能不能别再说那些‘别让精神疾病阻碍你’之类的话了？我们不会让我们自己阻碍我们自己，这暗示着我们在道德和个人方面存在缺陷。我（原文如此）并不是说你不应该挑战或对抗精神疾病给你带来的挑战，而是让我们少说点让人感到内疚的话。”

Even in its own marketing material, one vendor is not shy about showcasing questionable calls. The background check company Ferretly posted a screenshot of one of its reports that flagged this post as “political speech”: “can we quit all the talk about not letting mental illness stop you we’re not letting us stop us that implies moral and personal failure on our part im [sic] not saying that you shouldn’t challenge or fight what your mental illness throws at you but let’s cut the guilt tripping language.”

许多专家批评这种社交媒体分析方法既原始又有害。该技术缺乏常识和识别上下文线索的能力。

Many experts have criticized this kind of social media analysis as primitive and harmful. The technology lacks common sense and the ability to recognize context cues.

《华盛顿邮报》 2018 年报道，一家名为 Predictim 的保姆背景调查服务公司在根据社交媒体帖子预测某人是否有可能成为虐待儿童的看护者时也犯了类似的错误。11 “当一名保姆的扫描结果被标记为可能存在欺凌行为时，提出该请求的母亲感到不安，她表示，她无法判断软件识别出的是老电影台词、歌词或其他短语，还是真正的欺凌语言。”

A babysitter background check service called Predictim made similar mistakes when trying to predict whether someone would potentially be an abusive caregiver based on their social media posts, reported the Washington Post in 2018.11 “When one babysitter’s scan was flagged for possible bullying behavior, the unnerved mother who requested it said she couldn’t tell whether the software had spotted an old movie quote, song lyric or other phrase as opposed to actual bullying language.”

《华盛顿邮报》曝光此事后不久，Predictim 的网站就消失了。显然，这项技术无法理解上下文、幽默和讽刺。

Predictim’s website disappeared shortly after the exposé in the Post. Clearly, the technology could not make sense of context, humor, and sarcasm.

“即使使用最先进的人工智能，包括社交媒体在内的人类语音的自动处理也极其不可靠。计算机根本无法理解语境。我不愿想象人们因为某些计算机判定他们‘态度不好’或其他危险信号而被不公平地拒绝工作，”美国公民自由联盟高级政策分析师杰伊·斯坦利在接受Axios采访时表示。12

“The automated processing of human speech, including social media, is extremely unreliable even with the most advanced AI. Computers just don’t get context. I hate to think of people being unfairly rejected from jobs because some computer decides they have a ‘bad attitude,’ or some other red flag,” said Jay Stanley, senior policy analyst at the American Civil Liberties Union, to Axios.12

“我认为赋予这类算法如此大的权限真的很危险，”凯·摩尔说。“这是一种非常糟糕的算法。它就像关键词搜索一样。” 13

“I think it’s really dangerous to give these kinds of algorithms so much authority,” Kai Moore said. “It’s such a terrible algorithm. It’s a key word search.”13

这就引出了一个问题：算法是如何训练的？它如何知道什么是真正的暴力威胁，或者何时有人在推特上分享暴力歌词？究竟什么构成了网络欺凌？有自残倾向的人在社交媒体上分享什么？如果能够识别出这些人，难道没有比将有自残倾向的人排除在就业之外更好的方法吗？

This raises the question of how the algorithm was trained and how it knows what real threats of violence are or when someone is sharing violent song lyrics on their Twitter feed. And what exactly constitutes bullying online? What do people who are prone to self-harm share on social media? And if it can be identified, isn’t there something better to do with that information than exclude people who are self-harming from employment?

摩尔很幸运，他们的雇主没有理会社交媒体背景调查，没有解雇他们。其他人可能就没那么幸运了。

Moore was lucky that their employer disregarded the social media back-ground check and didn’t fire them. Others might not have been so lucky.

自我考验

PUTTING MYSELF TO THE TEST

我们先把偷看别人社交媒体动态的道德问题放在一边，集中讨论一个更基本的问题：这些工具真的有用吗？由于这些应用程序的开发者很少透露他们的算法是如何决策的，所以用我自己的数据进行测试，可以让我了解这些工具能否准确预测我会成为哪种类型的员工。

Let’s set aside the ethics of secretly looking at people’s social media feeds for a second and focus on an even more basic question: Do these tools work? Because the developers building these applications don’t share much on how their algorithms make decisions, testing them with my own data provides some means of seeing whether these tools accurately predict what kind of employee I would be.

我正准备在我的 Twitter 和 LinkedIn 个人资料上运行 Humantic AI 的算法。Humantic AI 的服务可以在供应商的网站上访问。要使用 Chrome 扩展程序，我必须获得 Humantic 的批准。（当时，每月套餐费用约为 250 美元。）

I am getting ready to run Humantic AI’s algorithm over my Twitter feed and my LinkedIn profile. Humantic AI’s services are accessible on the vendor’s website. To use the Chrome extension, I had to be approved by Humantic. (A monthly package cost about $250 at the time.)

Humantic AI 的首席执行官 Amarpreet Kalkat 告诉我，微软、洛克希德·马丁和其他公司的招聘人员都使用过 Humantic AI 的性格预测工具。该软件可以让招聘人员和招聘经理决定每个输入项（也就是性格特质）的权重。对于他们正在招聘的职位，他们可以决定理想候选人的“态度和展望”应该是零分、十分还是介于两者之间的任何分数。团队合作能力和一般行为（无论其含义如何）也是如此。然后，软件会根据招聘经理的输入对候选人进行排名。

The CEO of Humantic AI, Amarpreet Kalkat, shared with me that recruiters working for Microsoft, Lockheed Martin, and other companies had used Humantic AI’s personality prediction tool. The software let recruiters and hiring managers decide how much to weight each input, aka personality trait. For the role they are hiring for, they can decide whether an ideal candidate’s “Attitude and Outlook” should be zero or ten or any score in between. The same goes for team working skills and general behavior (whatever that may mean). The software then ranks the candidates based on the hiring managers’ inputs.

我通常喜欢测试技术（嘿，我可能会对自己有新的认识！），但使用这个工具让我有点不安。也许算法比我自己或我希望别人了解的更了解我。如果算法认为我的性格很糟糕怎么办？这说明我什么问题？我还能找到其他工作吗？人工智能会发现我内心深处是一个充满怨恨和消极的人吗？想到这些，感觉有点像我十三岁那年遇到一位朋友的妈妈，她是一位心理治疗师——我以为她一看我，就能立刻看穿我饱受折磨的灵魂。（她可能看出我当时是个笨拙的青少年，有很多不安全感。）当时的我感到很害怕，就像现在一样脆弱。

I usually enjoy testing technologies (Hey, I might learn something new about myself!), but with this tool I am feeling a bit squeamish. Maybe the algorithm knows more about who I am than I know about myself or what I want others to know about me. What if my personality is awful according to the algorithm? What does that say about me? Will I ever qualify for another job? Will the AI discover that I am secretly a resentful and negative person? Thinking about this feels a bit like when I was thirteen years old and met a friend’s mom who was a therapist—I thought when she looked at me, she could immediately see into my tormented soul. (She probably could tell that I was an awkward teenager with lots of insecurities.) It was frightening and I felt vulnerable just like now.

即时社交媒体分析

INSTANT SOCIAL MEDIA ANALYSIS

我聘请了托马斯·查莫罗-普雷穆齐克（Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic）来和我一起测试这些即时性格报告。他是一位心理学教授，他认为人工智能在充满偏见的招聘领域是一股非常棒的客观力量。

I have recruited Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic to test these instant personality reports with me. He is a psychology professor and believes AI is a wonderful objective force in the biased world of human hiring.

在我们安排采访地点的时候，我得知查莫罗-普雷穆日克住在威廉斯堡滨水区一栋新建的高层建筑里——离我的公寓步行十五分钟。圣诞节和新年之间的那一天，布鲁克林很冷，我们在曼哈顿的办公室感觉很遥远。他建议我们周五早上在他大楼里一个安静的公共休息室见面。

While we arrange where to meet for an interview, I find out that Chamorro-Premuzic lives in a new high-rise development on the waterfront in Williamsburg—a fifteen-minute walk from my apartment. On a day between Christmas and New Year’s, it’s cold in Brooklyn and our offices in Manhattan feel far away. He suggests we meet in a quiet common room in his building on a Friday morning.

他比我想象的要矮，一头黑发，胡子拉碴。他说话带点南美口音，而且好奇心很强。他想了解我的一切，我的工作，以及我为什么对人工智能如此着迷。他自己也一样。

He is shorter than I expected, has dark hair and a scruffy beard. He speaks with a slight South American accent and is driven by curiosity. He wants to know all about me, my work, and why I am fascinated by artificial intelligence. He is too.

他说：“我可能有点天真和乐观，但我确实认为数据驱动工具及其大规模部署也将帮助我们了解自己和我们的潜力。”

“I might be a little bit naive and optimistic, but I do think that data-driven tools and the deployment of it at scale would also help us understand ourselves and our potential,” he says.

Chamorro-Premuzic 认为，我们的个性根植于我们所做的一切，包括我们的网络生活。“你听的音乐很大程度上反映了你典型的情绪状态、你的个性、你的对不同事物的兴趣程度、你的好奇心程度、你的智力水平、你看的电影。”

Chamorro-Premuzic believes that our personality is embedded in everything we do, including in our online lives. “The music that you listen to says a lot about your typical emotional state, your personality, your level of interest in different things, your curiosity level, your intelligence level, the movies that you watch.”

这件事让我深有感触。我对自己的音乐品味不太自信——我承认我喜欢开车时大声唱欧洲垃圾歌曲，但我希望没人发现。2020年，我当了妈妈，在那些朦胧的新生儿时期，我看了很多《英国家庭烘焙大赛》和《完美！》，真的，还有一些非常可疑的真人秀节目。算法，拜托，别用这个来评判我的智商！

This one hits me. I am not too confident in my musical taste—I admit I love singing out loud to Eurotrash songs while driving and I hope no one will ever find out. In 2020, I became a mom and during those hazy newborn days I watched a lot of The Great British Baking Show, Nailed It!, and, really, some very questionable reality TV shows. Please, Algorithm, don’t judge my intelligence based on this!

当然，Chamorro-Premuzic 列出的除了电视节目和音乐品味之外，还有更多因素可以帮助我们理解他人。例如，在招聘需要友善态度的客服人员时，Uber 评分可能会有所帮助。“Uber 或 Lyft 的评分可以充分体现你的热情、亲切、友好或令人愉悦的程度。如果他们的 Uber 评分只有 3.9 分（满分 5.0 分），那可能就不是了。3.9 分意味着，如果这个人经常使用 Uber，那么他已经系统性地惹恼并冒犯了数百名司机。”

There are of course more things on Chamorro-Premuzic’s list that help us make sense of people than our taste in TV shows and music. Uber ratings, for example, could be helpful when hiring someone for a customer service job that requires friendliness. “Things like Uber or Lyft ratings say a lot about how cordial, agreeable, friendly, or pleasant you are. If they have an Uber rating of 3.9 [out of 5.0]—probably not. A rating of 3.9 means that that person has systematically upset and offended hundreds of drivers if they use Uber enough.”

我以前从未查看过我的 Lyft 评分（我不使用 Uber），但现在我查看了——感觉轻松多了。过去七年里，我总共乘坐了 250 趟车，司机给我的评分都是 5.0 分（满分 5.0 分）。14 （不过，如果司机不采取行动给我评分，Lyft 默认会给我五星评分。）15这里面有什么规律可以说明我的情况吗？

I have never checked my Lyft rating before (I don’t use Uber), but now I do—and I feel relieved. Drivers have given me a rating of 5.0 out of 5.0 during my 250 total rides over the past seven years.14 (Although a five-star rating in Lyft is the default if the driver does not take action and rate me.)15 Is there a pattern here that says something about me?

“如果你对一个人进行足够长时间的观察，哪怕只是观察一个人，你就会明白，首先，人们的性格非常一致，而这一点有时我们自己并不清楚。但当别人看我们时，他们看待我们的方式却非常一致。”查莫罗-普雷穆日克说道。

“If you examine people for long enough, just one individual, you will understand that, first of all, people are very consistent and that’s sometimes not clear to us. But when others look at us, they see us in very consistent ways,” Chamorro-Premuzic says.

这就是这项技术的承诺，直观地说，我们的个性将成为我们在网上所做的一切的一部分——因为我们这样做了。

That is the promise of this technology, and intuitively it makes sense that our personality would be part of everything we do online—because we did it.

人工智能非常擅长发现模式，包括在海量数据中发现人类性格的模式，而如果没有计算机的帮助，人类根本无法做到这一点。这正是人工智能如此强大的原因之一。它带来了一些人类此前未能大规模成功实现的全新能力。

AI is very good at finding patterns, including finding patterns of people’s personalities in large data sets, something humans really can’t do without the help of computers. This is one of the reasons artificial intelligence is such a powerful force. It brings something new to the table that humans have not been successfully able to do at scale.

“如今，你不需要问人们很多问题就能了解他们的喜好，他们是外向还是内向，是神经质还是沉稳，是智商高还是低，是坚毅还是敏捷，”查莫罗-普雷穆日克说。“你只要观察一下他们典型的行为模式就行了。”

“Nowadays, you don’t need to ask people a lot of questions to understand what their preferences are and whether they are more extroverted or introverted, more neurotic or stable, or whether they have higher or lower IQ, grit or agility,” Chamorro-Premuzic says. “You can just look at their typical patterns of behaviors.”

模式识别技术不仅用于招聘，也是互联网的驱动力。像Facebook和谷歌这样的公司收集我的点赞、点击、帖子——我在他们的平台上展示和留下的一切。16通过这些所谓的线上数据废气（与线下世界的数据混合），软件可以推断出我的偏好、需求、动机和性格特征，以便营销人员能够更精准地定位我。17

Pattern recognition technology not only is used in hiring but also is the driving force of the internet. Companies like Facebook and Google collect my likes, my clicks, my posts—everything I showcase and leave behind on their platforms.16 From this so-called online data exhaust (mixed with data from the offline world) the software infers my preferences, needs, motivations, and personality traits so marketers can target me more precisely.17

剑桥分析公司也使用了类似的模式识别技术。该公司臭名昭著地利用预测算法，根据Facebook数据构建大规模人格档案，以操纵公众舆论。在英国，剑桥分析公司受雇于“脱欧”运动，试图通过算法说服英国人投票脱欧。18在美国，剑桥分析公司受雇于泰德·克鲁兹的总统竞选团队，随后又帮助唐纳德·特朗普当选总统。19其目的是为每位选民构建心理测量人格档案，然后针对特定人群，说服他们以某种方式投票。20在情报界，这些策略被称为“心理战” 。21

Cambridge Analytica used similar pattern recognition technology. The company, infamously, used predictive algorithms to build mass personality profiles based on Facebook data to move public opinion. In the United Kingdom, Cambridge Analytica was hired by the Leave.EU campaign to try to algorithmically convince Brits to vote to exit the European Union.18 In the United States, Cambridge Analytica was hired by Ted Cruz’s presidential campaign and then to help elect Donald Trump as president.19 The idea was to build psychometric personality profiles of every voter and then target individuals to persuade them to vote a certain way.20 In the intelligence community these tactics are known as “psychological warfare.”21

当我开始深入研究剑桥分析公司的方法时，我惊讶地发现它们与 Humantic AI 生成的我的性格档案背后的算法如此相似。剑桥分析公司本质上是根据大五人格测试/OCEAN 人格评估建立的心理档案。22这类社交媒体分析的理论基础是由组织心理学家 Michal Kosinski 和 David Stillwell 奠定的，他们在剑桥大学心理测量中心工作期间发表了关于根据 Facebook 点赞预测性格特征的有影响力的论文。23例如，他们发现“喜欢”太空堡垒卡拉狄加的人可能是内向的。“喜欢”Lady Gaga 的 Facebook 用户可能是外向的。24在另一篇论文中，研究人员表示，他们能够从 Facebook 点赞中推断出高度敏感的个人属性，包括性取向、种族、宗教和政治观点、性格特征、智力、幸福感、药物滥用、年龄和性别。25他们声称，一旦他们的算法分析了用户的数百个 Facebook 点赞，它就能比该人的配偶更准确地预测该人的性格。

When I started digging a little deeper into Cambridge Analytica’s methods, I was surprised to find just how similar they are to the algorithm behind my personality profile generated by Humantic AI. Cambridge Analytica essentially built psychological profiles based on the Big Five/OCEAN personality assessment.22 The theoretical groundwork for this type of social media analysis was laid by organizational psychologists Michal Kosinski and David Stillwell, who published influential papers about the prediction of personality traits based on Facebook likes while working at the University of Cambridge’s Psychometrics Centre.23 They found, for example, that people who “liked” Battlestar Galactica were likely to be introverts. Facebook users who “liked” Lady Gaga were likely to be extroverts.24 In another paper, the researchers stated that they were able to derive highly sensitive personal attributes—including sexual orientation, ethnicity, religious and political views, personality traits, intelligence, happiness, substance abuse, age, and gender—from Facebook likes.25 They claimed that once their algorithm analyzed hundreds of a user’s Facebook likes, it could predict that person’s personality more accurately than the person’s own spouse could.

科辛斯基现任斯坦福商学院教授，​​也是 Humantic AI 的科学顾问委员会成员。

Kosinski, now a professor at Stanford Business School, sits on the science advisory board of Humantic AI.

我们又是谁？

WHO ARE WE, AGAIN?

那么，算法，托马斯·查莫罗-普雷姆日克是谁？他“隐藏”的性格特征是什么？征得他的同意后，我用 Humantic 的人工智能分析了他的推特：算法预测他“善于分析”、“谨慎”和“深思熟虑”：“对查莫罗-普雷姆日克来说，团队合作是与生俱来的。查莫罗-普雷姆日克在与……合作时，能取得最佳成果。”低监管。不要试图表现得太友好。他们可能不太以人为本。避免直接冲突[…] 要正式一点。

So, Algorithm, who is Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic? What are his “hidden” personality traits? With his consent, I run Humantic’s AI over his Twitter feed: The algorithm predicts he is “Analytical,” “Cautious,”and “Deliberate”: “Being a team player comes naturally to Chamorro-Premuzic. Chamorro-Premuzic delivers best results when working with low supervision. Don’t try to be too friendly. They might not be very people oriented. Avoid direct confrontation […] be formal.”

作为一名组织心理学家，查莫罗-普雷穆日克做过几十个这样的测试，对自己的性格非常了解。“你从中看出了自己吗？”我问。

As an organizational psychologist, Chamorro-Premuzic has done dozens of these tests and knows his personality pretty well. “Do you see yourself in this?” I ask.

“我觉得大概有一半我认同，另一半我并不认同，”他说。“我肯定会说需要自主。我感觉低监管环境下工作比高监管环境下工作更好。团队合作——是的。正式一点——绝对不行。”（就连我也能证明，他更喜欢非正式的，而且我刚认识他。）

“I think about half of it I probably identify with and the other half not,” he says. “I would say definitely the need for autonomy. I work with low supervision better than with high supervision. Team player—yes. Be formal—definitely not.” (Even I can attest that he prefers to be informal and I have just met him.)

“我很谨慎。是的，”他开玩笑地说。（其实他不是！）“我的公关和传播部门会嘲笑我，但我会告诉他们，尤其是考虑到我每次发推文他们都很害怕。”

“I am cautious. Yeah,” he says jokingly. (He is not!) “My PR and communications department will laugh at this one, but I will tell them, especially as they are very scared every time I tweet something.”

接下来，我们用 Humantic 的算法对 Chamorro-Premuzic 的领英动态进行分析。结果显示，AI 预测他“有影响力”、“精力充沛”且“冲动”。几分钟前，在 Twitter 上，同样的算法预测他善于分析、谨慎且深思熟虑。

We next run Humantic’s algorithm over Chamorro-Premuzic’s LinkedIn feed. In this case, the AI predicts that he is “Influential,” “Energizing,” and “Impulsive.” A few minutes earlier, on Twitter, the same algorithm predicted that he is analytical, cautious, and deliberate.

Deliberate

“我会说我更冲动，而不是谨慎和深思熟虑。这两者是截然相反的极端，”查莫罗-普雷姆日克说道。这项技术认为，基本上有两个不同的托马斯·查莫罗-普雷姆日克。

“I would say I am more impulsive than cautious and deliberate. And the two are the opposite extreme,” Chamorro-Premuzic says. The technology thinks there are basically two different Tomas Chamorro-Premuzics out there.

这并不是研究人员所期望的结果。心理学家们研究人格特质已有数十年，发现它们相对而言随着时间的推移保持稳定。26如果该算法能够从Chamorro-Premuzic的LinkedIn个人资料中识别出他的真实性格特征，那么它应该能够从他的Twitter动态中生成一份非常相似的性格档案——尤其是在我两次报告的时间间隔不到五分钟的情况下。（如果性格是流动的、不断变化的，我们就不应该将其用于就业评估。）

That is not the result that researchers would expect. Psychologists have studied personality traits for decades and found that they are relatively stable over time.26 If this algorithm picks up Chamorro-Premuzic’s true personality traits from his LinkedIn profile, it should generate a very similar personality profile out of his Twitter feed—especially since I ran the reports less than five minutes apart. (If personality was fluid and ever changing, we shouldn’t use it in employment assessments.)

但这种情况并没有发生。我感到有点难过，因为查莫罗-普雷穆日克对这项技术如此兴奋。“这里面有一种‘把所有东西都扔到墙上，看看哪些会粘住’的感觉，”他承认。

But that doesn’t happen. I feel kind of bad, since Chamorro-Premuzic is so excited about the technology. “There is an element of ‘throw everything against the wall and see what sticks’ here,” he admits.

然后，我和他运行了另一家名为 Crystal 的公司的算法工具，分析他的领英个人资料，看看这个算法能否预测他的性格。这次的三个关键词是“直接”、“自信”和“竞争”。

He and I then run the algorithmic tool from another company called Crystal over his LinkedIn profile to see if this algorithm could predict his personality. This time the three keywords are “Direct,” “Assertive,” and “Competitive.”

Crystal AI 领英

“我认为，直接、自信、有竞争力比谨慎、深思熟虑更好，”他说。“‘如果有人开会迟到，托马斯会很沮丧。’我很容易沮丧。就是这样。所以，开会迟到只是让我沮丧的众多事情之一。‘说话非常直接或直截了当。’没错。‘喜欢争论和辩论。’没错。‘能独立完成任务，按时完成任务。’没错。我觉得这个更好！”他很兴奋。

“Direct, assertive, and competitive I think is better than cautious, deliberate,” he says. “‘Tomas gets frustrated if someone is late to a meeting.’ I get frustrated very easily. Full stop. So being late to a meeting is just one of the many things that frustrates me. ‘Speak very directly or bluntly.’ Yes. ‘Enjoys argument and debate.’ Yes. ‘Work independently to meet a deadline.’ Yes. I would say this one is better!” He’s excited.

“‘专注于一点’。不一定。我的意思是，我喜欢从一个点跳到另一个点。‘自信地坚持自己’。绝对不是。过去十年，我一直在写书，教我们如何避免把自信误认为能力。”

“‘Stays focused on one point.’ Not necessarily. I mean, I like to jump from one to the next point. ‘Assert yourself with confidence.’ Definitely not. I spent the last ten years writing books on how we shouldn’t mistake confidence for competence.”

又是一堆混杂的结果。

Another mixed bag of results.

“你觉得它的准确度如何？”查莫罗-普雷穆日克问我。

“How accurate was it for you, would you say?” Chamorro-Premuzic asks me.

我们研究了我的“成绩单”。我在很多方面的数据差异很大。我的 DiSC（支配力、影响力、稳重感、尽责感）影响力得分在领英上是 3，在推特上是 7.8。至于“稳重感”，系统预测我在领英上是 2.8，在推特上是 7.0。

We study my “report cards.” My numbers in many categories are very different. My DiSC (Dominance, Influence, Steadiness, Conscientiousness) influence score is 3 on LinkedIn and 7.8 on Twitter. For “Steadiness,” the system predicts 2.8 on my LinkedIn and 7.0 on my Twitter.

“我感觉在这两个预测中我完全是另外一个人。”

“I feel like I’m a completely different person in these two predictions.”

查莫罗-普雷穆齐克对此表示同意：“除了情绪稳定性以外，他们都非常不同。”

Chamorro-Premuzic agrees: “They’re all very different, except emotional stability.”

相同的算法，根据算法运行的社交信息流，结果会有很大差异。

Same algorithm, very different results depending on which social feed the algorithm runs over.

看到这些结果，Chamorro-Premuzic 认为仍然需要人工干预：“人工智能主要是一种预测机器。而人类的判断力是知道如何处理预测的能力。” 他建议对算法进行抽查，尤其是在预测不一致的时候。“好吧，也许我应该寻找其他数据，看看它们是否一致。也许我应该探究一下为什么会有差异。也许我应该看看你的工作经历，看看哪些是有用的，哪些是无用的东西？这就是为什么你需要能力和专业知识。”

Seeing these results, Chamorro-Premuzic thinks there is still a need for human intervention: “AI is mostly a prediction machine. And human judgment is the ability to know what to do with a prediction.” He recommends spot-checking algorithms. Especially when the predictions don’t line up. “Well, maybe I should look for other data and see if it’s consistent. Maybe I should explore why there is a difference. Maybe I should look at your job history and see, you know, what’s the signal and what’s noise? And that’s why you need competence and you need expertise.”

不幸的是，我们人类并不总是能够迎接这一挑战并提出正确的问题来批判性地审视摆在我们面前的技术。

Unfortunately, we humans don’t always rise to this challenge and ask the right questions to critically examine technology that is put in front of us.

信任机器

TRUST THE MACHINE

在研究人工智能在就业领域的应用时，我采访了许多招聘经理。大多数人都指出，他们希望人工智能能够解决的一个主要问题是：他们收到的求职申请数量让他们应接不暇。人工智能承诺可以快速解决这个问题。一位招聘经理一位经理开始使用基于人工智能的简历筛选器，因为他的招聘人员被大量的简历淹没了，他需要技术解决方案，他告诉我，他的员工并没有检查算法是否有效，因为人工智能永远不会犯错。

While researching the use of artificial intelligence in employment, I spoke to a lot of hiring managers. Most pointed to one main problem they were hoping AI would solve: they are overwhelmed by the number of job applications they receive. AI promises a quick fix. One hiring manager, who started using an AI-based résumé screener because his recruiters were drowning in résumés and he needed a technical fix, told me that his people are not checking whether the algorithm works, since artificial intelligence never makes mistakes.

佐治亚理工学院的研究人员设计了一个实验室实验，充分展现了人们对科技缺乏怀疑的态度：在实验中，研究人员用假烟雾制造了一个紧急火灾报警装置。大多数参与者跟随一个他们知道难以在空间中导航的机器人撞上了砖墙，尽管他们自己知道最近的紧急出口在哪里。“即使机器人指向一个没有明显出口的黑暗房间，大多数人也不会选择从他们进来的路安全地离开，”研究人员写道。27

Researchers at Georgia Tech built a lab experiment that illustrates this lack of skepticism of technology all too well: in the experiment, the researchers created an emergency fire alarm with fake smoke, and most participants followed a robot, which they knew had trouble navigating the space, into a brick wall even though they themselves knew where the closest emergency exit was located. “Even when the robot pointed to a dark room with no discernible exit, the majority of people did not choose to safely exit the way they entered,” wrote the researchers.27

人类常常盲目遵循科技设备的任何指示，因为我们许多人认为科技更优越、更客观。正因如此，科技才得以不受约束，一些不可靠的算法可能会在无人察觉的情况下造成真正的危害。

Humans often blindly follow whatever technical devices tell us because many of us believe technology is superior and more objective. That’s how technology goes unchecked and dodgy algorithms might cause real harm without anyone noticing.

托马斯·查莫罗-普雷穆齐克对我在推特和领英上预测性格结果的差异还有另一种解释：我可能更倾向于使用其中一种。这或许没错，尽管Crystal和Humantic AI工具都声称，即使是大约五百字的文字样本也足以从任何文本中提取出性格特征。我数了一下我的领英个人资料里的字数——超过五百字。

Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic has another explanation for the discrepancies in my Twitter and LinkedIn predictive personality results: I might use one medium more than the other. That might be true, although both the Crystal and Humantic AI tools claim that even a writing sample of about five hundred words is enough to pull a personality profile out of any text. I counted the words in my LinkedIn profile—there are more than five hundred words.

这就引出了我的下一个观点：如果算法没有足够的数据，或者没有足够多的“好”数据来预测我的性格，它难道不应该至少警告用户，而不是生成个人资料吗？或者，它至少应该显示一个免责声明，说明该预测的准确率非常低，因此不应该用于做出高风险的决策，包括招聘。

Which brings me to my next point: If the algorithm doesn’t have enough data, or not enough “good” data, to predict my personality, shouldn’t it at least warn the user that is the case and not generate a profile? Or maybe it could at least display a disclaimer that the prediction will have a very low accuracy rating and therefore shouldn’t be used to make high-stakes decisions, including hiring.

问题是，一旦我们在仪表板上看到候选人的排名和他们的数字，我们就会相信它们是真实的，即使它们可能只是一个准确率较低的预测，这意味着预测可能完全错误，但该技术的呈现方式让我们相信它是有效的。

The problem is that once we see the ranking of candidates and their numbers on the dashboard, we believe they are real even though they might just be a prediction with a low accuracy rating, meaning the prediction could be totally off, but the way the technology is presented makes us believe it works.

我们在很多算法中都看到了一个问题——准确性与结果需求之间的矛盾。过去几年，数百家基于人工智能的初创企业和公司进入人力资源市场，面临着巨大的盈利压力。让算法提醒用户其数据不足、不值得信任，这在商业上可能不太合理。

It’s a problem we see in a lot of algorithms—accuracy versus the need for results. Hundreds of AI-based start-ups and companies have entered the human resource market over the past few years and are under tremendous pressure to make money. It might not make much business sense to have an algorithm alert the user that it doesn’t have enough data and shouldn’t be trusted.

因此，公司通常会在算法中构建不同的准确度等级。问题在于，每个准确度等级的结果仍然简洁明了。因此，警察局使用的面部识别算法可能会声称某人匹配成功，但仔细查看其细则后，准确度可能会显示为 60% 或 70%——这个准确度并不算高，尤其对于风险极高的刑事司法系统而言。

So, instead, companies often build different accuracy levels into their algorithms. The problem is that each accuracy level still showcases the same neat and clear results. So a facial recognition algorithm used by a police department might claim that someone is a match, but when one looks at the fine print it may state that the accuracy is 60 or 70 percent—not very high, especially for the high stakes of the criminal justice system.

警察不应该仅凭低置信度分数就逮捕某人，但底特律居民罗伯特·朱利安-博尔查克·威廉姆斯 (Robert Julian-Borchak Williams) 却在 2020 年初因算法错误的人脸识别匹配而被捕。28

A police officer shouldn’t arrest someone based on a low confidence score, but Robert Julian-Borchak Williams, a Detroit resident, was arrested early in 2020 because of a wrongful facial recognition match by an algorithm.28

回想起来，我参加这些人工智能测试之前不应该这么紧张。在我和托马斯·查莫罗-普雷穆日克的案例中，所有算法都无法确定我们的身份。

In retrospect, I shouldn’t have been so nervous before I took these AI tests. In my and Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic’s cases, none of the algorithms agreed on who we were.

文字游戏

WORD GAMES

我与这两家公司讨论了预测性格的结果，并对他们的方法感到惊讶。

I talked to the two companies about the predictive personality results and was surprised to learn about their methods.

Humantic AI 的首席执行官 Amarpreet Kalkat 告诉我，他们公司的算法使用自然语言处理库来分析输入系统的文本。对于普通用户来说，这让他们很难理解该工具是如何生成结果的——它具体预测的是文本中的哪些词，或者推文中的哪些词。

Humantic AI’s CEO Amarpreet Kalkat told me that his company’s algorithm uses natural language processing libraries to analyze the text that is fed into the system. For the average user, that makes it hard to understand how the tool generates results—which words in the text or which words in tweets it specifically predicts upon.

Crystal 的创建者向我深入介绍了他们如何在内部验证测试。Crystal 要求一些用户参加传统的 DiSC 性格测试，回答大量问题。如果用户认为他们的结果准确，这些数据将作为 AI 模型的基准数据。然后，AI 会收集与该用户相关的所有文本：“这些信息包括他们在 LinkedIn 个人资料上使用的短语、不同的词汇、职位、雇主，以及几乎所有与该用户相关的信息，”Crystal 首席执行官 Drew D'Agostino 说道。

Crystal’s creators described to me in-depth how they validate their tests internally. Crystal asks some users to take traditional DiSC personality tests answering lots of questions. If the user rates their results as accurate, this data is used as ground truth for the AI-based model. The AI then takes in all the text that is associated with this user: “That information is things like the phrases they use on LinkedIn profiles, different words, job titles, employers, pretty much any information that is associated with that user,” said Drew D’Agostino, CEO of Crystal.

为了预测我的性格，Crystal 的人工智能会将我在领英上使用的词汇与其他参加过传统性格测试的 Crystal 用户在领英上使用的词汇进行比较。我与谁的词汇共同点最多，系统就会根据该用户的传统性格测试结果来预测我的性格。

To predict my personality, Crystal’s AI compared the words I used on LinkedIn to the words other Crystal users with a traditional personality test on record have used on LinkedIn. Whoever I have the most words in common with, the system then bases my personality prediction on that user’s traditional personality test results.

职位名称和其他描述性词语（包括地名）被输入到模型中似乎有些奇怪，因为我可能用过类似的词语来描述我的工作经历，就像其他住在纽约市的记者一样。这是否意味着我可能和其他使用类似词语、在我附近生活和工作的人拥有相同的性格？或者那些从事相同职业的人？Crystal 承认，目前还没有独立研究证实其方法的有效性。

It seems odd that job titles and other descriptive words, including location names, are fed into the model since I probably used similar words to describe my job history as did other reporters who live in New York City. Does that mean I might have the same personality as others who use similar words and live and have worked near me? Or those who work in the same profession? Crystal acknowledged that there are no independent studies verifying that its method works.

评估工具的约翰·斯科特认为，理论上，即时性格测试可以高效且经济实惠。“当其中一些测试的基础数据或算法设计充满错误时，问题就出现了，”他谈到Humantic AI 和 Crystal 的软件。“正是这种对最新技术的追求，导致了这些评估工具的商业化，而这些工具的存在是以牺牲合理、专业的实践和良好的科学性为代价的。”

John Scott, who evaluates assessment tools, thought that in theory instant personality tests could be efficient and cost effective. “The problem exists when the data that underlies some of this is filled with errors or the design of the algorithms is filled with errors,” he said about Humantic AI’s and Crystal’s software. “It’s this going after the latest technologies that has resulted in a commercialization of these assessment tools that exist at the expense of sound, professional practice and good science.”

我不想仅凭自己的小实验就对这两款工具做出判断。因此，我们与纽约大学的一位计算机科学、一位心理学、一位社会学教授以及其他同事合作，并与纽约大学数据科学中心的四名研究生合作，进行了一项更大规模的实验，比较Humantic AI和Crystal。我们的团队招募了90多名纽约大学的学生，并使用他们的领英页面、简历和推特资料来审核这两家公司的算法，简而言之，就是以更科学的方式和更大的样本量重复了我和Chamorro-Premuzic所做的事情。29

I didn’t want to rely on my own small experiment alone to make a judgment call about these two tools. So, together with a computer science, a psychology, and a sociology professor and other colleagues at NYU, we worked with four graduate students from NYU’s Center for Data Science to run a larger experiment comparing Humantic AI and Crystal. Our team recruited more than ninety students at NYU and used their LinkedIn pages, résumés, and Twitter profiles to audit these two companies’ algorithms, basically repeating in a nutshell what Chamorro-Premuzic and I did in a more scientific way and with a larger sample size.29

在早期测试阶段，我们发现了一个令人不安的事实。我们将同一份简历以原始文本文件和 PDF 格式上传到 Crystal，结果对相同文档的性格预测略有不同。

In an early testing phase, we made an unsettling discovery. We uploaded the same exact résumé to Crystal as a raw text file and as a PDF and got slightly different personality predictions off of identical documents.

当我们分别对参与者的 Twitter 和 LinkedIn 个人资料运行 Humantic 的人工智能时，该软件对我们研究中的许多人返回了不同的性格预测——就像它对 Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic 和我所做的那样，这与许多表明性格特征大多随时间保持稳定的研究结果相矛盾。30

When we ran Humantic’s AI separately over participants’ Twitter and LinkedIn profiles, the software returned different personality predictions for many of the people in our study—just like it did for Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic and me, contradicting many research studies that show that personality traits are mostly stable over time.30

当我们将 Crystal 与 Humantic AI 直接进行比较时，这两种工具为研究参与者分配了不同的 DiSC 分数。

When we compared Crystal directly to Humantic AI, the two tools assigned different DiSC scores to the study participants.

我联系了 Humantic AI 和 Crystal，邀请他们就这项研究发表评论。Crystal 这次没有回复我的提问。Humantic AI 的首席执行官 Amarpreet Kalkat 指出，这项研究的样本量较小，只有 94 名学生，而且由于2021年，“人性化AI算法经历了三次重大修订”，该公司目前主要专注于为销售团队提供个性化洞察。（对我来说，为销售团队提供如何与人打交道的建议，比起用这类算法进行招聘，对AI的应用风险更低。）

I reached out to Humantic AI and Crystal and invited the companies to comment on this study. Crystal this time did not answer my queries. Humantic AI’s CEO Amarpreet Kalkat noted that the sample size of the study was on the smaller side, with 94 students, and that since 2021 “Humantic AI algorithms have undergone three major revisions” and that the company is now primarily focusing on giving personality insights to sales teams. (To me, giving sales teams advice on how to approach people is a less high-stakes usage of AI then using these kinds of algorithms for hiring.)

不幸的是，这些以及其他未经测试和未经验证的算法仍然存在，使得找工作的过程更加不透明，并给忙碌的招聘经理带来可疑的好处。

Unfortunately, these and other untested and unverified algorithms are still out there, making the process of finding a job even more opaque and delivering questionable benefits to busy hiring managers.

但还有其他人工智能工具有望准确地找到求职者的性格特征，我们接下来将进行探讨。

But there are still other AI tools that promise to accurately find personality traits of job applicants, which we explore next.

* IBM 已经停止了 IBM Watson Personality Insights。

* IBM has already discontinued IBM Watson Personality Insights.

第三章

CHAPTER 3

我们玩的游戏

The Games We Play

关于创造性人工智能测试

On Creative AI Tests

秒自从我开始研究人工智能在工作中的应用以来，我就听说过基于人工智能的电子游戏。与枯燥的评估不同，求职者可以通过玩电子游戏来了解他们是否适合这个职位。

Since I started researching how artificial intelligence is used at work, I’ve heard about AI-based video games. Instead of boring assessments, applicants play video games so companies can learn whether they are the right person for the role.

如果简历筛选工具不可靠，偷偷搜索别人的社交媒体也不管用，或许玩游戏是个更好的办法。话说回来，谁不想靠玩电子游戏找工作呢？

If résumé screeners are not reliable and secretly scouring people’s social media doesn’t work, maybe playing games is a better approach. I mean, who doesn’t want to play video games to get a job?

这个想法很吸引人，这些游戏被广泛用于吸引应届大学毕业生进入大公司，尤其是金融行业。

The idea is alluring and these games are in widespread use for jobs that attract recent college graduates to large companies, especially in finance.

马丁·伯奇就是这样在找新工作时遇到这项技术的。我叫他零号病人，因为他是第一个我认识的一个人向他申请的公司索取了他的数据并采取了法律行动。

And that’s how Martin Burch encountered the technology when he was looking for a new job. I call him Patient Zero, because he is the first person I know who requested his data from the companies he applied to and initiated legal action.

伯奇三十五六岁，多年来一直在道琼斯和《 华尔街日报》从事数据工作，从纽约到伦敦，再到巴塞罗那。2021年，他申请了彭博伦敦的数据分析师职位，这个职位与他之前的工作类似。

Burch is in his mid-thirties and has worked with data for Dow Jones and The Wall Street Journal for years, moving from New York to London to Barcelona. In 2021, he applied for a data analyst position at Bloomberg in London, a role that was similar to the work he was already doing.

“在数据处理领域找工作，能和彭博社比肩的公司并不多，”伯奇说道。“这份工作看起来对我来说是个不错的机会，可以稍微调整一下我的技能，做我真正喜欢的事情，还能和最优秀的人共事。”

“There are not very many companies at Bloomberg’s level when you are looking for a job in data processing,” Burch said. “This job looked like it would be a good way for me to slightly pivot my skills and do something that I really enjoy and work with the best people.”

2021年5月2日，星期日，伯奇写了一封求职信，强调自己符合这份工作的条件，并提交了申请。他很快收到了彭博社的回复，要求他完成一家名为Plum的加拿大公司进行的数字评估。邮件中写道：“请注意，如果您不完成评估，您的申请将被撤回。” 他很想得到这份工作，于是他点击了链接，立即开始进行游戏化评估。

On Sunday, May 2, 2021, Burch wrote a cover letter highlighting why he would be qualified for the job and submitted an application. He immediately got a response from Bloomberg that asked him to complete a digital assessment by a Canadian company called Plum. “Please note your application will be withdrawn should you not complete the assessment,” read the email. He wanted the job, so he followed the link and started playing a gamified assessment right away.

游戏的优势

THE ADVANTAGE OF GAMES

如果您已经申请过麦当劳、波士顿咨询集团、彭博社、德勤、卡夫亨氏、IBM、高露洁棕榄、现代、惠而浦、麦肯锡、Postmates 或许多其他公司的职位，您可能被要求玩一套视频游戏。

If you have applied to a job at McDonald’s, Boston Consulting Group, Bloomberg, Deloitte, Kraft Heinz, IBM, Colgate-Palmolive, Hyundai, Whirlpool, McKinsey, Postmates, or many other companies, you might have been asked to play a suite of video games.

正如我们所见，自Indeed和Monster等求职平台出现以来，许多雇主表示，他们被求职申请淹没了，尤其是入门级职位，这类职位在应届大学毕业生中很受欢迎。很少有申请者拥有丰富的工作经验，因此，招聘时看重潜力和个性（而不是技能和经验）似乎更合理。

As we have seen, since the dawn of job platforms like Indeed and Monster, many employers say they are drowning in applications, especially for entry-level programs, which are popular with recent college graduates. Very few of the applicants have extensive work experience, so hiring for potential and personality (versus skills and experience) seems to make a lot of sense.

“根本的前提是，我们都有一定的倾向性，这些倾向性会决定我们能否成功，”人工智能游戏供应商 Pymetrics 的前首席执行官 Frida Polli 说道：“大量研究表明，不同的认知、社交、情感或性格特征确实会使人们特别适合角色 A，而不太适合角色 B。这项研究早于 Pymetrics 的出现，我们所做的一切本质上就是让这些特征的衡量不再依赖于自我报告问卷，而是更多地依赖于衡量你的行为。”（2022 年，Pymetrics 被 Harver 收购，Harver 是一家提供一系列评估服务的供应商，涵盖软技能分析、面试和背景调查服务。Pymetrics 游戏套件已被整合到更广泛的 Harver 平台。Frida Polli 曾担任 Harver 的首席数据科学官，但于 2023 年 4 月辞职。）1

“The fundamental premise is that we all sort of have certain predispositions and they’ll lead us to be more versus less successful,” said Frida Polli, the former CEO of AI games vendor Pymetrics: “There’s been a lot of research showing that different cognitive, social, and emotional or personality attributes do make people particularly well suited for role A and less well suited for role B. That research predates Pymetrics and all we’ve done is essentially make the measurement of those things less reliant on self-report questionnaires and more reliant on measuring your behavior.” (In 2022, Pymetrics was acquired by Harver, a vendor that offers a suite of assessments, from soft skills analysis to interviews and background-checking services. The Pymetrics game suite has been incorporated into the broader Harver platform. Frida Polli became the chief data science officer at Harver, but resigned in April 2023.)1

供应商表示，无论应聘者申请哪个职位，这些游戏都能适用于多种不同的工作。关键在于应聘者的个人特质与现有员工的特质有多少重合。

It doesn’t matter which positions someone is applying for, the games can work for many different jobs, the vendors say. It’s all about how much the individual applicant’s traits overlap with the traits that current employees exhibit.

马丁·伯奇被要求玩的游戏就是由 Plum 公司开发的，该公司首席执行官凯特琳·麦格雷戈 (Caitlin MacGregor) 表示，数字游戏也越来越多地被用来寻找合适的员工进行内部晋升或担任领导职务。

Digital games are also increasingly used to find the right employees for internal promotions or leadership positions, said Caitlin MacGregor, CEO of Plum, the company that built the game Martin Burch was asked to play.

我采访过的招聘算法游戏供应商表示，他们的工具减少了人为的偏见，并专注于求职者的天赋、人力潜力和软技能。

The vendors of algorithmic games for hiring that I spoke to said their tools reduce human bias and focus on applicants’ innate talents, human potential, and soft skills.

直觉上，这种说法没错：由于我们的性格，有些工作感觉更适合我们。但也存在相反的观点：我确实见过很多性格各异的医生和老师，他们各自找到了在类似工作中取得成功的方法。内向、外向以及具有其他性格特征的人都能在同一份工作中取得成功。我理解人们不想雇佣混蛋，但技能……更重要？我在这里强调这个论点，但我希望我的会计师被聘用不是因为他们和同事有相同的性格，而首先是因为他们具备成为一名优秀簿记员的技能。

Intuitively, this feels right: because of our personalities, some jobs feel like they are better suited for us. But there is also a counterargument: I have certainly met many doctors and teachers who all had different personalities and they each have found ways to be successful in similar jobs. Introverts and extroverts and people with other personality traits can succeed doing the same job. I understand that people don’t want to hire jerks, but aren’t skills more important? I am pushing the argument here, but I hope my accountant was not hired because they have the same personality as their colleagues, but first and foremost because they have the skills to be a good bookkeeper.

但在招聘中，个性越来越受到重视。2技能固然重要，但作用有限，而且越来越弱。快速的技术变革和包括新冠疫情在内的异常事件迫使许多公司及其员工迅速适应新的工作方式并学习新技能。3

But in hiring, personality is a growing focus.2 Skills matter, but only to a point and less and less so. Rapid technological change and unusual events, including COVID, forced lots of companies and their employees to quickly adjust to new ways of working and to pick up new skills.3

“五年前，每个人都想招聘 Ruby on Rails（编程语言）开发人员。那是当时最热门的语言，你永远都找不到足够的人才。现在，没人愿意招聘 Ruby on Rails 开发人员。这些硬技能的保质期越来越短了，”MacGregor 说。“我们需要首先关注潜力，然后再将资格作为决策标准之一。”

“Five years ago, everybody wanted to hire Ruby on Rails [programming language] developers. That was the hottest thing and you couldn’t get enough of them. Now nobody wants to hire Ruby on Rails developers. The shelf-life of those hard skills is just getting smaller and smaller,” MacGregor said. “We need to be focusing on potential first and then be looking at eligibility as one of the decision-making criteria.”

凯特琳·麦格雷戈（Caitlin MacGregor）本人之所以能与人共同创立Plum，部分原因在于她之前的老板在她开始第一份工作时给了她一个机会。麦格雷戈没有相关经验，但她之前的老板相信她的潜力，相信她可以为这家慈善机构开创一个新的业务部门。她的工作是为这家慈善机构创建一家社会企业，打造一家不依赖血汗工厂、本地制造的定制服装公司。通过这次挑战，她发现了自己创业的潜力。

Caitlin MacGregor herself cofounded Plum in part because a former boss had taken a chance on her when she started her first job. MacGregor had no relevant experience, but her former boss believed in her potential and that she could start a new business arm of the charity. Her job was to create a social enterprise for the charity, building a sweatshop-free, locally made, custom apparel company. Through this challenge she found her entrepreneurial side.

“如果我的老板没看到我的潜力，那纸面上根本就没有任何关于我了解服装行业制造和供应链管理的证明。我必须从头学习一切，”她说。而她成功了。

“If my boss hadn’t seen my potential, there was nothing on paper that said that I knew anything about manufacturing and supply chain management in the apparel business. I had to learn everything from scratch,” she said. And she succeeded.

潜力第一，技能第二

POTENTIAL FIRST, SKILLS SECOND

正如前文所述，许多企业领导者表示，在不确定的时期（无论是疫情还是在动荡的初创环境中，优秀的员工能够轻松适应不断变化的世界，并自学新技能和知识。4但是，招聘经理如何从简历或面试中推断出申请人具有团队合作精神或能够轻松应对新挑战呢？这几乎是不可能的。

As noted earlier, instead of specific expertise, many business leaders say that what’s helping companies in uncertain times—be it a pandemic or a volatile start-up environment—are employees who can easily adjust to a changing world and teach themselves new skills and knowledge.4 But how do hiring managers deduct from a résumé or in a job interview that an applicant is a team player or adapts easily to new challenges? That’s almost impossible.

这就是人工智能游戏的用武之地。

And that’s where AI games come in.

“最终，我突然灵光一闪，”弗里达·波利谈到她在 Pymetrics 的那段经历时说道，“我想，‘好吧，我们知道如何衡量软技能了。我们知道如何以更科学、更客观的方式衡量招聘人员和求职者想要了解的自身特质。我们不需要像茶叶一样去解读简历。’”

“Ultimately, I just had this light bulb go off,” Frida Polli said of her time at Pymetrics, “thinking, ‘Okay, we know how to measure soft skills. We know how to measure the things that recruiters and candidates are looking to understand about themselves in a much more scientific, objective way. We don’t have to tea-leaf-read off a résumé.’”

Safe Hammad 是游戏化测评提供商 Arctic Shores 的首席技术官兼联合创始人，他认为人工智能游戏还有另一个好处。与传统的性格测试和求职面试相比，人工智能游戏中嵌入的行为测试降低了求职者伪造答案的能力：“当我问你一个问题，如果你处于这个位置，你会如何反应时，你不会想，‘哦，我会怎么反应？’ 你会想，‘哦，提问者希望我说些什么，才能让我更有可能获得这份工作？’ 所以，不问问题，就很难伪造答案，而且主观性也低得多。”

Safe Hammad, the chief technology officer and cofounder of game-based assessment provider Arctic Shores, believes there is a further benefit of AI games. Behavioral tests embedded in AI games reduce candidates’ ability to fake their answers compared to traditional personality tests and job interviews: “When I ask a question about how would you react if you’re in this position, you’re not thinking, ‘Oh, how would I react?’ You’re thinking, ‘Oh, what does the person asking me want me to say that’s going to give me the best chance of getting that job?’ So without asking questions, it’s a lot harder to fake and it’s a lot less subjective.”

Criteria 评估产品副总裁 Matthew Neale 表示，人工智能游戏也更能吸引求职者。大多数人讨厌冗长的技能评估或回答大量的性格测试问题，但大多数求职者却喜欢玩电子游戏。求职者在玩游戏时，他们的游戏行为会展现出他们的性格特征。

AI games are also more enjoyable for job applicants, said Matthew Neale, vice president of assessment products at Criteria. Most people hate lengthy skills assessments or answering lots of personality test questions, but most applicants enjoy playing video games. While an applicant is playing, their in-game behaviors reveal aspects of their personality.

例如，社交能力得分无法通过把候选人放在虚拟房间，然后测量他们接触了多少人来预测。社交能力得分更加抽象。“实际上，你根本意识不到，”Arctic Shores 的 Hammad 在谈到其公司的评估工具时说道。“那里“我们会做一些任务，让你选左，选右，然后稍微施压一下，最后得出社交能力的衡量标准，”他说，“对我来说，这简直就是魔术。我稍微理解一下这里面的科学原理。我当然懂其中的数学，但这真的就像魔术​​一样。”

For example, a sociability score wouldn’t be predicted by putting a candidate in a virtual room and measuring how many folks they approach. It’s more abstract. “Actually, you really wouldn’t realize it,” Hammad of Arctic Shores said of his company’s assessment tool. “There are a few tasks where we ask you to choose left, choose right, and press you a little bit and we come out with a measure of sociability,” he said. “For me, it’s magic. I understand the science a little bit underneath. I certainly understand the mathematics, but it’s like magic.”

数据工程师出身的求职者马丁·伯奇（Martin Burch）被游戏制作人Plum要求玩一个排序游戏。游戏要求他展示两排三个不同的形状，并让他选择第三排的第三个形状，以测试他的模式识别能力。

Martin Burch, the data engineer turned job applicant, was asked by game maker Plum to play a sorting game. The assessment showed him three different shapes in two rows and asked him to choose which shape should be the third one on the third row, testing his pattern recognition abilities.

软件让他解决越来越多的排序任务。过了一会儿，他开始琢磨这些游戏跟工作有什么关系。“这道关于方块图案的问题跟我从网站上抓取数据的能力有什么关系？难道我们不应该在工作中测试我的能力吗？”他自问。

The software wanted him to solve more and more sorting tasks. After a while, he wondered what these games had to do with the job. “What does this question about the patterns on these blocks have to do with my abilities to scrape data from websites? Shouldn’t we be testing my abilities in the job?” he asked himself.

伯奇并非唯一有此疑问的人。索菲，这位海军老兵，从Chapter 1转行成为软件开发人员，在应聘的一家公司让她玩一款名为Cognify的游戏时，也曾有过类似的疑问。“对我来说，”她说，“作为一名退伍军人，参加考试和测验，或者承受压力对我来说不算什么，但我不知道为什么Cognify测试让我感到焦虑。我想是因为我知道它和软件工程无关。这才是真正让我焦虑的地方。”

Burch is not the only one with that question. Sophie, the navy veteran turned software developer from Chapter 1, had similar questions when a company she applied at asked her to play a game called Cognify. “For me,” she said, “being a military veteran being able to take tests and quizzes or being under pressure is nothing for me, but I don’t know why the Cognify test gave me anxiety. I think it’s because I knew that it had nothing to do with software engineering. That’s what really got me.”

索菲拥有信息科学研究生学位，主修数据科学和交互设计。她不明白，解决限时谜题或玩类似俄罗斯方块的电子游戏，怎么能对她在软件开发领域取得成功的潜力做出有意义的评估。

Sophie has a graduate degree in information sciences, with specialties in data science and interaction design. She didn’t understand how solving a timed puzzle or playing video games that feel like Tetris could lead to a meaningful calculation of her potential to succeed in software development.

“我当时就想，什么？我不明白。这不重要，”她一边玩游戏一边想。“公司想要多元化，包容性，但在思维方式上，你并没有体现多样性和包容性；每个人的想法都不一样。所以，当你只选择那些能在60秒内解开谜题的人时，你如何体现多样性和包容性呢？

“I’m just like, what? I don’t understand. This is not relevant,” she thought as she played the games. “Companies want to do diversity and inclusion, but you’re not doing diversity and inclusion when it comes to thinking; not everyone thinks the same. So how are you inputting that diversity and inclusion when you’re only selecting the people that can figure out a puzzle within sixty seconds?”

输掉一场比赛还是丢掉一份工作

LOSING A GAME VERSUS LOSING A JOB

索菲和马丁·伯奇觉得这些评估并非可有可无。伯奇必须完成才能被彭博社考虑录用，所以他完成了。他在周日参加了Plum测试。第二天，恰逢英国银行假日，他收到了彭博社的一封电子邮件。邮件里传来坏消息：他被拒绝了。

Sophie and Martin Burch felt that the assessments weren’t really optional. Burch needed to complete his to be considered for the job at Bloomberg, so he finished it. He took the Plum test on a Sunday. The next day, which was a bank holiday in the UK, he received an email from Bloomberg. It contained bad news: he had been rejected.

伯奇的回复速度之快和被拒本身都让他感到意外。他当时在一家直接竞争对手那里工作，经验也符合职位描述，而且有过成功的记录。但即便如此，他仍然没有被考虑。

The turnaround time was surprising for Burch as was the rejection itself. He was working at a direct competitor, his experience lined up with the job description, and he had a track record of success. But still, he was no longer being considered.

他给彭博社的一位招聘人员发了一封邮件，询问发生了什么事。彭博社前校园招聘经理索菲·沃利斯（Sophie Wallis）回复道：“我在我们的系统上查看了你的申请，发现你的申请被拒绝了，因为你完成的Plum评估没有达到我们的标准。很遗憾，我们无法进一步审核你的申请。”

He emailed a recruiter at Bloomberg and asked what happened. An answer came from Sophie Wallis, the former manager of campus recruiting at Bloomberg: “Looking at your application on our system I can see that your application was rejected due to not meeting our benchmark in the Plum assessment that you completed. Unfortunately on that basis we are not able to take your application any further.”

伯奇被算法拒绝了。这让他很不舒服。他知道自己有资格胜任这份工作，不会轻易放弃。

Burch had been rejected by an algorithm. This didn’t sit right with him. He knew he was qualified for the job, and he wasn’t going to give up so easily.

“有很多原因导致你可能不适合这份工作，”他承认。但他不明白，连续添加积木或回答性格测试的问题与预测他是否能够以结构化的方式抓取网站数据，这是他申请的工作所需的主要技能之一。

“There are lots of reasons why you might not be the right fit for a job,” he acknowledged. But he didn’t understand how adding blocks in a row or answering questions in a personality quiz has anything to do with predicting whether he can scrape websites in a structured way, which was one of the main skills needed for the job he applied for.

专家称这种情况缺乏表面效度，即求职者无法理解测试或评估与工作岗位的关联。（普拉姆表示，这可以确保匹配到与工作相关的人才。）评估是否具有表面效度是像查尔斯·汉德勒这样的组织心理学家所关注的问题。二十多年来，他一直致力于帮助企业找到合适的招聘工具：“如果求职者问‘他们为什么要问我这个问题？’，那你就有麻烦了。”

Experts call this lack of face validity, when someone does not understand how a test or assessment is related to the job. (Plum said that it ensures that it matches talents that are job relevant.) Whether an assessment has face validity is a concern for organizational psychologists like Charles Handler, who for over twenty years has helped companies find the right tools for their recruiting processes: “If you have an applicant saying, ‘Why are they asking me this?’ you got a problem.”

马丁·伯奇正是这么问自己的。他曾在一家领先的新闻机构工作多年。通过那段工作经历，他了解到自己对自己的数据拥有一些权利。“那时，我放弃了那些老掉牙的GDPR工具。”

That’s exactly what Martin Burch asked himself. He had worked for years at a leading news organization. Through that work, he learned that he had some rights to his own data. “At that point, I got out the good old GDPR tools.”

通用数据保护条例（GDPR）实际上是一部相当近期的里程碑式数据保护和隐私法。它赋予欧盟和英国居民及公民向公司了解其个人数据使用情况的权利。了解了这些情况后，伯奇联系了普拉姆，并索要他的数据。正因如此，他才被称为“零号病人”，也是我所知第一个利用这项法律深入挖掘并查明自己被拒原因的人。

General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR) is actually a pretty recent landmark data protection and privacy law. It gives residents and citizens in the European Union and in the United Kingdom the right to learn from companies how their personal data has been used. With that knowledge in mind, Burch reached out to Plum and requested his data. That is what makes him Patient Zero, the first person I’m aware of who used the law to dig deeper and find out more about why he was rejected for a job.

我还联系了Plum，并与该公司首席执行官凯特琳·麦克格雷戈（Caitlin Mac-Gregor）进行了交谈。她告诉我，她公司的产品是基于证据的：“心理学家已经做过研究，过去的经验和教育背景并不能很好地预测未来的表现。它可以告诉你一个人是否能胜任这份工作。它可以告诉你，‘有人能胜任这份工作吗？’但它不会告诉你他们是否能做好这份工作。它不会告诉你他们的表现是低劣、中等还是顶尖。你无法从过去的经验和过去的经历中获得这些数据。”如果你想知道一个人是否会表现出色并能继续留在这个职位上，就需要教育。你需要我们评估的数据。

I also reached out to Plum and spoke with the CEO, Caitlin Mac-Gregor. She told me that her company’s products are evidence based: “Psychologists have done the research, and past experience and past education, [that information] is not a strong predictor of future performance. It can tell you if somebody can hit the job running. It can tell you, ‘Can somebody do this job?’ But it will not tell you if they will do it well. It won’t tell you if they will be a low performer or an average performer or a top performer. You can’t get that data from past experience and past education if you want to know if somebody is going to perform well and stay in the role. You need the data that we assess for.”

围绕人工智能游戏传递的信息听起来就像梦想成真，任何人都可以根据其天生的能力和特质找到理想的工作：“关键在于理解这些行为是什么，当你做出这些行为时，就像你的水桶被装满了一样，它会驱动你，”Mac-Gregor 说。“这款（软件工具）正在量化驱动每个人的因素、能力和行为，直至‘这可能会激励你，而这可能会耗尽你的精力’。”

The messaging around AI games sounds like a dream come true, where anyone can be matched to the perfect job based on their innate abilities and traits: “It is understanding what are those behaviors, that when you do them, it’s like your bucket gets filled, it drives you,” Mac-Gregor said. “This [software tool] is quantifying what drives each individual person and the competencies and behaviors right down to ‘this might drive you and this drains you.’”

善于执行的人不需要被事无巨细地管理。他们会驱使自己完成任务，因为他们热爱其中的满足感。Plum 的“游戏”衡量的是解决问题的能力、个性和社交智力。Caitlin MacGregor 表示，尽管这简化了公司筛选的十项才能，但它对一个人的了解更为全面。

People who are good at executing don’t need to be micromanaged. They will drive themselves to fulfill a task because they love the satisfaction. Plum’s “games” measure problem solving, personality, and social intelligence. Caitlin MacGregor said that this is a more holistic understanding of a person—albeit reduced to the ten talents the company screens for.

Plum 的流程始于工作分析——员工需要什么才能胜任这份工作？Plum 会进行一项八分钟的多项选择题调查，要求雇主公司的利益相关者找出 Plum 测试的十个特质中，哪五个对该职位最重要。（凯特琳·麦格雷戈回避了如果某个对工作至关重要的特质或技能不属于 Plum 的十个特质，会发生什么情况的问题。）

Plum’s process starts with a job analysis—what does an employee need to be successful in this job? An eight-minute survey of multiple-choice questions asks stakeholders at the employer company to figure out which five of the ten traits that Plum tests for are the most important for the role. (Caitlin MacGregor avoided answering questions about what happens if a trait or skill important to a job is not part of the ten Plum traits.)

然后，Plum 申请人评估由三个部分组成。第一部分是模式匹配测试——你会得到两行三个形状图案，第三行只有两个形状，你需要添加另一个符合该序列的形状；第二部分是性格测试；第三部分是情境判断测试，申请人需要阅读一些关于职场潜在问题的短文，并被问及他们会如何应对。

Then, the Plum applicant assessment consists of three parts. The first is a pattern-matching test—you are given three shape patterns in two rows and only two shapes in the third row and you have to add another one shape that fits the sequence; a personality test; and a situational judgment test, where applicants read short stories of potential problems in the workplace and are asked how they would react.

MacGregor 给我举了一个虚构的候选人 Maya 的例子：Maya 的产品经理职位匹配率高达 95%，但运营总监的匹配率只有 65%。她可能有经验但评估显示，作为产品经理，她更像是公司其他 5% 的顶尖员工，因此她更适合并能出色地完成这个职位。
