MacGregor gave me an example of a fictional candidate named Maya: Maya scored a 95 percent match for product manager, but only a 65 percent match for director of operations. She may have experience in both roles, but the assessment showed that, as a product manager, she is more like the other top 5 percent of the workforce at the company, so that’s where she would be a better fit and excel.

这是一种预测、预报、预估，因此当我听到像凯特琳·麦格雷戈这样的首席执行官如此权威地宣称求职者就像小说中的玛雅人一样，在某项工作上比在另一项工作上表现更出色时，我感到很有趣。

This is a prediction, a forecast, a prognosis, so it’s interesting for me to hear that CEOs like Caitlin MacGregor say so authoritatively that job applicants, like the fictional Maya, would be better in one job than in another.

令人惊讶的是，一些招聘经理在决定候选人是否应该晋级下一轮或被拒绝时，竟然只考虑候选人的性格。专家表示，一个人在新工作中成败的原因有很多：经理、团队、公司文化、个人情况、技能、过往工作经历以及性格。令人费解的是，大多数评估只考虑候选人的特质和技能。

It’s striking that some hiring managers are okay with considering only a candidate’s personality when making a decision of whether the individual should advance to the next round or be rejected. Experts say that there are many reasons why someone might fail or succeed at a new job: the managers, the team, the company culture, a personal situation, their skills, their past work experiences, their personality. It’s fascinating that most assessments take only the traits and skills of the candidates into consideration.

我不知道我们是否真的能够更全面地考虑申请人以及他们即将加入的团队。除非这项工作能够完成，否则某些人工智能工具找到正确方案的想法或许只是一种幻想。

I wonder if we will ever be able to consider applicants, and the teams they are about to join, more holistically. Unless this work is done, it may be magical thinking that some AI tools have found the right formula.

与此同时，马丁·伯奇从普拉姆那里收到了他的乐谱：

In the meantime, Martin Burch received his scores from Plum:

问题解决： 75.06

Problem-Solving: 75.06

社交智力： 35.401

Social Intelligence: 35.401

勤奋： 20.598

Industriousness: 20.598

有序度： 76.299

Orderliness: 76.299

稳定性： 32.487

Stability: 32.487

自尊： 29.822

Self-Regard: 29.822

智力素质： 34.812

Intellectual Disposition: 34.812

经验倾向： 10.135

Experiential Disposition: 10.135

热情： 42.673

Enthusiasm: 42.673

自信度： 4.333

Assertiveness: 4.333

同情心： 73.42

Compassion: 73.42

礼貌： 88.818

Mannerliness: 88.818

伯奇没有得到太多解释，他很想知道这些数字意味着什么。这些是百分比吗？88分是高分还是低分？哪些分数与彭博的评估相关？（我问了普拉姆，这些数字都是100分制，越高越好。）

Burch didn’t get much of an explanation and he wondered what the numbers meant. Were these percentages? Was 88 a high score or a low score? Which scores were relevant in Bloomberg’s assessment? (I asked Plum and the numbers are out of 100; the higher, the better.)

对于不询问自身数据的普通求职者来说，结果会更加模糊。测试者会了解他们最重要的三个特质。

For regular job candidates who do not inquire about their data, the results are more vague. Test takers learn about their three most important traits.

我也参加了 Plum 评估，我最重要的三个特质是沟通能力、团队合作精神和说服力。我和 Burch 交换了我们参加的测试的笔记，很确定我们参加的是同一项测试；Plum 只有一套游戏。但我不确定沟通能力、团队合作精神和说服力（我在 Martin Burch 参加的同一项 Plum 测试中得分最高的特质）与他从 Plum 获得的十二类结果有何关联。例如，说服力与热情、智力倾向和勤奋有何关系？Plum 的评估似乎试图衡量某些特质，然后以某种方式将它们转化为其他特质。该公司告诉我，本质上每个 Plum 天赋/能力都有一个相关的算法。例如，沟通能力包括以下能力：清晰地解释关键概念、倾听和关注他人、回应观众并表现出同理心。清晰地解释关键概念的能力由以下特征组成：热情、自信、有序和社交智力。

I took the Plum assessment, as well, and my three most important traits were communication, teamwork, and persuasion. Burch and I compared notes on the tests we took and are pretty sure we took the same one; Plum has only one suite of games. But I am not sure how communication, teamwork, and persuasion, the traits I scored highest on in the same Plum test Martin Burch took, are connected to the twelve categories of results he got from Plum. How is persuasion related to enthusiasm, intellectual disposition, and industriousness, for example? It seems like Plum’s assessment is trying to measure certain traits, then somehow translates them into other traits. The company told me that essentially there is an associated algorithm for each Plum Talent/Competency. For example, communication consists of these competencies: explaining key concepts with clarity, listening and attending to others, and responding to an audience and showing empathy. The competency explaining key concepts with clarity is composed of the following traits: enthusiasm, assertiveness, orderliness, and social intelligence.

这项调查引发了更多问题。首先，这些人工智能游戏的底层是如何运作的？我在报道Pymetrics时曾对它有所了解。该公司给我发了一个链接，让我可以亲自体验他们的游戏套件。

This inquiry raised more questions. For one: How do these AI games work under the hood? I was given a glimpse when I reported on Pymetrics. The company sent me a link to try out its suite of games myself.

使用 PYMETRICS

PLAYING WITH PYMETRICS

再次，我一开始有点紧张。也许我的性格特征不如我希望的那么“好”？也许游戏会发现我内心刻薄又记仇？

Once again, I am a bit nervous getting started. Maybe my personality traits aren’t as “good” as I hope? Maybe the game will find out I am secretly mean and vindictive?

我深吸一口气，开始玩。Pymetrics 套件中的首批游戏之一颇具复古风，带有早期电子游戏的美感，让人想起《吃豆人》之前的样子。

I take a deep breath and start playing. One of the first games in the Pymetrics suite is kind of vintage, with an early video game aesthetic. Think pre-Pac-Man.

我看到一个白色背景，上面有一个蓝色、橙色或黄色的气球。我的任务是一次给一个气球充气。每次我点击“充气”，气球就会膨胀一点，然后我会收到五美分的虚拟币。我的目标是尽可能多地赚钱。但如果气球在我点击“领取”收到钱之前爆掉，我这一轮的所有数字收益都会消失。

I see a white background with either a blue, orange, or yellow balloon. I am tasked with inflating one balloon at a time. Every time I click “pump,” the balloon expands just a little and I receive five virtual cents. My goal is to earn as much money as possible. But if the balloon pops before I press “collect” and receive my money, all my digital earnings for that round disappear.

当我玩游戏时，系统会收集有关我的行为的不同数据点 - 接收所有信号，从我的鼠标移动到点击间隔。

As I play, the system is collecting different data points about my behavior—taking in all the signals, from my mouse movements to intervals between clicks.

作为一名玩家，我边玩边学：我很快就发现橙色和黄色的气球爆得更快，所以我确保在只抽几次之后就能早点拿到钱。但我可以抽蓝色的气球二十多次，赚两美元以上，这比其他气球赚的钱要多。

As a player, I learn as I go: I quickly figure out that the orange and yellow balloons pop faster, so I make sure to collect my money earlier, after just a couple of pumps. But I can pump the blue balloons more than twenty times, earning over two dollars, which is more than I can make with the other balloons.

在玩气球游戏的时候，我琢磨出了一个策略，并利用这个策略赚了更多钱。也许软件把我评为一个敢于冒险的人，希望这是件好事？！

While playing the balloon game, I figure out a strategy and earn more money using this insight. Maybe the software is scoring me as a risk-taker and that’s hopefully a good thing?!

我给39个气球充气后，赚了14.40美元。屏幕上出现了一条信息：“你在高风险情况下坚持一致的做法。衡量特质：风险。”

After pumping up thirty-nine balloons, I have earned $14.40. A message appears on the screen: “You stick to a consistent approach in high risk situations. Trait measured: Risk.”

这些视频游戏并不是特别吸引人，但我明白它们并不是专门为我的娱乐而设计的。

The video games are not super engaging, but I understand that they are not designed solely for my entertainment.

当我玩游戏时，基于机器学习的系统会测量八项认知、社交和情感特质，包括慷慨、公平、情感和注意力。我感到双重脆弱：求职本身就是一个高风险的场景，而玩一款会“揭示”我内心深处性格特征的游戏则有点吓人。

While I’m playing, the machine learning–based system measures eight cognitive, social, and emotional traits, including generosity, fairness, emotion, and attention. I feel doubly vulnerable: a job application is a high-stakes setting and playing a game that will “reveal” my innermost personality traits is kind of scary.

在现实的求职环境中，系统会将我的特质与我申请的职位上已有的成功员工进行比较。如果我的特质与他们的相似程度相似，我就能进入下一轮招聘。如果我的特质不一致，我很可能会被这份工作拒绝。

In a real-world job application setting, the system would compare my traits to those of successful employees already working in the job for which I’m applying. If my traits line up with theirs to a similar degree, I’d advance to the next round of hiring. If my traits don’t line up, I most likely would be rejected for this particular job.

玩游戏的时候，我的脑海里会不时地自言自语。我一边抽气球，一边不停地问自己，这游戏可能在测试什么。和陌生人分享虚拟货币，或者按方向键匹配屏幕上箭头指向的方向，这是什么意思？其他游戏则更直接：屏幕上一串数字一个接一个地闪过，我必须记下它们的顺序。

During the game playing, my mind has random meta conversations with myself. I keep asking myself what this game might be testing as I am pumping balloons. What does it mean to share virtual money with strangers or hit the arrow keys to match the direction the arrows on the screen point? Other games are more straightforward: series of numbers flash on the screen one right after another and I have to note down the sequence.

有些测试，比如需要我尽可能快地按下空格键的测试，我感觉很困惑。它们感觉跟我能想到的任何工作都没什么关系。

For some of the tests, like the one where I have to press my spacebar as fast as I can, I am just confused. They don’t feel like they are related to any kind of job I can think of.

寻找高绩效人才

THE SEARCH FOR HIGH PERFORMERS

当新客户与 Pymetrics 签约时，公司必须至少选择 50 名在其目标职位上表现出色的员工。这些员工会玩 Pymetrics 的游戏来生成训练数据。接下来，Pymetrics 的系统会将这些员工的数据与从超过 200 万人中随机抽取的一万多人的游戏数据进行比较，以找出这批成功员工与其他人群相比的独特之处。

When a new client signs up with Pymetrics, the company must select at least fifty employees who have been successful in the role it wants to fill. These employees play Pymetrics’ games to generate training data. Next, Pymetrics’ system compares the data from those employees with game data from more than ten thousand people randomly selected from over two million to find what makes this batch of successful employees special compared to the rest of the population.

“这基本上就是了解在某个职位上取得成功的人与我们所谓的基线群体有何不同，”弗里达·波利说道。该系统构建了一个模型，用于识别和排序客户成功员工最具体的技能，并确保该模型的公平性。

“It’s basically understanding how people that are successful in a role are different from what we call a baseline group,” Frida Polli said. The system builds a model that identifies and ranks the skills most specific to the client’s successful employees and also makes sure the model is fair.

Pymetrics 以能够发现求职者身上最难训练的特质而自豪，这些特质包括灵活性、学习能力和果断性。该公司表示，他们使用的“最先进的”数据科学推荐引擎与 Netflix、亚马逊和 Spotify 使用的相同。

Pymetrics prides itself on finding traits in job applicants that it says are hardest to train for, including flexibility, learning ability, and decisiveness. The company says it utilizes the same “state-of-the-art” data science recommendation engines used by Netflix, Amazon, and Spotify.

但正如所有用户所知，Netflix 和亚马逊的人工智能工具并非总是准确无误。这对于向我推荐产品的人工智能工具来说并非问题——如果人工智能误解了我的偏好，导致我什么都没买，那就是亚马逊的损失。当人工智能游戏用于招聘和晋升时，风险要高得多：如果人工智能工具误解了我的性格，即使我是一个非常合格的候选人，也拒绝了我，我肯定不会高兴。

But as every user knows, Netflix’s and Amazon’s AI-based tools don’t always get it right. That’s not a problem with an AI tool that recommends products to me—it’s Amazon’s loss if its AI gets my preferences wrong and I don’t buy anything. The stakes are much higher when AI games are used for hiring and giving promotions: if an AI tool gets my personality wrong and rejects me even though I am a well-qualified candidate, I wouldn’t be so happy.

专家认为，将成功员工作为衡量标准存在几个问题：谁来决定谁是成功的？如果根据年度绩效评估来选拔成功员工，这可能会带来问题，因为事实证明，由于自身偏见，管理者对女性和有色人种员工的评价更为负面。5员工之所以被视为高绩效员工，是因为他们的管理者喜欢和他们一起喝啤酒，还是这些人本身就具备高绩效？高绩效究竟意味着什么？如何客观地量化？

Experts see a couple of issues when it comes to using successful employees as a benchmark: Who decides who is successful? If successful employees are selected on the basis of annual performance reviews, that might be a problem because it’s been shown that managers rate women and employees of color more negatively because of their own biases.5 Are employees perceived as high performers because their manager likes to grab a beer with them or are these folks objectively high performers? And what does it mean to be a high performer, anyway—how is that objectively quantified?

另一个问题是样本量和样本内部的多样性。如果样本量太小，包含许多被选为高绩效者的白人男性，那么该工具就有可能捕捉到他们的特质和偏好，而忽略其他可能属于不同种族和/或性别的合格申请人的特质和偏好。

Another issue is sample size and diversity within the sample. If the size of the sample is too small and includes many white men, who are selected as high performers, there is always a risk that the tool will pick up their traits and preferences and not the traits and preferences of other qualified applicants who might be of a different race and/or gender.

Pymetrics 竞争对手 Criteria 的 Matthew Neale 分享了一个例子，解释了为什么像 Pymetrics 这样只关注高绩效员工并将其与普通人群进行比较，在招聘过程中可能会存在风险。Neale 的公司的任务是寻找可用于为客户组织招聘高绩效医疗工作者的评估方法。

Matthew Neale from Pymetrics’ competitor Criteria shared an example that explains why looking only at high performers and comparing them to the general population, as Pymetrics does, might be risky in hiring. Neale’s company was tasked with finding assessments that could be used to hire high-performing healthcare workers for the client’s organization.

尼尔想了解高绩效医护人员与普通人群有何不同——他们有什么特别之处吗？Criteria 最初模仿 Pymetrics 的方法，让“成功”员工接受测试，然后将结果与普通人群进行比较。“当我们只关注高绩效员工时，”尼尔说，“我们发现高绩效员工在与他人互动时比普通人群更热情、更随和、更友好。”

Neale wanted to understand how high-performing healthcare workers may be different from the general population—is there something that makes them special? In an approach that at first mimicked Pymetrics’, Criteria had “successful” employees take a test and then compared the findings to the general population. “When we looked at just the high performers,” Neale said, “we found the high performers are more warm and agreeable, more friendly in their approach when they are interacting with others than what is typical in the general population.”

他继续说道：“如果你只看高绩效员工的数据，你可能会说，我们需要雇佣那些热情、友好、随和的人。”

He continued, “If you only looked at that data of the high performers, you might say, we need to go and hire people who are warm, friendly, and agreeable.”

但这可能会让公司走上错误的道路。

But that would have led the company down the wrong path.

他说：“当你把表现不佳的人带进来时，事实证明，他们和表现出色的人一样热情、友好、随和。”表现优异和表现不佳的医护人员都比一般人群更热情、友好、更随和。

“When you bring in the poor performers,” he said, it turns out, “well, they’re just as warm and friendly and agreeable as the high performers.” High- and low-performing healthcare workers are warmer, friendlier, and more agreeable than the general population.

如果公司在寻找高绩效员工的特殊之处时，只将高绩效员工与普通人群进行比较，他们可能会发现一些高绩效员工与普通人群的区别，但这可能无法预测员工是否能成功。

If companies only check high performers against the general population in searching for what makes their high performers special, they might find something that distinguishes the high performers from the general population, but that might not be a predictor of success.

如果这家公司根据医护人员的友好程度和热情程度来招聘他们，那么他们招聘的标准就与工作成功无关了。这就好比根据高水平篮球运动员的成绩来评判他们的成功。身高，比一般人高。但表现不佳的篮球运动员也比一般人高。

If this company had hired healthcare workers based on how friendly and warm they were, they would have hired people based on a criterion that had nothing to do with being successful in the job. It would have been like basing high-performing basketball players’ success on their height, which is taller than the average person. But low-performing basketball players are also taller than the average person.

尼尔能够缩小该组织中高绩效医疗保健工作者与低绩效工作者之间的区别，看他们对待工作的组织性、勤奋性和认真程度。

Neale was able to narrow down what distinguished high-performing healthcare workers at this organization from low performers to how organized, diligent, and conscientious they were toward their work.

当我与其他专家交谈时，他们对 Pymetrics 和其他 AI 游戏供应商的产品表达了额外的担忧。

When I talked to other experts, they shared additional concerns about Pymetrics’ and other AI game vendors’ products.

Pymetrics 表示，其游戏源自认知和神经科学测试。正因如此，一位专家认为 Pymetrics 的游戏可以揭示心理健康问题的迹象，而在美国，公司在向求职者发出录用通知之前，不允许对心理健康问题进行评估或询问。6

Pymetrics says its games are derived from cognitive and neuroscience tests. Because of that, one expert suggested that Pymetrics’ games could uncover signs of mental health issues, something that is not allowed to be assessed or questioned in the United States before a company makes an offer to an applicant.6

APTMetrics 的首席运营官约翰·斯科特 (John Scott) 在第一章中就发现了简历筛选器中所有错误的关键词，他经常被请来检查新技术是否公平合法。他质疑这些人工智能游戏中的一些是否真的衡量了性格特征，还是仅仅衡量了玩家的游戏水平。“吹气球真的能衡量冒险精神吗？”

John Scott, the COO (chief operating officer) of APTMetrics, who found all the wrong keywords in résumé screeners in Chapter 1, is often brought in to check whether new technologies are fair and legal. He questioned whether some of these AI games really measure personality traits or just measure how well someone plays the games. “Is blowing up balloons really a measure of risk-taking?”

所以，也许我在电子游戏中是个疯狂的冒险者，但这能让我成为工作中的冒险者吗？毕竟，工作中除了分数之外还有更重要的事情要做。我越想越觉得，我可能就是这样的：我喜欢在电子游戏中冒险，因为没有什么危害，但在现实生活中，我往往会更加谨慎。

So, maybe I am a crazy risk-taker in a video game, but does that make me a risk-taker in my job when something more is at stake than a score in a game? The longer I think about it, this could be me: I love taking risks in video games because there isn’t any harm, but in real life I tend to be more guarded.

“其次，敢于冒险是这份工作的必要特质吗？”斯科特问道。或许，在一家玩过Pymetrics游戏的公司里，许多成功的会计师比普通人更敢于冒险，但这份工作或许根本不需要冒险。

“And, second, is risk-taking a characteristic necessary for this job?” Scott asked. It may just so happen that many successful accountants at a company that played Pymetrics’ games are risk-takers compared to the general population, but taking risks may not be required for the job at all.

万宝盛华集团 (ManpowerGroup) 的组织心理学家兼首席创新官 Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic 认为，预测分析尽管他将其视为一项突破性技术，但就连他也对Pymetrics的游戏持怀疑态度。他和两位合著者在其著作《招聘的未来》中对Pymetrics这样的公司持有强烈的看法，认为它们大量借鉴了实验心理学、神经科学和其他领域的知识，包括其软件套件中的抽气球游戏。

Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic, the organizational psychologist and chief innovation officer at ManpowerGroup, generally sees predictive analytics as a breakthrough technology, but even he is skeptical about Pymetrics’ games. He and his two coauthors in his book The Future of Recruitment have strong opinions about companies like Pymetrics, which borrow heavily from experimental psychology, neuroscience, and other fields, including the balloon-pumping game in their software suites.

“这些任务并非旨在预测与工作相关的行为，甚至不是为了衡量个体差异，而是为了研究认知过程或群体动态。这意味着，关于它们与工作绩效之间关系的科学证据有限，甚至根本不存在，”作者写道。7 “虽然它们是由心理学家开发用来衡量人类行为的，但除非与特定的工作任务仔细匹配并经过本地验证，否则它们可能不适合预测与招聘相关的现实世界结果。”

“These tasks are not designed to predict work-relevant behaviors or even to measure individual differences but to study cognitive processes or group dynamics. This means that scientific evidence for their relationship to job performance is limited or nonexistent,” the authors wrote.7 “While they are developed by psychologists to measure human behaviors, they might not be suitable to predict the real world outcomes relevant in recruitment unless carefully matched to specific job tasks and locally validated.”

换句话说，Chamorro-Premuzic 和他的合著者表示，这些测试能否预测工作绩效尚不清楚。（Pymetrics 表示，该公司采用了最佳实践来展示其所衡量特质与工作之间的相关性。）

In other words, Chamorro-Premuzic and his coauthors state that it is unknown whether these tests can predict job performance. (Pymetrics said that the company used best practices for showing job relevance of the traits that it measures.)

Pymetrics 分享了一份文件，概述了其游戏的历史和科学解释。我读了一款名为 BART 的爆气球游戏的描述，感觉自己像个傻瓜。在玩的时候，我发现蓝色气球需要更长的时间才能爆破（Pymetrics 认为玩家无法做到这一点），所以我在游戏中积累了更多的钱，而这正是我被要求做的。我猜我的行为听起来像是一个敢于冒险的人，我天真地以为这是件好事——谁不想要一个敢于冒险、推动公司前进的员工呢？

Pymetrics shared a document that outlines the history and a scientific explanation of its games. I read the description of the balloon-popping game called BART and felt like a fool. While playing, I had figured out that the blue balloons took much longer to pop (which Pymetrics thought players would not be able to do), so I was able to amass more money playing the game, which I’d been tasked to do. My behavior came off as being a risk-taker, I assume, which I naively thought was a good thing—who doesn’t want an employee who takes risks and pushes the company forward?

但 Pymetrics 通过电子邮件分享的一份文件（通常要求收件人签署一份保密协议，而我并没有被要求签署）称，在气球游戏中冒险与赌博倾向和职场特立独行有关。“相反，BART 的低风险评分与更保守的行为和更高的权力地位相关。”

But the document Pymetrics shared via email, which normally requires the recipient to sign a nondisclosure agreement which I wasn’t asked to sign, says that taking risks in the balloon game is associated with a tendency toward gambling and workplace maverickism. “Conversely, low-risk scores on the BART have been associated with more conservative behavior and higher positions of power.”

发现蓝色气球比黄色和橙色气球爆裂的时间更长——这跟我的冒险倾向无关——如果我是真正的求职者，这可能会给我带来麻烦。我的游戏结果很可能表明我不适合担任领导职务。

Figuring out that the blue balloons took longer to pop than the yellow and orange ones—which doesn’t say anything about my risk-taking tendencies—could have bit me in the behind if I were a real job applicant. My results in the game would have probably indicated that I was not cut out for a leadership position.

二十多岁的大学毕业生克劳迪娅·普罗斯托夫（Claudia Prostov）对Pymetrics的游戏也不太感冒。她于2020年获得密西西比大学学士学位，并通过Indeed、Glassdoor、LinkedIn和学校的求职网站申请工作。同年晚些时候，普罗斯托夫申请了麦当劳的运营助理职位，并受邀体验Pymetrics的游戏。

Claudia Prostov, a college graduate in her twenties, isn’t so sure about Pymetrics’ games either. She received her BA from the University of Mississippi in 2020 and applied to jobs through Indeed, Glassdoor, LinkedIn, and her school’s career website. Late that year, Prostov applied for an operations associate role at McDonald’s and was invited to play Pymetrics games.

她对评估很感兴趣，所以为了做好准备，她在网上查阅了相关游戏信息。但她在玩的时候感到有些不自在：“我觉得自己做事有点太快了，”她说。“我玩的时候几乎都在过度思考这个游戏的含义。”

She was curious about the assessment, so to prepare herself, she read about the games online. But she felt self-conscious when playing them: “I feel like I did things a little bit too fast,” she said. “I was almost overthinking what the game meant as I was playing it.”

我同意普罗斯托夫的观点。我玩游戏的时候总是感到很不自在，总是琢磨着软件为什么要我做这做那。

I agree with Prostov. I felt self-conscious the whole time I was playing the games, constantly wondering why the software was asking me to do this or that.

Pymetrics 将 Claudia Prostov 最突出的特质认定为专注、慷慨和公平。但她并不这么认为。她觉得自己被误解了——她一直认为决策力和努力才是她最突出的特质。麦当劳通知她，她未能进入公司招聘流程的下一阶段。

Pymetrics identified Claudia Prostov’s strongest traits as focus, generosity, and fairness. But that’s not how she thinks of herself. She feels misrepresented—she believes decision-making and effort are her strongest traits. McDonald’s informed her that she didn’t advance to the next stage in the company’s hiring process.

认知挑战

THE COGNIFY CHALLENGE

Cognify 的游戏套件并不是为了发现申请人的个性，而是为了预测他们的能力。

Cognify’s suite of games is less about finding an applicant’s personality and more about predicting their abilities.

“我们经过多年的研究，比如几十年的研究，发现善于处理信息、学习新知识和解决问题的人往往在工作中表现更出色，”销售 Cognify 游戏套件的 Criteria 公司测评副总裁马修·尼尔 (Matthew Neale) 说道。“这是人与人之间非常容易理解的个体差异。”

“We know from years and years of research, like decades in research, that people who are good at processing information, learning new information, and solving problems tend to do better in the job,” said Matthew Neale, the vice president of assessments at Criteria, which sells Cognify’s suite of games. “This is a really well-understood individual difference between people.”

尼尔和他的团队决定设计一些谜题和游戏来衡量解决问题和处理问题的能力。“我们知道这与工作表现息息相关。所以这降低了整个情况的风险，因为我清楚地知道自己在衡量一个人的哪些方面，”他说。

Neale and his team decided to build puzzles and games to measure problem-solving and processing skills. “We know that it’s related to job performance. And so this de-risks the whole situation because I understand what I’m measuring in someone,” he said.

我玩的第一款游戏是俄罗斯方块，只不过拼图碎片不会以特定的速度飞向我。我会得到一个网格，然后把碎片移进去——这是一个计时练习，旨在测试我的解题能力、视觉和空间能力。这很有趣，也不难，但我总是忘记我正在被计时。感觉我玩得挺慢的。

The first game I play is a version of Tetris, except that the puzzle pieces don’t come at me at a certain speed. I get a grid and have to move the pieces in there—it’s a timed exercise and it’s supposed to measure my problem-solving skills and my visual and spatial abilities. It’s fun and not super hard, but I keep forgetting that I am being timed. It feels like I am pretty slow.

下一局游戏更难。屏幕底部有一个目标数字，气泡里还有数学公式。我必须在气泡消失前找到正确的公式。

The next game is harder. I get a target number at the bottom of the screen and math equations in a bubble. I have to click the right equation before the bubble evaporates.

我一直以为自己很擅长基础数学方程式，因为我高中时辅导过小学生做作业，大学时还在德国做过服务员。在德国，朋友们聚餐时通常会分摊账单，服务员负责算数。但现在游戏里，泡泡层出不穷，我必须快速地把它们打掉。这游戏太难了！每次打不掉一个泡泡，我都会很懊恼，也不知道自己玩得怎么样。也许是因为我很久没玩电子游戏了，所以速度不快吧？

I always thought I was really good at basic math equations because I helped elementary school kids with their homework when I was in high school and I also worked as a waitress in college in Germany. Groups of friends going out in Germany tend to split the bill, leaving the server to do the math. But now in the game, there are tons of bubbles coming up and I have to hit them super fast. This game is hard! I am getting annoyed at myself when I miss a bubble and I’m not sure how good I am at the game. Maybe I am not fast because I haven’t played video games in a while?

我也不确定我是否做过需要即兴解决数学问题的工作。这能向雇主展现出我的能力吗？

I am also not sure if I ever had a job in which I had to solve math problems on the fly. What does that tell an employer about my abilities?

然后我必须阅读几份工作文件，并标记其中的所有错误——这是一项基本的英语练习。虽然英语不是我的母语，但这个游戏出奇地简单，但我肯定需要更多时间才能读完每份文件。

I then have to read a couple of work documents and mark all the mistakes in it—it’s a basic English exercise. Although English isn’t my first language, the game is surprisingly easy, but I definitely need more time to get to the end of each document.

Cognify 团队精心设计了这些游戏，并在人工监督下运行，以便雇主了解某个候选人被选中的原因。Cognify 使用大约 20 个数据变量，团队知道哪些变量可以预测什么。

Cognify’s team chose to highly engineer the games and run them with close human supervision so employers know why a certain candidate is chosen. Cognify uses around twenty variables of data and the team knows which variables predict what.

其他工具会直接利用每一次点击、每一次拖动、每一个时间间隔、每一次鼠标移动——这可能会生成数百甚至数千个数据点。但这也使得理解系统记录了哪些信号以及这些数据点测量的内容变得更加复杂。“当方程中的特征、变量和预测因子较少时，计算起来就会容易得多，”尼尔说道。

Other tools will directly utilize every click, every drag, every time interval, every mouse move—generating potentially hundreds or even thousands of data points. But that makes it more complicated to understand which signals the system records and what these data points are measuring. “It’s an order of magnitude easier when you have fewer features, variables, and predictors in the equation,” Neale said.

如果游戏开发者有数百、数千或数十万个预测器，则不清楚每个预测器与工作之间的关系。

If game developers have hundreds or thousands or hundreds of thousands of predictors, it’s not clear how each predictor is related to a job.

“你失去了说‘嗯，这就是为什么这个人得到这个分数，这个人得到那个分数。这就是那个人在玩游戏时为了获得更高分数所做的事情’的能力，”尼尔说。如果无法充分解释算法的结果，开发人员将很难解释为什么这对特定角色来说是一个好的测试，以及为什么公司应该信任它的结果。

“You lose the ability to say, ‘Well, this is why this person got this score and this person got that score. This is what that person did when they were playing the game to get a better score,’” Neale said. It will be much harder for developers to describe why this is a good test for a particular role and why a company should trust the algorithm’s results if they can’t be adequately explained.

通过仔细梳理数据点，他的团队还发现了一些具有预测性但可能不公平的特征。

By closely combing through the data points, his team also found features that are predictive but possibly unfair.

“在某些情况下，我们会拒绝机器学习算法的建议，”尼尔说。当团队开发一款益智游戏时，计算机了解到，检查时间，也就是求职者开始游戏之前的时间，是一个非常重要的因素。“算法识别出，那些需要更少的检查时间，更快地迈出第一步的人，平均而言比那些花很长时间才迈出第一步的人更善于解决问题。”这看起来像是一个中性的预测因素。

“There are some situations where we will reject the recommendations made by the machine learning algorithms,” Neale said. When the team built a puzzle-based game, the computer learned that the inspection time, the time before a job applicant starts a game, is a really important factor. “What the algorithm identified was that people who need less inspection time, who make the first move faster, are on average better problem solvers than people who take a long time to make that first move.” It looks like a neutral predictor.

如果每个人都有同样的机会坐在安静的地方，不受干扰地快速学习游戏知识，那就更好了。当然，我们的生活要复杂得多。有些人可能需要多花一分钟来阅读或理解游戏说明。而有些人可能家里没有安静的房间。

And that would be true if everyone had the same chance to sit down in a quiet place and quickly learn about the game without interruption. But, of course, our lives are more complicated. Some of us might need another minute to read or understand instructions. Others might not have a quiet room available at home.

“如果你在一个干扰较多的环境中完成评估，你不太可能独自一人，更有可能被人撞见，那么你在最初的检查时间内就更容易被打断。这会损害你的比赛表现，”尼尔说。

“If you are completing the assessment in an environment where there are more disruptions, where you are less likely to be alone, where you are more likely to have people walking in on you, then you can be more easily interrupted in that initial inspection time. And that would harm your performance in the game,” Neale said.

如果人工智能系统仅根据一个预测因素就预测审查时间较短的申请人是更好的问题解决者，那么这是不公平的，因为预测因素很容易因外部因素而发生变化，并且可能无法反映某人的真实能力。

It wouldn’t be fair for an AI system to predict that applicants who have a shorter inspection time are better problem solvers based on just that one predictor, which can easily vary because of outside factors and may not reflect someone’s true abilities.

“在这种求职游戏中，谁更容易被打扰？谁更容易被人撞见？谁更容易被孩子走过来跟他们说‘我需要点东西’？”尼尔问道。当然是母亲。惩罚更容易被打扰的母亲是不公平的。因为可能的干扰而惩罚任何求职者也是不公平的——我们都会不合时宜地接到电话或电子邮件。

“Who is more likely to have an interruption while they are doing this kind of job application game? Who might be more likely to have someone walking in on them? Who might be more likely to have a kid come up to them and say, ‘I need something’?” Neale asked. Mothers, of course. It would not be fair to penalize mothers, who are more likely to be interrupted. It’s also not fair to penalize any applicant based on a possible distraction—we all get phone calls or emails at inopportune times.

“这是人类和专家为这种情况带来的公平公正的体现，而人工智能却对此一无所知，”尼尔说道。“这就是为什么我们决定进行改进和干预。”

“That is an aspect of fairness and equity that the humans and the experts bring to this kind of situation that the AI doesn’t know about,” Neale said. “That is why we decided to tinker up there and intervene.”

该团队决定不将该信号纳入算法中。

The team decided not to include this signal in the algorithm.

但只有研究人员仔细研究人工智能工具如何分析求职者的数据，这种有意识地关闭和打开变量的情况才会发生。

But this kind of conscious turning off and turning on of variables can only happen if researchers closely investigate how the AI tool analyzes job applicants’ data.

对于马修·尼尔 (Matthew Neale) 来说，这就是游戏设计师（通常拥有数据科学背景）和心理学背景人士之间的区别。数据科学家通常只想获取越来越多的数据，包括来自简历、社交媒体资料和人工智能游戏的数据，以便预测他们想要的结果。心理学家马修·尼尔 (Matthew Neale) 则持有不同的看法：“我们的领域更多的是‘我们应该关注哪些信息？’我们如何设计这些应用体验才能获得正确的数据？然后，我们确实可以引入数据科学家来分析这些信息。但如果你不关注或控制你输入算法的数据，那么你将面临高风险。”他说道。

For Matthew Neale, this is the difference between game designers, who often come from a data science background, and folks who have a psychology background. Data scientists, more often than not, just want more and more data, including data from résumés, social media profiles, and AI games to predict the outcome they are after. Matthew Neale is a psychologist and has a different approach: “Our domain is more ‘what information should we be looking at?’ How do we design these application experiences to get the right data? And then indeed we can bring in the data scientists to analyze that information. But if you are not paying any attention to or exercising control over the data that you’re feeding into the algorithm, then you are in a situation where there’s high risk,” he said.

这就是为什么他和 Criteria 只使用与职位相关的数据。团队有意识地决定，如果数据与职位缺乏关联，就不会使用任何现成的数据，例如社交媒体信息。

That’s why he and Criteria are using only data related to the job. The team made a conscious decision not to use just any data that is readily available, like social media feeds, if it lacks connection to the position.

“你最终得到的数据质量低劣，可靠性也较低。这会让你面临做出最终不合法的雇佣决策的风险，”尼尔说。“你从这里获得的预测水平，也就是服务提供商所说的信号水平，通常非常低。”

“You’re ending up with data that is poor quality and is less reliable. It puts you at risk of making employment decisions that, at the end of the day, are not legal,” Neale said. “The levels of prediction that you’re getting from here, the levels of signal that the providers are talking about, are often really low.”

这也引发了同意的问题，因为大多数人还没有同意让他们的推特信息被用于招聘决策。

It also raises the issue of consent, because most people haven’t agreed to let their Twitter feed be used in hiring decisions.

海军退役程序员索菲在找到工作之前，曾投递了146份软件开发员职位申请。她也接触过基于人工智能的游戏。她甚至在YouTube上练习过这些游戏，那里有一大批视频制作者，致力于帮助人们在求职评估中取得成功。

Sophie, the navy veteran and coder who sent out 146 applications for software developer positions until she found a job, also encountered AI-based games. She even practiced for them on YouTube, where a whole brigade of how-to video makers is trying to help people succeed in job assessments.

索菲申请了 IBM 的职位，需要参加 Cognify 评估，但她觉得这与她申请的职位无关。我给马修·尼尔播放了我面试索菲的录音，他对 Cognify 游戏套件非常了解。索菲说：“对我来说，作为一名退伍军人，参加考试和测验或者承受压力对我来说不算什么。但我不知道为什么认知测试会让我焦虑，我想是因为我知道它与软件工程无关——这才是真正让我焦虑的原因。”她实际上已经在线练习过，但觉得自己比其他人慢，所以在被拒绝时将此铭记在心。索菲说：“任何让我参加 Cognify 测试的工作——我都会自动拒绝。”

Sophie applied to IBM and had to do a Cognify assessment that she felt was not relevant to the job she was applying for. I played the recording of my interview with Sophie for Matthew Neale, who knows a lot of about the Cognify game suite. “For me, being a military veteran, being able to take tests and quizzes or being under pressure is nothing for me,” Sophie said. “But I don’t know why the cognitive tests gave me anxiety, but I think it’s because I knew that it had nothing to do with software engineering—that’s what really got me.” She had actually practiced online but felt she was slower than others and took it to heart when she was rejected. “Any job that gives me a Cognify test—I’m automatically just going to say no,” Sophie said.

马修尼尔承认：“如果有人在我们的评估中获得不好的体验，那显然总是令人失望的，尤其是我们投入了大量精力为考生打造的这项评估。”

“It’s obviously always disappointing when someone doesn’t have a positive experience playing one of our assessments, particularly one that we’ve put so much effort into building to be an engaging experience for candidates,” Matthew Neale acknowledged.

“Cognify 的初衷是考察人们学习、处理信息和解决问题的能力。我认为这些技能与软件设计息息相关，”他说，“这就是我在评估和职位之间建立的联系。”

“The intention behind Cognify is to look at people’s ability to learn, to process information, to solve problems. I suppose that these kinds of skills are relevant in software design,” he said. “That’s the connection that I would draw between the assessment and the role.”

此外，尼尔表示，IBM 已尽职尽责。该公司对其软件开发人员进行了 Cognify 测试，发现高绩效软件开发人员的评估得分高于其他开发人员。IBM 还确保评估不会歧视不同群体的申请人。

In addition, Neale said that IBM did its due diligence. The corporation tested Cognify on its software developers and found that high-performing software developers scored higher on the assessment than others. IBM also made sure the assessment was not discriminating against different groups of applicants.

对索菲来说，Cognify 不仅仅是又一次“愚蠢”的评估（用她的话来说）。这次评估让她心烦意乱。“当时我甚至想放弃，心想，‘好吧，也许这个行业不适合我，或者我就是太笨了。’然后我就真的开始自责了，”她说。她非常沮丧，好几个星期都没找工作。

For Sophie, Cognify wasn’t just another assessment that was “dumb,” in her words. This one messed with her head. “At that moment in time, I wanted to give up and I was like, ‘All right, maybe this industry isn’t for me or maybe I’m just dumb.’ And then I was just really beating myself up,” she said. She was so down, she didn’t apply for jobs for a few weeks.

直到一位以前的学生找到工作，索菲才从低谷中走出来。索菲一直在教这位学生，所以她告诉自己不能当个冒名顶替者。她再次开始求职，最终找到了一份软件开发人员的职位。

Sophie came out of the funk only when a former student found a job. Sophie had been teaching this student, so she told herself that she couldn’t be an imposter. She started applying again and eventually landed a role as a software developer.

游戏无法做到的事情

WHAT GAMES CANNOT DO

马丁·伯奇（Martin Burch）在申请彭博社职位时参加了Plum测试，他也经历过类似的沮丧。他多年来一直在为工作抓取网站数据，所以他想知道，如果自己还能在彭博社继续抓取网站数据，为什么还要填写形状序列呢？如果他不擅长形状排序，那么既然他已经成功地完成了工作的基本工作，这些游戏又有什么意义呢？

Martin Burch, who took the Plum assessment as part of his application to Bloomberg, had a similar demoralizing experience. He had been scraping websites for years for his job, so he wondered why he had to fill in a sequence of shapes if he would still be scraping websites for the job at Bloomberg. And if he wasn’t very good at shape sequencing, why did the games matter when he was already successfully doing essential functions of the job?

“这类测试试图衡量认知能力，”莱斯大学工作心理学教授弗雷德·奥斯瓦尔德告诉我。这些测试可能与工作表现相关，但它应该取代以往的工作经验吗？“如果一个人申请的工作与他们过去做过的工作类似，那么除了简历中展示的内容之外，这又如何衡量推理能力呢？”推理测试能否比以往经验更准确地预测一个人的推理能力，这一点值得怀疑。

“These types of measures are trying to measure cognitive ability,” work psychology professor Fred Oswald at Rice University told me. The tests could be related to job performance, but should it just override previous job experience? “If the job that a person is applying for is similar to what they’ve done in the past, how does this measure reasoning at above and beyond what’s evidenced in the résumé?” It is doubtful that a reasoning test is a better prediction than previous experience.

AI游戏公司的高管们强调了其招聘工具所依赖的科学的重要性。Plum的首席执行官也对竞争对手进行了抨击。“这是真正的科学，”凯特琳·麦格雷戈谈到她公司的工具时说道。“我们击败了那些游戏化类型的评估公司，是因为我们科学的准确性。”

AI games executives emphasized the importance of the science underpinning their hiring tools. Plum’s CEO also took a jab at her competitors. “This is real science,” Caitlin MacGregor said about her company’s tool. “We beat out the gamification-type assessment companies because of the accuracy of our science.”

她说，客户的体验也证明了 Plum 在实践中是有效的。她知道其他人工智能工具都是建立在劣质科学之上的：“我们非常担心我们行业里的‘蛇油’或伪科学。”

She said that her customers’ experiences also provide evidence that Plum works in practice. She knows that other AI tools are built on shoddy science: “We get very worried about the snake oil or the bad science in our industry.”

MacGregor 向我分享了 Plum 的技术手册，其中包含超过 90 页的资料，详细记录了他们的算法是如何测试的，以及她的团队是如何确保算法有效的。（其他公司拒绝与我分享他们的技术报告，而这些报告本应阐述这些测试是如何验证的，在我看来，这些报告应该放在每家公司的网站上。）

MacGregor shared Plum’s technical manual with me, which includes more than ninety pages of how their algorithm was tested and how her team made sure it worked. (The other companies declined to share their technical reports with me, which are supposed to lay out how these tests were validated and which, in my opinion, should be featured on every company’s website.)

曾专攻人工智能和招聘的就业律师马修·谢勒（Matthew Scherer）阅读了这份技术报告。作为律师，他研究了许多来自人工智能供应商的技术和验证报告，以评估其声明的准确性，并帮助雇主公司决定他们想要使用哪些具体工具。

Matthew Scherer, a former employment lawyer specializing in artificial intelligence and hiring, read the technical report. As part of his job as a lawyer, he studied many technical and validation reports from AI vendors to assess the accuracy of their claims and help employer companies decide which specific tools they wanted to use.

他对 Plum 的报告印象不深：“整份报告读起来就像是长达九十页的努力，目的是转移读者的注意力，让他们忽略一个事实：第一，Plum 并没有衡量候选人履行任何特定工作职能的能力；第二，它所衡量的东西并不能完全预测候选人是否能表现出良好的工作表现。”

He was not too impressed with Plum’s report: “The entire report reads like a ninety-page effort to distract readers from the fact that, one, Plum does not measure candidates’ ability to perform the functions of any specific job, and two, the things it does measure are not all that predictive of good job performance.”

Scherer 核对了报告中 Plum 的统计数据。相比随机数生成器，Plum 的测试对工作绩效的预测准确率如何？根据 Scherer 的计算，“Plum 的 Talent Match 分数比随机为每个候选人提供 Talent Match 分数，能多提供 1.7% 到 18.5% 的候选人工作能力信息。”

Scherer checked Plum’s statistics in the report. How well do its tests predict job performance versus a random number generator? According to Scherer’s math, “Plum’s Talent Match scores tell you anywhere from 1.7 percent to 18.5 percent more about a candidate’s ability to perform the job than you would get by giving random Talent Match scores to each candidate.”

这意味着，在最佳情况下，Plum 的评估结果能解释求职者 18.5% 的工作表现。在最佳情况下，求职者 81.5% 的工作表现评分无法通过 Plum Talent Match 得分来解释。在最坏情况下，Plum 的评估结果只能预测求职者 1.7% 的工作表现，而求职者 98.3% 的工作表现无法通过 Plum 的评估结果来解释。我想，总比没有好。（Plum 表示，他们的预测准确率为 0.36）有效性指数，该公司表示，该指数更准确地代表了评估。

That means, in a best-case scenario, Plum’s assessments account for 18.5 percent of someone’s job performance. In the best-case scenario, 81.5 percent of an applicant’s job performance rating cannot be explained by the Plum Talent Match score. In the worst case, Plum’s assessments predict 1.7 percent of someone’s job performance, and 98.3 percent of a candidate’s job performance cannot be explained by Plum’s assessments. I guess it’s better than nothing. (Plum said that they have a .36 predictive validity index, which, the company stated, is a more accurate representation of the assessment.)

对莱斯大学的弗雷德·奥斯瓦尔德来说，这些数字一点也不令人失望：“这些数字相当平均。” 他提醒说，没有哪个测试能够100%覆盖候选人的工作表现。但他的问题是，这些测试是否真的与工作表现相关。

To Fred Oswald of Rice University, these numbers are not disappointing at all: “These numbers are pretty average.” He cautions that no one has a test that can cover 100 percent of a candidate’s job performance. But the question for him is if the tests are actually relevant and related to job performance.

马修·谢勒认为，AI游戏过于抽象，并非适用于所有工作：“报告中的信息并未表明，这是一种评估候选人执行大多数测试工作能力的特别有效的方法。这并不奇怪，因为它只衡量非常抽象/通用的特征——与任何特定工作的职责相去甚远。”

Matthew Scherer believes the AI games are too abstract to be relevant for every job: “The information in the report does not suggest that this is an especially effective method of assessing candidates’ ability to perform most of the jobs for which it was tested. That’s not surprising, because it only measures very abstract/generic characteristics—far removed from the duties of any particular job.”

这就是很多游戏的症结所在。它们衡量的不是一个人能否出色地完成工作的核心职责，而是试图评估一个人的性格是否适合这份工作。

That’s the crux of a lot of games. They don’t measure how well someone will perform the core duties of a job; instead, they attempt to assess whether someone has the right personality for a job.

对于求职者来说，这些AI游戏的具体内容往往比较模糊，因此，一个致力于帮助求职者的行业应运而生。人们可以在线观看和体验气球游戏，为面试做准备，还可以观看无数视频，了解其他用于招聘或寻找内部候选人的AI游戏。

For applicants, it’s often nebulous what these AI games entail, so in response, there is a whole industry out there trying to help job seekers. Folks can watch and play the balloon game online in preparation for their assessment games and watch countless videos of people explaining other AI games used for hiring or finding internal candidates.

遗憾的是，许多此类工具都是根据成功员工的游戏成绩进行校准的，因此没有任何教程能够预测AI正在寻找什么。有些游戏有计时限制，因此应聘者应确保自己没有分心，并且睡眠充足。

Unfortunately, many of these tools are calibrated to successful workers’ results on the games, so no tutorial can anticipate what the AI is looking for. Some games are timed, so candidates should ensure they are not distracted and have slept well.

即使是专家，包括就业律师，有时也会参与评估人工智能工具，但他们也并不总是了解这些工具在评估什么。如果该工具（无意中）歧视并对任何群体造成不利影响，公司可能会陷入困境。

Even experts, including employment lawyers, who are sometimes brought into the process to evaluate AI tools, don’t always know what these tools are evaluating. Companies may get in trouble if the tool (unintentionally) discriminates and causes adverse impact on any group.

纳撒尼尔·格拉瑟 (Nathaniel Glasser) 是爱泼斯坦·贝克尔和格林律师事务所 (Epstein Becker & Green) 驻华盛顿特区的劳动法律师。他和同事亚当·福尔曼 (Adam Forman) 受聘为那些在购买人工智能工具前进行尽职调查的雇主检查人工智能工具。“我们经常看到的是，虽然并非总是如此，但在较新的组织中，一些初创的供应商往往不够成熟，他们对涵盖该工具使用的法律框架缺乏全面的了解，”格拉瑟说道。

Nathaniel Glasser is an employment lawyer with Epstein Becker & Green, based in Washington, DC. He and his colleague Adam Forman have been hired to check out AI tools for employers that are doing their due diligence before buying an AI tool. “What we have seen is often, not always, but often, in newer organizations, some of the start-up vendors are less sophisticated and they don’t have the total understanding of the legal framework that’s going to cover the use of the tool,” Glasser said.

他回忆起几年前的一次特殊情况，当时他和同事被请去评估一家人工智能游戏供应商，该游戏评估的是风险承担能力、信任度等特质。在公司放心使用该工具进行招聘决策之前，尽职调查的一部分工作是进行试点测试。结果并非公司所愿：“在正式上线前经过多轮测试后，该工具显示出对女性求职者不利的影响，无论对输入内容、特质以及算法本身进行何种调整，他们都无法确信它不会继续产生这种不利影响。”格拉瑟回忆道。

He recalled a specific situation a few years back when he and his colleague were brought in to evaluate a vendor of AI games that assessed risk-taking and trust, among other traits. Part of the due diligence was a pilot test before the company felt comfortable using the tool to make hiring decisions. The outcome wasn’t what the company had hoped for: “After multiple rounds in beta prior to going live, the tool demonstrated adverse impact against the female applicants, and no matter the tweaks to the inputs and the traits and the algorithm itself, they couldn’t get confident that it wouldn’t continue to create this adverse impact,” Glasser recounted.

女性通过该工具测试的比例与男性不同，而且这种差异与工作无关。

Women didn’t pass the tool at similar rates compared to men, and the difference had nothing to do with the job.

如果评估中男性和女性或不同种族之间分数的统计差异与工作技能或要求有关，这种“无意歧视”可能是合法的。例如，对于消防工作，申请人可能需要携带200磅或更重的设备，主管可能会认为这对工作至关重要。这样的测试可能会将更多的女性排除在外。但如果这种差异是出于工作相关的业务需要，例如消防员需要携带重型设备，公司可能可以合法地使用这种测试（尽管人们可以并且已经对这类评估提出了质疑）。但格拉瑟和福尔曼并不认为这种推理适用于他们的客户。

If the statistical differences between the scores of men and women or of different races in an assessment is related to the skills or requirements of the job, this type of “inadvertent discrimination” may be legal. For example, for firefighting jobs, applicants might have to carry two hundred pounds or more of equipment, which a supervisor might argue is essential to the job. A test like that may exclude more women than men. But if this difference is in a job-related business necessity, like carrying heavy equipment for firefighters, a company may legally be able to use that kind of test (although people could challenge and have challenged these kinds of assessments in court). But Glasser and Forman didn’t think that reasoning applied to their client.

“即使这种差异是由于男女之间的性格差异造成的，我们也不确定这对于这份工作来说是否必要。因此，我们将寻找一种歧视性较小的替代方案，可能采用一种完全不同的选拔方法，”格拉瑟说。法律风险太高了。

“We don’t know for sure that, even if the difference is attributable to some personality difference between men and women, that is necessary for this particular job. And so we are going to look for a less discriminatory alternative that might be using a completely different method of selection,” Glasser said. The legal risks were too high.

他们的客户决定不与这家AI游戏供应商合作，而是找到了其他评估方法。格拉瑟回忆说，这家供应商当时还是一家初创公司，但之后发展壮大，业绩也相当不错。他希望这家供应商能从这些测试中吸取教训。

Their client decided not to work with this AI games vendor and found another assessment to use. The vendor, Glasser recalled, was a start-up at the time and since then has grown and done quite well. He hopes it learned from these tests.

2021 年 12 月，德克萨斯州莱斯大学的工业组织心理学家团队（其中包括弗雷德·奥斯瓦尔德）和人力资源研究组织 (HumRRO) 发表了一篇论文，指出尽管该团队在构建和评估评估工具方面拥有数十年的经验，但他们为测试招聘中最具预测性的性格特征——尽责性而构建的人工智能游戏并不能可靠地预测它。8

A team of industrial-organizational psychologists at Rice University, Texas, which included Fred Oswald, and the Human Resources Research Organization (HumRRO) published a paper in December 2021 showing that the AI games they built to test for the most predictive personality trait in hiring, conscientiousness, didn’t reliably predict it, despite the team’s decades-long experience building and evaluating assessment tools.8

组织心理学家、行业播客Science 4-Hire主持人查尔斯·汉德勒 (Charles Handler)表示，他的客户中至少有五人尝试过 Pymetrics，但后来放弃了该工具，因为他们没有得到他们所希望的结果。

Charles Handler, the organizational psychologist and host of the industry podcast Science 4-Hire, said that at least five of his clients tried Pymetrics and then abandoned the tool because they didn’t get the results they had hoped for.

沃尔玛前组织绩效高级总监、查尔斯·汉德勒（Charles Handler）人力资源播客的嘉宾戴维·富特雷尔（David Futrell）在沃尔玛工作时，也曾有过类似的AI游戏体验。“毫无疑问，我们运营着地球上迄今为止规模最大的选拔和评估机器。我们每天测试一万到一万五千人，”富特雷尔说。“每年加起来，测试人数超过四百万。而且，这还只是沃尔玛的入门级员工。”

David Futrell, former senior director of organizational performance at Walmart and a guest on Charles Handler’s HR podcast, had a similar experience with AI games when he was still working at the retailer. “There’s no doubt that what we run is the biggest selection and assessment machine that’s ever existed on the planet. We test, every day, between ten and fifteen thousand people,” Futrell said. “That adds up to somewhere north of four million every year. And it’s just entry-level hires for the store.”

他的团队掌握了海量数据，并开展了许多研究来测试新技术。“当这台机器“当学习理念首次出现时，我非常兴奋，因为在我看来，它似乎能解决我们在预测方面遇到的所有问题。所以我们投入了大量精力，尝试使用这些基于机器的算法来构建预测器。”

His team has access to an incredible amount of data and has conducted many studies to test out new technologies. “When this machine learning idea first came out, I was very excited by it because it seemed to me like it would solve all of the problems that we had with prediction. And so we really got into it and did a lot of work trying to build predictors using these machine-based algorithms.”

几年前，沃尔玛收购了一家使用人工智能游戏供应商的在线零售商。Futrell 和他的团队试用了这款软件。“你会做一些看起来与工作毫无关系的任务。但它们据称可以衡量一些潜在的性格特征，比如你愿意承担风险的程度，”他说。他个人觉得这些游戏很有吸引力，但结果并不乐观。“我们发现它效果不太好。”

A few years back, Walmart acquired an online retailer that was using an AI games vendor. Futrell and his team took the software for a spin. “You would do these tasks that didn’t look work-related at all. But they were purported to measure some underlying aspects of personality, like your willingness to take risks,” he said. He personally found the games very engaging, but the results weren’t promising. “We found that it just didn’t work well.”

事实上，AI游戏与工作绩效之间存在轻微的负相关性。换句话说，这些游戏似乎根本不起作用。

In fact, the AI games were slightly negatively correlated with job performance, if anything. In other words, the games didn’t seem to work at all.

牺牲合格的候选人

SACRIFICING QUALIFIED CANDIDATES

马丁·伯奇想知道自己在普拉姆测试中到底做错了什么，以至于被自动拒绝：“我这方面哪些方面没达到标准？是因为我脑子里旋转图形的能力，以及完成测试中智商评估部分的能力？还是因为我的性格或情感问题？”

Martin Burch wondered what he did so wrong in the Plum assessment that he was automatically rejected: “What thresholds have I failed to meet here? Is it about my ability to rotate shapes in my head and complete the IQ intelligence assessment portion of the test? Or is it something to do with these personality or emotion questions?”

在伯奇收到的Plum发来的邮件中，他没有得到任何具体的答复。该公司告诉他，招聘决策权不在于他们：“Plum不进行自动化决策……雇主可能会选择将候选人的Plum信息与其他几个数据点（简历、求职信、其他评估、面试等）一起纳入招聘和选拔流程的决策中。”

In the email Burch received from Plum, he didn’t get any concrete answers. The company told him that it was not the one making hiring decisions: “Plum does not perform automated decision-making…. The employer may choose to consider the candidate’s Plum information along with several other data points (résumé, cover letter, other assessments, interviews, etc.) as part of their decision-making within the recruitment and selection process.”

这似乎是个好主意。如果一家公司考虑游戏化性格测试、候选人的简历、求职信、面试和其他评估来做出决定，这似乎是一种合理的方法。

That seems like a good idea. If a company takes into account gamified personality tests, a candidate’s résumé, cover letter, interview, and other assessments to make a decision, that seems like a reasonable approach.

然而，彭博招聘人员索菲·沃利斯（Sophie Wallis）明确表示，由于马丁·伯奇（Martin Burch）未通过普拉姆（Plum）评估，因此不再考虑担任该职位。她没有提到在发出拒绝信之前，有人同时评估了伯奇的简历和求职信。对马丁·伯奇来说，这强烈暗示他被拒绝仅仅是因为普拉姆分数。（普拉姆确实允许雇主使用分数线，即自动拒绝得分低于一定门槛的申请人。）

Except the Bloomberg recruiter Sophie Wallis had explicitly stated that because Martin Burch didn’t pass the Plum assessment, he was no longer considered for this job. She did not mention that someone had also assessed Burch’s résumé and cover letter at the same time before sending the rejection. To Martin Burch, this strongly suggested that he was rejected based on the Plum score alone. (And Plum does allow employers to use cut scores, which automatically reject applicants that scored below a certain threshold.)

我曾与其他使用 Pymetrics 和其他 AI 游戏化测评的招聘公司交流过，他们都表示，他们使用 AI 游戏作为筛选：在流程的这个阶段，游戏结果是筛选候选人、让其他候选人进入下一轮的唯一依据，而不是 Plum 在邮件中列出的更复杂的流程。从不同维度评估候选人需要花费大量时间，因此公司通常不会这样做。

I have talked to other hiring companies that use Pymetrics and other AI-gamified assessments and all of them shared that they use the AI games as a screen: at that stage in the process, the game results are the sole reason why candidates are cut and others are moved to the next round of hiring, not the more elaborate process Plum laid out in the email. It takes a lot of time to assess candidates on different dimensions, so companies often don’t do it.

使用人工智能游戏作为筛选机制让马丁·伯奇感到难以接受。他不仅接受了彭博社的拒绝，还想进一步了解该公司的决策流程，尤其是在查阅了欧盟的《通用数据保护条例》（GDPR）之后，该条例规定个人“有权不受仅基于自动化处理的决策的约束”。9他认为自己的权利受到了侵犯，正如索菲·沃利斯（Sophie Wallis）在邮件中指出的那样，他因为Plum的自动评估而被彭博社从申请人名单中剔除。

Using AI games as a screening mechanism didn’t sit right with Martin Burch. Instead of just accepting Bloomberg’s rejection, he wanted to know more about the company’s decision-making process, especially after he checked the European Union’s GDPR (General Data Protection Regulation) laws, which state that individuals “shall have the right not to be subject to a decision based solely on automated processing.”9 He believed that his rights had been violated, as indicated by Sophie Wallis’s email stating that he was cut from Bloomberg’s applicant pool based on Plum’s automated assessment.

法律明确规定，如果数据主体知情同意，可以使用自动决策。伯奇不记得自己曾明确同意彭博社的做法。

The law clarifies that automated decision-making can be used if data subjects give informed consent. Burch didn’t recall giving explicit consent to Bloomberg.

他决定在伦敦聘请一位劳动法律师。他还联系了彭博社，要求其提供隐私声明以及根据《通用数据保护条例》(GDPR) 处理他的数据。经过一番沟通，伯奇认为彭博社没有回答他所有的问题，于是他和律师向英国数据管理机构——信息专员办公室 (ICO) 提交了投诉。ICO 支持伯奇的观点，并告诉彭博社：“通过审查所提供的信息，我们认为你们还有更多工作要做。因此，我们现在希望你们采取措施解决与该个人相关的任何未解决的问题。”

He decided to hire an employment lawyer in London. He also reached out to Bloomberg asking for its privacy notice and his data under the GDPR. There was some back-and-forth, but Burch felt that Bloomberg didn’t answer all his questions, so he and his lawyer filed a complaint with the UK data governing body, the Information Commissioner’s Office (ICO). The ICO sided with Burch, telling Bloomberg: “From reviewing the information provided, it is our decision that there is more work for you to do. As such, we now expect you to take steps to address any outstanding issues with the individual.”

2021年3月15日，在ICO介入纠纷后，伯奇和他的律师收到了彭博社的回复，其中描述了彭博社如何在招聘过程中使用评估方法，并明确指出：“根据英国GDPR第22(1)条的定义，此初步选拔决定是自动的。” 就是这样。

On March 15, 2021, after ICO’s intervention in the dispute, Burch and his lawyer received a reply from Bloomberg that described how it uses assessments in the hiring process and stating unequivocally: “This initial selection decision is automatic, as defined under Article 22(1) of the U.K. GDPR.” There it was.

对大多数人来说，这或许只是一句普通的官僚术语，但这却是一个令人难以置信的发现。我报道招聘领域人工智能应用已有五年多，供应商和用人单位都曾无数次告诉我，他们的人工智能工具并不能自动做出招聘决策。我被告知，招聘决策背后有人工审核，而且没有人被“机器人”直接拒绝。这种说法总让人感觉不对劲，尤其是考虑到供应商声称他们的工具在招聘过程中节省了时间和金钱，而自动化拒绝似乎正是企业想要使用人工智能的原因。

It’s something that probably reads like a normal sentence of bureaucratic jargon to most people, but this is an incredible revelation. I have covered artificial intelligence used in hiring for over five years and I don’t know how many times vendors and employer companies have told me that their AI tools do not make automatic hiring decisions. I was told that there is a human in the loop to review the decisions and that no one is being rejected outright by “robots.” This argument always felt off, especially because vendors argue that their tools save time and money in the hiring process, and automating rejections seems like exactly why companies want to use AI.

但在伯奇的案例中，彭博社承认了这一点：该算法决定了谁在数据分析师职位上被拒绝以及谁能进入下一轮。

But in Burch’s case, Bloomberg admitted it: this algorithm decided who got rejected for a data analyst job and who advanced to the next round.

“很高兴看到这样的书面形式，”伯奇说。

“It’s good to see that in writing,” Burch said.

他很高兴，未来申请彭博的求职者现在会知道，他们基于游戏的评估结果将被用来自动拒绝他们，或将他们纳入下一轮招聘。此外，伯奇希望彭博的招聘经理能够意识到，使用这种评估方法是一个错误。他试图向他们证明，普拉姆评估方法正在淘汰包括他自己在内的优秀候选人。

He is glad that future job seekers who apply to Bloomberg will now learn that their game-based assessment will be used to automatically reject them or move them into the next round of hiring. In addition, Burch hopes that hiring managers at Bloomberg will realize that this particular assessment is a mistake to use. He is trying to prove to them that the Plum assessment is weeding out good candidates, including himself.

如果彭博坚持继续与普拉姆合作，马丁·伯奇也无能为力。但他很高兴自己向彭博证明了自动决策或许并不能节省太多时间：他估计，他的调查肯定耗费了彭博员工大量的精力。他希望其他申请人也能效仿他的做法，要求提供类似的信息。“他们从这个自动化流程中节省的成本、时间，或者其他任何节省，都被他们必须审核每一份申诉的事实抵消了，”伯奇说。

If Bloomberg insists on continuing to work with Plum, Martin Burch can’t do anything about it. But he is glad he showed Bloomberg that automatic decision-making may not save that much time: he figures that his inquiry must have cost Bloomberg’s staff a lot of work. He is hoping other applicants will follow his lead and demand similar information. “The cost savings or the time savings or whatever savings they’re getting out of this automated process, then it’s kind of negated by the fact that they would have to review every one of those appeals,” Burch said.

他也很高兴布隆伯格在另一件事上听从了他的律师。布隆伯格向马丁·伯奇提供了8000英镑（约合9700美元）的赔偿。“他们同意全额支付这笔款项，这显然是承认了他们的不当行为，”马丁·伯奇在伦敦金斯利·纳普利律师事务所的律师乔治亚·罗伯茨写道。

He was also happy about Bloomberg following his lawyer’s lead on another matter. Bloomberg offered Martin Burch 8,000 pounds (about $9,700): “Their agreement to pay the sum in full is a clear admittance of wrongdoing,” wrote Georgia Roberts, Martin Burch’s lawyer at Kingsley Napley in London.

（彭博社没有回应多次置评请求。）

(Bloomberg didn’t answer multiple requests to comment.)

推断性格特征的人工智能游戏可能效果不佳，预测价值也较低。例如，一篇文献综述得出的结论是，性格与约 5% 的工作绩效相关。10这意味着，我们约 95% 的工作绩效与性格无关，因此，性格可能并非评估某人是否适合某项工作的最佳标准。

AI games inferring personality traits may not work well and have low predictive value. A review of the literature, for example, concluded that personality is correlated with about 5 percent of job performance.10 This means that about 95 percent of our work performance has nothing to do with our personality, so personality might not be a great way to assess if someone is the right person for a job.

但还有另一种常见的评估策略我们尚未探索。

But there is another common assessment strategy we have yet to explore.

第四章

CHAPTER 4

你說什麼？

You Said What?

面部表情和语调分析

On Facial Expression and Tone-of-Voice Analysis

我我坐在家里的办公桌前，准备参加一场“工作面试”。这次面试和普通的Zoom面试略有不同——面试现场不会有人。我精心打扮，化着妆，不是为了任何人，或者更准确地说，是为了笔记本电脑上摄像头的绿色指示灯。

I am sitting at my desk at home, getting ready for a “job interview.” This one is a bit different from a regular one via Zoom—there will be no humans on the other side. I am getting dressed up and putting on makeup for no one, or maybe more accurately, for the green camera light on my laptop.

在这次由人工智能评分的面试中，我将在电脑上收到问题，并有几分钟时间回答问题并录制自己的视频。这种单向视频面试在招聘中非常普遍。数百万人已经参加过这种面试，世界上一些最大的公司也在使用。1

In this job interview, which will be scored by AI, I will receive questions on my computer and have a few minutes to answer them and record myself. These types of one-way video interviews are widespread in hiring. Millions of people have done them, and they’re used by some of the largest companies in the world.1

我最头疼的就是找个合适的时间开始采访。我可以随时开始，但应该什么时候开始呢？我早上比较清醒吗？喝完咖啡后？午饭前？我应该现在开始，还是……再等五分钟？谁知道呢？感觉怪怪的。星期一两点？我决定就这么办。

The first thing I struggle with is finding a good time to start the interview. I could do it whenever, but when should I? Am I more alert in the morning? After coffee? Before lunch? Should I start now or maybe give it another five minutes? Who knows? The whole thing feels weird. At two o’clock on Monday? I decide to just go for it.

我点击了Retorio（开发此工具的供应商）发来的链接。第一个窗口打开了：“对我们来说，您不仅仅是一份简历，我们希望了解更多关于您的信息。” 听起来不错！

I follow the link I have received from Retorio, the vendor that built this tool. The first window opens: “For us you are more than a CV and we would like to know more about you.” Sounds good!

然后系统会要求我将图像置于屏幕中央，并避开背景中的任何灯光。检查一下。

Then I am being asked to center my image on the screen and avoid any lights in the back. Check.

第一个问题是：“在工作中的社交场合，你觉得自己扮演什么角色？”然后软件告诉我“做你自己——这不是考试。”我有几分钟时间准备，然后有一分钟时间回答问题。

First question: “In social situations at work, what role do you find yourself in?” The software then tells me to “be yourself—it’s not a test.” I get a few minutes to prepare and then I have a minute to answer the question.

我想了一会儿，深吸一口气，尽量让自己听起来乐观、充满活力，这很奇怪，因为这里没有人，但我希望人工智能能够预测我是一个积极的人。

I think for a second, take a deep breath, and try to sound as upbeat and full of energy as I can, which is weird, since no one is here, but I want the AI to predict that I am a positive person.

“所以，在工作社交场合，我总是乐于与人聊天、建立联系。你知道，这能营造出一种真正良好的工作氛围……”

“So, in social situations at work, I think I’m always interested in chatting with folks and connecting with them. And, you know, just creating a really good climate at work …”

自言自语的感觉真是怪怪的。当然，我比传统的求职面试要轻松得多，在传统的面试中，我会和招聘人员或招聘经理面对面交流，或者至少通过视频会议。我感觉自己像是在对着虚空说话，完全不知道自己该如何表达。

It’s more than a little weird talking to myself. Granted, I am less nervous than in a traditional job interview, where I would meet with recruiters and hiring managers in person or at least via video conference. I feel like I am speaking into a void and have no idea how I am coming off.

他们让我选择看我回答问题的视频。这才是最痛苦的部分。看到我努力让自己显得聪明、精力充沛、容易相处、容易被录用，真是令人尴尬。回想起来，我希望自己能用不同的方式回答一些问题。我是不是应该避免谈论我有多喜欢工作中的社交环节？也许他们会觉得我太爱社交，不够努力？

I’m offered the option to watch the video of myself answering the question. And that is the most painful part. It’s cringeworthy to see myself trying to sound smart and energetic and relatable and hireable. In retrospect, I wish I would have answered some questions in a different way. Should I have avoided talking about how I love the social aspect of work? Maybe they think I am too social and don’t work hard enough?

我感觉自己有点紧张，这很奇怪。自从2018年在一次会议上第一次接触到基于人工智能的技术以来，我就一直想做这件事。在一次在关于人工智能在招聘中的应用的演示中，HireVue 的代表声称，通过分析候选人在面试过程中的面部表情、语气和用词，可以揭示候选人是否适合该职位。这听起来很神奇。最终，人工智能工具可以确保我们只聘用有能力的人，因为我们可以洞察他们内心深处的想法和行为。

It’s weird how nervous I am. I have wanted to do this since I first encountered AI-based technology at a conference in 2018. During a presentation on AI used in hiring, the HireVue representative claimed that an analysis of facial expressions, tone of voice, and the words candidates use during interviews reveals whether a candidate is suitable for a given job. It sounded like magic. Finally, an AI tool could make sure we only hired competent people, because we could tap into their innermost thoughts and behaviors.

我以前招过人，深知其中的艰辛。面试的时候，你怎么知道一个人能不能胜任你安排的工作？他们当然会说自己无所不能，但我招过足够多的人，我明白，对自己能力的自信并不等于胜任。

I have hired people before and I know how hard it is. How do you know from a job interview if someone can do the work you need them to do? Of course they will say they can do everything, but I have hired enough folks to understand that professed confidence in one’s abilities doesn’t equal competence.

视频采访中的下一个问题出现在屏幕上：“你曾经为某项活动或比赛进行过训练吗？如果有，能跟我讲讲吗？”

The next question in my video interview appears on-screen: “Have you ever trained for something—an event or race? If so, can you tell me about it?”

我想了几秒钟，然后脱口而出下一个令人尴尬的答案：“是的，我训练过一些东西。我实际上训练过……我想学……有一年夏天，我决定要学怎么跑五英里。所以我开始对这个目标非常明确。我第一次出去跑步的时候，大概能跑三十秒，走三十秒，跑三十秒，走三十秒……”

I think about it for a few seconds and off I go with the next cringeworthy answer: “Yeah, I’ve trained for something. I’ve actually trained for … I wanted to learn … One summer I decided I wanted to learn how to run five miles. And so I just started to be very clear about it. The first time I went out for a run and maybe was able to run for thirty seconds, walk for thirty seconds, run for thirty seconds, walk for thirty seconds …”

到目前为止，我还不确定该如何看待这次经历。也许我只是比较老派，更喜欢面对面的面试，因为面试可以变成真正有意义的对话，公司的人会了解我，我也会更多地了解他们。单向视频面试完全是另一回事。我独自一人待在公寓里那间狭小的办公室里；电话那头没有人，我基本上是在录制自己的自我介绍。

So far, I am not sure what to make of the experience. Maybe I am just old-school and prefer in-person job interviews because they can turn into really meaningful conversations in which the organization’s people learn about me and I learn more about them as well. Doing a one-way video interview is a different beast. I am alone in my tiny little office in my apartment; no one is on the other end and I am basically recording a presentation of myself.

下一个问题：“请告诉我你为了完成一个项目或任务而不得不‘惹恼一些人’的经历。”

Next question: “Tell me about a time when you had to ‘ruffle a few feathers’ to get a project or task done.”

“有一次，我为一个纪录片项目编写了一套新的课程。大学里很多人对此有很多意见……”

“So there was a time when I wrote a new curriculum for a documentary program. And there were a lot of people at the university that had a lot of opinions …”

Retorio 的人工智能正在分析我说的话、我的面部表情和我的语调。2然后，该工具会给出一个分数，显示我是否适合我所申请的工作。

Retorio’s AI is analyzing the words I say, my facial expressions, and my intonation.2 The tool will then come up with a score showing how qualified I am for the job I am applying for.

知道一台电脑在我说话的时候偷偷给我打分，感觉怪怪的。它比我还了解我吗？它是不是窥探到我的灵魂了？我的内心想法？

It’s weird to know a computer is secretly scoring me as I talk. Does it know more about me than I do? Is it getting a glimpse of my soul? My innermost thoughts?

Retorio 让我可以访问这个平台，让我像招聘经理一样查看自己的分数。我得了 93 分！太棒了！我对这个分数兴奋得有点奇怪——我还不知道它是否有意义，但这些数字真的很难让人忽视。

Retorio gave me access to the platform, allowing me to see my score as if I were the hiring manager. I scored 93 percent! Yeah! It’s weird how excited I am about this score—I don’t know yet if it’s meaningful, but it’s hard to ignore the numbers.

我惊讶于自己竟然如此符合条件。在“概要”选项卡下，软件显示我好奇、深思熟虑、坦诚、兼容且放松。

I’m surprised I am so qualified. Under the Summary tab, the software states that I am curious, deliberate, candid, compatible, and relaxed.

高分让我对这段奇特的经历感觉好受了一些。但几乎所有与我聊过单向视频面试的受访者都告诉我，他们不喜欢这种面试方式。

My high score makes me feel better about this bizarre experience. But almost all of the interviewees I spoke with about their one-way video interviews told me they didn’t like it.

其中一位是 Alex Huang。2018 年，他是芝加哥一家本地银行的年轻信贷分析师。那一年，他刚从伊利诺伊大学经济学专业和统计学专业毕业，申请了大约 30 个入门级银行和金融职位。当时，数字化招聘尚处于起步阶段，但在他发出的 30 份申请中，大约有 10 家公司要求他进行视频面试。如今，几乎所有美国大型金融公司和银行都要求入门级候选人先通过数字化招聘工具，然后才能与人工招聘经理交谈。

One of these people is Alex Huang. In 2018, he was a young credit analyst at a local bank in Chicago. He applied to about thirty entry-level banking and finance jobs that year while he was graduating from the University of Illinois with a major in economics and a minor in statistics.3 Digital hiring was in its infancy back then, but out of the thirty applications he sent out, about ten companies asked him to do video interviews. Today, almost all large financial companies and banks in the United States require entry-level candidates to first pass through a digital hiring tool before they are able to speak with a human hiring manager.

黄的梦想是在芝加哥市中心的一家更大的金融机构工作，但该公司要求单向视频他讨厌面试。“它没有给我机会展现真正的自我。我更喜欢与人打交道，”他在接受《华尔街日报》采访时说道。4

Huang had his dreams set on working at a bigger financial institution in downtown Chicago, but the company required a one-way video interview. He hated it. “It didn’t provide me the opportunity to show who I really am. I’m more of a people person,” he said in an interview with the Wall Street Journal.4

当时，黄的女友和一群朋友都在抱怨他们不得不接受视频采访。黄讨厌这个过程，讨厌独自一人在房间里讲话，他觉得自己的表现已经很明显了。

Huang’s girlfriend and his group of friends at the time were all complaining about the video interviews they had to do. Huang hated the process, hated speaking in a room by himself, and he thinks it showed.

“基本上，我根本没能熬过第一轮，”他说。他也没有得到任何有意义的反馈。被拒让他感到愤怒和沮丧。

“Essentially, I never really went past the first round,” he said. He also didn’t get any meaningful feedback. The rejections made him feel angry and frustrated.

他甚至决定撤回一份申请，因为该公司要求他进行视频面试：“到最后，我完全不适应这种面试方式，”他说。“我厌倦了被自己心仪的公司迅速拒绝。我决定换一种方式。” 他请求一种替代方案，比如与人工招聘经理进行电话沟通。

He even decided to withdraw an application because the company asked him to do a video interview: “In the end, I wasn’t comfortable with doing them at all,” he said. “I got tired of just quickly being rejected from the companies I want to work for. I decided I should approach it a different way.” He requested an alternative, such as a phone conversation with a human hiring manager.

这一策略并没有给黄带来预期的效果。他意识到大多数公司都运行着自动化沟通系统，他三次申请替代单向视频面试，其中一次获得了面对面面试的批准。另外两次，他都没有收到任何回复。

The strategy didn’t get Huang the desired results. He realized that most companies run automated communication systems, and out of his three requests for an alternative to the one-way video interview, he was granted an in-person interview once. The other two times, he didn’t hear anything back.

他决定不管。黄先生认为，如果一家公司连招聘策略都投入，连面试都不重视，那他就不想去那里工作了。

He decided not to care. Huang thinks that if a company lacks the decency to invest in its hiring strategy and conduct in-person job interviews, he does not want to work there.

在接受《华尔街日报》采访之前，他甚至没有意识到，他面试的一些公司可能根本不会看视频，而是使用 HireVue 基于人工智能的视频面试工具来对候选人进行评分和排名。他以为所有面试都会由人工招聘经理观看。当我告诉他，他的一些视频面试可能已经被机器分析了，他很不高兴。“这让我有点害怕——他们还在做什么？你们还瞒着我什么？”他问道。

Until he spoke to the Wall Street Journal, he wasn’t even aware that some of the companies he was interviewing with might never watch the video, instead using HireVue’s AI-based video interview tool to score and rank candidates. He assumed all of the interviews would be watched by a human hiring manager. He was not pleased when I told him that some of his video interviews probably had been analyzed by a machine. “That kind of scares me—what else are they doing? What else are you hiding without telling me?” he asked.

利用人工智能分析求职者的面部表情、语调和用词，这看似科幻，如今却已成为现实，并已在美国及其他国家用于招聘。面部表情和语调分析也已应用于工作中，例如监控员工的会议、销售电话以及呼叫中心的客户互动。

What seems like science fiction—analyzing job applicants’ facial expressions, tone of voice, and the words they use with artificial intelligence—is already reality and is used for hiring in the United States and abroad. Facial expression and tone-of-voice analysis is also being used at work to monitor employees’ conference and sales calls and customer interactions in call centers.

尽管我们目前介绍的三种人工智能应用——简历筛选器、社交媒体扫描器和游戏化测评——都存在诸多缺陷，但这种分析工具的适用性应该更加科学和公平，前提是人们能够克服对接受计算机面试的厌恶情绪。事实证明，这并非小问题。

Whereas the three AI applications we have covered so far—résumé screeners, social media scanners, and gamified assessments—have multiple drawbacks, the case for this analytical tool is supposed to be more scientific and fair, that is, if a person can get beyond their aversion to being interviewed by a computer. As it turns out, this is not a small problem.

其他专家则认为这项技术只是数字骗人的花招，毫无科学依据。然而，它却决定了数百万人的未来，因为基于人工智能的视频面试可以自动拒绝求职者，而且在金融、零售和酒店业中无处不在。让我们以我为实验对象，来探索这个新领域。我测试了一些工具，但效果并不总是令人满意。

Other experts say that this technology is digital snake oil and not rooted in science. Yet it decides the future of millions because AI-based video interviews can automatically reject applicants and are ubiquitous in finance, retail, and hospitality. Let’s explore this new frontier using me as the guinea pig. I tested some of these tools and was not always impressed by the results.

学习做一些奇怪的事情

LEARNING TO DO SOMETHING WEIRD

视频面试，尤其是针对应届大学毕业生申请大公司入门级职位的面试，已经变得非常普遍，以至于许多大学就业中心现在专门为学生提供视频面试培训。“学生们越来越早地接触到这些系统，”纽约大学沃瑟曼职业发展中心执行主任格雷西·萨基西安说道。（她的办公室还为学生提供了一个人工智能工具，向他们展示如何他们的简历与职位描述有多少重叠，以及他们应该做哪些改变才能通过机器筛选。

Video interviews, especially for recent college graduates for entry-level jobs at large companies, have become so widespread that many university career centers now specifically train students for them. “Students are encountering these systems earlier and earlier on,” said Gracy Sarkissian, the executive director of the Wasserman Center for Career Development at NYU. (Her office also offers students an AI tool that shows them how much their résumé overlaps with a job description and what they should change to get through the machine screening.)

但单向视频对于学生来说尤其难以应对。

But one-way videos are especially hard for students to deal with.

“这对学生来说是一个很大的未知数，”萨尔基相说。“我们的工作就是稍微揭开它的神秘面纱。我们会说，‘我不知道面试会是什么样子，但以下是一些你可能会遇到的情况。以下是一些你可能需要准备的东西。’并让学生知道他们将要面对的是什么。”

“It’s this big unknown to students,” Sarkissian said. “Our job is to demystify it a little bit. To say, ‘I don’t know what that interview’s going to look like, but here are some things you might expect. Here are some things you might want to prepare.’ And let the student know what they’re getting into.”

杜克大学经济系为学生提供了具体的视频面试技巧，其中包括：“练习对着镜头说话。一开始，对着屏幕而不是对着真人说话会感觉很奇怪。表现得自然些，慢慢说！” 5

Duke University’s economics department gives students concrete video interviewing tips that include suggestions like: “Practice talking into a camera. It feels very strange at first to talk to a screen rather than a person. Act natural, talk slowly!”5

然而，即使准备充分，单向视频面试对很多学生来说仍然感觉不自然：“当我们与人工智能面试时，感觉就像面对一个陌生人。感觉像一个没有面孔的陌生人。屏幕一片空白。很多时候，你只能盯着自己，所以对我们的一些学生来说，这可能是一个孤独的过程。”萨尔基相说道。

However, even with thorough preparation, one-way video interviews feel unnatural for many students: “When we are interviewing with AI, it feels like a stranger. It feels like a stranger without a face. It’s a blank screen. And oftentimes you’re staring at yourself and so it can be a lonely process for some of our students,” Sarkissian said.

由于萨基相在纽约大学的许多学生都必须参加视频面试，她最近也亲自尝试了一下。“感觉不太自然。我觉得这和我从学生们那里听到的很多关于视频面试的担忧很吻合，”她说。“学生们渴望与雇主建立真诚的联系，但这种联系很难建立。”

Since so many of the students Sarkissian works with at NYU must take video interviews, she recently tried one herself. “It didn’t feel so natural. And I think it aligns with a lot of what I’m hearing from our students about their anxieties around it,” she said. “Students desire a genuine connection with employers, and it’s hard to get that connection.”

许多留学生和有言语障碍的学生尤其担心某些自动化系统可能会对他们进行处罚，因为语音转文本软件对他们来说可能不太准确。在面对面面试中，许多人可能想透露自己的言语障碍，但在视频面试中这是不可能的。

Many international students and students with speech impairments are especially afraid that some of these automated systems may penalize them, because speech-to-text transcription software could be less accurate for them. In an in-person interview, many may want to disclose their speech impairment, but that’s not possible in video interviews.

萨尔基相说：“他们不知道自己在这些虚拟面试中会被如何评估，这确实会造成另一层焦虑。”“一些学生被警告说，这些技术会歧视并偏向某些特征，因此他们完全拒绝视频面试。”

“They don’t know how they’re being assessed in these virtual interviews and that does create another layer of anxiety,” Sarkissian said. “Some students are warned that these technologies discriminate and privilege certain characteristics over others, and so they refuse video interviews altogether.”

在劳动力市场紧张、美国每个求职者大约只能找到两份工作的情况下，她认为雇主应该重新考虑他们的一些招聘策略，特别是如果他们希望吸引顶尖人才的话。6

In a tight labor market where there are roughly two jobs for every job seeker in the United States, she believes that employers should reconsider some of their hiring strategies, especially if they wish to attract top talent.6

“Z世代的学生是价值观驱动的一代。他们希望确保自己能够融入组织的文化，确保组织的使命和价值观与他们自己的一致，而这一点在线上面试中很难评估，”萨尔基相说道。

“Gen Z students are a values-driven generation. They want to make sure that they can connect with the culture of the organization, that the mission and values of the organization are in line with their own and that’s something that’s difficult to assess when you were interviewing in a virtual way,” Sarkissian said.

民主化招聘

DEMOCRATIZING HIRING

尽管许多求职者对这项技术持负面态度，但视频面试业务却蓬勃发展。最大的供应商之一 HireVue 宣布，其在 2022 年 11 月进行了 3300 万次单向面试，高于 2021 年 10 月的 2000 万次。7

Despite the negative feelings many job applicants have toward the technology, the business of video interviews is thriving. One of the largest vendors, HireVue, announced that it conducted its thirty-three-millionth one-way job interview in November 2022, up from twenty million in October 2021.7

截至 2023 年年中，其客户已涵盖 60 多家《财富》100 强企业，其 AI 视频技术已被联合利华、达美航空和希尔顿等品牌采用。（HireVue 表示，它不会确认或披露任何客户的身份。）

As of mid-2023, its customers include more than sixty Fortune 100 companies, and its AI video technology has been used by brands like Unilever, Delta Air Lines, and Hilton. (HireVue says that it does not confirm or disclose the identity of any customer.)

HireVue 的许多客户并非只想填补几个空缺职位，而是想一次性面试数千人。最极端的情况是，一位客户在一个周末内就面试了 1500 个地点的 5 万名求职者。

Many of HireVue’s clients are not looking to fill a couple of open positions but rather are interviewing thousands of people at once. On the extreme end, one customer interviewed fifty thousand applicants for jobs in fifteen hundred locations over one weekend.

自 2016 年起担任 HireVue 首席执行官的凯文·帕克 (Kevin Parker) 表示，在疫情期间，远程招聘成为常态，HireVue 的影响力得到了极大扩展，他最近转任执行顾问一职。他说，HireVue 的使命是实现招聘民主化——让每个人都有平等的机会申请工作。

HireVue’s reach expanded tremendously during the pandemic when remote hiring had to become the norm, said Kevin Parker, CEO of HireVue since 2016, who recently transitioned to an executive advisory role. He said that HireVue’s mission is to democratize hiring—give everyone an equal chance to apply for a job.

我们的创始人是盐湖城的一名大学生，他无法获得面试机会或工作机会，因为他想去的公司都不来盐湖城面试。于是，他开始利用视频向越来越多的人开放人才库。

“Our founder was a college student here in Salt Lake who could not get an interview or could not get a job because the companies he wanted to work for weren’t coming to Salt Lake City to interview anybody. And so he set about a process by using video to open the talent pool to more and more people.”

那是在 2004 年。帕克说，尽管底层技术已经发生了变化，但使用 HireVue 工具的公司仍然秉承着 HireVue 成立时的理念；公司不想局限于少数申请者，而是想给更多人一个机会：“随着时间的推移，他们意识到，寻找人才的传统方式——无论是看简历，还是只去某些学校或从某些公司招聘——都限制了他们可以交谈的人数。他们已经彻底改变了这种状况，他们正在利用技术接触更多的人，并通过各种新的方式面试和聘用最优秀的人才。”

This was in 2004. Parker says that although the underlying technology has changed, the companies that use HireVue’s tools follow the same ethos from way back when HireVue was founded; instead of a small applicant pool, companies want to give more people a chance: “They’ve recognized over time that the old sort of ways of finding talent—whether it’s looking at a résumé or only going to certain schools or hiring from certain companies—really limited the number of people they can talk to and they’ve really changed that and they’re using technology to reach more people and interview and hire the best talent in a variety of new ways.”

人类招聘经理一直对某些群体表现出偏见，例如那些就读于哈佛等名校或在谷歌等特定公司工作的人；几十年来，女性和有色人种一直被低估。

Human hiring managers have consistently exhibited bias in favor of certain groups, such as those who attended prestigious schools like Harvard or worked for certain companies like Google; women and people of color have been underestimated for decades.

帕克认为，他的公司招聘方式比大多数人的面试方式更公平。HireVue 采用结构化面试，这意味着每个人都会被问到相同的问题，从而减少了在比较申请人时产生的偏见。结构化面试几乎没有聊天的空间，而这种聊天很容易滋生偏见。

Parker believes the way his company does hiring is more fair than the way most humans conduct job interviews. HireVue uses structured interviews, which means that everyone is asked the same questions, which reduces bias in comparing applicants. Structured interviews leave very little room for chatting, where bias can easily creep in.

我们人类喜欢与他人建立联系，在求职面试中，我们很多人都喜欢建立人际关系。我们经常会问对面的人在哪里上学，是否认识相同的人，是否有相似的爱好。意识到自己拥有一个人际关系并非人与人之间建立的私人联系，但事实证明，当人类做出招聘决策时，面试中人们提出不同的问题和闲聊会更多地暴露出人为偏见。招聘经理可能会无意识地偏爱某位候选人，因为他们就读于同一所大学，而不是因为该候选人比其他人更有资格。

We humans love to connect with other humans, and in job interviews, many of us like to make a human connection. We often ask the person across from us where they went to school, if we know the same people, have similar hobbies. It’s wonderful realizing that you have a personal connection with another human being, but it turns out that when humans make hiring decisions, interviews in which people ask different questions and chitchat bring out more human bias. A hiring manager may unconsciously prefer one candidate because they went to the same college and not because that person is more qualified than others.

HireVue 的客户有两种选择：一是人工审核视频，并按分数对候选人进行排序；二是让算法分析视频，并按分数进行排序。“我们的独特之处在于，我们利用这些视频，并运用人工智能帮助公司找到最适合其职位的人才，”帕克说道，“我们在这方面取得了巨大的成功。”

HireVue’s customers have two options: they can review videos by humans and sort candidates by score, or they can have the videos analyzed by an algorithm and ranked by score. “We’re unique in the sense that we’re taking that video and now using artificial intelligence to help companies find the very best talent for the job that they have,” Parker said. “We’re seeing tremendous success with that.”

与许多尖端技术一样，全面的科学评估往往滞后于企业将产品推向市场。像 HireVue 这样的人工智能黑匣子，使得测试和分析这些工具尤为困难，因为我们无法访问输入数据，不知道数据是如何分析的，也无法获得最终结果。我们主要依赖于供应商和客户公司的口口相传，相信该技术有效且能够做出公平的决策，尽管有些供应商本身并不完全理解他们的工具是如何做出决策的。

Thorough scientific assessment, as with many bleeding-edge technologies, lags behind companies bringing their product to market. AI black boxes, such as HireVue’s, make it especially difficult to test and analyze these tool because we don’t have access to the input data, we don’t know how the data is analyzed, and we do not have the results. We mainly have to rely on the vendors’ and the client companies’ words that the technology works and makes fair decisions even though some vendors themselves don’t fully understand how their tools make decisions.

因此，我和我的同事 Jason Bellini 决定尽可能多地了解这些技术并亲自进行测试。

So my colleague Jason Bellini and I decided to learn as much as we could about the technologies and test them ourselves.

赫瑞维

HIREVUE

在 HireVue 的测试面试中，我们见到了 Gabriella。在一段预先录制的视频中，她表示正在为“Eastmond Paper”招聘一名客户支持代表：“我们热衷的一些事情，以及“我们关注的重点是像主人翁一样行事，成为行业领导者，以及以客户为中心。请告诉我们你热衷的事物，以及你为什么非常适合这个职位。”她说道。

In HireVue’s test interview we meet Gabriella. In a prerecorded video, she says that she is hiring for a customer support representative role at “Eastmond Paper”: “Some of the things we are passionate about and focused on are acting like an owner, being an industry leader, and customer obsession. Tell us some of the things you are passionate about and why you will be a great fit for the role,” she says.

下一个问题要求杰森解决一个问题。一段视频开始播放，一位年轻人坐在办公桌前，戴着耳机：“感谢您致电客服。我叫杰伊。今天我能为您做些什么？”

The next question asks Jason to solve a problem. A video starts playing, a young man is sitting at his desk with a headset: “Thanks for calling customer support. My name is Jay. How can I assist you today?”

画面一分屏开始，一位女士生气地说：“是啊。我的账户好像出了点问题。我把账单设置成了自动扣款，但最新账单显示我已经拖欠了三笔款项，我的服务面临被终止的风险。这已经是我第三次尝试解决这个问题了，但贵公司似乎没人关心。如果你们现在不能帮我解决这个问题，我就换家了。”

A split screen starts with a woman saying angrily: “Yeah. There seems to be an error with my account. I have got my bills set up to auto-bill and my latest statement says that I am three payments behind and I am at risk of having my service terminated. This is my third attempt to resolve this issue and no one at your company seems to care. If you can’t help me resolve this right now, I am going to take my business elsewhere.”

客服人员用略带轻蔑的语气告诉客户，她的信用卡可能过期了，这只会让客户更加恼火。她要求与客服人员的经理通话。一个新窗口打开：“如果您是这位客服代表，请告诉我们，您会如何应对这位客户的不满。”
