The agent tells the customer in a somewhat dismissive voice that her credit card may have expired, which only gets the customer more upset. She demands to speak to the agent’s manager. A new window opens: “If you were in the position of this customer service support representative, tell us how you would respond to this customer’s frustration.”

杰森开始回答：“我来这里是为了让事情变得更好……”

Jason starts his answer: “I am here to try to make things better …”

Jason 面试结束后，我们采访了 HireVue 的首席心理学家 Nathan Mondragon。Jason 直接开口询问他的表现：“我刚刚参加了客服代表的面试。我表现怎么样？”

After Jason completes the interview, we talk with Nathan Mondragon, HireVue’s chief psychologist. Jason jumps right in and wants to know about his performance: “I just did the interview for a job as a customer service representative. How did I do?”

“我们首先要看的是与之相关的人工智能评分，”蒙德拉贡说。杰森很幸运，他知道自己的成绩是多少。普通申请者永远不会知道。“你可以看到，你得了37分。”

“The first thing we look at is the AI score that’s attached to it,” Mondragon says. Jason is lucky that he learns what his result is. Regular applicants will never know. “You can see that up here, you scored a 37 percent.”

“这很不错，对吧？”杰森问道。

“That’s pretty good, right?” Jason asks.

“不，”蒙德拉贡笑着对杰森说，有点难以置信。“这可是满分一百分啊。”

“No,” Mondragon says, smiling at Jason, a little incredulous. “That’s out of one hundred.”

杰森做了个鬼脸。

Jason makes a face.

“所以，本质上来说，你不太适合，”蒙德拉贡说着，给了杰森一个略带歉意却又鼓励的微笑。他说，他自己也觉得自己不太适合这份工作。

“So you’d be a low match, essentially,” Mondragon says, giving Jason a small apologetic, but encouraging smile. He says he thinks that he himself would be a low match for the job, as well.

也许杰森的性格不适合做客服工作？又或者他的回答不够详细？

Maybe Jason doesn’t have the right personality for the customer service job? Or maybe his answers didn’t contain enough details?

“如果求职者得分只有 37%，雇主会看他们的视频吗？他们难道不会直接拒绝这个候选人吗？”杰森问道。

“If a job applicant scores 37 percent, is an employer even going to look at their video? Wouldn’t they just reject the candidate?” Jason asks.

“不，不，绝对不行。实际上，我们建议候选人可以以此为依据进行排名，但他们仍然会去观看不同的视频，”蒙德拉贡说。“至于他们是否想看，则由公司决定。”

“No, no, absolutely not. Actually, what we would recommend is that the candidates can be ranked by that, but they still go and look at the different videos,” Mondragon says. “It’s up to the company to decide if they want to watch.”

“但他们可能会决定，‘嘿，这个叫杰森·贝里尼的家伙只得到了 37% 的选票，不值得我们花时间，’”杰森说。

“But they might decide, ‘Hey, this guy Jason Bellini has 37 percent, not even worth our time,’” Jason says.

“如果你的分数这么低，他们可能会说，我们可能不会看完所有视频，但他们可能会看一道题，”蒙德拉贡解释道。8

“If you score so low, they might say, we may not watch all the videos, but they may watch a question,” Mondragon explains.8

从技术上讲，公司可以这样做，但他们为什么要这么做呢？我感觉自己被供应商和招聘公司误导了，他们告诉我，他们花了数千美元购买的人工智能评分实际上被忽略了，视频仍然由人工观看。如果一个系统不能减轻你的招聘负担，那为什么还要花钱安装呢？

Technically, companies can do that, but why would they? I have a feeling I am being misled by vendors and employer companies telling me that the AI scores they pay thousands of dollars for are essentially being ignored and humans still watch the videos. Why pay for and set up a system if it is not helping to ease your hiring burden?

在沟通中，供应商和公司从未承认过这一点，因为大多数求职者可能不愿意得知自己被人工智能直接拒绝。或许，这些公司担心如果人们发现自己使用了这种尖端技术，会引起公众的强烈反对。

In conversation, vendors and companies have never admitted to this because most applicants probably wouldn’t be happy to learn that an AI outright rejected them. And maybe companies fear a public backlash if folks find out that they use this kind of bleeding-edge technology.

但在行业专用的会议环境中，没有人会想到会有像我这样的记者出现，一些供应商已经坦诚地告知了公司应该如何最好地使用他们的产品。

But in industry-only settings at conferences, where no one suspects that reporters like me will show up, some vendors have been honest about how companies should best use their products.

在疫情期间举行的一次线上人力资源技术会议上，Curious Thing AI 的前副总裁马克·亚当斯 (Mark Adams) 表示，该公司销售基于人工智能的电话面试软件，并演示了该人工智能工具的仪表板。“[自动面试]的录音在这里，如果我愿意，我可以播放，但通常这不是最佳的时间利用方式，因为它的最终目的是减少你的筛选时间，只关注你想要的候选人。所以你可以听录音，但我们不建议你这样做。”

At an online HR tech conference during the pandemic, Mark Adams, the former vice president at Curious Thing AI, a company that sold AI-based phone interview software, was doing a demo of the AI tool and showed the tool’s dashboard. “The recording of [the automated interview] is here, and I can play it back if I choose to, but generally that’s not the best use of time, because the whole point of it is to reduce your screening time and just focus on candidates you want. So you can listen to it, but we don’t recommend that you do that.”

在那里，亚当斯向招聘经理明确指出：不要花时间在面试录音上。

There, Adams spelled it out to hiring managers: Do not spend time on the interview recording.

HireVue 还告诉我，最终决定谁会被拒绝的并非是他们：“我们不会决定你是否被录用，”前首席执行官凯文·帕克 (Kevin Parker) 说。“我们不想处于那种境地。这仍然是招聘公司非常个人的决定。”

HireVue also told me that in the end, it is not the one making the final call on who is getting rejected: “We’re not making the decision about whether you get hired,” Kevin Parker, former CEO, said. “We don’t want to be in that position. That’s still a very personal decision on the part of the hiring company.”

但在一封我通过州公共记录请求获得的邮件中，HireVue 的首席心理学家却表达了不同的意图。这封邮件来自 HireVue 与亚特兰大公立学校之间的交流。亚特兰大公立学校从 2017 年左右开始使用 HireVue 的技术来面试新教师和新员工。

But in an email I obtained through a state public records request, HireVue’s chief psychologist showed a different intention. This email is from an exchange between HireVue and Atlanta Public Schools, which began using HireVue’s technology to interview new teachers and staff around 2017.

2017年9月21日星期四晚上7:38，内森·蒙德拉贡（Nathan Mondragon）在一封电子邮件中写道：“他们很高兴开始使用33%的及格分数线。这意味着任何分数低于33分的人都将被视为不及格。”

On Thursday, September 21, 2017, at 7:38 p.m., Nathan Mondragon wrote in an email: “They are excited to start using the assessment with a 33 percent cut score. This [sic] anyone scoring at 33 or lower will be a Not Pass.”

我第一次读到这封邮件时，完全不知道分数线是什么，但深入了解之后，我明白了。分数线是招聘过程中用来筛选候选人的分数。在某些情况下，如果求职者的分数低于分数线，就会被拒绝。

When I first read the email, I had no idea what a cut score was, but when I found out more, it made sense. A cut score is a score that is used to filter people out in the hiring process. In some cases, if job applicants don’t score above the cutoff, they are rejected.

2020 年，当我与亚特兰大公立学校 (APS) 前人力资源副总裁 Skye Duckett 交谈时，她表示学校系统当时仅将 HireVue 的 AI 工具用作试点研究，并且向负责招聘的校长隐瞒了 AI 评分。决策，在后台测试 HireVue 的 AI 是否比他们以前的评分系统更好。

When I talked to the former vice president of human resources at Atlanta Public Schools (APS) in 2020, Skye Duckett, she said that the school system only used HireVue’s AI tool as a pilot study at the time and were hiding the AI scores from the principals, who make the hiring decisions, to test in the background whether HireVue’s AI is better than their previous scoring system.

达克特表示，她看到了试点项目的积极成果，大约六个月后就能获得更准确的数据。在我们跟进之前，她就离开了亚特兰大公立学校，另谋高就；我多次联系她的继任者，但一直没有得到回复。于是我再次提交了信息自由申请，并从学区与外部律师的通信中得知，2021 年 6 月，亚特兰大公立学校收到了美国司法部 (DOJ) 就其使用 HireVue 系统一事的调查。（HireVue 表示，它不知道最近的调查，并拒绝置评。）

Duckett said that she was seeing encouraging results from the pilot and would have better data in about six months. She left Atlanta Public Schools for another job before we could follow up; I reached out to her successor multiple times, but never heard back, so I filed another Freedom of Information request and learned from correspondence between the school district and outside lawyers that in June 2021 Atlanta Public Schools received a Department of Justice (DOJ) inquiry regarding their use of HireVue. (HireVue says it is not aware of a recent inquiry and declined to comment.)

野外视频采访

VIDEO INTERVIEWS IN THE WILD

我想了解各大机构如何在实际情况下使用 HireVue 来做出关乎招聘人员的重大决策。他们如何理解这项技术的运作机制？他们采用了哪些制衡机制？

I wanted to understand how organizations use HireVue “in the wild” to make high-stakes decisions about who gets hired. How do they understand how the technology works? What kind of checks and balances do they employ?

HireVue 帮我联系了他们的一位客户。谢尔顿·班克斯 (Shelton Banks) 是芝加哥一家名为 re:WORK 的非营利组织的首席执行官。他的组织致力于帮助少数族裔在职场中晋升，获得薪酬更高的工作——通常是科技公司的销售职位。

HireVue put me in touch with one of its clients. Shelton Banks is the CEO of a nonprofit called re:WORK in Chicago. His organization specializes in helping minorities move up in the workforce and into better-paying jobs—often sales jobs in technology companies.

每隔几个月，班克斯就需要挑选人才加入他的销售培训项目。在八个周末的时间里，他教学生们如何进行电话营销、如何在求职面试中脱颖而出，以及如何精心策划自己的销售故事。他们还学习如何将之前工作中学到的销售和客户服务技能运用到Salesforce、DocuSign以及最近的HireVue等公司的技术销售岗位上。

Every few months, Banks needs to select people into his sales training program. Over the course of eight weekends, he teaches students how to cold call, how to excel in job interviews, and how to craft their stories. They also learn how to transfer the sales and customer service skills they’ve learned from their previous jobs to tech sales roles at companies such as Salesforce, DocuSign, and, recently, HireVue itself.

Banks 的团队需要找到他们认为能够在 re:WORK 计划中取得成功并且在毕业后能够找到工作的人，因此他们需要候选人进行良好的面试。

Banks’s team needs to find people they think will succeed in re:WORK’s program and will also secure a job after graduating from the program, so they need candidates to interview well.

班克斯是黑人，祖籍芝加哥南区。他理解学生们的处境。他自己高中辍学，没有拿到大学学位，有时甚至很难找到工作，直到有人给了他机会。他的学生们很努力，但很多学生没有家人或朋友来帮助他们润色简历。

Banks is Black and originally from the South Side of Chicago. He understands where his students are coming from. He himself dropped out of high school and didn’t get a college degree and at times struggled to find employment until someone gave him a chance. His students are trying hard, but many don’t have family or friends who could help polish their résumé.

“没人教你如何面试。你的祖父母会说‘准时到场，尽力而为’，”他说。“面试就是不断尝试，不断摸索。”

“Nobody teaches you how to interview. Your grandparents are like ‘show up on time and give it your best,’” he said. “Going on the interview, it’s trial and error.”

他的学生95%是黑人和棕色人种，他们很难找到高薪工作，而且大多来自服务匮乏或贫困的家庭——班克斯讨厌这些说法。“我们一直在培训来自我们称之为‘尚未开发和被忽视’的群体的候选人。”

His students, who are 95 percent Black and brown, struggle to find well-paying jobs and are mostly from underserved or underprivileged backgrounds—terms that Banks hates. “We’ve been training candidates from what we like to call ‘untapped and overlooked’ communities.”

他的周末项目收费参加，成功地提高了人们的收入。“有些人每月大概能挣八九百美元，要么是做零售，要么是开Uber，要么就是做些零工。项目结束后，他们通常每年能挣6.3万美元左右。”

His weekend program, which people are paid to attend, has been successful in raising people’s incomes. “Roughly eight to nine hundred bucks a month is what some people are making, either working retail or driving Uber, or just kind of odd jobs, and when they leave the program, they typically make around $63,000 a year.”

2017年加入该项目时，班克斯并不急于尝试用人工智能来寻找人才，但他很快意识到传统的求职面试并不奏效。起初，他与志愿者合作挑选合适的申请人。班克斯和他的团队制定了一份招聘标准，并请志愿者根据1到5的等级对人们的回答进行评分。

When he joined the program in 2017, Banks wasn’t eager to try AI in his search for people to join the job-readiness program, but he soon understood that traditional job interviews weren’t working. At first, he worked with volunteers to select the right applicants. Banks and his team put together a hiring rubric and asked volunteers to score people’s answers on a scale from 1 to 5.

但班克斯说，志愿者对面试的评分并不一致，他们经常开始支持候选人，而不是评判他们的答案。

But the volunteers scored the interviews inconsistently and they often started rooting for the candidates rather than judging their answers, Banks said.

有一次，班克斯问了一位候选人一个志愿者会问的典型问题：“告诉我你失败的一次经历。”

Once, Banks asked a candidate a typical question that volunteers would ask: “Tell me about a time you failed at something.”

求职者告诉团队：“我从来没有失败过。”

The job seeker told the team: “I’ve never failed at anything.”

班克斯笑了起来。“太糟糕了，”他对那位候选人说。“你什么意思？你现在失业了。先生，你面临挑战，拜托，”他回忆道。“但有趣的是，一位志愿者会说，‘好吧，伙计，太棒了。你很有信心。’”

Banks started laughing. “That was horrible,” he said to the candidate. “What do you mean? You are unemployed right now. You have challenges, sir, come on,” he recalled saying. “But interestingly enough, a volunteer would say, ‘Okay, man, that’s awesome. You are confident.’”

班克斯说，志愿者根据自己的感受和观点对受试者进行评分。一些高分并不一定与班克斯及其团队在项目中与学生相处的经验相符。

Volunteers scored people based on their own feelings and opinions, Banks said. Some high scores didn’t necessarily match the experience Banks and his team consequently had with the students in the program.

“我们会邀请这些高分者参加这个项目，然后在整个八周的时间里，我们总会遇到各种各样的障碍，比如‘伙计，你水平参差不齐。我帮你考了八周……谁给你这颗金星的？’”他说。这些候选人不仅在项目中苦苦挣扎，而且当班克斯安排他们参加实际面试时，很多人都没有得到工作。

“We would invite these high-scoring people to the program and then throughout the eight weeks, we would just run into roadblocks like, ‘Man, you are rough around the edges. I got you for eight weeks…. Who gave you this gold star?’” he said. Not only were these candidates struggling in the program, but also when Banks put them into real-world interviews, many didn’t get a job.

他想尝试一下 HireVue 的人工智能工具，结果却遇到了一些意想不到的惊喜。re:WORK 的一位董事会成员向他介绍了 HireVue，这位董事是一家投资 HireVue 的风险投资公司的合伙人。Banks 获得了免费使用 HireVue 人工智能面试工具的权限，但初次尝试时并没有感到特别兴奋。

He wanted to give HireVue’s AI tool a shot and encountered some interesting surprises. He was introduced to HireVue by one of the board of directors of re:WORK, who is a partner at a venture capitalist firm that invested in HireVue. Banks was granted free access to HireVue’s AI interviewing tool but wasn’t overly excited when he first tried it.

“我们和大多数人一样，都抱有怀疑态度。‘伙计，这行不通。这会带有偏见。这会很危险，’”他回忆道。“我们已经意识到，危险无处不在，偏见无处不在。”

“We were skeptics like most people were. ‘Man, this isn’t gonna work. This is going to be biased. This is gonna be a danger here,’” he recalled thinking. “And we’ve realized that there’s danger everywhere, there’s going to be bias everywhere.”

该人工智能工具根据求职者在技术销售工作中可能需要的不同特质对人们进行评分，包括沟通技巧、主动性和解决问题的能力。

The AI tool scores people on different traits that job candidates probably need in a tech sales job, including communication skills, initiative, and problem-solving abilities.

在 HireVue 的第一轮测试中，候选人的得分从 99% 一路下滑至 5%。Banks 首次测试了 AI 的准确率，只选取了 HireVue 认为最优秀的候选人。“一群“十个人。我想说，其中七个人都找到了工作，”班克斯回忆道。但这个过程并不容易，他说。“我很难让那七个人找到 HireVue 认为最好的工作。”

In the first round of using HireVue, candidates scored from 99 percent all the way down to 5 percent. For his first test of the AI’s accuracy, Banks took only the people HireVue had labeled as the best. “Cohort of ten folks. I want to say seven of them got jobs,” Banks recalled. But that process was not easy, he said. “It was difficult for me to get the seven people jobs that HireVue said were the best.”

然后他决定反其道而行之。他再次使用 HireVue 的工具筛选了下一批候选人，并选出了人工智能评分最低的十个人。“这是我这辈子遇到的最差的一批人，”他笑着说。“他们一个都没找到工作。”

He then decided to do the opposite. He used HireVue’s tool again on the next set of candidates and took the ten people the AI scored lowest. “Worst cohort of my life,” he laughed. “None of them got jobs.”

班克斯开始相信这个人工智能工具或许有其独特之处。他仔细研究了结果，发现HireVue会给那些听起来令人信服的人打更高的分：“他们说话用词恰当，语气、音调和节奏都恰到好处，让人听得懂。但他们缺乏背景知识。他们没有回答问题，只是听起来很棒而已。” 机器和人类招聘人员都可能被这种说法所吸引。班克斯表示，那些听起来令人信服的人最终获得了工作。

Banks started to believe that there might be something to the AI tool. He took a closer look at the results and noticed that HireVue gives a higher score to people who sound convincing: “They talked and used all the right words and the tone and pitch and pace was on point and understandable. But they had no context. They didn’t answer the question, they just sounded great.” It’s something both machines and human recruiters may fall for. The convincing people got the jobs, according to Banks.

换句话说，HireVue 似乎过分重视候选人的表达方式而非内容，但许多人类招聘经理也是如此，因为从面试中几乎不可能预测出一个自称是积极销售人员的人在工作中是否真的是一个积极销售人员。

In other words, HireVue seemed to be overindexing a candidate’s delivery over their content, but so were many human hiring managers, since it’s almost impossible to predict from a job interview whether someone who says they are an aggressive salesperson really is an aggressive salesperson on the job.

这款人工智能工具能够识别出谁的面试听起来更有说服力。Banks 被说服了。从那时起，re:WORK 就一直在使用 HireVue 的人工智能视频软件。“就这么一个小工具，它改变了我们的招聘方式，也改变了我们的培训方式。” 他明白 HireVue 的人工智能工具并非万无一失，但该工具的分析结果比人类志愿者的评分更准确。这些工具让他了解学生的面试技巧水平，然后他会在 re:WORK 培训期间努力提高这些技能。

The AI tool is able to pick up who sounds convincing. Banks was sold. re:WORK has been using HireVue’s AI video software ever since. “Just that little piece, it changed the way we recruit and changed the way we train.” He understands HireVue’s AI tool is not bulletproof, but the tool’s analyses are better than the human volunteer ratings. They give him a baseline of where his students are in terms of interviewing skills, which he then tries to improve during the re:WORK training.

经过一系列测试后，Banks 决定采用混合模式：现在每个群组大约由 60% 的 HireVue 评分为高绩效者、30% 的中等水平申请者以及 10% 来自垫底。“你会发现这群人有着不同的思想和经验，”他说。他注意到，许多在 HireVue 上得分较低的学生不怕问一些基本问题，这对他的学生的成功至关重要。得分高的学生往往不敢问。

After a bunch of testing, Banks decided he wanted a mix: each cohort now consists of roughly 60 percent of folks HireVue scored as high performers, 30 percent middle-tier applicants, and 10 percent coming from the bottom. “You get this diversity of thought and diversity of experience in the cohort,” he said. He noticed that many of those who scored low on HireVue are not afraid to ask basic questions, which is important for his students’ success. Folks who scored high are often too afraid to ask.

Banks 决定不仅使用 HireVue 招募人才，而且由于他正在教授人们如何高效面试，所以还将 HireVue 融入到项目本身中。现在，他的学生在面试过程中会再次参加 HireVue 面试。“如果你的分数是 16 分，我会教你一些东西。然后我会把你重新带回 HireVue，现在你的分数是 80 分。” 大约 70% 的学生在第二次 HireVue 面试中提高了分数。他主要想知道学生们的进步程度，以及他们是否能够战胜机器，最终获得工作。

Banks decided to not only use HireVue to recruit people into the program but also, because he is teaching people how to interview well, add HireVue into the program itself. Now, partway through his students do another HireVue interview. “If you scored a 16, I will teach you something. And then I throw you back in HireVue and now you score 80.” Roughly 70 percent of his students improve their score in the second HireVue interview. He essentially wants to know how far his students have come and if they can beat the machines and potentially score a job.

有时，班克斯会推翻自己精心设计的“招聘”系统，尤其是在有人真正有兴趣加入这个项目的时候。“我看到你处于最底层，我就想，伙计，我想帮你。这肯定会很艰难。但有时，他们证明 HireVue 错了。”

Sometimes Banks overrides his own calibrated “hiring” system, especially when folks are really interested in joining the program. “I see you’re in the bottom bucket and it’s like, man, I want to help you. This is going to be rough. But sometimes, they prove HireVue wrong.”

他相信，将人类的判断与人工智能相结合，有助于他做出最佳选择。“你不应该总是听从工具的指引。但工具会帮助你做出明智的决定，”他说。

He believes combining his human judgment with AI helps him make the best selections. “You shouldn’t always listen to the tool. But the tool will help you make an informed decision,” he said.

如今，他和他的团队使用一份为期两周的在线自学管理指南来评估人们是否应该加入该项目。谢尔顿·班克斯（Shelton Banks）深思熟虑地实施了这项技术，进行了测试，并制定了一套适用于他的培训课程的流程。令我感到不安的是，在整个过程中，这项技术从未受到质疑，除非他和他的团队考虑到潜在的偏见——但他们一致认为偏见无处不在。

Today, he and his team use a two-week self-guided online learning management guide to gauge if people should join the program. Shelton Banks thoughtfully implemented the technology, tested it, and came up with a process that works for his training courses. What’s troubling to me is that along the way, the technology was never questioned except when he and his team thought about potential bias—but agreed that bias is everywhere.

HireVue 在其评估中声称，其技术可以通过收集的数据来衡量认知能力，包括思维敏捷性、推理能力和数字能力。结果显示了每位申请人的“软技能”分析。候选人的沟通能力和获得“动力与说服力”的评分。该类别描述为目标导向，并努力在绩效上超越自我的人。候选人分为新手、发展中、中级、高级和专家级。此外，还会根据申请人的谈判和说服能力以及个人稳定性（即他们在压力下保持冷静的能力）进行评分。

In its assessments, HireVue claims that its technology can measure cognitive abilities, including mental agility, reasoning, and numerical ability, out of the data it collects. The results show a “soft skills” analysis of each applicant. Candidates are scored on their communication skills and also get a score for “drive and persuasion.” That category is described as someone who is goal oriented and tries to exceed in performance. Candidates are categorized as novice, developing, intermediate, advanced, or expert. Applicants are also scored for their negotiation and persuasion capabilities and their personal stability—how calm they remain under pressure.

任何求职面试，无论是人工评分还是人工智能评分，有趣的是，求职者只会谈论他们的经历。我们无法看到求职者在工作中的具体表现。“如何判断一个人是否能胜任某项工作，这本身就存在局限性。最好的方法是让他们先做一段时间，看看他们的表现如何。但显然你做不到，”HireVue 首席数据科学家 Lindsey Zuloaga 说道。“因此，评估人才，本质上是一种了解实际工作内容和工作表现的替代方法。”

What’s interesting with any job interview—if it’s scored by humans or by AI—is that a candidate only talks about their experiences. We are not seeing the candidate in action at their job. “There is just a limitation of how do you know if someone’s going to do well at a job. The best way to know would be to let them do the job for a while and see how they do. And obviously you can’t do that,” said Lindsey Zuloaga, the chief data scientist at HireVue. “So assessing people is, in nature, kind of a proxy to getting to the actual job and the performance in the job.”

无论是真人面试还是人工智能，都无法100%准确地预测那些在面试中声称自己擅长团队合作的人在工作中是否真的具备团队合作精神。正如谢尔顿·班克斯所发现的那样，有些人可能面试表现不错，但在某个职位上却可能难以成功。

Neither job interviews with humans nor AI can predict with 100 percent certainty whether someone who says they are a team player in a job interview is really a team player on the job. Just like Shelton Banks found out, some people might interview well but may not succeed in a certain role.

即使存在这些限制，HireVue 表示 AI 评分能够准确反映候选人的特质。它的具体工作原理是什么？

Even with these limitations, HireVue says that the AI scoring is an accurate reflection of a candidate’s traits. How does it work under the hood?

得分表现

SCORING PERFORMANCES

“它是你说什么、怎么说以及你通过面部动作表现出来的情绪的结合，”内森·蒙德拉贡 (Nathan Mondragon) 在 2018 年接受我前同事、《华尔街日报》记者杰森·贝里尼 (Jason Bellini) 采访时说道。“它是这三层叠加的结果。”

“It’s a combination of what you say and how you say it and the emotions you portray in your facial movements,” Nathan Mondragon told Jason Bellini, my former colleague and correspondent at the Wall Street Journal in 2018. “It’s a combination of all three layers on top of themselves.”

HireVue 前首席执行官凯文·帕克 (Kevin Parker) 表示，招聘经理在面试中评估候选人的传统方式是：关注求职者说什么、如何表达以及他们的面部表情。

Kevin Parker, HireVue’s former CEO, said that this is how hiring managers have traditionally assessed people during job interviews: taking in what applicants say, how they say it, and their facial expressions.

该算法通过已在职人员的视频面试进行训练，这些人员回答了相同的问题，并被招聘公司评为低、中、高绩效员工。人工智能可以找出这些在职人员在用词、面部表情和语调上的共同点。

The algorithm is trained with video interviews from individuals already in the job who have answered the same questions and have been rated as low, middle, or high performers by the company hiring. The AI figures out which words, facial expressions, and tones of voice these incumbents have in common.

然后，将求职者的视频与算法进行对比，算法通过给出百分比排名来告诉人类招聘经理该求职者可能是表现不佳还是表现优异，就像杰森得到的那样。

The videos of the incoming job applicants are then run against the algorithm, which tells human hiring managers whether the applicant is likely to be a low performer or a high performer by giving them a percentage ranking, just like Jason got.

在 HireVue 的私人辅导中，我了解到一些更有趣的信息，了解该公司如何从这些视频面试中提取个性特征。

In a private tutorial with HireVue, I learned a couple more interesting nuggets on how the company pulls out personality traits from these video interviews.

“某些语言、文本、语言组合、类别和库会指示并关联某些性格特征，”内森·蒙德拉贡说道。“如果团队合作很重要，与他人合作也很重要，而有人在使用‘我’和‘我’等词类，而不是‘我们’、‘团队’和‘人们’，那么代词的使用就会影响该团队与他人合作的倾向。”我的翻译如下：如果你经常使用‘我们’和‘团队’ ，这表明你在工作中是一位优秀的团队合作者。

“There’s certain language and text and language combinations and categories and libraries that indicate and link to certain personality traits,” Nathan Mondragon said. “If teamwork is important and working with others is important, somebody is using word categories of I and me versus we, team, and people, pronoun usage is going to have an impact on that team’s orientation of working with others.” Here is my translation: if you use we and team a lot, it shows you are a team player at work.

一位参加教程的人总结道，这似乎很简单。对我来说，背景很重要。申请人是否被要求谈论领导团队的经历，或者他们独自从零开始的项目？这难道不重要吗？因为他们可能会更多地使用“我”而不是“我们”。

It seems very elementary, one of the attendees of the tutorial concluded. For me, context is everything. Was the applicant asked to talk about leading a team or about a project that they started alone from scratch? Wouldn’t that matter, since they would likely use more I than we?

在网络教程中，蒙德拉贡接着说道：“我举的代词用法的例子，是我们使用自然语言处理进行文本分析时的例子。它只是五万个数据点中的一个、两个，甚至五个数据点……反正任何特征都不会产生太大的影响。成千上万个特征叠加在一起，最终生成了结果。”

In the web tutorial, Mondragon then said: “The example I gave, pronoun usage, is an example of when we looked at the text analysis using natural language processing. That is one, two, maybe five data points out of what could be fifty thousand data points…. No feature has a lot of impact anyway. There are thousands of features rolled together to generate the results.”

我很高兴听到求职者不会因为过多使用“我”或“我们”而被拒绝，但那些经常说“我们”的人真的是团队合作者吗？这感觉太过简化了，而且完全没有体现我们作为团队成员的能力。

I am glad to hear that no job applicant would be rejected for using too much I or we alone, but is it really true that the folks who say we more often are team workers? It feels like an oversimplification and it isn’t saying anything about our capabilities as a team player.

克服偏见的挑战

THE CHALLENGE OF OVERCOMING BIAS

偏见是人工智能工具面临的真正威胁。根本问题不仅在于这些工具是否有效，还在于它们是否公平对待每个人。“确保不以任何方式植入偏见非常重要，”HireVue 首席数据科学家 Lindsey Zuloaga 表示。

Bias is a real threat with AI tools. The basic question is not only whether these tools work but also whether they treat everyone fairly. “Just making sure bias isn’t baked in in any way is really important,” said Lindsey Zuloaga, the chief data scientist at HireVue.

许多公司更喜欢使用人工智能工具而不是人工招聘，他们采纳供应商的营销信息，并声称这些工具没有偏见或偏见较少。

Many companies prefer AI tools to human hiring, and they adopt the vendors’ marketing messages and say that the tools are bias-free or less biased.

“我们向候选人承诺，我们将确保一致性和公平性，”达美航空前人才招聘副总裁詹妮弗·卡彭特 (Jennifer Carpenter) 在一段关于 HireVue 基于人工智能技术的宣传视频中说道。“包括 HireVue 使用人工智能进行的评估在内的一些评估，使我们能够确保尽可能消除偏见。”

“It’s a commitment to our candidates that we are ensuring consistency and fairness,” said Jennifer Carpenter, the former vice president of talent acquisition at Delta Air Lines, in a promotional video about HireVue’s AI-based technology. “Some of the assessments, including Hire­Vue’s assessment using AI, allow us to ensure that we are removing bias whenever we can.”

许多供应商进行偏见测试的方式如下：在招聘评估中，最常用的公平性检查方法是俗称的“五分之四规则”，这已成为美国的一项非正式招聘标准。美国就业监管机构之一——平等就业机会委员会 (EEOC) 于 1978 年发布了指导方针，规定招聘程序应选择大致相同比例的男性、女性和不同种族群体的人员。圣路易斯华盛顿大学法学教授 Pauline Kim 就我为《麻省理工学院技术评论》撰写的一篇文章，解释了“五分之四规则”。“如果男性 100% 通过了在招聘流程的下一步中，女性需要至少通过 80% 的评估。”所以，举例来说，如果有 1,000 名男性申请，其中 800 人通过评估，那么男性的通过率为 80%。现在假设也有 100 名女性申请。根据平等就业机会委员会的五分之四规则，要使评估被视为“公平”，至少需要有 64 名女性通过评估，因为女性的通过率为 64%（80% 的五分之四）。当然，80% 的女性通过评估才是公平的，因为通过率与男性相同，但五分之四规则允许一些回旋余地。

Here is how many vendors do bias testing: the most frequently used method of checking fairness in hiring assessments is what’s colloquially known as the four-fifths rule, which has become an informal hiring standard in the United States. The Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC), one of the regulators of work in the United States, released guidelines in 1978 stating that hiring procedures should select roughly the same proportion of men and women and people of different racial groups. Speaking to me for a piece I wrote for the MIT Technology Review, Pauline Kim, a law professor at the Washington University of St. Louis, explained the four-fifths rule. “If men were passing 100 percent of the time to the next step in the hiring process, women need to pass at least 80 percent of the time.” So, for example, if 1,000 men applied and 800 made it through the assessment, that is an 80 percent passing rate for men. Now let’s say that 100 women also applied. For the assessment to be considered “fair” under the four-fifths rule by the EEOC, then at least 64 women needed to make it through the assessment, because that is a passing rate for women of 64 percent (four-fifths of 80 percent). Of course, passing 80 percent of women through the assessment would be precisely fair, being the same passing rate as for men, but the four-fifths rule allows for some wiggle room.

如果一家公司的招聘工具违反了五分之四规则，平等就业机会委员会可能会对其做法进行更严格的审查。“对雇主来说，这并非空头支票，”金说道。“如果雇主确保这些工具不带有严重歧视性，它们很可能不会引起联邦监管机构的注意。”

If a company’s hiring tools violate the four-fifths rule, the EEOC might take a closer look at its practices. “For an employer, it’s not a bad check,” Kim said. “If employers make sure these tools are not grossly discriminatory, in all likelihood they will not draw the attention of federal regulators.”

一个缺点是，五分之四规则传统上并未进行交叉性检验，尤其未针对那些可能因属于少数族裔且是女性而受到歧视的人群。该规则会将男性与女性、不同种族群体进行比较，以查看他们是否以相似的比率通过考试，但不会将白人男性与亚裔美国人或拉丁美洲女性进行比较。“你可能会找到一些符合五分之四规则的测试结果，用于男性与女性、黑人与白人之间的比较，但它可能会掩盖对黑人女性的偏见，”金说道。

One drawback is that the four-fifths rule traditionally has not been tested for intersectionality, especially people who may be discriminated against because they are part of a racial minority and they are women. The rule compares men with women and one racial group with another to see if they pass at similar rates, but it doesn’t compare, for example, white men with Asian American or Latin American women. “You could have something that satisfied the four-fifths rule [for] men versus women, Blacks versus whites, but it might disguise a bias against Black women,” Kim said.

几年前，许多开发人员认为，如果不考虑年龄、种族、性别等因素，算法就“自然”不会出现偏差。“然而，人们天真地认为‘我们没有把这些因素输入模型，所以它就不会有偏差’。这显然是错误的，”Kim 说。

A few years back, many developers thought that algorithms would be “naturally” bias-free if age, race, gender, and so forth weren’t used. “People have been naive, though, to think that ‘we are not feeding that into our model, so it can’t be biased.’ That’s obviously not true,” Kim said.

当使用其他特征（即所谓的代理指标）时，与工作无关的人口统计数据可能会悄然出现。例如，一些雇主发现，员工居住地离工作地点越远，他们辞职的可能性更高。因此，拒绝来自某些邮政编码的申请人或许是有道理的。但在美国，或许在其他地方也是如此，邮政编码并非良性指标。

Non-job-related demographics can creep in when other features, so-called proxies, are used. For example, some employers have figured out that the farther an employee lives away from their worksite, the higher the chances of them quitting. So it might make sense to reject applicants from certain zip codes. But in the United States, and possibly in other places as well, zip codes are not benign proxies.

“鉴于美国种族隔离的历史，邮政编码实际上与种族高度相关，”埃默里大学法学院教授、人工智能和招聘专家伊菲奥玛·阿琼瓦 (Ifeoma Ajunwa) 表示。“所以，例如，如果招聘算法决定使用邮政编码，从技术上讲这并不违法。它没有使用种族。但在实践中，它是一种替代因素，可能会对少数族裔产生截然不同的影响。”

“Given the history of segregation in the United States, zip codes are actually highly correlated with race,” said Ifeoma Ajunwa, Emory University School of Law professor and an expert in AI and hiring. “So if, for example, a hiring algorithm decided to use zip codes, technically that’s not unlawful. It’s not using race. But in practice, it’s a proxy and it could have a disparate impact on racial minorities.”

我还采访了美国一家大型公司的人才招聘经理。他们的团队每天要筛选数百人。他们还遇到了另一个看似无害的代理，结果却存在种族偏见的例子。

I also spoke to a talent acquisition manager at one of the largest companies in the United States. Their team screens hundreds of people every day. They had another example of a benign-seeming proxy that turned out to be racially biased.

我不能透露此人的名字，因为该公司拒绝了我的正式采访请求。但此人认为分享此类信息很重要，所以我同意让他们进行背景采访。我可以引用他们的话，但不能透露他们的名字或他们所在的公司。

I can’t name this person because the company denied my official interview request. But this person believed it was important to share this kind of information, and so I agreed for them to speak on background. I am allowed to quote them, but I am not allowed to reveal their name or the company they work for.

在团队的研究中，他们发现，认识至少一名店员的求职者更有可能留任至少六个月。他们有朋友，有关系，比没有关系的人更深入地融入公司，因此他们的工作年限更长，而这正是公司期望的目标，因为招聘和培训新员工需要花费资金。

In the team’s research, they found that applicants who knew at least one person who worked in the store were more likely to stay at least six months. They have friends; they have a connection; they are more embedded than folks with no connections, so their work tenure is longer, which is a desired goal of the company because hiring and training new employees costs money.

因此，招聘团队开始询问求职者，他们认识多少在他们申请的门店工作的人。公司本可以将这个指标作为自动招聘工具的一项标准，因为它具有预测性，但人才招聘负责人希望首先深入挖掘，理解它为什么具有预测性。当他们按种族群体检查答案时，得到了令人惊讶的结果。

So the hiring team started asking job applicants how many people they knew who worked in the store where they are applying. The company could have used this proxy as one criterion in an automated hiring tool because it’s predictive, but the talent acquisition leader wanted to first dig deeper and understand why it’s predictive. When they checked the answers by racial groups, they got surprising results.

“你发现，亚裔美国人很可能认识店里的员工。但非裔美国人的情况则截然不同。他们通常不认识店里的任何员工。”他们说道。

“What you found was that for Asian Americans, they were very likely to know someone who worked at the store. For African Americans, it was a huge difference. They usually did not know anyone who worked in the store,” they said.

该公司决定不采用这一标准，因为尽管它具有预测性，但却引入了种族偏见。“如果你采用这一标准，就好像你不知道它到底是真的，还是只是种族/民族的替代品，”他们说。

The company decided not to use this criterion because, although it is predictive, it introduces racial bias. “If you implement that item, it’s like you don’t know if it’s really that item or that it’s just a surrogate for race/ethnicity,” they said.

只有当你知道自己在寻找什么样的偏见，并仔细检查你的招聘方法、问题和算法结果时，才能发现这种隐藏的偏见。“很难知道是否存在你不知道且没有衡量的地方，对吧？所以我认为这是一项持续进行的工作，”HireVue 首席数据科学家 Lindsey Zuloaga 说道。

You can only find this sort of hidden bias if you know what kind of bias you are looking for and you closely examine your hiring methods and questions and the results of your algorithms. “It’s really hard to know if there is bias baked in somewhere that you just don’t know about and you’re not measuring, right? So I think it’s a continual work in progress,” said Lindsey Zuloaga, HireVue’s chief data scientist.

持续偏见的危险

THE DANGER OF PERPETUATING BIAS

HireVue 的工具中使用了面部表情分析技术，这是一项颇具争议的技术。在求职面试中解读和分析面部表情公平吗？它能预测求职成功吗？

In its tools HireVue used facial expression analysis, a controversial technology. Is reading and analyzing facial expressions in job interviews fair? And does it work to predict job success?

HireVue 首席心理学家 Nathan Mondragon 表示：“如果你考虑面部运动，你会发现不同的面部动作会展现不同的情绪，比如微笑、皱眉、眉毛运动……以及面部肌肉的运动，微笑。在这里，你可以看到你开始微笑，嘴唇也开始卷曲。” 他指着 Jason Bellini 的视频说道，“这些都是实际的数据库数据点，它们共同作用，赋予了人们特定的情绪、特质、个性和思维方式。”

“If you think of facial movements,” said Nathan Mondragon, Hire­Vue’s chief psychologist, “there are emotions that are portrayed in different movements of the face, smiling and frowning, eyebrow movements…. The muscle movement of the face, smiling. Here you can see you’re starting to have a smile with the lip curl,” he said, pointing at Jason Bellini’s video. “Those are actual database points, and they roll together to give certain emotions and traits and personality and thinking styles.”

蒙德拉贡的意思是，HireVue 可以从我们面部肌肉的运动中提取出意义。

What Mondragon is saying is that HireVue can pull meaning out of the movements of the muscles in our face.

“所以，有些情绪可能是轻蔑、恐惧、愤怒、喜悦、惊讶、幸福。其中一些情绪和特质——并不意味着它们重要，而是当它们在统计上与工作表现相关时才重要，”蒙德拉贡说。“例如，对于零售工作或专业销售工作来说，积极主动和友好可能是一项重要的特质，但对于软件开发人员来说，它可能会产生相反的效果。”

“So, some would be contempt, fear, anger, joy, surprise, happiness. Some of those emotions and traits—it doesn’t mean they’re important, it means they’re important when it’s linked statistically to performance on the job,” Mondragon said. “For example, being engaging and friendly could be an important trait for a retail job or a professional sales job, but for a software developer, it might have an opposite effect.”

如果高绩效员工在面试中展现出相同的面部表情和情绪，那么这些情绪就很重要。这就是联系所在。

These emotions are important if high performers in the job showcase the same facial expressions and emotions during their job interviews. That’s the link.

内森·蒙德拉贡说，这些表情几乎是无意识地浮现在我们脸上的。他用杰森举了一个生动的例子：“如果我说，‘杰森，现在是星期五下午。我们刚认识。我打算给你一百万美元，但你只有一个周末的时间花光它。你会先买什么两样东西？’”

And Nathan Mondragon says the expressions come onto our faces almost unconsciously. He tries a live example with Jason: “If I said, ‘Jason, it’s Friday afternoon. We just met. I’m going to give you a million dollars, but you only have the weekend to spend it all. What would be the first two things you would buy?’”

“哦，你现在就问我？”杰森问。“如果你给我一百万美元让我周末花，但我只能买两件东西……嗯……”

“Oh, you are asking me right now?” Jason asked. “If you give me a million dollars to spend over the weekend and I can only buy two things … hmm …”

“就是它，”蒙德拉贡兴奋地喊道，吓了杰森一跳。“你的眼睛像这样向下看，然后‘嗯’地叫了一声。所以，两秒的视频捕捉，两秒的数据，但视频的每一微秒都被定格了，你的眼球向下移动，你的头部倾斜，你进入了另一种思维方式。很多时候，“眼睛向下看”意味着更深层次的思考方式，而向上看则可能是一种创造性的思维方式。”

“And there it is,” Mondragon yelled excitedly, startling Jason. “Your eye went like this and down and you went, ‘umm.’ So two seconds of a video capture, two seconds of data, but every microsecond of the video frame is frozen and your eye movement went down and your head tilted and you went into an alternative thinking style. A lot of times ‘eye going down’ means a deeper thinking style, and going up can be a creativity thinking style.”

蒙德拉贡表示，只有当算法在训练数据中发现了类似行为模式时，这种“思维风格”的例子才有意义。但是，求职者在面试中的思维风格与他们的最终工作表现究竟有何关联呢？

Mondragon said this example of “thinking styles” is only relevant if the algorithm has found a pattern of similar behaviors in the training data. But what do candidates’ thinking styles in job interviews have to do with their performance on the job?

正如我们所见，在这个新的招聘世界中，雇主似乎常常难以审阅收到的所有简历，而使用人工智能分析和排名潜在员工则显得更容易。然而，将求职者与现有员工进行比较并非没有陷阱。

As we have seen, in this new world of hiring, it seems like it’s often too burdensome for employers to go through all the résumés they receive and it feels much easier to have an AI analyze and rank potential employees. But comparing job applicants to current employees is not without pitfalls.

我与法学教授伊菲奥玛·阿琼瓦（Ifeoma Ajunwa）就此进行了探讨。她多年来一直研究算法决策在招聘中的应用，并多次在国会作证。“如果表现最佳的员工的面部表情能够预测其工作成功，那我们不应该在招聘中使用这类信息吗？”我问道。

I talked to law professor Ifeoma Ajunwa about this. She has studied algorithmic decision-making in hiring for years and has testified many times in front of Congress. “What if the facial expressions of the highest-performing employees are meaningful in predicting success on the job? Shouldn’t we use this kind of information in hiring?” I asked.

Ajunwa 又问了一个问题：“表现最佳者的人口结构是怎样的？” 她之所以提出这个问题，是因为在确定表现最佳者群体的过程中，可能存在历史和结构性偏见。“华尔街表现最佳者大多是男性。这是否意味着女性即使有机会也无法成为高绩效者？”

Ajunwa answered with another question: “What is the demographic of the highest performers?” She asks because there could be historical and structural biases at play in how the group of highest performers is determined. “The highest performers on Wall Street are mostly men. Does that mean women can’t be high performers if given the chance?”

我们知道女性也可以表现优异。但问题是，如果一家公司的高绩效员工名单和数据集中大部分是男性，算法可能会识别出男性的面部表情、语气和用词，并将其与高绩效联系起来，即使这可能与工作所需的技能或特质无关。这可能只是男性比女性更多地使用面部表情或用词。

We know women can be high performers. But the problem is that if a company has mostly men in their high-performer list and in their data sets, the algorithm might pick up men’s facial expressions, their tones, and the words they use and equate that with high performance, even though it may have nothing to do with any skills or traits one needs for the job. It could just be facial expressions or words that more men use than women.

这可能会降低一些女性表达的权重，就像亚马逊简历解析器所发生的情况一样，由于它是根据主要来自男性申请人的数据进行训练的，因此它降低了人们简历中“女性”一词的权重。

That could down-weight some women’s expressions, just like what happened with the Amazon résumé parser that down-weighted the term women on people’s résumés because it was trained on data from mostly male applicants.

另一个问题是，高绩效者最初是如何成为高绩效者的？

The other question is, How did the high performers become high performers in the first place?

“这就是使用高绩效的问题，因为你真的必须问，‘一家公司过去是否给予过平等的机会给“你希望每个人都成为高绩效者吗？’除非你能回答‘是’，否则你的高绩效者样本就已经存在偏差了，”Ajunwa 说。

“That’s the problem with using high performance, because you really have to ask, ‘Did a company in the past give an equal opportunity to everyone to be a high performer?’ And unless you can answer that question ‘yes,’ then your sample of high performers is already biased,” Ajunwa said.

另外，如果我们想在未来实现员工队伍的多元化，那么利用过去雇佣过的员工来训练人工智能，使其基于过去的招聘决策，是否合理？难道我们不想吸引不同的员工吗？

Also, if we want to diversify our workforce going forward, does it make sense to use a pool of employees hired in the past to train the AI on essentially past hiring decisions? Wouldn’t we want to attract different employees?

“当你观察我的整个面部表情并试图匹配精确的面部表情时，这并不一定会产生思维上的多样性，因为你试图匹配非常相似的人，”阿朱瓦说。

“When you’re looking at my full facial expressions and you’re trying to match exact facial expressions, that’s not necessarily going to create diversity in thought because you’re trying to match people who are quite similar,” Ajunwa said.

她表示，科学已经证明，多元化的群体能够创造更佳的商业成果。如果仅仅依靠绩效高低的人员来构建数据集，而不是依靠与工作相关的具体想法和技能，也可能会引入与工作无关的随机特征。

Science has shown that diverse groups of people produce better business results, she said. Relying on high and low performers to build a data set and not the concrete ideas and skills that are tied to the job could also bring in random features that have nothing to do with the job.

如果面部表情与工作无关呢？选择可以完全随机，仅依赖于用于训练算法的主导群体的特征。例如，有些人生气时会哭，但计算机会根据他们流泪的面部表情推断出他们很悲伤。

What if facial expressions have nothing to do with the job? The selection could be totally random and just rely on the features of the dominant group that was used to train the algorithm. For example, some people cry when they are angry, but the computer would infer from their tearful facial expression that they are sad.

也许一家公司里的高绩效员工都喜欢滑雪，但这和工作有什么关系吗？是不是所有高绩效员工都毕业于哈佛大学，所以哈佛大学最适合应聘者？还是过去的招聘经理更喜欢哈佛毕业生？

Maybe the high performers in a company all like snowboarding, but does that have anything to do with the job? Did all the high performers go to Harvard and so Harvard best prepares candidates for the job? Or did a hiring manager in the past prefer people who graduated from Harvard?

求职面试中的面部表情和语调可能和头发颜色一样随机。如果我们在视频面试中观察表现优异的人，发现大多数人都是棕色头发，那么无监督算法就能发现这一点，并只选择棕色头发的人。当然，人类知道头发颜色与工作无关，但计算机却不知道——它只寻找统计上的联系，而不关心这种联系是随机的还是有意义的。

It could be that facial expressions and the intonation in our voices in job interviews are just as random as hair color. If we look at high performers in video interviews and most people have brown hair, an unsupervised algorithm could pick up on that and choose only people with brown hair. Of course, a human would know that hair color has nothing to do with the job, but a computer wouldn’t—it just looks for a statistical connection and doesn’t care if the connection is random or meaningful.

Ifeoma Ajunwa 认为，提高透明度将是理解针对高绩效者训练的算法是否真正有效的关键。如果透明度足够高，其他人，包括像她这样的学者，就可以核实结果。

Ifeoma Ajunwa believes that more transparency will be the key to understanding whether algorithms trained on high performers really work. If there is transparency, other people, including academics like her, can check the results.

“雇主可能不知道，”她说。“而且也没有办法向申请人解释这个决定。我觉得这很不对，因为想想看，当我们申请信贷被拒时，我们有权进行审查，我们会收到一封信，告诉我们被拒的具体原因。但当涉及到像生计这样重要的事情，比如有机会养活自己、穿衣打扮，我们没权利仅仅因为一个机器或算法做出了这个决定就进行审查。所以这似乎是有问题的。”

“The employer may not know,” she said. “And then there’s no way to explain the decision to the applicant. And this strikes me as wrong, because if you think about it, when we apply for credit and we’re denied, we have a right to review, we get a letter that tells us exactly why we were denied credit. But when it comes to something as important as our livelihood, as having the opportunity to feed ourselves and clothe ourselves, we don’t have a right to review just because a machine or an algorithm made that decision. So this seems problematic.”

Ajunwa 承认，在传统的招聘流程中，大多数情况下求职者都不会被告知被拒绝的原因，但她希望招聘经理能够知道他们选择这个候选人而不是另一个候选人的原因。

Ajunwa acknowledges that most of the time applicants in traditional hiring processes are also not told why they were denied the job, but she hopes that hiring managers would know the reason why they chose one candidate over another.

也许这种完全透明正是我们在招聘过程中应该努力追求的？这样，我们就可以确保招聘算法和人工招聘经理的责任，同时也可以讨论如何让招聘和算法在工作中的使用对每个人都更加公平公正。

Maybe this full transparency is something we should strive for in the hiring process anyway? This way, we could keep hiring algorithms and human hiring managers accountable and also discuss how we can make hiring and using algorithms at work more equitable and fair for everyone.

解读面孔

READING FACES

计算机真的能从我们的面部表情中读出我们的情绪吗？软件的功能是什么？它的准确度如何？我们每个人的情绪都一样吗？这些情绪在我们每个人的脸上都以同样的方式表现出来吗？我对此表示怀疑。

Can a computer really read our emotions on our face? What does the software do and how accurate is it? Do we all experience the same emotions and are they represented the same way on all of our faces? I have my doubts.

我敢打赌，很多人像我一样，多年来都被人误读过自己的面部表情，或者误读过别人的表情。几年前，我有个学生，他平淡的面部表情总是看起来很悲伤。我们经常问她是否还好，或者感觉难过——她会说她感觉很好。我们只是误解了她的表情。

Many people, I bet, like me, have had their facial expressions misread over the years or have misread others’. I had one student a few years back whose neutral facial expression always looked sad. We would often ask her if she was okay or feeling sad—and she would say that she was feeling absolutely fine. We just misread her facial expression.

说实话，我个人对面部表情被误读这件事很不满。我经常遇到这种情况，因为我长着一张所谓的“臭脸”。这些年来，学生们总是问我是不是在生他们的气，而我当时只是在说话，看起来很正常（或者说我当时是这么想的！）。显然，我平常的表情有时会被误认为是愤怒的。算法很可能会把我的面部表情归类为愤怒——仅仅因为我的眉头即使在放松的时候也会微微皱起——尽管我当时可能并没有感到愤怒。

And to be honest, I have a personal beef with facial expressions being misread. It has happened to me a bunch because I have what some call a resting bitch face. Over the years, students have asked me if I am angry with them when I am just talking and looking normal (or so I thought!). Apparently, my neutral face is sometimes misperceived as angry. An algorithm would likely classify my facial expression as angry—just because my brows are slightly furrowed even when I am relaxed—although I might not feel anger at that moment.

所以，如果面试中表现优异的人没有表现出“愤怒”的表情，那么在面试中使用面部表情分析可能会给我带来负面影响。我可能会因为我的“臭脸”而被拒绝。（顺便说一句，我现在留着长刘海遮住眉毛，所以很久没遇到过“臭脸”的问题了。）

So using facial expression analysis in job interviews could turn out negatively for me if high performers in the job were not using “angry” facial expressions during their job interviews. I might get rejected for my “resting bitch face.” (As a side note, I now wear long bangs covering my brows, and so I haven’t encountered the resting-bitch-face problem in a while.)

另一个误读面部表情的好例子是，有人在微笑，但并不开心。我经常在尴尬的场合强迫自己微笑，包括在求职面试中。在这种情况下，计算机算法很可能会把我归类为开心，尽管我的感觉恰恰相反。

Another good example of misreading facial expressions is people who are smiling, but are not happy. I have often forced myself to smile in awkward situations, including in job interviews. In such instances, a computer algorithm would likely classify me as happy, although I am feeling the opposite.

为了理解情绪和面部表情的科学原理，我咨询了一位专家——丽莎·费尔德曼·巴雷特（Lisa Feldman Barrett）。她是马萨诸塞州波士顿东北大学的杰出心理学教授。她是一位中年教授，语速很快，留着齐肩的棕色长发，几十年来一直在研究情绪。

To understand the science of emotions and facial expressions, I consulted an expert, Lisa Feldman Barrett, a university distinguished professor of psychology at Northeastern University in Boston, Massachusetts. She is a fast-talking middle-aged professor with shoulder-length brown hair who has studied emotions for decades.

我们交谈时，她刚刚完成了一项重要的研究，而这项研究正是我想要问她的问题。我们每个人的面部表情表达情绪的方式都一样吗？（面部运动算法是否能够捕捉到这一点，并真正检测到我们的情绪？）

When we spoke, she had just finished a major research endeavor tackling the exact question I wanted to ask her. Do we all express our emotions the same on our faces? (And is a facial movement algorithm able to pick this up and essentially detect our emotions?)

她这样描述她的研究：“我们的主要问题是“是否存在普遍的面部表情来表达情绪？人们在生气、害怕或高兴时，面部表情是否具有普遍性？他们是否能以普遍的方式识别某些面部结构作为情绪表达？”巴雷特与来自不同学科、持有不同观点的合著者们在两年多的时间里每周开会，阅读了一千多篇论文。

Here is how she described her research: “Our major question was whether there are universal facial expressions of emotion, and whether people move their faces in universal ways when they’re angry or when they’re afraid or when they’re happy. And do they recognize certain facial configurations as expressions of emotion in a universal way?” Barrett and her coauthors from different disciplines with opposing viewpoints met weekly for more than two years and read over a thousand papers.

多年来，心理学主要依赖于保罗·艾克曼（Paul Ekman）在 20 世纪六七十年代的研究和理论，这些理论认为情绪（几乎）是普遍存在的。该理论认为，每个人都至少会感受到六种基本情绪。这些情绪通过大致相同的面部表情来表达，几乎每个人都能识别，因此计算机也能检测到。（内森·蒙德拉贡（Nathan Mondragon）在解释 HireVue 使用的面部运动检测分析时特别引用了艾克曼的研究。）

For many years, psychology mainly relied on Paul Ekman’s studies and theories from the 1960s and 1970s that stated emotions are (almost) universal. The idea is that everyone feels at least six base emotions. These emotions are indicated by roughly the same facial expressions that almost every human can recognize, and therefore computers could detect too. (Nathan Mondragon specifically referenced Ekman’s research in his explanation of the facial movement detection analysis HireVue uses.)

丽莎·巴雷特和其他科学家采用了其他研究方法，并发现了其他情况：“现在有针对非洲多种文化的研究，也有针对巴布亚新几内亚其他文化的研究，当你开始剥离方法的各个部分时，所有普遍性的证据都会土崩瓦解，”巴雷特说。

Lisa Barrett and other scientists used other research methods and found something else: “Now there are studies with many cultures in Africa, other studies with other cultures in Papua New Guinea, and when you start to peel away the parts of the method, all the evidence for universality really falls apart,” Barrett said.

巴雷特说，与其说每个人的情绪表达都相似，不如说“你看到的是可靠的差异”。人们在面部表情上表达情绪的方式存在差异。例如，巴雷特研究了皱眉是否可靠地出现在愤怒的场景中。我们是否曾看到皱眉表达愤怒以外的其他情绪？

Instead of finding that everyone has similar expressions for emotions, “what you see is reliable variation,” Barrett said. There are differences in how people express emotions on their faces. For example, Barrett investigated whether scowling is reliably seen in episodes of anger. And do we ever see scowling expressing emotions other than anger?

“当然，人们生气时皱眉的次数比你预料的要多，但他们皱眉的程度不足以让人相信这是愤怒的表现。这只是人们众多表情中的一种，”巴雷特说。“所以人们会因愤怒而哭泣；会因愤怒而微笑；会因愤怒而睁大眼睛。事实上，睁大眼睛喘息的表情被认为是恐惧的普遍表现，但在美拉尼西亚，它更像是一种威胁或愤怒的表情……人们的面部表情多种多样，当他们不生气时，当他们集中注意力时，当他们非常专注时，当他们胀气时，他们都会皱眉。

“Sure, people scowl more than you would expect by chance when they’re angry, but they don’t scowl with the degree of reliability that would be required to say that this is the expression of anger. It’s one expression out of many expressions that people make,” Barrett said. “So people can cry in anger; they can smile in anger; they can widen their eyes in anger. In fact, the wide-eyed gasping face that is supposed to be the universal expression of fear is more like a threat or anger face, for example, in Melanesia…. People move their faces in many ways and people scowl when they are not angry, when they’re concentrating, when they are really focused, when they have gas.”

也许我是那种在集中注意力时会下意识地皱眉的人。

Maybe I am one of the folks who is subconsciously scowling when I am concentrating.

巴雷特表示，她的研究表明，心理学界目前普遍认为面部表情和潜在情绪具有多变性，但基于人工智能的面部运动技术——情感人工智能——却停留在过时的普遍情绪旧理论中。“如果你把人工智能看作这类研究的消费者，你会发现他们使用的是一个非常刻板的模型。他们的整个科学体系都建立在这个模型之上，这本身就存在很大问题。”

Barrett said her research shows that the consensus in psychology is now that facial expressions and underlying emotions have variability, but the AI-based facial movement technologies called affective AI are stuck in the old theory of universal emotions that, she said, is outdated. “If you think about AI as being sort of a consumer of this research, they’re using the very stereotypical model. That’s what they’ve built their whole science around and it’s hugely problematic.”

“计算机视觉是一项非常棒的面部运动检测技术，”巴雷特继续说道，比如捕捉我皱眉的幅度，但它无法帮助猜测这些动作背后可能蕴含的情绪。“它无法告诉你这些动作的含义，也无法告诉你情绪的含义，它只能告诉你动作本身。所以，当一家公司说‘我们能读懂快乐、悲伤和愤怒’时，他们的意思是，他们能捕捉到微笑、皱眉和怒容，但他们并不真正了解这些情绪的含义。他们混淆了测量结果和对测量结果的解读。”

“Computer vision is a fantastic technology for detecting facial movements,” continued Barrett, like capturing how much I am furrowing my brow, but it’s not helpful to guess the possible emotions behind those movements. “It tells you nothing about the meaning of those movements. It tells you nothing about the emotional meaning. It only tells you the movements. And so when a company says, ‘We can read happiness and sadness and anger,’ what they mean is that they can capture smiles and frowns and scowls and they don’t really know what the emotional meaning is. They confuse the measurement with the interpretation of the measurement.”

那么，如果计算机捕捉到的面部动作不具有普遍意义，我们为什么要在面试中使用它们呢？对于特定工作中所需的面部表情，并没有科学依据，除非那些整天与顾客打交道的人可能想多笑笑，才能……被认为有帮助。但是，计算机工程师需要什么样的面部表情呢？教授？实验室助理？保险经纪人？仓库工人？需要明确的是，HireVue 衡量的不是工作中可能与工作无关的面部表情，而是面试时的面部表情。这就引出了一个问题：面试中的面部表情、潜在情绪或“思维方式”与人们在特定工作中的表现有何关联。

So, if the facial movements that a computer captures don’t carry universal meaning, why would we use them in job interviews? There is no science about facial expressions you need in a given job, except maybe folks who work with customers all day may want to smile a lot to be perceived as helpful. But what facial expressions do computer engineers need? Professors? Lab assistants? Insurance brokers? Warehouse workers? And to be clear, HireVue doesn’t measure facial expressions on the job that may or may not be job relevant, but it measures facial expressions in job interviews. It begs the question what facial expressions and underlying emotions or “thinking styles” in job interviews have to do with how well people perform in a given job.

“动作和动作的意义是有区别的。有些人低头可能是因为他们在思考，而另一些人低头可能是因为他们在看笔记。我的意思是，这里的重点是，动作本身并没有意义，”她说。“面部表情不是通往心灵的窗户。”

“There’s a difference between a movement and the meaning of the movement. It could be that some people are looking down because they’re thinking and other people are looking down because they’re looking at their notes. I mean, the point here is that the movements don’t have inherent meaning,” she said. “The face is not a window into the mind.”

丽莎·巴雷特还表示，“思维方式”并没有科学依据。“我们根本不知道一个人向上或向下看究竟意味着什么，”她说。

Lisa Barrett also said that “thinking styles” are not supported by sound science. “We just don’t know what the meaning is of someone looking up or down,” she said.

放弃面部分析

GIVING UP ON FACIAL ANALYSIS

当丽莎·巴雷特 (Lisa Barrett) 和其他专家公开表示他们不相信面部运动技术能够准确推断我们的情绪时，HireVue 突然改变了在其产品中使用面部表情分析的态度。

As Lisa Barrett and other experts publicly shared that they didn’t believe facial movement technology could accurately infer our emotions, HireVue suddenly changed its tune about using facial expression analysis in their products.

2018 年，凯文·帕克 (Kevin Parker) 告诉我，HireVue 的 AI 产品取得了“巨大的成功”。

In 2018, Kevin Parker told me that HireVue was seeing “tremendous success” with its AI product.

2019 年，电子隐私信息中心 (EPIC) 向联邦贸易委员会提交了一份投诉，指控 HireVue“从事不公平和/或欺骗性贸易行为”。EPIC 提出了一系列担忧，其中包括 HireVue 采取的以下方法：计算求职者的分数的方法求职者并不知道，甚至 HireVue 本身也常常不知道。

In 2019, the Electronic Privacy Information Center (EPIC) filed a complaint with the Federal Trade Commission alleging that HireVue “engaged in unfair and/or deceptive trade practices.” EPIC had a long list of concerns, among them that the methods HireVue employed to calculate a job applicant’s score were not known by the job applicant and often not even known by HireVue itself.

2021年1月，在EPIC投诉、我在《华尔街日报》发表的调查报道、《华盛顿邮报》对HireVue的另一篇曝光文章以及其他一些持怀疑态度的报道——所有这些报道都质疑面部表情分析在招聘中的合理性——之后，HireVue宣布将逐步淘汰面部表情分析。HireVue前首席执行官凯文·帕克在接受《连线》杂志采访时表示：“它确实为客户增加了一些价值，但不值得担忧。”

In January 2021, after the EPIC complaint, my investigative report in the Wall Street Journal, another exposé of HireVue in the Washington Post, and other skeptical coverage—all questioning the soundness of facial expression analysis in hiring—HireVue announced that it was phasing out facial expression analysis. “It was adding some value for customers, but it wasn’t worth the concern,” HireVue’s former CEO Kevin Parker said to Wired.

当时，我们与帕克和首席数据科学家林赛·祖洛阿加（Lindsey Zuloaga）通了电话。我和同事特别询问了他们，​​为什么决定放弃他们长期捍卫的面部表情分析。他们说，原因是自然语言处理技术已经进步了很多，不再需要分析面部表情了。

At the time, we jumped on a call with Parker and chief data scientist Lindsey Zuloaga. My colleague and I asked them specifically why they decided to drop the facial expression analysis that they had defended for so long. The reason, they said, was that natural language processing technology has gotten so much better and there was no longer any need to analyze facial expressions.

帕克说：“我们一开始就认为这有助于理解，结果发现它与口语所传达的内容重叠。”

“We started out with this idea that it was going to be helpful to understand, and it turned out that it just overlapped with what the spoken word was communicating,” Parker said.

那么，为什么这么多年还要使用面部表情分析，如果与求职者说的话有重叠，还要对人们进行这种侵入性测试呢？难道是因为 HireVue 没有检查过吗？

Then why use facial expression analysis in the first place for all these years and subject people to the invasive practice if it overlapped with the words that job applicants said? Maybe because HireVue hadn’t checked?

但根本问题当然并未消失。HireVue 在 2021 年开始逐步淘汰面部表情分析后，仍然为在视频面试中使用语调分析辩护。Lisa Barrett 认为，语调分析与面部表情分析有着同样的根本问题：这种分析缺乏科学依据。

But of course the underlying problem is not gone. After HireVue started phasing out the facial expression analysis in 2021, it still defended using tone-of-voice analysis in video interviews, something Lisa Barrett says has the same underlying problems as facial expression analysis: there is no science underpinning this kind of analysis.

2022 年 4 月，我读到了 Lindsey Zuloaga 为 HireVue 撰写的一篇新博客文章。文章结尾处悄悄提到，在取消面部表情分析功能一年后，该公司现在也逐步淘汰语调分析。我向她咨询了他们为什么要取消这项服务。她提出了与公司一年前相同的理由：语调分析并没有带来显著的好处。HireVue 现在将只使用候选人的用词。

Then in April 2022, I read a new blog post Lindsey Zuloaga had written for HireVue. Near the end, it was quietly mentioned that a year after removing the facial expression analysis, the company was now also phasing out the tone-of-voice analysis. I checked in with her and asked why they were dropping it. She used the same argument the company had made a year earlier: there was no significant benefit from tone-of-voice analysis. HireVue will now just be using the words candidates say.

这不禁让人质疑：为什么公司在 2021 年移除面部表情分析功能时，没有同时移除语音分析功能？在那个时候，甚至更早的时候，语音分析功能对招聘结果没有任何帮助，这难道不是显而易见的吗？如果它从来没带来什么提升，为什么公司这么多年一直用它来筛选求职者？HireVue 知道它到底有没有用吗？这种对技术的滥用，难道不会导致很多人被错误地筛选掉吗？

It raises the questions: Why didn’t the company remove the voice analysis in 2021 when it removed the facial expression analysis? At that time or even much earlier, wouldn’t it have been clear that it was not adding anything? And if it was never adding much, why did the company use it to screen job applicants for all those years? Did HireVue even know whether it worked or didn’t work? Wouldn’t this misuse of technology lead to lots of people erroneously getting screened out?

如今，为了构建一个模型来识别求职面试中的特质和能力，HireVue 聘请了训练有素的主题专家，手动审核视频面试文件，并使用评分标准来评估应聘者是否展现出团队合作精神、追求成果或其他特质和能力。这些分数以及应聘者的用语将成为算法的训练数据，用于与求职者进行比较和排名。

Today, to build a model to determine traits and competencies from job interviews, HireVue uses trained subject matter experts to manually review the video interview files and use a rubric to check whether someone demonstrates team orientation, drive for results, or other traits and competencies. These scores and the words that the applicants say become the training data for the algorithm that job applicants are compared to and ranked against.

我很高兴听到 HireVue 最终放弃了面部表情和语音语调分析。但在 AI 工具中使用不科学的方法就像打地鼠游戏。一家公司放弃了一种颇具争议的方法，又出现了另一种简陋的方法，或者其中一些 AI 方法又在不同的产品中回归。新的 AI 工具不断涌现，它们使用面部表情和语调分析来评判求职者，或在视频通话中广泛使用该技术。供应商常常感觉自己根本不学习——或者不想学习。

I was glad to hear that HireVue finally dropped facial expression and voice intonation analysis. But using unscientific methods in AI tools is like a game of Whack-A-Mole. One company drops a controversial method, another rudimentary method shows up or some of these AI methods return in different products. New AI tools have cropped up that use facial expression and tone-of-voice analysis to judge job applicants or use the technology generally in video calls. It often feels like vendors just don’t learn—or don’t want to learn.

埃森哲人才与组织绩效实践前董事总经理 Brian Kropp 对众多进入这个拥挤领域的 AI 技术工具有着令人惊讶的看法。新技术正在他说，解决问题是解决问题，而不是解决问题。例如，面部表情分析几年前就出现了。一些人工智能供应商想出售这项技术，并认为将其推广给企业用于招聘可能会有用。但他们忽略了一个重要的问题：“我们究竟在解决什么问题？” Kropp问道。

Brian Kropp, former managing director in talent and organizational performance practice at Accenture, has a surprising view of the many AI tech tools coming into this crowded arena. It is new technology looking for a problem to solve, he said, rather than the other way around. For example, facial expression analysis came out a few years back. Some AI vendors wanted to sell the technology and decided it might be useful to market it for companies to use in hiring. But they are missing an impor­tant point: “What problem were we actually solving?” Kropp asked.

在他看来，这些都是自找麻烦的解决方案，很多方案可能并不适用于招聘。“技术进步的速度完全超出了大多数人力资源主管掌握这些技术并思考如何利用它们的能力，”克罗普说道。

In his view, these are solutions in search of a problem and many may not work for hiring. “The technology advances are just completely outpacing most HR executives’ ability to take that technology and figure out what to do with it,” Kropp said.

即使一家公司决定取消某个有争议的功能，另一家公司也会尝试，即便科学家早已揭穿了这些方法的真相。历史总是在实时重演。

Even if one company decides to get rid of a controversial feature, another will try it, even though scientists have already debunked the methods. History repeats itself in real time.

电话面试

PHONE INTERVIEWS

在一次人力资源技术会议上，我看到一份公司介绍引起了我的注意。Curious Thing AI 前副总裁马克·亚当斯 (Mark Adams) 声称，该公司的人工智能可以通过基于人工智能的自动电话面试，自动了解求职者的性格和英语水平。

At an HR tech conference, I saw a company presentation that caught my attention. Mark Adams, the former vice president of Curious Thing AI, claimed that the company’s AI could automatically find a person’s personality and their competency in speaking English by conducting automated AI-based phone interviews.

这项服务旨在招聘海外呼叫中心员工，因为许多西方公司试图将客户服务部门外包，但必须确保客服人员能够熟练掌握英语。该公司总部位于澳大利亚，亚当斯表示，自新冠疫情爆发以来，公司业务量增长了两倍，当时公司需要从面对面面试转向远程面试。许多公司选择了Curious Thing提供的全自动解决方案。2020年，该公司分析了约200万分钟的面试。如果平均面试时间约为15分钟，那么该公司的人工智能已经分析了约13万次面试。Curious Thing 表示，它为客户降低了 65% 的招聘成本。

The service is aimed at hiring call center employees abroad because a lot of Western companies try to outsource their customer service departments but must ensure that agents have a good command of English. The company’s headquarters is in Australia and Adams said that its volume of business has tripled since the beginning of the COVID pandemic, when companies needed to switch from face-to-face to remote interviews. Many chose the fully automated solution Curious Thing offers. In 2020, the company analyzed about two million minutes of interviews. If the average interview takes about fifteen minutes, the company’s AI has analyzed about 130,000 interviews. Curious Thing says it lowered hiring costs for its clients by 65 percent.

在演示中，亚当斯以应聘者的身份打电话来演示该工具。一个女声响起：“欢迎参加由 Curious Thing AI 主持的数字面试。我叫 Christine。非常感谢您今天加入我们。这将是一个简短的面试，包含六到十个问题。请记住，我认为答案没有对错之分。您可以将其视为一次分享会。我的话说得够多了。我迫不及待地想了解更多关于您的信息。我们开始吧。您是美国公民还是永久居民？”

In the presentation, Adams demonstrates the tool by calling in as an applicant. A female voice starts speaking: “Welcome to the digital interview hosted by Curious Thing AI. My name is Christine. Thank you very much for joining me today. It will be a short interview of six to ten questions. Please remember, I don’t think there are right or wrong answers here. You can treat this as a sharing session. Enough of me talking. I can’t wait to know more about you. Let’s start. Are you a US citizen or permanent resident?”

（第一个问题已经让我感到疑惑了。你在面试时不必回答这个问题可能是有原因的——这个问题在法律上是有问题的，因为雇主不能基于国籍进行歧视。但我跑题了。）

(The first question already raises my eyebrows. There might be a reason why you haven’t had to answer that question in a job interview—the question is legally problematic because employers can’t discriminate on the basis of national origin. But I digress.)

在演示过程中，亚当斯不断回答标准面试问题，包括：

During the demo, Adams keeps answering standard interview questions, including these:

• “您为什么申请这个客户服务代表职位？”

•“Why did you apply for this customer service representative role?”

• “您认为自己五年后会怎样？”

•“Where do you see yourself in five years’ time?”

• “你会如何处理一个难缠的客户的询问？请举个例子。”

•“How would you handle an inquiry from a difficult customer? Please give me an example.”

• “请告诉我您发现客户难以理解的一次经历。”

•“Please tell me about a time when you found a customer difficult to understand.”

然后，他解释了该工具如何分析申请人：“人工智能实际上是在聆听口头表达，然后将其实时转换为文本。分析只是基于对话文本。因此，我们的人工智能分析的是候选人说了什么，而不是他们说话的方式。”亚当斯说。

He then explains how the tool analyzes applicants: “The AI is actually listening to the spoken word and then it’s being streamed into text in real time. And the analysis is just done on the text of the conversation. So it’s just what the candidate says, not how they say it, which is analyzed by our AI,” Adams says.

然后，招聘人员可以根据对他们来说最重要的标准对候选人进行排名：“因此，根据我的经验，英语、适应力、客户关注度、团队合作精神等等，可以立即获得最适合该特定职位的候选人子集。”

A recruiter can then rank the candidates according to which criteria are most important to them: “So English, resilience, customer focus, teamwork, and so forth to really instantly get a subset of the candidates who are the best fit for this particular role based on my experience.”

为了测试这项技术，我购买了每月 199 美元的订阅服务。马克·亚当斯说得对：创建账户并开始使用非常简单。我从一系列特质中，选择了韧性、谦逊和适应性。其他可以选择的特质包括商业敏锐度、积极性、客户至上、团队合作、解决问题能力等等。

To test the technology, I bought a monthly subscription for $199. Mark Adams was right: it was pretty easy to set up an account and get started. From a list of attributes, I chose resilience, humility, and adaptivity. Other traits I could have chosen were business acumen, motivation, customer focus, teamwork, problem-solving, and a few others.

我邀请来面试的第一个人就是我自己。

The first person I invited to take the interview was myself.

我拨通了电话，接通了数字面试官克里斯汀。她让我回答一个关于艰难工作环境的问题。我主动告诉她，我曾经有一位事无巨细的老板，并且告诉他很难对付。回答完所有问题后，我终于看到了结果。我的适应性得分为0.77，韧性得分为0.77，谦逊得分为0.78。有趣的是，这些分数基本上是一样的。

I dialed the number and got Christine, the digital interviewer. She asked me to answer the question about a tough work situation. I went ahead and told her I once had a boss who was a micromanager and how tough that was to deal with. After answering all the questions, I was able to see my results. I scored 0.77 on adaptability, 0.77 on resilience, and 0.78 on humility. Interesting that they were essentially the same scores.

我的英语能力也得到了8.5分（满分9分），我的技能水平达到了专家级。我不得不说，我对这个分数感到自豪——我是美国移民，英语是我的第二语言。

I also scored 8.5 out of 9 on English competency and my skill level was ranked expert. I have to say I felt proud of the number—I am an immigrant in the United States and English is my second language.

然后，我用不同的邮箱地址再次邀请自己参加同样的数字面试。我想知道这些系统在异常情况下的表现，以便更清楚地了解人工智能的工作原理。

I then invited myself to the same digital interview again using a different email address. I wanted to know how these systems behaved in unusual circumstances, which could show more clearly how the AI worked.

我参加过很多人力资源会议，也和很多供应商交流过。他们反复告诉我，如果有人说话有问题，如果识别他人声音有问题，或者现场一片寂静，软件就能识别出这些问题。

I have attended numerous HR conferences and have talked with a lot of vendors. They repeatedly told me that if someone had issues speaking, if there was a problem with the detection of another person’s voice, or if there was silence, the software would recognize the problem.

所以我想读一篇德语（我的母语）的文章。克里斯汀问完每个问题后，我都会用德语阅读维基百科。心理测量学的条目，广泛涉及心理学的测量。

So I thought I would read a text in German, my native language. After every question Christine asked, I read in German the Wikipedia entry for psychometrics, which deals broadly with measurements in psychology.

这是我读到的内容：Die Psychometrie ist das Gebiet der Psychologie, das sich allgemein mit Theorie und Methode des Psychologischen Messens befasst ……等等。我没有说出任何英语单词。

Here is what I read: Die Psychometrie ist das Gebiet der Psychologie, das sich allgemein mit Theorie und Methode des psychologischen Messens befasst … And so on and so forth. No words in English crossed my lips.

我以为用德语回答完所有问题后，系统会发来一条错误消息，说无法计算任何分数。

I thought after answering all the questions in German I would get an error message from the system saying it couldn’t compute any scores.

当我收到结果信息时，我大吃一惊。事实上，AI 给我的英语能力评分是 6 分（满分 9 分），总体而言，我的英语水平被认为是“合格的”。

I was surprised when I got a message with the results. In fact, the AI gave me a score of 6 out of 9 for English competency, and overall my skill level in English was deemed “competent.”

为了安全起见，我又做了一次测试，用德语阅读了同样的文章。我的成绩依然是6分（满分9分），我的英语水平被认为“合格”。

Just to be safe, I did the test again, reading the same text in German. Again, I scored a 6 out of 9 and my skill level in English was deemed “competent.”

结果让我感到惊讶，因此我用另一个 AI 工具 myInterview 做了类似的实验。

The results surprised me, so I did a similar experiment with another AI tool, myInterview.

观察自己的乐趣

THE JOY OF WATCHING YOURSELF

MyInterview 是一款类似于 HireVue 的视频面试工具。该公司总部位于以色列。

MyInterview is a video interviewing tool similar to HireVue’s. The company is based in Israel.

该公司联合创始人兼首席执行官本杰明·吉尔曼（Benjamin Gillman）告诉我，大约有四千家中小型公司使用该工具。超过 340 万名候选人通过myInterview.com参加了面试。

The company’s cofounder and CEO, Benjamin Gillman, told me that around four thousand small to medium companies use the tool. Over 3.4 million candidates have interviewed with myInterview.com.

与 HireVue 类似，在myInterview.com上，求职者可以通过手机或电脑接收问题，并录制自己的回答过程，无需人工干预。然后，该工具会根据生成的语音转文本转录，分析求职者的语调和用词。

Similar to HireVue, at myInterview.com, job applicants receive questions on their phone or their computer and record themselves answering with no human on the other side. The tool then analyzes the intonation of an applicant’s voice and the words they say, based on a speech-to-text transcript the tool generates.

招聘经理会收到一个匹配分数——本质上就是候选人与职位的匹配程度。招聘经理还会查看五个因素性格分数可以预测候选人的认真程度、创新程度等等。

The hiring manager is sent a match score—essentially, how good a fit the candidate is for the role. Hiring managers also see a five-factor personality score that predicts how conscientious, innovative, etcetera, the candidate is.

吉尔曼表示，该系统只需要候选人三十秒的讲话时间，就能了解他们是否适合某项工作以及他们的性格如何。

Gillman said the system needs only thirty seconds of a candidate speaking to give insights into how well suited they are for a given job and what their personality is.

我觉得很奇怪，吉尔曼一直坚持认为该工具并没有告诉人力资源招聘经理应该聘用谁，因为人工智能实际上会根据候选人与职位的匹配程度给招聘经理打分，并根据结果对申请人进行排名。

It was odd to me that Gillman kept insisting that the tool wasn’t telling HR hiring managers whom to hire because the AI literally gives hiring managers a score on how well candidates match the role and ranks applicants according to their results.

与首席执行官交谈后，公司给了我一个登录名，然后我继续进行我的实验。

After speaking with the CEO, the company gave me a login and I proceeded with my experiments.

我决定招聘一名办公室经理/研究员。该工具会询问我关于招聘职位的具体问题。

I decide to hire an office manager/researcher. The tool asks me specific questions about the role I am hiring for.

对于你的候选人来说

How important is it for your candidate to

•特别关注细节？一点也不重要 / 有点重要 / 中等重要 / 非常重要

•maintain specific attention to detail? Not important at all / Somewhat important / Moderately important / Very important

•在一定程度上掌控自己的任务和截止日期？完全不重要 / 有点重要 / 中等重要 / 非常重要

•be in control of their own tasks and deadlines to a certain extent? Not important at all / Somewhat important / Moderately important / Very important

很难抉择。“特别注重细节？我觉得这有点重要，”我自言自语道。“嗯，不，也许比较重要？”我点击了“比较重要”。

It’s hard to choose. “Maintain specific attention to detail? I would say that’s somewhat important,” I say, thinking out loud. “Hmm, no, moderately important maybe?” I click on Moderately important.

“在一定程度上掌控自己的任务”是什么意思？我很好奇。他们应该掌控还是不掌控，或者在一定程度上掌控？我敢打赌，每个老板都会有不同的看法。这到底是有点重要、中等重要还是非常重要？嗯。很难说，但这很重要，因为候选人的评分和匹配将基于以下因素：这些选择。在我选择了求职者需要具备的所有特质之后，我就可以开始选择问题了。

What does “being in control of your own tasks to a certain extent” mean? I wonder. Should they be in control or not or to a certain extent? I bet that would differ from boss to boss. And is it somewhat important or moderately important or very important? Hmm. It’s hard to say, but this matters because candidates will be scored and matched based on these selections. After I choose all the attributes the job applicants need to have, I get to select questions.

该系统的工作原理与 Curious Thing 类似：招聘经理可以轻松选择不同的问题，例如“请介绍一下自己”和“是什么让您成为这个职位的最佳人选？”

The system works similarly to Curious Thing’s: a hiring manager can easily pick different questions like, “Please introduce yourself,” and, “What makes you the best person for this role?”

然后，我主动去面试我设立的办公室经理/研究员职位。“嗨，我叫，嗯，希尔克·谢尔曼，我申请的是办公室管理员/研究员的职位。嗯，我……我觉得我很擅长管理一个非常直接、清晰的办公室。我想让每个人都开心……”我就不多说我那些枯燥的回答了，也不多说我为什么非常适合这个职位。

I then invite myself to do the interview for the office manager/researcher position I set up. “Hi, my name is, umm, Hilke Schellmann and I am applying for the role of office administrator slash, ahh, researcher position. Umm, I am, I think I am very good at running a very straightforward, clear office. I want to make everyone happy …” I will spare you the details of my boring answers arguing why I am perfect for the role.

录制完成后，我再次看着自己——这真是一次令人尴尬的经历，但我闭上眼睛，按下回车键并发送了出去。

After I finish recording, I watch myself again—a really cringeworthy experience, but I close my eyes and hit enter and send it in.

然后，招聘经理，也就是我，收到了结果。系统显示我符合这个职位 83% 的匹配率！（匹配分数表明，我与最初设定的理想候选人（当时我必须选择技能或特质的重要性）有 83% 的重叠度。）

The hiring manager, me, then gets my results. The system says I am an 83 percent match for the role! (The match score indicates that I have an 83 percent overlap with the ideal candidate I set up at the beginning when I had to choose how important a skill or trait was.)

它告诉我：“HS（我！）可以被描述为富有创造力、安全感十足、条理清晰。” 感谢算法！我还免费获得了一次性格分析。

“HS [me!] can be described as creative, secure, and organized,” it tells me. Thanks, Algorithm! I also get a personality analysis thrown in for free.

然后我重新进行了面试，回答的不是办公室经理/研究员职位的问题，而是像面试我目前这份工作一样。我会说：“我认为我是这个职位的最佳人选，因为我有两个研究生学位。我有一个哥伦比亚大学的新闻学学位……”以及“我具备我所需的所有经验。我大概有12年的工作经验，我已经准备好了。我非常敏捷，适应力强，非常乐于接受新的挑战。”

I then redo the interview and instead of answering questions for the office manager/researcher role, I respond as if I am interviewing for the job I have. I say things like, “I think I am the best person for the role because I have two graduate degrees. I have one degree in journalism from Columbia University …” and, “I bring all the experience I need. I have probably twelve years of experience on the job and I am ready to go. I am very agile, resilient, very interested in taking on new challenges.”

凭借这些答案，我仍然获得了令人印象深刻的 82 分（至少我是这么认为的！）与角色的匹配度为百分之几，这很了不起，因为我并没有真正回答我被问到的问题。

With those answers I still score an impressive (or so I think!) 82 percent match with the role, which is extraordinary, since I didn’t really answer the questions that I was asked.

然后，我一遍又一遍地回答所有问题，一遍又一遍地重复“我喜欢团队合作”。我的匹配率高达71%，简直太棒了！

I then answer all questions by looping the sentence “I love teamwork” over and over again. I score a remarkable 71 percent match with the role!

接下来，我重复了“好奇的事物”实验。我用德语回答了所有问题，并阅读了维基百科上关于心理测量学的同一篇文章：

Next, I repeat the Curious Thing experiment. I answer all the questions in German, reading the same Wikipedia entry on psychometrics:

心理测量是心理学的基本原理，是心理学理论和方法的全部内容……

Die Psychometrie ist das Gebiet der Psychologie, das sich allgemein mit Theorie und Methode des psychologischen Messens befasst …

令我惊讶的是，我没有收到任何错误信息。相反，AI 给我的匹配度是 73%，尽管我一句英语都不会说，而且我用德语说的话也与这份工作毫无关系。

To my surprise, I don’t get an error message. Instead, the AI scores me a 73 percent match for the role, even though I didn’t speak a word of English and the things I said in German had nothing to do with the job.

MyInterview 向我展示了软件生成的文字记录。以下是它根据我的德语胡言乱语写成的：

MyInterview showed me the transcript the software generated. Here is the gibberish it concocted out of my German:

因此湿度是一个问题。

So humidity is desk a beat-up.

社会学，它能治病吗？

Sociology, does it iron?

采掘材料线虫适应。

Mined material nematode adapt.

安全位置，介子前半部分伽马它们的财富在 IMD 和事实上渴望传递给欧亚大陆和 Z 这个特定的位置介子。

Secure location, mesons the first half gamma their Fortunes in for IMD and fact long on for pass along to Eurasia and Z this particular location mesons.

因此 BD rr 为 2。

So BD r r by 2.

我想知道，把我的德语翻译成胡言乱语只是个例外，还是算法本身就存在这种模式。于是我问当时和我一起工作的一位研究生，她能不能记录一下她用中文阅读了同一篇维基百科文字。她照做了，结果与这份工作职位的匹配率高达80%，令人印象深刻。软件再次尝试用英文“理解”她的中文，结果她的文字记录和我的一样，都是乱码的“英文”。

I wondered whether it translating my German into gibberish was just an outlier, or if this is a pattern with the algorithm. So I asked one of the graduate students I was working with at the time if she could record herself in Chinese reading the same Wikipedia text. She did and she scored an impressive 80 percent match with this job role. Again, the software tried to “make sense” of her Chinese in English and her transcript is gibberish “English” just like mine:

所以看到你来展示思想研究，真正的努力在年轻的孩子从跳舞在那张桌子下真正的弗朗西斯雪茄不要无能的女服务员小 T 恤年轻，激情隔离它的蜂蜜，我应该这么说。

So seeing you coming to show thought study, real hard in young children from dance around that table under the truly Francis cigar don’t incompetent waitressing little t-shirt youthful, passions the honey on isolating it, such that I should say.

这个实验让我有很多疑问。如果系统把德语或中文和英语混淆，并分析一份乱码的文字记录，得出结果，那么这个人工智能能预测出任何真实的东西吗？

The experiment left me with many questions. If the system confuses German or Chinese with English and analyzes a transcript that is gibberish and pulls results out of that, does the AI predict anything real?

我再次通过 myInterview 进行 Zoom 通话，与前首席营销官 Eliav Rodman 和前工作心理学家 Clayton Donnelly 进行了交谈。我解释说，尽管我在面试时说的是德语，收到的只是含糊不清的英文记录，但我的职位匹配率仍然达到了 73%。

I got on a Zoom call with myInterview again and spoke with the former chief marketing officer Eliav Rodman and the former work psychologist Clayton Donnelly. I explained that, even though I spoke in German in my interviews and received a gibberish transcript in English, I still received a 73 percent match score with the role.

当他们都向我道谢并说这是有用的反馈时，我感到很惊讶。

I was surprised when they both thanked me and said this was useful feedback.

“我喜欢和测试系统的人进行这些讨论，因为你们现在做的事情对我们来说只是个边缘案例，”罗德曼说。“大多数用户只是按照系统预期的方式使用，不会对系统进行过度改造，但我们从那些对系统进行过度改造的人身上学到的东西最多。”

“I love these discussions with people who are testing the system, because what you’re doing here is an edge case for us,” Rodman said. “Most users just use the system the way it’s intended to be used and don’t torture it, but we learn the most from people who are torturing it.”

但系统到底做了什么？

But what did the system do exactly?

唐纳利说：“它所做的就是，它认为你是一个讲英语的客户，有英语的问题，并试图根据你的回答制作一份记录。”

“What it was doing is, it thought that you were an English-speaking client with English-speaking questions and it was trying to make a transcript from that,” Donnelly said.

他承认，这份文字记录是胡言乱语。系统通常会生成一份文字记录，除了语气之外，还会用它来给求职者评分。但克莱顿·唐纳利接下来的话让我大吃一惊：显然，myInterview 的人工智能引擎是一台拥有自身智慧的思考机器：“它肯定知道你当时说的不是英语，”他说，“你看到的内容——都是些胡言乱语。”

He acknowledged that the transcript was gibberish. The system produces a transcript and usually uses it to score job seekers in addition to their tone of voice. But Clayton Donnelly surprised me with what he said next: apparently, myInterview’s AI engine is a thinking machine with its own intelligence: “It knows that you weren’t speaking English, for sure,” he said. “The content you can see—it’s random nonsense.”

说实话，我很惊讶“思考机器”竟然能够区分“标准英语”的文字记录和包含随机英语单词的文字记录，但唐纳利认为，该系统不仅能够判断文字记录是否无意义，而且在统计结果时还会降低其优先级：“它主要根据你的音频、语气和音调来评分，而不是根据你说的内容。”

I was honestly surprised that a “thinking machine” could distinguish transcripts of “proper English” and transcripts with random words in English, but Donnelly believes the system not only understood whether a transcript didn’t make sense but also deprioritized it when tallying my results: “It scored you primarily on your audio, on your tone and pitch, not on what you said.”

这真是让我大吃一惊。分析我的语调，怎么能得出73%的匹配率呢？电脑从我的语调和音调中，检测到了哪些与工作要求相关的信息，比如对细节的关注？唐纳利没有向我解释这部分——也许他只是不知道人工智能是如何运作的。

That is astonishing to me. How can analysis of the intonation of my voice work to create the 73 percent match score? What kind of information does the computer detect in my intonation and pitch that is related to the requirements of the job, including maintaining specific attention to detail? Donnelly didn’t explain that part to me—maybe he just didn’t know how the AI worked.

我带着难以置信的语气问唐纳利：“我的语调和角色的吻合度有73%吗？”

With a tone of disbelief, I then asked Donnelly: “The intonation of my voice was a 73 percent match with the role?”

“是啊，干得好，”他笑着说。

“Yeah, well done,” he said, laughing.

我与休斯顿莱斯大学心理学教授兼组织与劳动力实验室主任弗雷德·奥斯瓦尔德分享了我的研究成果。他拥有数十年分析招聘评估的经验。过去几年，他开始深入研究职场中的人工智能工具。

I shared my findings with Fred Oswald, the psychology professor at Rice University in Houston and the director of the Organization & Workforce Laboratory. He has decades of experience analyzing assessments for hiring. The last few years, he has started to take a closer look at AI tools in the workplace.

我告诉他，我用德语回答了所有问题，以为会出现错误信息或零分，结果却得到了 73% 的职位匹配率和性格预测；我的研究生回答了所有问题用中文提问，收到了另一份乱码记录，与职位匹配率为 80%。

I told him how I answered all questions in German, expecting an error message or a zero score result, but received a 73 percent match to the role and a personality prediction; and how my graduate student answered all questions in Chinese, received another gibberish transcript, and was an 80 percent match to the role.

“我很高兴你向算法提出这些挑战，因为它们值得关注，”奥斯瓦尔德说。他对myInterview.com 的结果并不满意。“基于随机输入就得出高匹配度的职位似乎不太合适。结果应该可靠，并且应该清楚地解释人工智能做出决定的原因，而这次的答案相当混乱。”

“I’m glad you’re posing these challenges to the algorithms because they deserve some attention,” Oswald said. He wasn’t impressed by the results myInterview.com put out. “A high fit to the job based on random input doesn’t seem appropriate. Results should be reliable and it should be clear why an AI made a decision, which is pretty muddled in this case.”

奥斯瓦尔德还质疑语音语调分析是否真的已经到了黄金时段。“关于语调，我还没看到太多研究证据。在什么情况下语调能提供与工作相关的信息？我认为目前的论点是，我们真的不能用语调作为招聘的数据——这看起来既不公平，也不可靠，也站不住脚。作为一名教授，这一点不用我多说，我认为这显而易见。”

Oswald also questioned whether voice intonation analysis is really ready for prime time. “Intonation, I don’t see much research evidence. What are the situations where intonation would provide any job-relevant information?
