I think the argument currently has to be that we really can’t use intonation as data for hiring—that just doesn’t seem fair or reliable or valid. You don’t need me saying that as a professor, I think it’s just obvious.”

他并非想阻碍创新，但他认为人工智能供应商需要更加慎重地考虑测试产品的内容和方式。研究也必须迅速跟上，以测试这些新工具是否公平可靠，是否有效——这意味着，如果测试的制定者声称它能衡量性格，我们就需要验证它是否真的能衡量性格，而不是其他什么，或者什么都不是。

He doesn’t want to discourage innovation, but he believes that AI vendors need to be more thoughtful about what and how they are testing their products. Research also has to catch up quickly to test these new tools to see whether they’re fair and reliable and if they work—meaning that, if the makers of the test say it’s measuring personality, we need to test whether it’s really measuring personality and not something else or nothing at all.

任重道远

A LONG WAY TO GO

一组德国记者测试了 Retorio 的视频采访软件，结果表明，当他们使用绿屏在同一个虚构的受访者身后插入不同的背景（例如书架）时，受访者的性格分数会发生变化。9

A team of German journalists tested Retorio’s video interview software and showed that when they used a green screen to insert a different background behind the same fictional interviewee, such as a bookshelf, the personality scores changed.9

但同样的技术已经在工作场所：例如，在呼叫中心，人工智能被广泛用于分析客户的声音，以检测愤怒、攻击或压力，并追踪中断和讲话时长。在保险理赔电话中，一些供应商表示，他们的软件可以“检测到独特的声音特征，这些特征可能预示着欺诈或信息隐瞒的可能性很高”。这些供应商还表示，他们的工具可以用来分析录音，包括Zoom通话。

But the same kind of technology is already being used in the workplace: in call centers, for example, AI is widely used to analyze customer voices to detect anger, aggression, or stress and tracks interruptions and speech length. In insurance claims calls, some vendors say that their software can “detect unique vocal characteristics that may indicate a high probability of fraud or concealment of information.” These vendors also say that their tools can be used to analyze recorded audio, including Zoom calls.

总的来说，基于人工智能的视频面试还有很长的路要走，才能不仅为公司节省时间和金钱，还能挑选出最合格的求职者。

In general, AI-based video interviews have a long way to go before they can be used to not only save companies time and money but also pick the most qualified job applicants.

2021年，我用myInterview做了最后一次测试。我把我的答案输入到一个AI语音生成器中，然后让电脑在没有任何人的情况下，将我的陈述“读”进myInterview。我的AI语音与职位的匹配度达到了79%——比我用真实声音的匹配度高出几个百分点！这个工具完全没有检测到镜头前没有人，我的声音是由AI工具生成的。

I did one last test with myInterview in 2021. I typed my answers into an AI voice generator and had a computer “read” my statements into myInterview with no one on the screen. My AI voice scored a 79 percent match for the role—a few percentage points higher than my score when I used my authentic voice! The tool never detected that there was no human in front of the camera and that my voice was generated by an AI tool.

事实上，这类候选人造假行为在美国已经成为一个严重的问题，联邦调查局（FBI）正在展开调查。2022年6月，FBI向各公司发出警告，提醒他们警惕招聘过程中使用深度伪造视频：“深度伪造包括对视频、图像或录音进行令人信服的修改和操纵，以歪曲某人实际上并未做过或说过的事情。” 10

In fact, this kind of candidate faking has become such a problem in the US that the FBI is investigating. In June 2022, the FBI issued a warning to companies about deepfake videos in hiring: “Deepfakes include a video, an image, or recording convincingly altered and manipulated to misrepresent someone as doing or saying something that was not actually done or said.”10

HireVue 首席数据科学家 Lindsey Zuloaga 表示，远程招聘和远程办公通常也会导致招聘过程中出现更多的候选人欺诈行为。“有些人想找工作，他们确实想得到这份工作，于是就雇人代他们进行评估或面试。” 而第一天，Zoom 上就出现了其他人。这种候选人欺诈行为确实是一个问题，但许多公司也担心关于人们试图受雇担任远程职位，然后使用远程访问公司系统来试图窃取公司数据。

Remote hiring and remote work have also generally led to more candidate fraud in hiring, said Lindsey Zuloaga, the chief data scientist at HireVue. “There are people trying to get a job, they legitimately want the job, and they hire someone to take an assessment or an interview for them.” And on the first day, someone else shows up on Zoom. This kind of candidate fraud is a problem, but many companies are also worried about people trying to get hired for remote roles, and then using remote access to a company’s system to try to steal data from the company.

“我想知道我们最终是否需要实施更多种类的身份验证，”祖洛阿加说。

“I wonder if eventually we’ll just have to implement more kinds of identity verification,” Zuloaga said.

求职者也在尝试其他方式超越算法。我在社交媒体上看到有人使用 ChatGPT 和其他大型语言模型在单向视频面试中实时生成答案。例如，如果求职者有口音，有些人可能会选择使用基于人工智能的语音生成器来朗读答案。

Job applicants are also trying to outperform the algorithms in other ways. I have seen folks on social media using ChatGPT and other large language models to generate answers in real time during one-way video interviews. If applicants have an accent, for example, some may opt to use AI-based voice generators to speak their answers.

招聘供应商还有很多工作要做。与此同时，求职者仍然被要求使用这些工具。

Hiring vendors have a lot more work to do. Meanwhile, job applicants are still being asked to use these tools.

如果你想知道 Alex Huang 后来怎么样了？2018 年，他为了找工作拒绝了单向视频面试，现在我有个好消息要告诉你。在被邀请参加大约 30 场面试后，黄终于通过传统的面对面面试找到了工作。

If you wondered what happened to Alex Huang, who back in 2018 refused to do one-way video interviews in his job search, I have good news. After being invited to about thirty job interviews, Huang did find a job—through a traditional in-person interview.

我们去Alex Huang上班时，他把我们介绍给了他当时的老板——信贷经理Tony Velasquez，Velasquez在银行业工作了三十多年。Huang大约两个月前才开始工作，我和同事Jason开玩笑地想问问他的老板最近怎么样。（坦白说：我们问这个问题的时候Alex Huang就在我们旁边。）Velasquez的语气变得非常严肃。“在我三十年的银行生涯里，他可能是这行里最优秀的三四个年轻人之一，”他说。“Alex进步非常快，做得非常好。”

When we visited Alex Huang at work, he introduced us to his boss at the time, credit manager Tony Velasquez, who has been in banking for over thirty years. Huang had started about two months earlier, and my colleague Jason and I jokingly wanted to know from his boss how he was doing. (Full disclosure: Alex Huang was next to us when we asked the question.) Velasquez turned pretty serious. “In my thirty years of doing this, he’s probably one of the top three, four, or five kids who come through here,” he said. “Alex has come very far very quickly. He has done very well.”

第五章

CHAPTER 5

本质的你

The Essential You

论新人工智能工具背后的想法

On the Ideas Behind the New AI Tools

我2018年末，我在西雅图进行面部识别技术调查报道时，采访了RealNetworks的开发人员。RealNetworks是最早的多媒体播放器之一RealPlayer的开发商。正式拍摄结束后，公司员工向我和我的同事杰森展示了他们最新的项目——一个面部表情分析程序。开发人员告诉我们，它可以检测我们的性别、年龄和情绪。当我把脸对着镜头时，程序预测我是女性，而且比实际年龄年轻大约八岁——看起来比实际年龄年轻，真是太棒了！但当这个工具实时显示它如何通过我的面部表情变化来推断我的情绪是悲伤还是快乐时，我感到一阵莫名的亲切。

I n late 2018, on a reporting trip in Seattle investigating facial recognition technologies, I spoke to developers at RealNetworks, the makers of the RealPlayer, one of the first multimedia players. After our official filming part was done, folks from the company showed my colleague Jason and me their newest project, a facial expression analysis program. The developers told us it could detect our gender, age, and emotions. When I showed my face to the camera, the program predicted that I was female and about eight years younger than I was—yay to looking younger than my actual age! But it felt weirdly personal when the tool showed me in real time how it was inferring that I felt sad or happy as my facial expressions changed.

RealNetworks 并不是唯一一家致力于开发更深入地洞察我们的情绪。正如我们所见，其他开发者也构建了类似的工具，可以通过面部表情和语调推断人们的情绪。这些技术正在商店、医疗保健、招聘和工作中得到应用。

RealNetworks is not alone in building technologies that try to get a deeper look at our emotions. As we have seen, other developers have built similar tools that infer people’s emotions from their facial expressions and the intonation of their voice. These technologies are being used in stores, in health care, in hiring, and at work.

在本书中，我们探讨了公司用来甄别最佳候选人的多种策略：简历阅读、社交媒体监控、游戏测试、面部表情和语调分析、电话采访转录等等。所有这些策略都在寻求一种秘诀，能够最有效地解释候选人的特质，并预测其未来的表现。在这里，我想暂时放下工具的讨论，转而探讨这些工具背后的理念。

In this book, we have explored a number of strategies companies have used to identify the best candidates to hire: résumé readers, social media spying, game playing, facial movement and tone-of-voice analysis, transcribed phone interviews, and so on. All are seeking a way to find the secret formula that best explains what the candidate is like and best predicts their future performance. Here I would like to step back from looking at tools and explore where the ideas behind them are coming from.

我明白，尤其是在招聘和工作中，人们总想深入了解求职者和员工，了解他们“真正”的样子。（哎，我也想知道我自己——真正的我！）直觉上似乎没错，我的性格，本质上就是我，深深地烙印在我所做的每一件事里——但这种想法真的正确吗？

I get that people, especially in hiring and at work, want to look “under the hood” of applicants and employees and find out who they “really” are. (Heck, I want to know myself—who I really am!) It seems intuitively right that my personality, essentially who I am, is embedded in everything I do—but is that idea correct?

其基本假设是一种“本质主义”：人类拥有稳定的性格和人格特质，可以被分类和比较。更重要的是，我们通过外貌和我们留下的痕迹——无论是面部表情还是推文——来展现我们内在的性格特质和情感。这种观点认为，我的“本质”深植于我所做的一切之中，而柏拉图、苏格拉底和其他哲学家长期以来一直在争论这个问题。

The underlying assumption is a form of “essentialism”: that humans have a stable character and personality traits that can be categorized and compared, and, more importantly, that we reveal our internal character traits and emotions through physical appearance and the traces we leave behind—be they facial expressions or tweets. The idea is that my “essence” is embedded in all these things I do, something Plato, Socrates, and other philosophers have long debated.

这一假设已存在数千年，并在十八世纪末至十九世纪成为一门“科学”探索。相学家和颅相学家试图从人们的外在特征和表情中科学地推断其内在特征和行为——就像如今许多人工智能工具正在尝试的那样。当时，科学家声称头上的肿块可以反映性格特征（颅相学）。19世纪意大利犯罪学家切萨雷·龙勃罗梭（Cesare Lombroso）曾研究过罪犯和小偷的头骨，他和其他人则认为，罪犯生来如此，并拥有特定的面部特征（面相学）。

This assumption has been around for thousands of years, and in the late eighteenth and the nineteenth century it became a “scientific” endeavor. Physiognomists and phrenologists tried to scientifically infer inner characteristics and behaviors from people’s outside features and expressions—just like what many AI tools are trying to do today. At the time, scientists claimed that bumps on one’s head showed personality characteristics (phrenology). Cesare Lombroso, a criminologist who examined the skulls of convicted criminals and thieves in nineteenth-century Italy, and others believed that criminals were born as such and had specific distinguishing facial features (physiognomy).

相面学和颅相学已被广泛认为是伪科学，但回顾历史，就能明白为何它们曾如此吸引人，并不断重现。最新的迭代被嵌入到人工智能工具中，这些工具声称可以通过分析我们的面部动作、语音语调或Facebook帖子来揭示我们的性格。

Physiognomy and phrenology have been widely discredited as pseudoscience, but a look at history makes it clear why they were such appealing ideas that keep reemerging. The newest iteration is built into AI tools that claim to reveal our personalities through analysis of our facial movements or voice intonation or Facebook posts.

坏头骨，坏人

BAD SKULLS, BAD PEOPLE

“现代”相面术的起源之一，即认为我们内心深处的特征会展现在身体的外部，可以追溯到 18 世纪的瑞士神学家约翰·卡斯帕·拉瓦特 (Johann Kaspar Lavater)：布莱斯·阿圭拉·阿尔卡斯 (Blaise Agüera y Arcas)、玛格丽特·米切尔 (Margaret Mitchell) 和亚历山大·托多罗夫 (Alexander Todorov) 在他们 2017 年发表的论文《相面术的新衣》中写道，他“根据眼睛、眉毛、嘴巴和鼻子的形状和位置来分析性格，以确定一个人是否具有‘虚伪’、‘充满恶意’、‘不可救药的愚蠢’或‘疯子’等特征” 。1

One of the origins of “modern” physiognomy, the idea that our innermost characteristics are revealed on the outside of our bodies, can be traced to the eighteenth-century Swiss theologian Johann Kaspar Lavater: he “analyzed character based on the shape and positions of the eyes, brows, mouth, and nose to determine whether a person was, among other characteristics, ‘deceitful,’ ‘full of malice,’ ‘incurably stupid,’ or a ‘madman,’” wrote Blaise Agüera y Arcas, Margaret Mitchell, and Alexander Todorov in their 2017 essay “Physiognomy’s New Clothes.”1

最知名的颅相学家和相面学家之一是前面提到的切萨雷·龙勃罗梭。他认为人天生就是罪犯，因此得出结论，犯罪特征可以从他们的体貌特征中体现出来，包括他们的头骨。在一个案例中，龙勃罗梭发现“头骨枕骨处有一个凹陷，让人联想到‘野蛮人和猿猴’的头骨”。2颅相学的核心思想是，我们的大脑就像一块肌肉，有些区域比其他区域更活跃；因此，我们拥有不同的头骨轮廓，映射出大脑发育的差异。他们表示，通过解读和测量头骨的差异，颅相学家可以客观地发现性格特征。

One of the most widely known phrenologists and physiognomists was the previously mentioned Cesare Lombroso. He believed that people were born as criminals and concluded, therefore, that traits of criminality could be found in their bodily appearance, including on their skulls. In one case, Lombroso found “a depression on the occiput of the skull reminiscent of the skulls of ‘savages and apes.’”2 The central idea of phrenology was that our brain is a muscle and some regions are more active than others; therefore, we have different contours of the skull that map to the differences in the brain’s development. Through reading and measuring the differences in skulls, phrenologists could objectively find personality traits, they said.

如今，人们仍然普遍认为，根据一个人的外表来判断其内心状态。借助人工智能，开发者和研究人员希望客观地衡量和展现人类的行为方式，并预测他们的行为方式。人工智能目前还无法读懂我们的想法，但算法可以测量我们面部的动作、语调和言语。但这是否意味着它们揭示了某种本质主义的真理？

The same general idea of defining a person’s inner states based on their outside appearance is at work today. With AI, developers and researchers want to objectively measure and show how humans tick and predict how they will behave. AI can’t read our thoughts yet, but algorithms can measure the movements on our face, our intonation, and our words. But does that mean they reveal some essentialist truth?

加拿大安大略省伦敦市西部大学信息与媒体研究教授卢克·斯塔克 (Luke Stark) 写道：“人工智能视频采访技术声称能够理解或评估的许多能力和特质，与相面学和颅相学试图识别和利用的心理能力恰好吻合。”他研究的是人工智能的社会影响。3

“Many of the capabilities and traits AI-powered video interviewing technologies claim to understand or evaluate map neatly onto the mental faculties that physiognomy and phrenology sought to identify and leverage,” wrote Luke Stark, professor of information and media studies at Western University in London, Ontario, who researches the social implications of AI.3

例如，人工智能视频面试公司 Inclusive.hr（前身为 8 and Above）声称，可以通过一段 30 秒的面部表情和声音记录，了解求职者的“冒险精神”、“文化修养”、“足智多谋”和“智力”程度。同样，颅相学分析声称，可以通过“头顶”和“头顶”来了解一个人性格中“尽责性”、“仁慈”和“自尊”的体现。斯塔克及其合著者杰文·赫特森写道。4

“For example, AI video interviewing company Inclusive.hr (formerly 8 and Above) claims to understand how ‘adventurous,’ ‘cultured,’ ‘resourceful,’ and ‘intellect[ual]’ a job candidate is based on a thirty-second recording of their facial expressions and voice. Likewise, phrenological analysis claimed to understand how ‘conscientiousness,’ ‘benevolence,’ and ‘self-esteem’ were evident in a person’s character based on the ‘crown of the head’ and the ‘top of the head,’” Stark and their coauthor Jevan Hutson wrote.4

19世纪，另一种洞察人“本质”的方法出现了：摄影，这种激动人心的新兴媒介，有望将人们此前无法察觉的事物展现出来。19世纪80年代，英国探险家、人类学家和优生学家弗朗西斯·高尔顿尝试合成照片，试图找到“理想的典型”通过叠加照片，研究人员可以发现不同种族、科学家、罪犯和其他人的“种族歧视形式”。

In the nineteenth century, another method to get to the “essence” of a person emerged: photography was the new and exciting medium that promised to make visible what people couldn’t see before. In the 1880s, Francis Galton, an English explorer, anthropologist, and eugenicist, experimented with composite photos, trying to find the “ideal typical form” of different races, scientists, criminals, and others by exposing photos overlaid on one another.

回想起来，一位科学家竟然认为，通过叠加罪犯的照片就能找出“犯罪的面孔”，这在今天看来或许有些不可思议，但如今我们或许距离这些19世纪的方法并不遥远。人工智能这项新技术有望让事物“可见”，或者说，找到此前未知的模式。

In retrospect, it seems extraordinary to us today that by superimposing photos of convicted criminals, a scientist believed he could find the “face of criminality,” but we might not be so far off from these nineteenth-century methods today. AI is the new technology that promises to make things “visible,” or to find patterns, that were previously unknown.

几年前，宾夕法尼亚州哈里斯堡大学的研究人员发布了一篇新闻稿，介绍了一项名为“利用图像处理预测犯罪行为的深度神经网络模型”的研究。研究人员声称，他们利用照片构建了一个算法工具，可以推断照片中的人是否是罪犯。“该软件的准确率高达80%，并且没有种族偏见，仅凭一张脸部照片就能预测某人是否是罪犯。该软件旨在帮助执法部门预防犯罪。”研究人员相信他们找到了终极的犯罪预防工具。

A few years back, researchers at Harrisburg University in Pennsylvania circulated a press release about a study titled “A Deep Neural Network Model to Predict Criminality Using Image Processing.”5 The researchers had used photos to build an algorithmic tool that could infer whether the person depicted was a criminal or not, the researchers claimed. “With 80 percent accuracy and with no racial bias, the software can predict if someone is a criminal based solely on a picture of their face. The software is intended to help law enforcement prevent crime.” The researchers believed they had found the ultimate crime prevention tool.

在公众的强烈抗议之后，这篇论文从未发表。6这表明了当今研究人员正在尝试使用人工智能做什么，令人毛骨悚然地让人想起十九世纪相面师的工作——但通常没有受到质疑。

After a public uproar, the paper was never published.6 This shows what researchers are trying to use AI for today, eerily recalling the work of physiognomists of the nineteenth century—but often uncontested.

检测性别认同

DETECTING SEXUAL IDENTITY

另一个例子是，斯坦福商学院副教授 Michal Kosinski 和合著者 Yilun Wang 开发了一款人工智能，可以仅凭照片识别同性恋者。他们将其命名为“gaydar”，基于这样一种观点：许多人也会根据外貌形成对其性取向的印象。7 （当然，即使我们确实会这样做，也并不意味着这些印象就是真实的。）

In another example, Michal Kosinski, an associate professor at Stanford Business School, and coauthor Yilun Wang built an AI that can identify gay people from a photo alone, they said. They called it “gaydar,” based on the idea that many humans also form impressions of people’s sexual orientation on the basis of their appearance.7 (Even though we do this, it doesn’t mean the impressions are true, of course.)

在论文中，作者展示了“典型的直脸”和“典型的同性恋面孔”的合成照片，试图让某人性取向的“本质”变得可见。

In the paper, the authors show composite photos of “archetypal straight faces” and “archetypal gay faces,” trying to make visible the “essence” of someone’s sexual orientation.

软件工具真的能从人们的面部表情中检测出性取向吗？它不能，因为我们的性取向和面部特征之间没有因果关系：面部特征并不能决定一个人是否是同性恋，同性恋身份也不能赋予一个人独特的面部特征。

Can a software tool really detect sexual orientation in people’s faces? It cannot, because our sexual orientation and our facial features have no causal relationship: facial features do not make someone gay and being gay doesn’t give someone distinct facial features.

“同性恋”或“异性恋”选择如何展现自己，或许会有一些文化内涵，或许计算机可以识别这些信号，但这又有什么意义呢？这种工具以及类似的工具实际上可能会危及同性恋合法化国家的人们。

There may be some cultural connotations for how “gay” or “straight” people choose to present themselves, and maybe a computer could pick up those signals, but what’s the point? This and similar tools could actually endanger people in countries where being gay or lesbian is outlawed.

猜测人们的性取向是基于我们自身的偏见，我们应该努力摆脱这种偏见，而不是试图用人工智能来复制。

Guessing people’s sexual orientation is based in our own biased practices that we should work hard to get rid of—not try to replicate with AI.

但一些研究人员正试图将种族主义、阶级主义或恐同言论中得出的无证据的神话提升为“客观科学”，再次试图在我们的外表中找到暗示我们性取向的本质主义真理。

But some researchers are trying to elevate non-evidence-based myths drawn from racist, classist, or homophobic tropes into “objective science,” again trying to find essentialist truths in our appearance that connote our sexual orientation.

哈士奇和狼

HUSKIES AND WOLVES

相面术和颅相学从来都无法证明罪犯生来如此，也无法证明我们头上的凸起能表明我们是谁，但这种思维方式，包括对人进行分类和排名，却被用来为种族主义和白人至上主义辩护——将美国的奴隶、移民和非洲黑人贴上低等的标签。纳粹也曾用它来将犹太人描绘成低等的，并以此作为杀害他们的理由。8

Physiognomy and phrenology were never able to prove that criminals were born as such or that bumps on our heads show who we are, but this kind of thinking, which includes sorting and ranking people, has been used to justify racism and white supremacy—labeling enslaved people in the United States, immigrants, and Black Africans as inferior. It was also used by the Nazis to paint Jews as inferior and used as a rationale for killing them.8

尽管相面学作为一门科学在十九世纪末期不再流行，但它在学术界之外一直具有广泛的吸引力因为它与许多民间智慧相符。例如，在19世纪的英国，人们流行根据外貌来判断一个人的性格。事实上，今天我们中的许多人仍然会这样做，比如说某人面带怒容，或者看起来很开朗，或者其他任何与外貌相关的性格特质。在当时农村人向城市迁移的时期，外貌判断帮助初入都市的人们理解周围陌生的人。他们把这种观念运用到面部特征、衣着、手势和装饰上。

Although physiognomy as a science fell out of fashion in the late nineteenth century, it always had a broad appeal outside of academia because it was consistent with a lot of folk wisdom. For example, in nineteenth-century England, it became popular to judge people’s character based on their appearance. In fact, many of us still do this today when we say that someone has an angry face or looks open or whatever other personality quality we connect with their appearance. At that time of rural to urban migration, judging by appearance helped newly minted city people make sense of the unfamiliar others around them. And they applied the idea to facial features, clothing, gestures, and decoration.

如今，我们被要求永远不要以貌取人，这意味着，我们的确会以貌取人，也会以貌取人。正是人类的偏见常常会催生出种族主义、性别歧视和阶级歧视的社会等级制度，而我们自以为看到的面部表情和人们的整体外貌会帮助我们对他们进行分类；反过来，这些偏见也会影响我们雇佣谁。我相信，我们内心那些带有偏见的先入之见对很多人来说都是直觉的、正确的，但这些偏见并不一定正确。

Today, we are asked to never judge a book by its cover, which implies that, yes, we do judge books by their covers and humans by their looks or how they present themselves. It’s our human biases that often bring out racist, sexist, and classist social hierarchies and what we think we see in facial expressions and people’s general appearance that help us categorize them; in turn, they also influence who we hire. Our own internal biased preconceptions, which I am sure feel intuitive and right to many, are not necessarily correct.

“虽然我们几乎本能地根据面部表情形成印象，”阿圭拉·阿尔卡斯和他的合著者指出，“但这并不意味着这些印象是准确的。证据表明它们并非如此。” 9

“While we form impressions almost reflexively from facial appearance,” Agüera y Arcas and his coauthors state, “this does not imply that these impressions are accurate. The evidence suggests that they are not.”9

目前尚不清楚人工智能工具是否真的能发现重要的信息；许多研究人员使用深度神经网络构建算法，其中的“学习”和预测发生在隐藏层；因此，这些算法本质上是黑匣子。这种做法导致了算法出现问题和失败。使用这种技术也使得人类难以准确理解人工智能预测的差异是什么，以及这种差异是否真的有意义。

It’s not clear whether AI tools actually find information of significance; many researchers use deep neural networks to build their algorithms, where the “learning” and predicting happen in hidden layers; so, the algorithms are, essentially, black boxes. This practice has led to problems and misfires in algorithms. Using this kind of technology also makes it hard for humans to understand exactly what the difference is that the AI has predicted upon and whether the difference is actually meaningful.

狼和哈士奇的例子是说明人工智能工具失效的一个简单方法：研究人员编写了一个人工智能程序来学习狼和哈士奇的行为。研究人员使用带标签的动物照片来识别哈士奇和狼。AI 进行了自我训练，并在输入系统的新照片中正确识别了哈士奇和狼——直到它判断错误。

An easy way to illustrate an AI tool misfiring is the wolf and husky example: researchers programmed an AI to learn what wolves and huskies look like using labeled photos of the animals. The AI trained itself and identified huskies and wolves correctly in new photos fed into the system—until the tool got it wrong.

研究人员仔细检查了软件，试图找出该工具对哪些照片进行了预测。通过分析，研究人员发现，人工智能实际上并没有学会哈士奇和狼的长相；该软件只是根据背景中的某种东西——雪——来预测照片中是哈士奇还是狼。软件在训练照片中发现了一个规律：狼的照片背景中有雪，而哈士奇的照片没有。但随后，一张以雪为背景的哈士奇照片却让系统陷入了困境，这表明人工智能根本就没有“学会”哈士奇和狼之间的区别。

The researchers, looking closer, checked the software to reveal what in the photos the tool had made its predictions on. From this analysis, the researchers determined that the AI hadn’t, in fact, learned what huskies and wolves looked like; the software was predicting whether a photo showed a husky or a wolf based on something in the background: snow. The software noticed a pattern in its training photos that the pictures of wolves had snow in the background and the photos of huskies didn’t. But then a new photo of a husky with snow in the background tripped up the system, making it clear that the AI had not “learned” the difference between a husky and a wolf after all.

同样的问题，研究人员称之为“过拟合”，可能也发生在“同性恋雷达”的检测过程中。计算机自学解决了研究人员给出的问题。Michal Kosinski 和 Yilun Wang 甚至可能自己都不知道为什么计算机会把某人归类为“看起来像同性恋”。正如上一章所讨论的，HireVue（一家领先的单向视频面试招聘平台）以及其他人力资源领域的供应商，在其工具中使用深度神经网络进行面部运动分析，这可能导致了类似的过拟合问题。（HireVue 表示，它采用了多种方法来减少过拟合。）

The same problem, which researchers call “overfitting,” may have happened with the “gaydar” process. The computer taught itself to solve a problem the researchers gave it. Michal Kosinski and Yilun Wang might not even know themselves why the computer classified someone as “gay looking.” As discussed in the previous chapter, HireVue, one of the one-way video interview market leaders in hiring and other vendors in the HR world, used deep neural networks for facial movement analysis in its tools, and this could have led to similar overfitting issues. (HireVue says that it uses several practices to reduce overfitting.)

过度拟合是计算机能够在人脸中发现犯罪模式（即使实际上没有）的原因——它会从数据集中随机挑选出一些可能毫无意义的模式，但在研究人员看来却很有说服力。“机器学习无法区分具有因果意义的相关性和偶然相关性……深度学习无法提取不存在的信息，我们应该对声称它能够可靠地从图像中提取隐藏含义的说法持怀疑态度，因为逃避人类法官的判断。” 10 Agüera y Arcas 及其同事还指出，“值得强调的是，在这个（或任何）机器学习应用中，并不存在超人的魔法。”

Overfitting is why a computer may find patterns of criminality in people’s faces when there are none—it picks up random patterns in the data set that may have no meaning, but look convincing to the researchers. “Machine learning does not distinguish between correlations that are causally meaningful and ones that are incidental…. Deep learning can’t extract information that isn’t there, and we should be suspicious of claims that it can reliably extract hidden meaning from images that eludes human judges.”10 Agüera y Arcas and colleagues also note that “it is worth emphasizing that there is no superhuman magic in this (or any) application of machine learning.”

如果我们不仔细检查人工智能系统的结果，不进行大量的测试，不深入研究其结果，这类错误就很容易被忽略。对于哈士奇和狼来说，风险不大，但如果在就业环境中使用有缺陷的工具，就可能危及人们的生计和未来的机会。此外，如果我们不批判性地审视算法的训练过程，即使该工具只是发现了毫无意义的相关性，其结果也很容易让人觉得是客观科学的。

If we don’t double-check the results of AI systems, run many tests, and take a deeper look at the outcomes, these kinds of mistakes can easily slip through. With huskies and wolves, the stakes are low, but if a flawed tool is used in an employment setting, it can cost people their livelihoods and future opportunities. In addition, if we don’t critically examine the process of training an algorithm, the results can easily feel like objective science even if the tool just found meaningless correlations.

笔迹学的艺术

THE ART OF GRAPHOLOGY

过去，招聘经理容易相信伪科学，比如笔迹分析（笔迹学），几十年前，这种技术在法国的招聘中仍然很流行。伪科学方法通常直觉上是正确的：每个人的笔迹都不一样；因此，它至少能揭示出我们“本质”的一部分。

In the past, hiring managers have been prone to believe in pseudoscience, such as handwriting analysis (graphology), which a couple of decades ago was still popular in hiring in France. Pseudoscientific methods usually feel intuitively right: every individual’s handwriting is different; ergo, it must reveal at least some of our “essence.”

2004年，心理学家迈克·米勒德说：“所有招聘人员都在寻找‘圣杯’，以便为公司招到最优秀的人才。每个人都想快速解决问题。” 11法国笔迹学家为在招聘中使用笔迹分析辩护，因为他们认为，求职者可以润色简历，训练自己在面试和性格测试中给出正确答案，但笔迹是独一无二的，书写行为揭示了我们的个性，展现了无法伪造的真实的“你”。他们认为，由于笔迹是个性的一种表现，因此对单词和字母的构成方式进行系统分析可以揭示个性特征。

In 2004, psychologist Mike Millard said, “All recruiters are looking for the Holy Grail on how to get the best people for their companies. Everyone wants a quick fix.”11 Graphologists in France have defended using handwriting analysis in hiring because, they say, job applicants can embellish their résumés, train to give the right answers in job interviews and on personality tests, but handwriting is unique and the act of writing reveals our personality, the real “you” that can’t be faked. They maintain that because handwriting is an expression of personality, a systematic analysis of how the words and letters are formed can reveal personality traits.

“如果使用得当，笔迹学可以很好地表明一个人的性格结构、能力、成长和发展的能力，以及或许最重要的，他们的正直，”笔迹学家玛格丽特·怀特说道，她运用自己的技能为招聘人员评估求职者。12

“When used correctly, graphology can give a good indication of a person’s personality structure, their abilities, ability to grow and develop, and perhaps most importantly, their integrity,” said graphologist Margaret White, who uses her skills to assess job applicants for recruiters.12

《金融时报》在 2001 年写道：“例如，字母的大小表示信心，倾斜度与自发性有关，压力与能量有关。” 13

“For example, size of letters indicates confidence, slant is linked to spontaneity and pressure is associated with energy,” wrote the Financial Times in 2001.13

一些笔迹学家会分析公司顶尖员工的笔迹样本，以发现高管的主导性格特征。然后，他们还会检查求职者的笔迹样本，寻找相同的性格特征。

Some graphologists analyze handwriting samples from a company’s top performers to find dominant personality traits among executives. Then they examine job applicants’ handwriting samples looking for the same personality traits.

这听起来与如今人们对人工智能技术的描述类似。例如，供应商声称基于求职者的社交媒体动态进行性格分析，候选人很难伪造，从而快速洞察求职者内心的本质。许多人工智能游戏公司也采用同样的方法，让现有员工玩游戏来寻找“合适的”性格特质。但除非供应商进行工作分析，否则没有证据表明这些工具所发现的任何性格特质与工作相关技能相关。

This sounds similar to how AI technologies are described today. For example, vendors suggest personality analysis based on someone’s social media feeds, which would be hard for a candidate to fake, will give a quick look under the hood. Many AI gaming companies use these same methods, having current employees play the games to find the “right” personality traits. But unless the vendors do a job analysis, there is no evidence that any of the personality traits allegedly found by the tools are related to job-relevant skills.

也没有证据表明笔迹学有效。“笔迹学是一门伪科学，它声称能快速轻松地揭示一个人的思维方式，但没有证据表明这种思维方式被编码在笔迹中，”不列颠哥伦比亚省西蒙弗雷泽大学前生物心理学教授、《书写材料：笔迹学评估——笔迹分析研究》合著者巴里·贝耶斯坦 ( Barry Beyerstein) 表示。14心理学家罗文·贝恩 (Rowan Bayne) 对顶尖笔迹学家进行了测试，以验证他们的说法，他说这种做法“毫无用处……绝对没希望” 。15

There is also no evidence that graphology works. “Graphology is a pseudoscience that claims to be a quick and easy way of saying how someone’s wired, but there’s no evidence that this is encoded in handwriting,” stated Barry Beyerstein, a former professor of biological psychology at Simon Fraser University in British Columbia and coauthor of The Write Stuff: Evaluations of Graphology—the Study of Handwriting Analysis.14 Rowan Bayne, a psychologist who tested top graphologists against their claims, says the practice is “useless … absolutely hopeless.”15

心理学家表示：“多年来的大量研究表明，这些都是垃圾，不适合在任何专业场合使用。”法国格勒诺布尔大学的洛朗·贝格教授说：“如果你让一群笔迹学家研究同一段笔迹，他们肯定会得出不同的解释。这和占星术或命理学没什么区别。” 16血型分析也是如此，在日本，血型分析被广泛用于了解某人是否适合某项工作。目前没有科学证据表明血型与性格有关。17

“Lots of studies over the years have shown that it is all a load of rubbish and not fit for use in any professional setting,” said psychology professor Laurent Bègue, who works at the University of Grenoble in France. “If you ask a group of graphologists to study the same piece of handwriting, they all come out with different interpretations. It’s no different from astrology or numerology.”16 The same goes for blood type analysis, which was used widely in Japan to understand whether someone was a good fit for a job. There is no scientific evidence that our blood type is related to our personality.17

我确信，很多这类测试，以及几乎所有外在表现都会揭示我们内在“本质”自我的潜在假设，会成为聚会上或自我发现练习中的有趣游戏，但大多数都没有科学依据，我们不应该在招聘等高风险决策中使用它们——无论是在传统测试中，还是在人工智能中。一遍又一遍。

I am sure a lot of these tests and the underlying assumption that almost all our outward expressions reveal our inner “essential” self would be fun games to play at parties or as self-discovery exercises, but most are without scientific evidence, and we shouldn’t be using them in high-stakes decision-making like hiring—not in traditional tests and not in AI. Again and again.

第六章

CHAPTER 6

一种尺寸真的适合所有人吗？

Does One Size Really Fit All?

关于对残疾人的偏见

On the Bias Against Disabilities

西我们多次听说，人工智能供应商将他们的工具宣传为客观、公正、公平，并声称他们实现了招聘的民主化。这些供应商表示，每个人终于都有机会了；计算机不会像过去人类招聘经理那样走廉价或带有偏见的捷径；他们的工具会以同样的方式分析和评估每一位求职者。

We have heard a few times now that AI vendors market their tools as objective, unbiased, and fair and say that they democratize hiring. Everyone is finally getting a chance, these vendors say; the computer is not doing cheap or biased shortcuts that human hiring managers have done in the past; their tools analyze and assess every applicant the same way.

供应商们自信满满地宣称，基于人工智能的视频面试和人工智能游戏几乎适用于所有人。这也是这些工具吸引雇主的原因之一——一套算法就能设定所有员工的生产率，一套就业测试就能分析所有求职者。但对于残障人士来说，这些工具真的公平吗？

Vendors confidently declare that AI-based video interviews and AI games will work for (almost) anyone. That’s one reason these tools appeal to employers—one algorithm sets productivity rates for all workers or one employment test analyzes all job applicants. But when it comes to people with disabilities, will the tools work fairly?

美国约有 10% 至 25% 的人口患有残疾，包括从脑瘫到抑郁症、克罗恩病、耳聋和长期 COVID。1英国的情况也类似，政府统计数据显示，英国约有 24% 的人口患有某种形式的残疾。2在人类招聘的工作场所，残疾人的境况并不好——在美国，残疾人的失业率大约是非残疾人失业率的两倍，在英国则高出 20 至 30 个百分点。

About 10 to 25 percent of the US population have a disability, including mental and physical disabilities ranging from cerebral palsy to depression, Crohn’s disease, deafness, and long COVID.1 The figure is similar in the UK, where government statistics indicate that roughly 24 percent of the population are living with some form of disability.2 People with disabilities have not fared well in the workplace with humans doing the hiring—the unemployment rate for people with disabilities is roughly double the unemployment rate for people with no disabilities in the US, and 20 to 30 percentage points higher in the UK.

在本章中，我们将关注的不是特定的人工智能策略，而是许多策略共同面临的主要问题之一，即一刀切的方法，这种方法会延续对弱势群体的偏见，而不是克服它。

In this chapter, we will be looking not at a particular AI strategy but at one of the main problems many of the strategies share, a one-size-fits-all approach, which is perpetuating bias against a vulnerable population instead of overcoming it.

我想了解残障人士在完成这些基于人工智能的评估时可能会遇到哪些陷阱。我邀请了马萨诸塞州布兰迪斯大学的残障政策分析师兼客座科学家亨利·克莱普尔（Henry Claypool）与我一起评估不同的人工智能招聘工具。

I wanted to find out what kind of pitfalls people with disabilities might encounter when they are asked to complete some of these AI-based assessments. I asked Henry Claypool, a disability policy analyst and visiting scientist at Brandeis University in Massachusetts, to assess different AI hiring tools with me.

披露还是不披露

TO DISCLOSE OR NOT TO DISCLOSE

亨利·克莱普尔是一位五十多岁的白人，他自己也是残疾人。大学期间，他在一次滑雪事故中脊髓受伤，导致两条腿和一只胳膊瘫痪。但这并没有阻碍他的职业生涯。克莱普尔曾在奥巴马政府任职，并帮助企业制定残疾人保险政策。

Henry Claypool, a white man in his fifties, is himself disabled. He sustained a spinal cord injury in a skiing accident during his college years that left him paralyzed in two legs and one arm. But this hasn’t held back his career. Claypool worked in the Obama administration and he helps companies with their disability policies.

他正看着 Pymetrics 游戏套件的其中一个开场画面。屏幕上要求玩家选择是玩针对色盲、注意力缺陷多动障碍或阅读障碍修改的游戏版本，还是玩未修改的版本。克莱普尔有点不知该如何选择。

He is looking at one of the opening screens of Pymetrics’ suite of games. It asks players to select whether they want to play a version of the games that’s modified for color blindness, ADHD, or dyslexia or a nonmodified version. Claypool isn’t so sure what to do.

“我想我确实有其中一种东西，但我没有“诊断之类的，”他跟我分享道。他说，尽管法律规定雇主必须为求职者提供合理的便利，但他对于这么早就向潜在雇主披露残疾信息感到不安。

“I think I do have a form of one of these things, but I don’t have any diagnosis or anything like that,” he shares with me. He says he feels uneasy about disclosing a disability to a potential employer so early on, although employers by law must offer reasonable accommodations to job applicants.

“你是不是把申请人逼到两难境地了？我应该选择披露信息并寻求便利，还是干脆硬着头皮上？”他问道。“我担心的是，如果我点击其中一项，就会披露一些信息，导致我失去这份工作的资格。如果我不点击，比如说，阅读障碍之类的，我就会比其他阅读和处理信息更快的人处于劣势。所以，无论如何，我都会失败。”

“You are putting the applicant on the horns of a dilemma, right? Do I choose to disclose and seek an accommodation or do I just push through?” he asks. “The fear is that if I click one of these, I’ll disclose something that will disqualify me for the job. And if I don’t click on, say, dyslexia, or whatever it is, I’ll be at a disadvantage to other people that read and process information more quickly. Therefore, I’m going to fail either way.”

他担心披露残疾信息会让他的申请被归入“B类”，招聘经理可能不愿理会。根据法律规定，求职者可以在招聘过程中要求提供合理的便利条件，但正如克莱普尔所说，许多求职者不敢提出这一要求，因为潜在雇主可能会认定申请人有残疾，从而忽略他们的申请。

He is afraid that disclosing a disability would essentially route his application in a “Pile B” that hiring managers may not want to touch. By law, a job candidate can ask for reasonable accommodation during the hiring process, but exactly like Claypool says, many candidates are afraid to ask because a potential employer might conclude that the applicant has a disability and ignore their application.

我向 Pymetrics 前首席执行官 Frida Polli 提出了这个问题。她表示，Pymetrics 在招聘过程中并没有告知雇主哪些申请人要求在游戏中提供便利，这本应有助于防止雇主歧视某些残障人士。

I brought this concern up with Frida Polli, the former CEO of Pymetrics. She said that Pymetrics did not tell employers which applicants requested in-game accommodations during the hiring process, which should have helped prevent employers from discriminating against people with certain disabilities.

她补充说，针对我的举报，公司会向求职者更清楚地说明这一信息，让他们知道，他们在游戏中住宿的需求是私密且保密的。（我已经无法访问 Pymetrics 的游戏了。）

She added that, in response to my reporting, the company will make this information clearer to applicants so they know that their need for an in-game accommodation is private and confidential. (I do not have access to Pymetrics’ games anymore.)

但除了游戏内为阅读障碍、注意力缺陷多动障碍和色盲提供的便利之外，患有其他残疾的求职者可能不知道自己会在这些游戏中遇到什么——他们怎么知道在开始游戏之前是否需要便利？（Pymetrics，现在的 Harver，表示它明确表示可以容纳三个（例如：注意力缺陷多动障碍、阅读障碍和色盲）。对于所有其他残疾，使用 Pymetrics 的雇主必须提供替代途径，Pymetrics 的说明中对此有明确说明。）

But beyond the in-game accommodations offered for dyslexia, ADHD, and color blindness, job applicants with other disabilities may not know what they will encounter in these games—how would they know if they need accommodation before they get started? (Pymetrics, now Harver, said it clearly stated it can accommodate three conditions—ADHD, dyslexia, and color blindness. For all other disabilities, employers using Pymetrics were required to provide an alternate pathway, and this was clearly stated in the Pymetrics instructions.)

“无论如何，现在我的焦虑加剧了，因为我知道自己可能处于劣势，”克莱普尔说。

“Either way, now my anxiety is heightened because I know I’m probably at a disadvantage,” Claypool says.

表现不佳还是测试有偏见？

POOR PERFORMANCE OR BIASED TESTING?

他玩的和我玩的是同一套游戏。一开始是给气球充气就能赚钱的游戏。他必须在气球爆掉之前把钱存起来。他用鼠标不停地给39个气球充气。

He is playing the same suite of games I played. It starts with the one where you get money for pumping up balloons. He has to bank the money before a balloon pops. He pumps and pumps thirty-nine balloons with his mouse.

“好的。现在腕管综合症正在形成，”他说。

“Okay. Now carpal tunnel is setting in,” he says.

几分钟后，他开始质疑自己，就像我一样。

A few minutes later, he is starting to question himself, just like I did.

“我真的很讨厌那款游戏，”他说，“我完全看不出它有什么逻辑。我知道自己正在接受某种测试，而它又不想让我明白测试的目的，这让我不得不努力去思考它究竟在期待什么。”

“I really hate that game,” he says. “I don’t see any logic in there at all. Knowing that I’m being tested by something that doesn’t want me to understand what it’s testing for makes me try to think through what it’s anticipating.”

换句话说，他脑子里和我一样在进行着元对话，试图弄清楚系统可能想要他做什么。这让他分心，因为他开始担心自己可能玩得不好。

In other words, he has the same meta dialogue going in his head that I had, trying to figure out what the system might want from him. And that distracts him from playing because he begins to fear he might not be doing well.

然后他开始玩一个游戏，屏幕上的数字快速闪动，你需要记住数字的顺序。“这让我很焦虑，”克莱普尔说。

He then moves on to the game where numbers quickly flash on the screen and you have to recall the sequence. “This raises my anxiety,” Claypool says.

“为什么？”我问。

“Why?” I ask.

“对我来说，记住一串数字很困难。每当我拿到用于身份验证的六位数代码时，我都必须看两遍，确保输入正确。”

“It’s difficult for me to recall a sequence of numbers. Whenever I get the six-digit code for my authentication, I have to look at it twice and make sure I got it right.”

克莱普尔的瘫痪导致躯干不稳定，这使得他难以使用传统键盘，这使他更难完成这项特定任务。

Claypool’s paralysis results in a trunk instability which makes it difficult to use a traditional keyboard, which makes it harder for him to fulfill this specific task.

正如之前提到的，我找到了一些 Pymetrics 的内部文档，其中描述了这款游戏。据说，申请人按下空格键的速度越快，他们的处理速度就越快，也就越聪明，越有创造力。

As mentioned earlier, I got ahold of some internal Pymetrics documents that describe this game. Supposedly, the faster the applicant hits the space bar, the higher their processing speed and the more intelligent and creative they are.

但是，如果有人患有运动障碍，他们的大脑可能运转良好，但他们的手可能不会运转得那么快；据推测，他们在这场比赛中的得分会较低，这可能意味着 Pymetrics 认为他们的智力和创造力低于平均水平。

But if someone has a motor disability, their brain might function well, but their hands may not function as fast; presumably, they would score lower on this game, which may mean to Pymetrics that they have below-average intelligence and creativity.

克莱普尔还有另一个问题：“按下键盘上的按钮和如何执行工作的基本职能之间有什么联系？”

Claypool has another question: “What is the connection between pushing on buttons on a keyboard and how one performs the essential functions of a job?”

我自己也想过这个问题。评估应该考察求职者是否能够胜任工作的基本职责，而不是关注其他特质或任务，因为这些特质或任务可能很随意，甚至可能与职位无关。对于克莱普尔来说，工作和尽可能快地按下键盘上的空格键之间有什么关系，这一点并不清楚。

I’ve wondered this myself. Assessments should be checking whether job applicants can fulfill the essential functions of a job and not focus on other traits or tasks, which could be arbitrary and may have nothing to do with the role. For Claypool, it’s not clear how a job and pushing the spacebar on a keyboard as fast as one can are related.

在他玩完所有游戏后，我问他有什么想法。

After he finishes playing all the games, I ask him what he thinks.

“最主要的感受是，面试过程压力很大，而且非常不人性化。我根本没法从面试官那里得到任何信息，比如‘我们接下来要做什么？我们为什么要这样做？’”他说。“人际交往对我来说至关重要，因为它能让我了解在特定情况下应该做什么。我处理信息的能力比平均水平慢，因此我处于明显的劣势，我认为这在测试结果中有所体现。”

“The main takeaway was that it was really stressful and that it was very impersonal. I wasn’t able to pick anything up off of an interviewer like, ‘Where are we going with this? Why are we doing this?’” he says. “Human interaction is kind of essential to me in terms of knowing what we are supposed to be doing in a particular situation. My ability to process information is slower than average and therefore I’m at a distinct disadvantage and I think it shows up in the test results.”

他和他的同龄人可能不得不玩这些游戏才能找到工作，这种想法让他感到不舒服。

The idea that he and his peers may have to play these games to get a job doesn’t sit right with him.

在一场关于人工智能招聘工具及其对残疾人的影响的网络研讨会上，美国残疾人协会主席兼首席执行官玛丽亚·汤恩表示，她担心求职面试中的面部表情和语音分析可能会对像她这样的残疾人产生负面影响。

In a webinar on AI hiring tools and the impact on people with disabilities, Maria Town, the president and CEO of the American Association of People with Disabilities, said she was worried that facial expression and voice analysis in job interviews could negatively affect people with disabilities like her.

“你可能看到我变得非常紧张。我患有脑瘫，这种残疾经常导致我痉挛，无法控制自己的动作。如果我接受这些测试，很可能会被认为不适合任何工作，也无法晋升。” 3

“You might be seeing me getting very nervous. I have cerebral palsy, a disability that often makes me spastic and unable to control my own movement. It’s likely that if I were subjected to one of these tests, it would deem me unqualified for any job and I would not advance in the process.”3

她说，问题在于决策过程缺乏透明度。技术或许已经成为企业用来遮羞的遮羞布。

The problem, she said, is that there is so little transparency about how decisions are made. And technology may have become a fig leaf for companies to hide behind.

“在很多情况下，技术可以消除直接问责，使人类决策者与这些招聘流程和其他人力资源流程的结果之间保持距离。” 4

“Technology, in many cases, has enabled the removal of direct accountability, putting distance between human decision-makers and the outcomes of these hiring processes and other HR processes.”4

需要更好的监管

THE NEED FOR BETTER REGULATIONS

在网络研讨会上，玛丽亚·汤恩恳求美国劳动世界监管机构之一的平等就业机会委员会（EEOC）开始采取行动：“正因如此，我们鼓励指导意见指出，求职者和其他决策结果将直接受到人工智能影响的人员应了解这些流程，并主动同意使用这些工具。”

In the webinar, Maria Town pleaded for the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission (EEOC), one of the regulators of the world of work in the United States, to start acting: “It’s for this reason that we encourage guidance to say that job seekers and others whose outcome decisions will be directly impacted by AI be informed of these processes and provide active consent for the use of these tools.”

亨利·克莱普尔也希望看到更多监管。他还希望公司能够重新考虑使用一些人工智能工具，包括这些游戏。他尤其担心残障人士，他们会尽力玩这些游戏，但可能无法做到，而公司将错失他们的才华。

Henry Claypool would like to see more regulation as well. He also hopes that companies will rethink using some AI tools, including these games. He is especially worried about people with disabilities who will try their best to play these games but might not be able to, and the company will miss out on their talent.

“想到人们必须经历这些才能获得真正的面试机会，我就觉得很生气，因为你可能因为没有以正确的方式处理信息而从这里开始。他们会因此错失多元化的申请资源。”

“This just makes me mad to think that people have to go through this to get an actual interview because you could get started out here because you’re not processing information the right way. And they’re going to miss out on a diverse applicant pool because of it.”

像 Pymetrics 这样的“一刀切”算法会在“高绩效”员工类别中寻找统计模式，而由于人类历史上的偏见，残障人士在劳动力中的代表性不足，因此该类别通常缺乏残障人士的游戏训练数据。此外，残障人士的经历和表达方式各不相同，并且呈现不同的谱系，由于这种差异性，他们的数据很可能无法被纳入统计模式。

A one-size-fits-all algorithm like Pymetrics’ looks for statistical patterns in the “high-performing” employees category, which often lacks game training data from people with disabilities since they are underrepresented in the workforce as a result of historical human bias. In addition, people with disabilities experience and express their disability individually and on a spectrum and in all likelihood their data would fall outside of statistical patterns because of this variability.

克莱普尔认为，如果招聘流程早期几乎所有的人际互动都被人工智能工具（这种工具正在迅速普及）取代，残障人士的求职之路将会更加艰难。“我们失去了那种人情味，真是太可惜了。有没有办法既能充分利用这些分析工具的优势，又不让人感到如此脆弱？我几乎感到害怕，”他说，“而且我感觉受到了某种侵犯，因为我被以我不太理解的方式试探。这种感觉很糟糕。”

Claypool believes it will be harder for those with disabilities to get hired if almost all personal interaction early in the hiring process is replaced with AI-based tools, which is rapidly increasing. “It is too bad that we’ve lost that human touch. Is there a way to use the merits of these analytic tools without leaving people feeling so vulnerable? I feel almost scared,” he says. “And a little bit violated that I have been probed in ways that I don’t really understand. And that feels pretty bad.”

他并不是唯一一个在使用自动招聘工具时遇到不愉快经历的人。

He is not the only one who has had unpleasant experiences with automatic hiring tools.

听不见 聋人和听力障碍人士

NOT HEARING DEAF AND HARD OF HEARING PEOPLE

索菲·鲍威尔 (S​​ophie Powell) 是纽约州罗切斯特市的一名黑人职业咨询师。她三十出头，在 2018 年 8 月至 2020 年 12 月期间，主要为聋人和听力障碍人士提供服务，参与了一项名为 ACCES-VR 的州政府资助项目。（她现在仍在为聋人提供服务）以及听力障碍人士，但在另一个组织中担任稍微不同的职务。）

Sophie Powell is a Black vocational counselor in Rochester, New York. She is in her early thirties and worked with mostly Deaf and Hard of Hearing folks between August 2018 and December 2020 for a state-sponsored program called ACCES-VR. (She still works with Deaf and Hard of Hearing people, but in a slightly different capacity at another organization.)

鲍威尔的工作是帮助残障人士就业。她帮助过各种各样的人找到工作——从零售业到罗切斯特大学的教授职位。她合作过的大多数人申请的是酒店和零售业的小时工，而这些行业中，人工智能招聘工具已经无处不在。

Powell’s job was to help people with disabilities find employment. She has assisted people in a variety of settings to get jobs—from retail to a professorship at the University of Rochester. Most people she worked with applied for hourly jobs in hospitality and retail, where AI hiring tools are ubiquitous.

对于残障人士来说，即使是申请工作也可能很困难。鲍威尔表示，在Indeed.com上申请工作对她的聋哑和听力障碍客户来说尤其困难，因为他们用英语评估申请人，而英语对很多人来说是第二语言。事实上，有些评估甚至连她自己都难以理解，而英语是她的母语。

For those with disabilities, even applying for jobs can be a struggle. Powell said that job applications on Indeed.com were especially difficult for her Deaf and Hard of Hearing clients because they assessed applicants in English, which is a second language for many. In fact, some assessments were even hard for her to make sense of and English is her first language.

鲍威尔懂美国手语 (ASL)，她会用手语向客户表达她对行为问题的理解，例如：“如果同事做了 X，你会怎么做？” “但聋哑人士会说，‘我不明白’，”鲍威尔回忆道。“这可能是出于文化角度；他们无法想象那样的情况以及他们会如何应对，也可能是语言的原因。”

Powell, who knows American Sign Language (ASL), would sign her understanding of a behavioral question to her client, for example, “What would you do if a coworker did X?” “But the Deaf person would be like, ‘I don’t get that,’” Powell recalled. “And it could be from a cultural perspective; they don’t just imagine situations like that and how they would respond, or it could be the language.”

许多聋哑人士首先学习的是英语和美国手语（ASL），而这两种语言是截然不同的。鲍威尔说，即使是专业的手语翻译，有时也会对如何在工作评估中向聋哑客户解释某个概念感到困惑。

English and ASL, which many Deaf and Hard of Hearing people learn first, are separate and distinct languages. Powell said that sometimes even a professional sign language interpreter can be puzzled about how to explain a particular concept in a job assessment to a Deaf client.

在英语中，意义来自于单词一个接一个的排列；例如，“一辆汽车撞到了一棵树”。在美国手语中，人们会用手势来表示汽车是如何撞到树的。

In English, meaning comes from words placed one after another; for example, “a car hitting a tree.” In American Sign Language, one would show with their hands how a car hits a tree.

其他职业顾问告诉我，英语中的细微差别，例如，性格测试询问某人是否“同意”、“强烈同意”、“不同意”或“强烈不同意”，在美国手语中很难理解。语言。因此，对于许多聋人和听力障碍人士来说，尽管他们可能能够阅读英语，但他们可能无法理解这些概念。

Other vocational counselors shared with me that nuances in English, for example, personality tests asking if someone “agrees,” “strongly agrees,” “disagrees,” or “strongly disagrees,” make little sense in American Sign Language. So for many Deaf and Hard of Hearing people, although they might be able to read English, they might not understand these concepts.

除了理解和翻译问题之外，Powell 遇到的另一个问题是测试通常有时间限制。她通常没有足够的时间阅读或聆听问题、理解问题内容、用手语向她的聋哑或听力障碍客户解释答案、让客户用手语回复 Powell，以及将答案翻译成英文。她估计，如果一项评估有十个问题，她和她的客户通常只能在规定时间内完成第三个或第四个问题。一个问题是，Powell 和她的客户在开始评估之前并不知道评估是否计时，所以他们可能会点击开始，然后时间用完，这使得之后很难获得便利。

Another problem Powell encountered, on top of the comprehension and translation issues, was that the tests are typically timed. There often wasn’t enough time for her to read or listen to the question, understand it, sign it to her Deaf or Hard of Hearing client, have the client sign their answer back to Powell, and for her to translate it into English. She estimated that, if an assessment had ten questions, she and her client often made it to only the third or maybe the fourth question in the time allotted. One problem was that Powell and her clients didn’t know if an assessment was timed before starting it, so they might click and begin and then run out of time, which made it hard to get an accommodation afterward.

这让鲍威尔很沮丧，她知道有些客户甚至为了来参加一个小时的预约都费尽心思。很多人攒了油钱，还安排了托儿服务。她不想让他们因为残疾而浪费整整一个小时，去做一场注定失败的评估。

This was frustrating for Powell, who knew that some clients worked hard to even get to their hour-long appointments with her. Many had saved up gas money and arranged childcare. She didn’t want them to waste an entire hour on an assessment they were doomed to fail because they had a disability.

像 HireVue 这样的供应商提供的视频面试对她的客户来说根本不起作用，因为她接触过的许多聋人和听力障碍人士并没有使用他们的声音。鲍威尔在客户遇到视频面试时会要求提供便利，因为法律要求大多数雇主提供便利。

Video interviews from vendors like HireVue didn’t work at all for her clients because many Deaf and Hard of Hearing people she worked with didn’t use their voices. Powell would request accommodation for her clients when they encountered video interviews, which most employers are required by law to offer.

我很惊讶地得知，当她提出调整要求时，结果是什么：“从来没有得到过回复。从来没有。”她说。她至少提出了20项调整要求。

I was surprised to learn what happened when she would request accommodation: “Never got responses. Ever,” she said. She asked for at least twenty accommodations.

在美国，根据《美国残疾人法案》，拥有超过 15 名员工的公司必须提供住宿。5可悲的是，索菲·鲍威尔并不是唯一有过这种经历的人。

In the United States, companies with more than fifteen employees must offer accommodations, according to the Americans with Disabilities Act.5 Sadly, Sophie Powell is not the only person who has had this experience.

帕蒂·桑切斯 (Patti Sanchez) 是一位直言不讳的中年纽约人，她搬到了佛罗里达州坦帕市，目前在麦克唐纳培训中心担任就业专员。桑切斯是拉丁裔，原籍波多黎各，并且是聋人。她主要服务于聋哑或听力障碍的求职者。她竭尽全力帮助每一位客户找到工作，并且不介意因此惹恼任何人。和索菲·鲍威尔一样，她也对招聘中使用的人工智能工具感到沮丧。

Patti Sanchez is an outspoken, middle-aged New Yorker who relocated to Tampa, Florida, where she now works as an employment specialist at the MacDonald Training Center. Sanchez is Latina, originally from Puerto Rico, and she is Deaf. She mainly works with job seekers who are Deaf or Hard of Hearing. She fights for every one of her clients to get a job and she doesn’t care if she ruffles any feathers doing it. Like Sophie Powell, she has been frustrated by AI tools used in hiring.

几年前，桑切斯的一位客户申请了亚马逊的职位，需要通过 HireVue 进行视频面试。桑切斯想申请一些便利条件。“于是我打了电话过去，结果邮箱都满了。”

A few years back, one of Sanchez’s clients applied for a job at Amazon that required a video interview through HireVue. Sanchez wanted to request accommodation. “So I called [the number] and the mailbox was full.”

随后，她在推特上表达了自己的不满：“@AmznFulfillment 的 #Deaf 面试如果在招聘活动前的最后一步使用 #hirevue，难度会加大。有没有人懂 #SignLanguage？而且残障人士邮箱已经满了，无法留言。”

She then took to Twitter to air her grievances: “@AmznFulfillment Interview for the #Deaf is getting more difficult if using #hirevue for the last step prior to the hiring event. Is there someone to understand the #SignLanguage? And the disability accommodations mailbox is FULL and unable to leave messages.”

她的直言不讳为她在坦帕赢得了一个特殊的绰号：“他们叫我‘鞭子’，”她笑着说道。

Her outspokenness has earned her a special nickname in Tampa: “They call me the Whip,” she said, laughing.

但就连党鞭在这个案例中也没有得到任何回复。相反，她带着她的客户和一名手语翻译来到了招聘现场，申请人通过 HireVue 面试后，进行了现场面试。她说服了那里的招聘经理对她的客户进行面试。

But even the Whip didn’t hear back in this particular case. Instead, she brought her client and a sign language interpreter to the job site, where applicants were interviewed in person after passing the HireVue interview. She persuaded the hiring managers there to interview her client.

她的策略奏效了。亚马逊雇佣了她的客户，但桑切斯表示，这类问题在使用自动化系统时很常见。想到许多雇主错失了那些才华横溢、敬业奉献的员工，而这些员工恰好身有残疾，但仍然可以胜任工作，并且积极性很高，这让她感到难过。

Her strategy worked. Amazon hired her client, but Sanchez said that issues like these are common when navigating automated systems. It makes her sad to know how many employers are missing out on talented and dedicated employees who just happen to have a disability but can still do the job and are highly motivated to work.

桑切斯说，公司通常根本不会考虑残疾人：“有时，当我向一家公司介绍为什么他们应该雇佣聋人和听力障碍人士时，”她说，“我我注意到很多首席执行官和经理都会说，‘哦，我没有想到这一点’，我想，这就是问题所在：你不会跳出固有思维模式，因为你只专注于一种方式。”

Sanchez said that often folks with disabilities are not even considered by companies: “Sometimes, when I give a presentation to a company on why they should hire a Deaf and Hard of Hearing person,” she said, “I notice so many CEOs and managers, they’re like, ‘ohh, I didn’t think of that,’ and I’m like, that’s the problem: you don’t think outside the box, because you’re just focused on one way.”

桑切斯说，这种态度也延伸到了招聘技术研发人员身上。这些技术的设计和生产往往没有考虑到残障人士。

This attitude extends to the people who build the technology used in hiring, Sanchez said. These technologies are often designed and produced without people with disabilities in mind.

即使公司努力提升无障碍性，努力也可能徒劳无功。索菲·鲍威尔回忆说，一些公司开始在视频评估中使用隐藏字幕，但这样做有时会带来另一个挑战，因为字幕速度太快，难以阅读。“他们必须记住，隐藏字幕试图跟上语音，但每个人的阅读速度都不一样。”

Even when companies try to bolster accessibility, the efforts may fall short. Sophie Powell recalled that some companies started to use closed captioning in video assessments, but doing so sometimes created another challenge because the captions ran too fast to read. “They have to keep in mind that the closed captioning is trying to follow along with the voice, but not everyone reads at the same pace.”

许多公司使用人工智能工具来简化招聘流程，并确保这些工具能够筛选每一位申请人，但他们可能低估了这些测试和评估（以及缺乏便利条件）给残疾人带来的困难程度。

Many companies use AI tools to make hiring easier and ensure that the tools screen every applicant, but they may underestimate how much harder these tests and assessments (and lack of accommodations) make it for people with disabilities.

帕蒂·桑切斯回忆起一次面试，面试官问了大约两百个性格相关的问题——太多了，她和她的客户根本无法把英语翻译成手语。面试花了很长时间，桑切斯甚至不明白这些问题和工作有什么关系，因为她的很多客户申请的是体力劳动或清洁工。“这跟刷马桶一点关系都没有，那用这个有什么意义呢？”她说。“这简直是浪费时间，而且对于那些真心想找工作的人来说，这简直让人沮丧。”

Patti Sanchez recalled one assessment that asked about two hundred personality-focused questions—too many for her and her client to translate back and forth from English to sign language. It took forever and Sanchez didn’t even understand what the questions had to do with the job because many of her clients apply for manual labor or janitorial positions. “This has to do nothing with cleaning toilet bowls, and so what’s the point to use this?” she said. “It’s a real waste of time and it’s frustrating for people who really want a job so badly.”

这次性格测试让她非常沮丧，她决定放弃。“我当时想哭，然后就想，‘我不想再浪费时间了，这太荒谬了。’”她说。桑切斯她决定为她的许多客户在遇到评估时采取一个激进的措施：“我替他们做。”她觉得这些测试和工作没多大关系，只是一个无关的障碍。

This particular personality test frustrated her so much that she decided she was done. “I want to cry and that’s where I’m like, ‘I’m not wasting time anymore, because it’s ridiculous,’” she said. Sanchez decided to take a radical step for many of her clients when they encounter assessments: “I do it for them.” She feels that the tests don’t have much to do with the job anyway and are just an unrelated obstacle.

远在千里之外，纽约州罗切斯特的职业咨询师索菲·鲍威尔也得出了同样的结论：“我为我服务的人感到非常沮丧，说实话，有时候我干脆就为他们做这些测试，因为我知道那些测试并不能代表他们作为一个人的真实面貌，”她说。

Thousands of miles away, Sophie Powell, the vocational counselor in Rochester, New York, came to the same conclusion: “I got so frustrated for the people I was serving that honestly sometimes I would just do it for them because I knew that those tests were not representing them as a person,” she said.

**不愿做出让步**

RELUCTANT ACCOMMODATIONS

帕蒂·桑切斯对客户经常遇到的这些数字测试非常熟悉：她会随机申请一些工作，进行“市场调研”，了解流程，以便更好地为客户提供帮助。她说，有些评估晦涩难懂，即使对她来说也难以理解——尽管她拥有学士和硕士学位，还会说英语。

Patti Sanchez is pretty familiar with these digital tests her clients encounter all the time: she does “market research” by randomly applying for jobs to understand how the process works so she can better assist her clients. Some of the assessments, she said, are obscure and hard to understand, even for her—and she has a bachelor’s and a master’s degree and speaks English.

对桑切斯来说，让她的客户与招聘经理亲自见面曾经意义非凡，因为许多招聘经理明白，残疾人也是人，他们也渴望工作，而且能够胜任这份工作。她感叹，在人工智能招聘时代，人际互动几乎消失了，尤其是在蓝领和计时工作方面，而她的大多数客户都申请这类工作。“这将是我在21世纪必须面对的一大挑战，”她说。

For Sanchez, having her clients meet with hiring managers in person used to make all the difference because many hiring managers understood that people with disabilities were human beings, often hungry to work, and could do the job. She laments that human interaction is essentially gone in the age of AI hiring, especially for the blue-collar and hourly jobs, which most of her clients apply for. “That’s going to be one big challenge I’m going to have to face in the twenty-first century,” she said.

帕蒂·桑切斯和索菲·鲍威尔的沮丧之情溢于言表。“这几乎让我怀疑自己是不是该回学校学法律之类的了，因为这太荒唐了。我想做点什么，”鲍威尔说。

Both Patti Sanchez’s and Sophie Powell’s frustration was palpable. “It almost made me want to figure out if I need to go back to school to study law or something, because this is ridiculous. I wanted to do something about it,” Powell said.

但她与客户相处的时间有限：“我无法集中精力因为我必须继续进行下一个工作，因为我正在努力帮助他们就业，所以我不能花太多时间去解决这个问题。”

But she had only limited time with her clients: “I couldn’t focus on that because I just have to keep going on to the next one because I’m trying to help them get employed, so I couldn’t put too much time into that frustration and trying to resolve that.”

与桑切斯一样，索菲·鲍威尔只是希望她的客户能够与真人见面并让对方相信自己的能力，而不是与无法理解他们的计算机见面。

Like Sanchez, Sophie Powell just wanted her clients to meet with a real person and convince that person of their abilities, not a computer, which wouldn’t understand them.

鲍威尔的另一项职责是跟进招聘经理，了解他们对客户的申请是否有任何疑问。她记得有一次与人力资源经理的通话，询问他们是否收到了客户的申请材料：“他们查看了客户的教育背景，知道他们上的是聋哑学校，然后人力资源经理马上在电话里告诉我，‘嗯，他们必须听一听。如果他们不听，我们就不能录用他们。’”

Another part of Powell’s responsibilities was following up with hiring managers to see whether they had any questions about her clients’ applications. She remembers one call specifically in which she talked to an HR manager and inquired if they had received her client’s application materials: “They saw their education history, that they went to a Deaf school, and immediately over the phone this HR person tells me, ‘Well, they have to hear. And if they don’t, then we can’t hire them.’”

鲍威尔大吃一惊。她回答说：“‘好的，我知道，但你知道《美国残疾人法案》（ADA）吗？或许有其他便利条件？我们先安排面试，然后再谈吧？’不行。点击。”

Powell was shocked. She replied: “‘Okay, I’m aware of that, but are you aware of the ADA [Americans with Disabilities Act]? And perhaps there is an accommodation available? How about we just schedule the interview first and then we can go from there?’ Nope. Click.”

挂断电话之前，人力资源经理告诉鲍威尔为什么她需要一个能听到声音的人：“这是一个装卸码头的职位，而且很危险，所以如果他们听不到卡车驶来的声音或类似的声音......我想，‘如果是在仓库里，你可以安装一盏灯，’”她回忆道。

Before they hung up, the HR manager told Powell why she needed someone who could hear: “It was a loading dock kind of position and it was because of danger, so if they don’t hear trucks coming or something like that…. I’m like, ‘If it’s in a warehouse, you can install a light,’” she recalled.

如果闪烁的警示灯可以算作一种合理的便利，那么公司很可能必须根据《美国残疾人法案》安装它。但对于那些日常出行（例如交通和儿童保育）已经捉襟见肘的人来说，残疾歧视索赔很难证明。

If a blinking light could be a reasonable accommodation, then a company in all likelihood would have had to install that under the Americans with Disabilities Act. But disability discrimination claims are hard to prove for folks who often already struggle with day-to-day activities such as securing transportation and childcare.

所有这些公司不遵守《美国残疾人法案》（ADA）规定的挫败感，让索菲·鲍威尔得出了一个令人警醒的结论：“显然，这是自愿选择的法律。这是一条你可以自愿接受的法律。”

All these frustrations with companies not following what is set out in the ADA led Sophie Powell to a sobering conclusion: “Apparently, it’s the law by choice. It is a law that you can buy into by choice.”

寻求公平

IN SEARCH OF FAIRNESS

《美国残疾人法案》、《英国2010年平等法案》以及世界各地其他类似的反歧视法之所以存在，是因为公平招聘很重要；每个人都有机会获得一份有报酬的工作并有饭吃。

The Americans with Disabilities Act, the UK Equality Act 2010 and other similar anti-discrimination laws around the world exist because it matters that hiring is fair; it matters that everyone gets a chance to have a paying job and put food on the table.

“这是许多人通往机遇的大门。它不仅关系到经济稳定，也关系到个人身份认同，”亚历山德拉·里夫·吉文斯（Alexandra Reeve Givens）说道。她是“民主与科技中心”（Center for Democracy and Technology）的首席执行官，该中心是一家非营利组织，倡导利用科技促进平等和人权。（全面披露：2021年，我和她共同撰写了一篇《纽约时报》的评论文章，探讨纽约市正在辩论的一项新的人工智能招聘法。）6

“This is the gateway to opportunity for so many people. It’s a huge part of not only economic stability but also personal identity for people,” Alexandra Reeve Givens said. She is the CEO of the Center for Democracy and Technology, a nonprofit that advocates for using technology to increase equality and promote human rights. (Full disclosure: She and I authored a New York Times opinion article together in 2021 about a new AI hiring law that was being debated in New York City.)6

她表示：“部署新工具可能会在已经存在访问挑战的领域设置人为障碍，这种风险确实令人担忧。”

“The risk that new tools are being deployed that are throwing up artificial barriers in a space that already has challenges with access is really troubling,” she said.

吉文斯和她的团队研究了招聘算法对残疾人和其他边缘群体的潜在影响。她认为，一些人工智能供应商的营销语言旨在让我们相信，他们的技术能够解决我们所有的招聘问题，无需进一步审查。

Givens and her team study the potential impacts of hiring algorithms on people with disabilities and other marginalized people. She thinks the marketing language of some AI vendors is designed to make us believe that their technologies are the answer to all our hiring problems and don’t need any further scrutiny.

“你听到有人说，‘嗯，这是迈向未来平等的一步’，对吧？由人来管理的人力资源管理本身就存在缺陷。人们会根据你的发型、肤色，或者你是否像他们的朋友来评判你，所以让我们转向游戏化测试吧，”吉文斯说道。她是已故克里斯托弗·里夫的女儿，克里斯托弗·里夫因在电影中扮演超人而闻名。1995年，他在一次骑马事故中瘫痪。

“You hear people saying, ‘Well, this is the move toward future equality,’ right? HR run by humans is inherently flawed. People are going to judge you based on your hairstyle or your skin color or whether you look like their friends or not their friends and so let’s move to gamified tests,” said Givens, who is the daughter of the late Christopher Reeve, best known for his film roles as Superman. In 1995, he was paralyzed in a horseback riding accident.

她并不相信这些卖家所宣称的积极说法：“我们希望看到有关人工智能使用的乐观故事，雇主们也对此深信不疑，却没有意识到这些工具实际上可以加深歧视，甚至比人类决策更糟糕，因为它们是大规模地进行歧视，而且它们的方式比个性化的人类偏见更难察觉，因为它隐藏在机器的决策背后。”

She doesn’t buy this positive narrative the vendors put out: “We want to see this optimistic story around the use of AI and employers are buying into that without realizing all of the ways in which these tools really can entrench discrimination and in a way even worse than human decision-making because they’re doing it at scale and they’re doing it in a way that’s harder to detect than individualized human bias, because it’s hidden behind the decision-making of the machine.”

我很幸运，成为少数有机会一窥这些人工智能游戏的人之一。我向吉文斯描述了这个空格键游戏。她对此并不感冒，并表达了担忧：这个游戏可能会筛选掉运动障碍人士，甚至可能筛选掉年纪更大的人。她还有另一个担忧：这项测试考察的是工作所需的技能吗？“他们试图用它作为替代指标，但这个替代指标能公平地预测工作所需的技能吗？我想说，对于一定比例的人口来说，答案是否定的。事实上，他们选择的测试方式肯定会以一种极不公平的方式筛选掉人群中的一大批人。”

I am lucky to be one of the few people who got a peek into these AI games. I described the spacebar game to Givens. She wasn’t impressed and shared her concern: the game might screen out people with motor impairments, maybe even people who are older. She had another concern: Does this test check for a skill that’s required for the job? “They’re trying to use this as a proxy, but is that proxy a fair predictor of the skills required for the job? And I would say here, the answer is no for a certain percentage of the population. And indeed, the way in which they’re choosing to test this is affirmatively going to screen out a bunch of people across the population in a way that’s deeply unfair.”

在有关工作中的人工智能的讨论中，一个反复出现的担忧是这些算法的训练数据中缺乏残疾人的代表性。

One concern that comes up again and again in discussions around AI at work is the lack of representation of people with disabilities in the training data of these algorithms.

“算法招聘工具‘学习’的主要方式之一是观察一组员工，找出他们有哪些共同特质，以及我们如何根据这些特质筛选未来的候选人？”吉文斯说道。残疾人在求职过程中历来面临歧视，而且在公司中，他们往往就业不足，代表性不足。“你会自动延续我们已知的劳动力市场中已经存在的排斥现象。”

“One of the main ways in which an algorithmic hiring tool ‘learns’ is by looking at a group of employees and figuring out what are the common traits that they share and how do we screen future candidates for those traits?” Givens said. People with disabilities have historically faced discrimination in finding jobs and are more often underemployed and underrepresented in companies. “You’re going to automatically be perpetuating the exclusion that we know already exists in the labor force.”

其他人也同意这一点。“人工智能社区面临的更普遍的挑战是如何处理异常值，因为机器学习系统会学习规范，并针对规范进行优化，不会以任何特殊的方式对待异常值。“这很正常。但很多时候，残障人士并不符合常态，”IBM 无障碍小组前研究员 Shari Trewin 在接受《麻省理工科技评论》采访时表示。 “如果你的数据集中性别多样性不足，你可以解决这个问题。但残障人士的多样性问题却不那么容易解决。” 7

Others agree. “The more general challenge for the AI community is how to handle outliers, because machine learning systems, they learn norms, they optimize for norms and don’t treat outliers in any special way. But oftentimes people with disabilities don’t fit the norm,” said Shari Trewin, former researcher in the IBM Accessibility group in an interview for MIT Technology Review. “If you don’t have enough gender diversity in your data set, you can fix that. It’s not so easy to fix disability diversity.”7

“如果整个系统的设置不考虑统计异常值，不仅不考虑它们，而且最终故意将它们排除在外，因为它们看起来不像你收集的统计中位数，你会怎么做？”吉文斯问道。

“What do you do when an entire system is set up not to account for statistical outliers and not only not to account for them, but to end up intentionally excluding them because they don’t look like the statistical median that you’re gathering around?” Givens asked.

供应商承诺进行偏见审计，但这些审计通常也不包括残障人士。事实上，这几乎是不可能的，因为残障人士的个体差异很大。

Vendors stipulate that they do bias audits, but those don’t usually include people with disabilities either. In fact, that would be almost impossible because disabilities are expressed so individually.

“我们确实知道，残疾人士并没有被考虑在内，”吉文斯说。“我之所以能如此肯定地说，是因为这些供应商经常说我们已经审核过平台是否存在偏见。他们的意思是，他们已经对种族和性别偏见进行了统计审计。仅此而已。这说明他们根本没考虑到残疾人士。”

“We know for a fact that people with disabilities aren’t being considered,” Givens said. “The reason I can say that with such certainty is that these vendors are very often saying we’ve audited our platforms for bias. And what they mean by that is that they’ve done a statistical audit for race and gender bias. And that’s it. That’s what tells me that they are not thinking about disability.”

莎莉·特雷温（Shari Trewin）也表达了类似的观点。“很多系统会将种族或性别建模为具有少量可能值的简单变量。但说到残疾，它有多种不同的形式和严重程度。有些是永久性的，有些是暂时的。我们任何人都可能在人生的任何时候加入或离开这个类别。这是一个动态的过程，”她说。8残疾人可能看起来不像现在的员工，但他们仍然可能能够胜任这份工作。

Shari Trewin echoed these sentiments. “A lot of systems will model race or gender as a simple variable with a small number of possible values. But when it comes to disability, there are so many different forms and different levels of severity. Some of them are permanent, some are temporary. Any one of us might join or leave this category at any time in our lives. It’s a dynamic thing,” she said.8 And people with disabilities may not look like the current employees, but nevertheless might still be able to do the job.

《美国残疾人法案》的要求是，求职者必须能够在需要时获得便利的情况下履行工作的基本职责。“这就避免了你进行一些大型统计分析，然后说，‘哦，好吧，这个人有点不符合条件，’”吉文斯说。“不，你需要根据他们的个人情况，参见：你测试他们是基于他们的工作能力，还是他们能在工作场所胜任？所以法律对此有规定，它对雇主的要求不仅仅是遵循基本的相关性。

The requirement in the Americans with Disabilities Act is that job applicants must be able to perform the essential functions of the job with accommodations if they need them. “That precludes you doing some big statistical analysis and saying, ‘Oh, well, that person kind of falls outside,’” Givens said. “No, you need to look at their individual circumstances and see: Are you testing them based on their ability to perform the job and could they do so in the workplace? So the law has something to say about this, and it’s asking more of employers than just following basic correlation.”

要了解申请人可能需要哪些便利，通常需要与人交谈，而不是与机器交谈。但问题在于，许多公司使用机器进行第一轮拒绝，因此很多申请人直到最后一轮招聘才有机会与人交谈。

Understanding that an applicant might need accommodations often requires a conversation with a human, not a machine. But the problem is that many companies use machines to make the first round of rejections, so many applicants don’t even get to speak to a human until they are in the final rounds of hiring.

“这项测试无法让一个人达到那个水平，无法与雇主进行细致的沟通，了解他们的能力以及他们将如何胜任该职位。所以，你甚至还没来得及就你将如何胜任该职位进行沟通就被筛选掉了。我认为这才是真正令人担忧的地方，”吉文斯说。

“The test isn’t letting somebody get through to that level, to be able to have the nuanced conversation with the employer about what their abilities are and how they would perform in the role. So you’re being screened out before you even get to have the conversation about how you would perform in the role. And that’s the part that I think is really troubling,” Givens said.

她主张公司也应该将一定比例的无需特殊安排的求职者引导至公司为残障求职者提供的便利条件，例如，安排与真人招聘经理的面试，而不是玩人工智能游戏。这样，雇主就有动力去关注“B组”中的求职者，也就是那些申请特殊安排的求职者。

She advocates for companies to also route some percentage of applicants without a need for an accommodation to whatever accommodation the company provides job applicants with disabilities, for example, offering a job interview with a human hiring manager instead of playing AI games. This way employers have an incentive to check out the job applicants in “Pile B,” the folks who requested an accommodation.

但无论是亚历山德拉·吉文斯，还是从律师转型为人工智能和招聘活动家的罗兰·贝姆，都不相信很多公司会采用这种方法。相反，他们亲身经历了使用这类人工智能工具的雇主们的冷漠态度。

But neither Alexandra Givens nor Roland Behm, a lawyer turned AI and hiring activist, believe that many companies will implement such an approach. Instead, they have experienced careless attitudes from employers that use these kinds of AI tools.

“在我与许多大型雇主的交谈中，我询问他们的验证和筛选流程时，他们普遍的回答是，他们什么都没做。基本上，他们进去后就说，‘财富250强企业中有70家都在用这个，’”贝姆在2022年2月向平等就业机会委员会作证时回忆道。9他描述了公司高管的从众心理：“我们为什么要花钱验证一下？因为你刚刚告诉我们所有这些公司都在用它，所以，它肯定没问题。

“In my conversations with many major employers, the general res­ponse to my questions asking about their validation and selection process is that they didn’t do any. That basically they go in there and they say, ‘This is being used by seventy out of the Fortune 250,’” Behm recalled in his testimony to the EEOC in February 2022.9 He described a herd mentality by company executives: “Why would we spend any money validating that? Because you’ve just told us that it’s being used by all of these companies, so, ergo, it must be okay.”

他还表示，如果这些工具被证明存在缺陷或歧视性，他发现雇主在责任方面存在严重的幼稚之处。“如果这项[测试]是非法的职前体检，那么每个参加评估的人都可能向雇主提出索赔。而当我们谈论每年筛查一千万人的大型雇主时，我们谈论的是一项潜在的重大责任，我认为很多雇主并不理解或意识到这一点，”贝姆说。

He also said he has encountered a grave naivete in regard to an employer’s liability if these tools are proven to be faulty or discriminatory. “If this [test] is an illegal preemployment medical examination, every person who takes that assessment has a potential claim against the employer. And when we’re talking about major employers who are screening ten million people a year, we’re talking about a potentially significant liability that I don’t think many employers are understanding or are aware of,” Behm said.

他也对企业打着创新牌的做法持谨慎态度，他基本上认为所有创新都是进步：“通过计算机算法洗白人类的偏见，可以让这些偏见看起来客观合理。虽然这或许很有创意，但世界不需要更多创新的方式来歧视残疾人。”

He is also wary of companies pulling the innovation card, basically saying that all innovation is progress: “This laundering of human prejudice through computer algorithms can make those biases appear to be justified objectively. And while it may be innovative, the world doesn’t need more innovative ways to discriminate against persons with disabilities.”

他希望所有雇主在使用一项技术之前，都能仔细考虑其可能带来的后果。“你可以使用，并不意味着你应该使用。或许应该把这一点刻在一块牌匾上，发给所有雇主，或者至少发给所有使用人工智能的自动决策系统的提供商，”贝姆说。

He wishes all employers would think through the possible ramifications of using a technology before utilizing it. “Just because you can, doesn’t mean you should. And maybe that should be inscribed on a plaque and given to all the employers, or at least all the providers of automated decision-making systems that use AI,” Behm said.

亚历克斯·吉文斯表示，企业需要做的不仅仅是遵守法律。企业需要要求供应商在产品中内置无障碍功能，并在残障人士身上测试这些工具，以确保这些工具不带有偏见或歧视性。

Alex Givens says that companies need to do better than just following the law. Companies need to demand from vendors that accessibility is built into the products and that these tools are tested on people with disabilities to ensure that the tools are not biased or discriminatory.

她认为，公司有责任改善社会，包括确保他们有包容性的招聘实践和提供公平的住宿条件，而这些流程在公司引入人工智能筛选时往往会丢失：“你失去的是在更人性化的互动中可以捕捉到的细微差别，或者在有对话空间的地方，人们可以欣赏他们的本来面目和他们所做的事情。”摆到桌面上来——而不是如何与模型所创建的虚假统计表示进行比较。”

She believes companies have a duty to better society, including making sure they have inclusive hiring practices and offering fair accommodations, processes that often get lost when companies introduce AI screens: “What you are losing is the nuance that you can pick up on in a more human interaction or a place where there is space for there to be dialogue for a person to be appreciated as they are and for what they bring to the table—as opposed to how they stack up against this false statistical representation that’s created by the model.”

同样的伦理考量不仅适用于基于人工智能的招聘工具，也适用于用于监控生产力（例如仓库生产力）的算法。这些基于人工智能的生产率可能会导致工人精疲力竭，一些工人甚至可能因为生产率过高而受伤或致残。战略组织中心的一项研究表明，亚马逊仓库因其生产率低而臭名昭著，其工人受伤的人数几乎是同类公司的两倍。10

The same ethical considerations should be applied not only to AI-based hiring tools but also to algorithms that are used to monitor productivity, for example, in warehouses. These AI-based productivity rates could lead to exhaustion, and some workers might even be injured or become disabled because of productivity rates. Amazon warehouses are infamous for their productivity rates, and their workers suffer almost twice as many injuries compared to similar companies, according to a study by the Strategic Organizing Center.10

专家将使用算法跟踪的亚马逊仓库称为“数字血汗工厂”，并担心这种一刀切的模式可能是非法的，并可能伤害特别脆弱的员工。

Experts call Amazon’s warehouses where algorithmic tracking is used “digital sweatshops” and are afraid this one-size-fits-all model could be illegal and might harm especially vulnerable employees.

一些能够胜任工作但可能需要临时安排的员工（例如，因为怀孕，需要坐一会儿或需要更多上厕所的时间）的生产率可能会降低。同样的情况也可能发生对于那些需要临时安排的残疾员工。平等就业机会委员会主席夏洛特·伯罗斯表示，因需要临时安排而对他们进行训斥或解雇可能是违法的。“过于严格地应用生产率算法会导致不合法的待遇。”

Some workers who can do the job but who may need temporary accommodation—because they are pregnant, for example, and need to sit down for a minute or need more bathroom breaks—could have lower productivity rates. The same might happen to those who develop a disability and need accommodation. Reprimanding or firing them for needing accommodations might be illegal, said Charlotte Burrows, chair of the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission. “An overly rigid application of a productivity algorithm will result in unlawful treatment.”

对于吉文斯和其他人来说，缺乏对残障人士的照顾，甚至缺乏对他们的关怀，是当今社会面临的重大民权问题之一。“思考一下科技如何改变人们获取机会的方式，以及它在哪些方面加剧了歧视，”她说。“这是一种道德上的缺陷。”

For Givens and others, the lack of accommodations and even thought for people with disabilities is one of the big civil rights questions of our day: “Thinking through how technology is transforming people’s access to opportunity and where it’s perpetuating discrimination,” she said. “It’s a moral failing.”

这不仅适用于残疾人或老年人。

And this does not apply only to people with disabilities or older people.

她说：“这是一个关乎我们社会运作的问题。”如果我们不解决这个问题，歧视就会继续存在，甚至可能变得更糟。

“This is a question about the functioning of our society,” she said. If we don’t get this right, discrimination will just continue and may even get worse.

变革案例研究

A CASE STUDY OF CHANGE

在就人工智能如何影响残障人士进行了这些发人深省的讨论之后，我想与平等就业机会委员会（EEOC）进行更深入的交流。该委员会的职责是确保全美范围内公平、平等地获得就业机会。我们都知道人工智能工具存在诸多问题，但为什么EEOC却无所作为呢？

After these sobering conversations about how AI affects people with disabilities, I wanted to have a longer talk with the EEOC, which is tasked with enforcing fair and equal access to employment across the United States. We know about all of these problems with AI tools; why is the EEOC doing so little?

我是2021年第一位就人工智能问题采访平等就业机会委员会（EEOC）委员基思·桑德林（Keith Sonderling）的记者。他曾是一名就业律师，被特朗普政府任命为EEOC委员，并于2020年9月宣誓就职。在他的任命听证会上，他多次表示，他听到过人们对人工智能工具的担忧，并决定将这一主题作为他的标志性项目之一。

I was the first reporter to interview EEOC commissioner Keith Sonderling in 2021 on AI. He is a former employment lawyer who was appointed to the EEOC by the Trump administration and sworn in in September 2020. During his confirmation hearings, he said that again and again he’d heard concerns about AI tools and decided to make this topic one of his signature projects.

Sonderling（德语中意为“不谙世事的怪人”，与这位专员的性情和举止完全不符）向我保证，根据法律规定，如果求职者因残疾而无法参加考试，雇主必须提供便利，但据我了解，这种情况并不总是发生。

Sonderling (which means “unworldly eccentric” in German and doesn’t fit the commissioner’s temperament and demeanor at all) assured me that, by law, employers must offer an accommodation if job applicants cannot take a test because of a disability, but, as I learned, that doesn’t always happen.

“残疾歧视年复一年地成为索赔案件中最多的案件之一。对平等就业机会委员会来说，残疾歧视问题极其严重，”他说。“我们需要一个完全自由、公平的工作场所，确保在工作中不会发生任何歧视。”

“Disability discrimination, year after year, is one of the highest-filed claims. For the EEOC, disability discrimination is extremely serious,” he said. “We need a workplace that is completely free and fair, and that there’s no discrimination happening while you’re at work.”

我很惊讶他竟然仍然将人工智能视为一项能够解决许多问题的突破性技术。“这其中有无限的益处，”他说，“[人工智能]是消除招聘和晋升偏见的绝佳途径，更重要的是，它能帮助雇主找到对工作满意度高的合适人选。对员工来说，他们也能找到适合自己的工作。所以本质上，如果设计和实施得当，它就是一项很棒的婚介服务。”

I was surprised that he still viewed AI as this breakthrough technology that would solve a lot of problems. “There’s unlimited benefits here,” he said. “[AI] is an excellent way to eliminate bias in recruiting and promotion, but also, more importantly, it’s going to help employers find the right candidates who will have high-level job satisfaction. And for the employees, too, they will find the jobs that are right for them. So essentially, it’s a wonderful matchmaking service if it’s properly designed and implemented.”

他确实提出了一些警告：“尽管人工智能可以帮助雇主快速找到合适的员工，并且可以通过让员工同时完成他们最擅长的任务和工作来帮助员工在工作场所茁壮成长，但它可能会比你能想到的一些原始歧视更严重，”桑德林说。

He did bring up some caveats: “Although artificial intelligence can help employers find the right employees quickly and can help employees thrive in the workplace by doing the tasks and jobs that they’re most adept to at the same time, it could potentially discriminate worse than some of the original discriminations you could think of,” Sonderling said.

重要的是要明白，该委员会主要打击两种类型的歧视。它起诉故意歧视的雇主，例如不雇用50岁以上的员工，或者因为员工怀孕而解雇他们。这些都是故意歧视，是违法的。

What’s important to understand is that the commission mainly goes after two types of discrimination. It sues employers that intentionally discriminate, for example, by not hiring people over fifty or by laying off an employee because they got pregnant. That’s intentional discrimination and unlawful.

该委员会还会追查那些本意良好但使用测试或其他工具无意中对“受保护群体”产生歧视影响的雇主，“受保护群体”是平等就业机会委员会 (EEOC) 的术语，指基于种族、肤色、宗教、性别、性取向、怀孕、国籍、年龄、残疾或基因信息的歧视。

The commission also goes after employers that might have had the best intentions but used tests or other tools that unintentionally have discriminatory effects against “protected groups,” which is the EEOC terminology for discrimination based on race, color, religion, sex, sexual orientation, pregnancy, national origin, age, disability, or genetic information.

这项无意歧视法规极有可能适用于人工智能工具，其历史可以追溯到1971年最高法院具有里程碑意义的“格里格斯诉杜克电力案”。桑德林解释说：“在该案中，威利·格里格斯和其他12名非裔美国员工起诉他们的雇主，指控该公司要求员工必须拥有高中文凭或通过一般智力测试才能获得高薪职位，违反了法律。” 这些员工辩称，学位和一般智力测试的要求与工作无关，因此筛选掉的非裔美国员工比白人员工更多。

The unintentional discrimination statute, which would most likely be applied to AI tools, goes back to a landmark 1971 Supreme Court decision called Griggs v. Duke Power. “In that case, Willie Griggs and twelve other African American employees sued their employer, alleging that the company was violating the law by requiring employees to either have a high school degree or pass a general intelligence test to qualify for a higher-paying position,” Sonderling explained. The employees argued that the degree and the general intelligence test requirements weren’t relevant to the job and filtered out more African American employees than white ones.

杜克电力公司不同意这种观点，并认为要求高中毕业或通过普通智力测试并不具有歧视性，因为这些要求对所有员工都适用。（而且（对普通人来说，这在我们很多人看来可能很合理。每个人都有机会上高中，都能通过普通智力测试，对吧？）

Duke Power disagreed and argued that requiring a high school degree or a passing score on a general intelligence test were nondiscriminatory because these requirements applied to all employees equally. (And as laypeople, that probably seems reasonable to many of us. Everyone gets a chance to go to high school and can pass a general intelligence test, right?)
