但当时在北卡罗来纳州，非裔美国人接受高中教育的可能性低于白人。而且考试成绩也不平等：“公司要求的通用智力测试的通过率，白人员工的通过率为58%，非裔美国人员工的通过率为6%。”桑德林补充道。

But at the time in North Carolina, African Americans were less likely to have a high school education than white Americans. And the tests were also unequal: “The pass rate for the general intelligence test that the company wanted to require was 58 percent for white workers and 6 percent for African American workers,” Sonderling added.

最高法院站在非裔美国工人一边，宣布以截然不同的比率评估不同种族申请人的评估工具是非法的，除非该公司可以证明该评估是为了测试特定的工作要求，但格里格斯诉杜克电力公司案中的情况并非如此。

The Supreme Court sided with the African American workers and declared assessment tools that passed applicants from different races at widely different rates to be unlawful, unless the company can make a case that the assessment is testing for specific job requirements, which was not the case in Griggs v. Duke Power.

过去的评估与今天的评估之间存在一个关键区别。直到最近，员工才知道需要通过哪些测试才能在公司获得高薪职位，但随着人工智能的出现，人们通常甚至不知道自己正在接受测试或评估，也不知道人工智能工具的决策依据是什么。由于如今缺乏这种知识，许多人无法提起歧视索赔。在格里格斯案以及无数其他评估挑战中，员工和求职者之所以能够提起诉讼，是因为他们知道自己接受了测试，了解测试内容，并且可以就其可能具有歧视性的原因提出论据。

There is one crucial difference between the assessments of the past and those of today. Employees, up until very recently, knew which tests they would have to pass to get a higher-paying job at a company, but with AI, folks often don’t even know that they are being tested or assessed or on what basis an AI tool makes decisions. Because of this lack of knowledge today, many won’t be able to file a discrimination claim. In the Griggs case and in countless other assessment challenges, employees and job applicants were able to bring a case because they knew they were tested, they knew what the test entailed, and they could make an argument about why it was potentially discriminatory.

即使求职者或员工知道人工智能游戏工具正在评估他们的工作，他们也不知道自己是如何被分析和评分的，也不知道他们被拒绝是基于优点还是因为算法错误。缺乏透明度。

Even if job applicants or employees know that an AI games tool, for example, is assessing them for a job, they do not know how they were analyzed and scored or whether their rejection was based on merit or on a faulty algorithm. There is no transparency.

这对每个人都有影响，尤其是对残疾。例如，在基于人工智能的视频面试中：“如果软件因为残疾（例如言语障碍）而无法理解面试者，即使他们是最合格的申请人，程序也会自动给他们低于非残疾申请人的分数，”桑德林说道。但到目前为止，还没有人能够提供任何证据表明这些工具对有言语障碍的申请人有效或无效，因为绝大多数基于人工智能的视频面试都是黑匣子。

That has consequences for everyone, but especially for people with disabilities. For example, in AI-based video interviews: “If the software cannot understand the interviewee because of a disability, such as a speech impediment, the program will automatically score them lower than someone without a disability, even though they are the most qualified applicant,” Sonderling said. But, so far, no one has been able to show any evidence that the tools work or don’t work for applicants with speech impairments, because overwhelmingly AI-based video interviews are black boxes.

2023 年 6 月，我与 HireVue 首席数据科学家 Lindsey Zuloaga 谈论了这个问题，她告诉我，公司已经对这个问题进行了深入思考，并且基于人工智能的语音转文本转录工具对于带有口音的英语使用者来说越来越准确。

I spoke to Lindsey Zuloaga, the chief data scientist at HireVue, about this in June 2023 and she told me that the company has thought extensively about this problem and that AI-based speech-to-text transcription tools are getting more accurate for English speakers with accents.

当我问她关于言语障碍人士的情况，以及不同的言语障碍如何导致语音转文本（AI 会用语音转文本来给求职者评分）的错误率更高时，她承认了一个问题：“这是一个非常有趣的领域，因为很难找到足够的数据，”她说。于是她建立了自己的数据集：“一天下午，我做了一个关于口吃的小研究。”

When I asked her about individuals with speech impairments and how different speech disabilities could lead to higher error rates in speech-to-text transcription, which the AI uses to score job applicants, she acknowledged a problem: “This is a whole interesting area because it’s so hard to find enough data on that,” she said. So she built her own data set: “One afternoon, I did my own little study on stuttering.”

Zuloaga 创建了一个数据语料库，用于一些临时测试：“我获取了一些记录，并手动对其进行了处理，使其看起来像是人们在口吃。”

Zuloaga created a data corpus for some ad hoc testing: “I took some transcripts and manually messed with them to make it look like people are stuttering.”

大多数口吃形式，例如申请人中断说话或重复单词的开头，都不会对人工智能的转录和预测造成问题。但她发现了一个问题：申请人重复整串单词。“重复长串单词会影响你的分数，”Zuloaga 说。她将自己的测试案例描述为极端的口吃案例，并想知道人类会如何评判它们。她很想与残疾人权利组织合作，获取更多数据，以更深入地研究这一领域。

Most forms of stuttering, such as when applicants stop their speech stream or repeat the beginning of a word, do not induce problems in the AI’s transcriptions and predictions. But she found one problem: when applicants repeat whole strings of words. “That long string repetition can hurt your score,” Zuloaga said. She described her test cases as extreme cases of stuttering and wondered how humans would also judge them. She would love to work with a disability rights organization to obtain more data to study this area in more depth.

关于人工智能游戏，平等就业机会委员会 (EEOC) 委员 Keith Sonderling 和委员会主席 Charlotte Burrows（几个月后我采访了她）认为，像 Pymetrics 在其人工智能游戏套件中那样，要求人们尽可能快地按下键盘上的空格键，或许值得商榷。“那些可能因残疾而无法使用键盘的人会对此有不同的理解，并可能因此受到不利影响，这并非因为具体的工作内容，而仅仅是因为他们在使用键盘时灵活性较低，”Burrows 说。“如果这在工作中不会成为问题，那么这可能违反了我们的法律。”

In regard to AI games, EEOC commissioner Keith Sonderling and the chair of the commission Charlotte Burrows (whom I interviewed a few months later) believe that asking someone to press the spacebar on the keyboard as fast as they can, as Pymetrics does in its suite of AI games, might be questionable. “Someone who maybe has a disability that affects their ability to use a keyboard will take that differently and could be disadvantaged, not for anything to do with the particular job, but solely because they are in the position of having to have less dexterity in their use of that keyboard,” Burrows said. “If that’s not a problem that will be ever relevant in the job, that could be a violation of our laws.”

另一个问题是，申请人不知道收集到的数据是如何被使用的，也不知道为什么自己被拒。如果没有确凿的损害证据（是键盘游戏导致他们被拒吗？是申请人的口吃导致了错误的预测？），在人工智能时代，几乎不可能获得这些证据，因此很难在美国法院提起诉讼并最终获得支持。

Another issue is that applicants don’t know how the data collected on them is used and why they have been rejected for an opportunity. Without having concrete evidence of harm (Did the key-pressing game result in them being rejected? Did an applicant’s stutter lead to the wrong prediction?), which is almost impossible to get in the age of AI, it is challenging to file a case in a US court that will stick.

包括埃默里大学法学教授伊菲奥玛·阿琼瓦在内的一些专家认为，我们需要修改法律以适应这一新现实。求职者应该能够“本身”（per se）提起诉讼，这意味着“从表面上看”，无需提供具体的损害证据。例如，一个行动障碍人士在玩一款要求他们尽可能快地按下空格键的人工智能游戏时，可以选择提起诉讼：“当使用招聘平台的原告遇到有问题的设计功能时——比如检查就业空白期的平台——她应该能够以歧视本身为由提起诉讼，然后雇主将被要求提供来自内部和外部审计的统计数据证据，以表明其招聘平台没有非法歧视某些群体，”阿琼瓦在《纽约时报》的一篇评论文章中写道。11

Some experts, including Ifeoma Ajunwa, the law professor at Emory University, have argued that we need to change our laws to adjust to this new reality. Job applicants should be able to file a case “per se,” which means “on its face,” without having concrete evidence of harm. For example, someone with a motor disability who plays an AI game in which they are asked to press the spacebar as fast as they can would have an option to file a lawsuit: “When a plaintiff using a hiring platform encounters a problematic design feature—like platforms that check for gaps in employment—she should be able to bring a lawsuit on the basis of discrimination per se and the employer would then be required to provide statistical proof from internal and external audits to show that its hiring platform is not unlawfully discriminating against certain groups,” Ajunwa wrote in a New York Times opinion piece.11

法律的变更可能会赋予人们质疑这些工具设计的权利，并要求公司负责证明其工具无害。这也可能有助于平等就业机会委员会（EEOC）展开调查。基思·桑德林表示，在有人提供证据之前，EEOC 束手无策。但在人工智能的新世界里，证据通常掌握在公司手中。

A change in the law could give people the right to challenge the design of these tools and make the company responsible for showing that its tool is not harmful. This could also help the EEOC start an investigation. Keith Sonderling said that the EEOC’s hands are tied until someone comes forward with evidence. But in this new world of AI, the evidence usually stays with the company.

“你之所以没有看到该领域出现更多诉讼，也没有看到更多联邦执法行动，一个重要原因是，员工可能不知道自己受到了计算机或个人的歧视——无论是故意的，还是通过不公正的测试结果，”桑德林说。“但就平等就业机会委员会 (EEOC) 调查人工智能和招聘索赔的权力而言，所有 EEOC 案件都必须从员工开始。”

“A big reason why you haven’t seen more litigation in this area or more federal enforcement in this area is that the employee may not know that they were discriminated against by a computer, by a person—whether it’s intentionally or through the results of a skewed test,” Sonderling said. “But as far as the EEOC authority to investigate AI and hiring claims, all EEOC cases have to start with an employee.”

我可以看出桑德林对平等就业机会委员会（EEOC）在公司使用人工智能方面缺乏执法或任何形式的沟通感到沮丧：“没有任何指导方针。没有任何针对人工智能使用的具体规定，无论是简历筛选，还是定向招聘广告、面部识别或语音识别，自从这项技术诞生以来，EEOC 就没有出台过任何新的指导方针。”他告诉我。

I could tell that Sonderling was frustrated by the lack of enforcement or any kind of communication from the EEOC in regard to companies using AI: “There have been no guidelines. There’s been nothing specific to the use of artificial intelligence, whether it is résumé screening, whether it’s targeting job ads or facial recognition or voice recognition, there have been no new guidelines from the EEOC since the technology has been created,” he told me.

我在 2021 年 7 月初采访了 Keith Sonderling。有关该主题的播客和印刷系列于当月晚些时候在《麻省理工学院技术评论》上发表。12以下是促使 EEOC 觉醒并调查工作中人工智能的事件时间表。

I interviewed Keith Sonderling in early July 2021. The podcast and print series on the subject were published later that month in MIT Technology Review.12 Following is a timeline of events that contributed to the EEOC waking up and looking into AI at work.

2020年12月

DECEMBER 2020

2020 年 12 月，11 名民主党参议员致信美国平等就业机会委员会，表达了对使用招聘技术的担忧：“虽然招聘技术可以有时候，它们会降低个别招聘经理偏见的影响，但也会重现并深化当今劳动力数据所反映的系统性歧视模式。” 13

In December 2020, eleven Democratic senators wrote a letter to the US Equal Employment Opportunity Commission expressing concerns about the use of hiring technologies: “While hiring technologies can sometimes reduce the role of individual hiring managers’ biases, they can also reproduce and deepen systemic patterns of discrimination reflected in today’s workforce data.”13

参议员们基本上是在提醒平等就业机会委员会（EEOC）要成为一个执法机构。“求职者和雇主依赖该委员会对行业进行严格的研究和监督，并提供适当的指导。” 信中特别询问该机构是否有权力和能力调查这些工具是否存在歧视。“我们要求提供有关该委员会开展必要研究和监督以确保公平招聘的权力和能力的信息。”

The senators basically reminded the EEOC to be an enforcement agency. “Job applicants and employers depend on the Commission to conduct robust research and oversight of the industry and provide appropriate guidance.” The letter asked specifically whether the agency had the authority and capabilities to investigate whether these tools discriminate. “We request information about the Commission’s authority and capacity to conduct the necessary research and oversight to ensure equitable hiring.”

2021年1月

JANUARY 2021

2021 年 1 月，平等就业机会委员会 (EEOC) 致函我，这封信后来被泄露，并发表在《麻省理工学院技术评论》的一篇文章中。14在信中，委员会承认当时并未调查任何人工智能工具：“据我们所知，委员会尚未收到投诉人提出的基于使用此类技术进行歧视的指控，委员会也没有开展指控此类歧视的执法程序。” 15 EEOC 表示，该委员会可能会遇到业界不愿共享数据的局面，而且针对不同公司软件进行校准的人工智能工具将阻止 EEOC 制定任何广泛的政策。

The EEOC responded with a letter in January 2021 that was leaked to me and was published in an article in MIT Technology Review.14 In the letter, the commission acknowledged that it was not investigating any AI tools at the time: “To our knowledge, the Commission has not received a charge of discrimination from a complainant alleging discrimination based on the use of such technologies, and the Commission has not conducted enforcement proceedings alleging such discrimination.”15 The EEOC stated that the commission would likely encounter hesitance from the industry to share data and that AI tools calibrated to different companies’ software would prevent the EEOC from instituting any broad policies.

“当我看到这样的回应时，我感到惊讶和失望，”行为健康人士的律师兼倡导者罗兰·贝姆 (Roland Behm) 说。问题。“这封信的整个基调似乎让平等就业机会委员会看起来更像是一个被动的旁观者，而不是一个执法机构。” 16

“I was surprised and disappointed when I saw the response,” said Roland Behm, the lawyer and advocate for people with behavioral health issues. “The whole tenor of that letter seemed to make the EEOC seem like more of a passive bystander rather than an enforcement agency.”16

当时，平等就业机会委员会（EEOC）由唐纳德·特朗普提名的珍妮特·迪隆（Janet Dhillon）领导。然而，有趣的是，司法部采取了更加积极主动的行动。当我向使用 HireVue 基于人工智能的招聘系统的亚特兰大公立学校（APS）提交信息自由请求时，我发现了一些有趣的信息。显然，司法部已开始对 APS 使用 HireVue 的情况进行调查。

At the time, the EEOC was run by Janet Dhillon, who had been nominated by Donald Trump. What’s interesting, though, is that the Department of Justice has taken a much more proactive role. When I filed a Freedom of Information request with Atlanta Public Schools (APS), which has used HireVue’s AI-based hiring system, I came across some interesting information. Apparently, the Department of Justice started an inquiry into APS’s usage of HireVue.

平等就业机会委员会（EEOC）的监督往往是被动的，但由于求职者很难证明存在歧视，该行业基本上不受美国最重要的招聘监管机构之一的影响。非营利组织Upturn的作者在一份关于该主题的报告中指出：“实际上，大多数雇主面临来自执法人员的太小压力，以至于无法对其甄选手段进行有意义的评估，并考虑歧视性较小的替代方案。” 17

The EEOC’s oversight is often reactive, but because it’s so hard for applicants to prove discrimination, the industry is basically untouched by one of the most important agencies tasked with overseeing hiring in the United States. In a report on the subject, the authors at the not-for-profit organization Upturn stated: “In practice, most employers face too little pressure from enforcers to meaningfully evaluate their selection devices and consider less discriminatory alternatives.”17

2021年10月

OCTOBER 2021

我在《麻省理工技术评论》上发表文章几个月后，我指责平等就业机会委员会 (EEOC) 对人工智能工具中歧视的证据（尤其是针对残疾人的歧视）没有做出反应，EEOC 宣布将成立一个人工智能工作组。

A few months after my MIT Technology Review stories were published, in which I called out the EEOC for not reacting to evidence of discrimination in AI tools, especially for people with disabilities, the EEOC announced that it was launching an AI task force.

专项小组听起来很棒——行动已经采取——但它们也可能只是让外界觉得某个机构在做一些事情，而实际上他们什么也没做。我对这种事态发展并不感到紧张。

Task forces sound great—action is taken—but they could also just make it look to the outside world that an agency is doing something, when really they are doing nothing. I wasn’t on the edge of my seat about this development.

2022年2月

FEBRUARY 2022

2022 年 2 月，平等就业机会委员会 (EEOC) 邀请我采访该委员会主席夏洛特·伯罗斯 (Charlotte Burrows)。

In February 2022, the EEOC offered me an interview with the chair of the commission, Charlotte Burrows.

我重申了我的担忧，并讨论了AI工具失效的具体例子。她向我保证，她的机构正在调查AI在职场决策中的应用：“对我们平等就业机会委员会（EEOC）和其他执法机构来说，认真思考AI如何从根本上改变就业实践至关重要，”她说。“我们必须确保[AI工具]不会成为通往歧视的高科技途径。”

I reiterated my concerns and we talked about specific examples of AI tools not working. She promised me that her agency was looking into AI being used to make decisions in the workplace: “It’s really important for us at the EEOC and other law enforcement agencies to be thinking about how AI is really fundamentally changing employment practices,” she said. “We have to make sure that [AI tools] don’t become a high-tech pathway to discrimination.”

对她来说，研究人工智能是平等就业机会委员会使命的核心：“我确实认为我们的机构对于确保每个人都有机会享受这个国家的基本协议至关重要，那就是人人享有平等和正义。”

To her, looking at AI is at the core of the EEOC’s mission: “I really see our agency as essential to ensuring that everyone has the opportunity to enjoy what is the basic agreement of this nation, which is equality and justice for all.”

2022年5月

MAY 2022

2022 年 5 月，我得到了一些有趣的消息：平等就业机会委员会 (EEOC) 终于与司法部联合发布了第一份关于人工智能和招聘的出版物——一份技术指导文件，18因此它不会追究任何人的责任或针对歧视案件执行法律，但它让公司知道 EEOC 正在关注他们，如果委员会发现所使用的技术歧视残疾人，他们就要承担责任。

In May 2022, I got a heads-up on some interesting news: the EEOC, together with the Department of Justice, finally released its first-ever publication on AI and hiring—a technical guidance document,18 so it’s not holding anyone accountable or enforcing the law against a case of discrimination, but it lets companies know the EEOC is watching them and they are on the hook if the commission finds out that the technologies used are discriminating against people with disabilities.

在一次媒体电话会议上，司法部民权助理部长克里斯汀·克拉克直言不讳：“今天，我们发出警告，要警惕盲目依赖人工智能和其他技术所带来的危险，我们看到这些技术越来越多地被雇主，”她说道。19她还要求雇主对其所使用的技术保持透明。

In a media call, Kristen Clarke, the assistant attorney general for civil rights at the Department of Justice, didn’t mince words: “Today we are sounding an alarm regarding the dangers tied to blind reliance on AI and other technologies that we are seeing increasingly used by employers,” she said.19 She also asked employers to be transparent about the technologies they are using.

尽管平等就业机会委员会和司法部发布的这份文件旨在指导如何使用人工智能工具，但它却迟迟未发布。“使用这些工具可能会对残疾求职者和员工造成不利影响。一旦发生这种情况，雇主可能会违反保护残疾人士的联邦平等就业机会法（EEO）。”

Although the document the EEOC and DOJ released was meant to be a guide on how to use AI tools, it was forthcoming. “The use of these tools may disadvantage job applicants and employees with disabilities. When this occurs, employers may risk violating federal Equal Employment Opportunity (‘EEO’) laws that protect individuals with disabilities.”

有时候，做这样的新闻工作很不容易。我们发现了一件又一件的不法行为，但感觉似乎什么都无法改变。但时不时地，也会出现一些变化，这份报告似乎是平等就业机会委员会迈向承认这些自动化系统存在问题的第一步。这是一个小小的胜利。现在，我比以往任何时候都更加相信改变是可能的。（我本身并不反对人工智能工具；我只是想确保这些工具能够挑选出最合适的候选人，并且不进行歧视。）

Sometimes it’s hard to do this kind of journalistic work. We find wrongdoing after wrongdoing, but it feels like nothing will ever change. But every now and then, there is a little bit of change, and this publication seemed like the first step by the EEOC toward acknowledging that there is a problem with these automated systems. A small win. Now more than ever, I believe that change is possible. (I am not per se against AI tools; I just want to make sure that the tools pick the best candidates and that they don’t discriminate.)

令我惊讶的是，平等就业机会委员会和司法部的声明如此广泛地涵盖了歧视的概念。在“雇主使用算法决策工具如何违反《美国残疾人法案》？”这个问题下，平等就业机会委员会和司法部写道：“雇主依赖一种算法决策工具，该工具有意或无意地‘屏蔽’了残障人士，即使该人士能够在合理的安排下完成工作。”

I was surprised how broadly the EEOC and DOJ announcement took the idea of discrimination. Under the question “How could an employer’s use of algorithmic decision-making tools violate the ADA?” the EEOC and DOJ wrote: “The employer relies on an algorithmic decision-making tool that intentionally or unintentionally ‘screens out’ an individual with a disability, even though that individual is able to do the job with a reasonable accommodation.”

我不是律师，但这听起来好像几乎所有残疾人士如果在工作中被拒绝，即使是在第一轮招聘中，只要他们能够在合理的安排下完成工作，都可以要求平等就业机会委员会强制执行。

I am not a lawyer, but that sounds like almost anyone with a disability could ask for EEOC enforcement if they were rejected for a job, even in one of the first hiring rounds, given they could do the job with reasonable accommodation.

我觉得这里有一个关键段落，对于使用 Pymetrics 或 Plum 的 AI 游戏等工具的雇主来说，可能会带来问题。性格测试：“如果一个空缺职位需要具备撰写报告的能力，雇主可能希望避免使用算法决策工具，因为这些工具会通过衡量申请人的性格与目前成功的报告撰写人的典型性格之间的相似性来评估这种能力。通过这样做，雇主可以降低拒绝那些擅长撰写报告，但由于残疾而性格在成功的报告撰写人中并不常见的人的可能性。”平等就业机会委员会写道。

Here is a critical paragraph that I think might turn out to be problematic for employers that use tools like Pymetrics’ or Plum’s AI games and personality tests: “If an open position requires the ability to write reports, the employer may wish to avoid algorithmic decision-making tools that rate this ability by measuring the similarity between an applicant’s personality and the typical personality for currently successful report writers. By doing so, the employer lessens the likelihood of rejecting someone who is good at writing reports, but whose personality, because of a disability, is uncommon among successful report writers,” wrote the EEOC.

更美好的未来

A BETTER FUTURE

我希望平等就业机会委员会和司法部能够追求广泛的执法目标，因为性格测试的使用非常普遍，特别是对于计时工人而言。

My hope is that the EEOC and DOJ will go after broad enforcement goals because the use of personality tests is so ubiquitous, especially for hourly workers.

向行业发出警告是朝着正确方向迈出的一步，但我采访过的专家们希望看到更多。作为第一步，行业需要提高透明度。申请人和员工必须知道他们何时被分析。我们还需要知道个人是如何被评估的。

It’s a step in the right direction to warn the industry, but experts I have spoken to want more. As a first step, the industry needs more transparency. Applicants and employees must know when they are being analyzed. We also need to know how individuals are being assessed.

其他批评人士对许多供应商用来规避审查的专有算法论点感到厌倦：“我们有一个不能透露的秘密武器，”弗兰克·帕斯夸莱（Frank Pasquale）如此形容这些公司。帕斯夸莱是布鲁克林法学院的教授，也是算法问责方面的专家。

Other critics are tired of the proprietary algorithm argument that many vendors utilize to avoid scrutiny: “We have a secret sauce that we can’t disclose to you,” Frank Pasquale said, characterizing what these firms sound like. Pasquale is a professor at Brooklyn Law School and an expert in algorithmic accountability.

他和其他人希望对这些工具进行更多的问责和独立审计，但不是由私营公司来做，因为付费审计很容易导致利益冲突，我在为《麻省理工技术评论》报道人工智能招聘领域的两项审计时就发现了这一点。20

He and others would like more accountability and independent audits of these tools, but not by private companies because payment for audits can easily lead to conflicts of interest, which I found when reporting on two audits in the AI hiring space for MIT Technology Review.20

涉案的两起审计，一次由 Pymetrics 出资，另一次由 HireVue 出资，暴露了利益冲突是如何潜伏的。所谓的“独立审计”可能被用来掩盖有争议的审计师认可印章背后的实践。两家供应商都利用审计结果进行营销。

The two audits in question, one paid for by Pymetrics, the other paid for by HireVue, showcased how conflicts of interest can creep in. The “independent audits” could have been used to hide controversial practices behind the auditors’ stamp of approval. Both vendors used the audits for marketing purposes.

HireVue 审计给我留下了深刻印象，因为它基本上是一场圆桌讨论，审计人员重点强调了利益相关者提到的潜在问题。审计人员并未访问 HireVue 的数据或算法。尽管如此，HireVue 还是发布了一份新闻稿，宣称“HireVue 致力于在招聘中透明且合乎道德地使用人工智能，引领行业发展”，并且 HireVue 的“评估在公平性和偏见问题上确实如宣传的那样有效”，21尽管审计人员实际上并未从技术层面审计训练数据、算法流程或结果。此外，任何想要从 HireVue 网站下载报告的人都必须签署一份准保密协议，这非常不寻常。（HireVue 表示，审计是向利益相关者分享公司方法和科学成果的机会。）

What struck me about the HireVue audit was that it was basically a roundtable discussion and the auditors highlighted potential problems stakeholders had mentioned. The auditors did not access HireVue’s data or algorithms. Nevertheless, HireVue issued a press release declaring that “HireVue Leads the Industry with Commitment to Transparent and Ethical Use of AI in Hiring” and that HireVue “assessments work as advertised with regard to fairness and bias issues,”21 although the auditors didn’t actually get to audit the training data, the algorithmic processes, or the results on a technical level. Additionally, anyone who wanted to download the report from HireVue’s website was required to sign a quasi nondisclosure agreement, which is highly unusual. (HireVue says that audits have been an opportunity to share the company’s approach and their science to stakeholders.)

在另一项针对 Pymetrics 游戏套件的审计中，该供应商聘请了东北大学的两位计算机科学教授 Christo Wilson 和 Alan Mislove 及其研究生来测试 Pymetrics 模型的公平性。22这项审计因将 Pymetrics 的四名成员列为报告的共同作者而受到批评，这让人对该报告的编辑独立性产生了怀疑。23此外，该公司在其营销材料中宣称其产品“经过独立审计”。

For the other audit, of Pymetrics’ suite of games, the vendor paid two computer science professors from Northeastern University, Christo Wilson and Alan Mislove, and their graduate students to test the fairness of the Pymetrics models.22 This audit was criticized for crediting four members of Pymetrics as coauthors of the report, which calls into question the very idea that this report was editorially independent.23 In addition, the company declared its product “independently audited” in its marketing materials.

研究人员确实访问了数据、模型和源代码，但并未测试这些工具是否选出了最合格的申请人：“我们关注的并非这些游戏是否真正衡量了人们在现实世界中工作的能力，”威尔逊说道。相反，该团队测试了这些工具是否遵循了被称为“四五分之一规则”的准行业“公平”标准。

The researchers did access the data, the models, and the source code but didn’t test whether the tools picked the most qualified applicants: “We are not looking at whether these games actually measure people’s ability to do work in the real world,” Wilson said. Instead, the team tested whether the tools abide by the quasi industry standard of “fairness” called the four-fifths rule.

根据五分之四规则，招聘筛选应选择大致相同比例的男性和女性，以及来自不同种族的人员：例如，如果有1000名男性申请，其中800人通过评估，那么男性的通过率为80%。如果也有100名女性申请，那么根据平等就业机会委员会的五分之四规则，评估要被视为“公平”，至少需要有64名女性通过评估，因为女性的通过率为64%（80%的五分之四）。当然，女性的通过率为80%才是公平的，因为女性的通过率与男性相同，但五分之四规则也留有一定的回旋余地。

According to the four-fifths rule, hiring screens should select roughly the same proportion of men and women and of people from different racial groups: so, for example, if 1,000 men apply and 800 make it through the assessment, that is an 80 percent passing rate for men. If 100 women also apply, for the assessment to be considered “fair” under the four-fifths rule by the EEOC, then at least 64 women need to pass the assessment because that is a passing rate for women of 64 percent (four-fifths of 80 percent). Of course, a pass rate of 80 percent for women would be precisely fair, being the same rate as men, but the four-fifths rule allows for some wiggle room.

这是一种最低联邦标准，而 Pymetrics 算法通过了测试：“最大的收获是 Pymetrics 实际上做得非常好，”威尔逊说。

It’s kind of a minimum federal standard, and the Pymetrics algorithm passed: “The big takeaway is that Pymetrics is actually doing a really good job,” Wilson said.

但也有人不同意这种观点：“实际上，这个问题更像是‘Pymetrics 是否做到了他们所说的？’而不是‘他们做的是否正确？’”麻省理工学院斯隆管理学院教授 Manish Raghavan 表示，他发表了大量关于人工智能和招聘的文章。

But others disagreed: “It effectively felt like the question being asked was more ‘Is Pymetrics doing what they say they do?’ as opposed to ‘Are they doing the correct or right thing?’” said Manish Raghavan, a professor at MIT Sloan School of Management who has published extensively on artificial intelligence and hiring.

在我与克里斯托·威尔逊（Christo Wilson）就交叉公平问题进行的交谈中，我萌生了“做正确的事情”的想法。威尔逊的团队并没有像平等就业机会委员会（EEOC）建议的那样，仅仅检查男性与女性、亚裔与黑人、白人与美洲原住民等等的“通过率”，而是测试了该模型是否考虑了交叉公平。这意味着，女性的通过率可能在可接受的范围内，但处于两个因素交叉点的黑人女性或亚裔美国女性的通过率是否也可接受？

And that idea of doing the right thing came up in my conversations with Christo Wilson in regard to intersectional fairness. Instead of just checking the “passing rates” of men versus women and Asian versus Black versus white versus Native American, and so forth, as the EEOC suggests, Wilson’s team also tested whether the model allows for intersectional fairness, meaning that passing rates might be in the acceptable range for women overall, but would Black women or Asian American women, who sit at the intersection of two factors, also pass at acceptable rates?

这是“性别阴影”研究中的一个问题，麻省理工学院的研究员 Joy Buolamwini 发现，三种面部检测工具存在她对数据集中所有女性的总体准确率在 92% 到 98% 之间，但对黑人女性的准确率只有 65% 到 79% 。24

This was a problem in the Gender Shades study in which MIT researcher Joy Buolamwini found that three face detection tools had an accuracy rate between 92 percent and 98 percent overall for all women in her data set, but only a 65–79 percent accuracy rate for Black women.24

“我们知道这通常是一个问题，”克里斯托·威尔逊说。“瞧，这确实是一个问题。”

“We know that it is typically an issue,” Christo Wilson said. “Lo and behold, it’s an issue.”

威尔逊的团队利用 Pymetrics 的人工智能工具研究了种族和性别的交叉情况，发现在某些情况下，包括黑人女性在内的交叉群体与白人男性相比，不符合五分之四规则。在最终报告发布前的一次采访中，他与我分享了这一信息。

Wilson’s team looked at intersections of race and gender in Pymetrics’ AI tool and found that in some instances intersectional groups including Black women did not pass the four-fifths rule compared to white men, for example. He shared this information with me during an interview before the final report was published.

但威尔逊回忆说，在报告发布之前，Pymetrics说服威尔逊及其团队将交叉公平性测试排除在最终审计报告之外，因为Pymetrics告诉研究人员，由于平等就业机会委员会（EEOC）的指导方针和判例法，他们无法实施交叉公平性测试。“如果Pymetrics无法真正纠正这个问题，那么就说他们失败了，这对我们是不公平的。”威尔逊解释了为什么这部分测试没有被纳入最终报告。（2022年收购Pymetrics的Harver公司拒绝置评。）

But before publication of the report, Pymetrics convinced Wilson and his team to leave their testing of intersectional fairness out of the final audit report because Pymetrics told the researchers that it couldn’t implement intersectional fairness because of the EEOC guidelines and case law, Wilson recalled. “It would be unfair for us to say that Pymetrics failed at this thing if they couldn’t actually correct it” was how Wilson described the reason for why this was left out of the final report. (Harver, the company which acquired Pymetrics in 2022, declined to comment.)

我认为威尔逊和他的团队进行的额外检查非常重要，即使这些检查并未包含在最终报告中。我们应该对交叉公平性进行测试，尽管平等就业机会委员会当时并未明确要求这样做。（我采访过的专家认为，平等就业机会委员会一直允许进行更多测试，例如，对交叉公平性进行测试。）

I believe it was important that Wilson and his team did the additional checks, even though they were not part of the final report. We should test for intersectional fairness even though the EEOC did not explicitly require it at the time. (Experts I talked to believe that the EEOC has always allowed more testing, for example, on intersectionality.)

2023 年 5 月，即 Pymetrics 审计两年后，平等就业机会委员会在其网站上发布了技术援助指南，正式要求公司实际检查交叉公平性。25

In May 2023, two years and change after the Pymetrics audit, the EEOC issued technical assistance guidelines on its website asking companies formally to actually check for intersectional fairness.25

因此，许多专家希望政府在这些工具上市之前对其进行测试，而不是依赖产品供应商支付的私人审计，因为这样会引发利益冲突：“应该有一个先发制人的监管，这样在你使用任何这些系统之前，平等就业机会委员会应该对其进行审查，然后颁发许可证，”弗兰克·帕斯夸莱说。

So, instead of relying on private audits paid for by product vendors that raise conflicts of interest, many experts want the government to test these tools before they come on the market: “There should be a preemptive regulation so that before you use any of these systems, the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission should need to review it and then license it,” Frank Pasquale said.

他说，美国食品药品监督管理局（FDA）在这方面是一个很好的榜样。与其允许任何类型的人工智能招聘工具进入市场，不如让供应商经过类似于FDA批准新药的预先审批流程。供应商不仅要向客户保证他们的人工智能工具不会造成伤害，还必须像制药商一样，首先通过双盲或三盲测试向政府证明这一点，因为就业领域的风险很高。这将是一个成本高昂的过程，但或许有必要确保这些工具不会损害求职者的利益。

The Food and Drug Administration is a good model here, he said. Instead of allowing any kind of AI hiring tools on the market, vendors would have to go through a preapproval process similar to how new medications are approved by the FDA. Instead of just assuring customers that their AI tools don’t cause harm, vendors would have to prove it to the government first in double- or triple-blind tests just like pharmaceutical manufacturers have to do, because the stakes in the employment arena are high. It would be a costly process, but it might be necessary to ensure that these tools don’t harm job applicants.

为了实现这一目标，国会需要修改法律，赋予平等就业机会委员会主动监管该领域的权力，而不是只在个人投诉后才追究雇主的责任。

For that to happen, Congress would need to change the law and give the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission the power to proactively regulate the field instead of only going after employers once an individual has complained.

我们有责任意识到这些发展，并努力影响立法者改变规则。我们不必被动地接受这个强加于我们的新世界。

It’s on us to be aware of these developments and to try to influence lawmakers to change the rules. We do not have to passively accept this new world that is being thrust upon us.

第七章

CHAPTER 7

寻找隐藏的宝石

Finding Hidden Gems

关于预测分析和安静招聘

On Predictive Analytics and Quiet Hiring

西我们正在进入一个人工智能时代，测量选项几乎无限。我们现在有办法记录键盘输入，追踪网站访问、电子邮件、Slack 消息、公司评论——几乎任何东西。但人工智能系统捕捉到的信号能揭示什么有意义的东西吗？许多人力资源部门的人认为它们能。在本章中，我们将从探讨人工智能如何应用于招聘，转向如何利用人工智能来监控和评估员工。

We are entering an era of mostly unlimited measurement options with artificial intelligence. We now have the means to record keystrokes and track website visits, emails, Slack messages, company reviews—almost anything. But do the signals that AI systems capture reveal anything meaningful? Many people in HR think they do. In this chapter, we pivot from exploring how AI is used in hiring to how AI can be used for monitoring and evaluating employees.

许多工作场所都存在两种主要的监控方式。一种是自上而下的监控：监控员工在工作场所（以及下班后）的一举一动，我将在下一章讨论这个问题。另一种是预测分析：分析信号以了解员工的技能，从而规划职业发展路径，并尽可能多地了解员工，使企业（以及员工）受益。

Two dominant strains of monitoring occur in many workplaces. One is top-down surveillance: monitoring every move an employee makes in the workplace (and after hours), which I tackle in the next chapter. The other is predictive analytics: analyzing signals to understand workers’ skills in order to build career paths and learn as much as possible about employees to benefit the business (and the employee).

这是一项相对较新的技术应用，主要用于公司内部系统。遗憾的是，目前公众对此的了解和批判性学术研究还不多。但对我来说，展示许多大公司内部正在发生的事情仍然很重要。

It’s a relatively new application of technology and mostly used in internal company systems. Unfortunately, there is not a lot of public knowledge and critical scholarship yet. But it’s still to me important to show what is happening inside many large companies.

人力资源作为侦察行动

HR AS A SCOUTING OPERATION

过去，大多数公司将员工视为成本中心——对许多组织而言，这无疑是最大的成本中心。人力资源被视为公司警察，负责确保每个人的行为规范，以保护组织。如今，人力资源正成为企业的关键组成部分。

In the past, most companies have seen their employees as cost centers—the largest one by far for many organizations. Human resources was viewed as the company police who made sure everyone behaved as a way to protect the organization. Now, HR is becoming a critical part of the business.

电信公司沃达丰前人力资源技术主管马克·斯塔菲尔德 (Marc Starfield) 表示：“如果我们想在缺乏人力资源的情况下实现公司真正发展，那根本就不可能实现。”

“If we want to really grow as a company without HR, it just wouldn’t happen,” said Marc Starfield, the former head of HR technology for Vodafone, a telecommunications company.

尤其是在美国，过去公司通常会直接解雇那些技能过时或不被看好的员工，并招聘具备所需技能的新员工。但对于大多数企业来说，这已不再是一个可持续的长期选择，因为空缺职位的数量超过了可供招聘的熟练失业工人的数量。1

Especially in the United States, in the past companies would simply lay off employees who had outdated or undesired skills and hire new ones with the desired skills. But that is no longer a sustainable long-term option for most businesses since there are more open positions than skilled unemployed workers to hire.1

如今，企业纷纷转向自身员工，寻找“隐藏的人才”。人力资源部门利用预测分析工具，试图了解公司内部员工，发掘组织内部此前未被发掘的人才和新领导者。一些研究人员将这种趋势称为“静默招聘”。

Companies are now turning to their own employees to find “hidden gems.” HR uses predictive analytics tools to try to understand a company’s own people and discover previously invisible talents and new leaders inside the organization. Some researchers call this trend “quiet hiring.”

几年前，一些人工智能供应商（主要是 Eightfold、Gloat 和 Fuel50）应运而生。这些公司以各种有趣的方式运用人工智能：例如，为员工创建一个内部市场，帮助他们学习新技能并申请内部职位。

Several AI vendors, mainly Eightfold, Gloat, and Fuel50, came onto the scene a few years ago. These companies use artificial intelligence in interesting ways: for example, to create an internal marketplace for employees to help them learn new skills and apply for internal positions.

目前，数百甚至数千家公司和政府机构正在使用这些工具，其中包括纽约州。Eightfold 已成为一家独角兽公司，2021 年估值达 21 亿美元。2

Hundreds if not thousands of companies and government agencies are now using these tools, including the State of New York. Eightfold has become a unicorn company and was valued at $2.1 billion in 2021.2

人工智能正在改变企业招聘和提拔内部候选人的方式，使其不再依赖资历和学位，而是更加注重技能。从我们目前对人工智能在人力资源领域的应用的了解来看，这是一个积极的发展。

AI is changing how companies hire and promote internal candidates by relying less on credentials and degrees and more on skills. From what we have covered so far about the use of AI in HR, this is a positive development.

“如果你回顾过去，你会发现招聘者通常会问‘你上的是哪所大学？你的GPA是多少？你在哪里工作？哦，你在IBM工作过？你肯定很优秀’，”人力资源技术市场行业分析师乔希·伯辛(Josh Bersin)说道。“而现在，我们则说，‘我们得先搞清楚哪些技能是关键。现在，我们得去找符合要求的人。’”

“If you go back in time, it used to be ‘What college did you go to? What was your GPA? Where did you work? Oh, you worked at IBM? You must be good,’” said Josh Bersin, an industry analyst of the HR technology market. “Now we’re in a world where we’re saying, ‘Let’s do some work to figure out what the skills are. Now let’s go out and find people that fit that.’”

Eightfold 运营着一个平台，员工可以使用他们的 LinkedIn 账户或简历快速创建个人资料。然后，人工智能会提取员工的技能，推断他们可能没有列出的技能，并推荐合适的工作。该公司也提供类似的招聘技术。

Eightfold runs a platform where employees can use their LinkedIn account or their résumé to build a quick profile. The AI then pulls out an employee’s skills, infers skills they might not have listed, and recommends appropriate jobs. The company offers similar technology for hiring.

Marc Starfield 是 Eightfold 软件的忠实粉丝。2022 年底我们采访时，他负责支持沃达丰约十万名员工的所有技术，以及所有有助于公司人力资源战略的项目。他来自南非，在人力资源技术领域工作了二十多年，常驻伦敦。

Marc Starfield is a fan of Eightfold’s software. When we spoke in late 2022, he was in charge of all technology that supports the roughly one hundred thousand Vodafone employees and any programs that help the company’s HR strategy. He has worked in HR technology for more than twenty years, based in London, and is originally from South Africa.

我们在拉斯维加斯的HR Tech展会上见面，这是全球最大的人力资源技术博览会之一。他告诉我，沃达丰有一个宏伟的目标，所以决定引入Eightfold：沃达丰希望从一家电信公司转型为一家科技和通信公司——其他行业的许多公司也在这样做。例如，许多银行不再只想做银行，他们想成为恰好涉足银行业务的科技公司。

We met in Las Vegas at HR Tech, one of the largest HR technology expos in the world. He told me that Vodafone has a big goal and that’s why it decided to bring in Eightfold: Vodafone wants to move from being a telecommunications company to being a technology and communications company—a move that many companies in other sectors are doing as well. For example, many banks don’t want to just be banks anymore; they want to be technology companies that happen to be in banking.

但科技人才需求旺盛，企业向科技领域的融合也使得员工跳槽变得更加容易。许多人已经这样做了。

But tech talent is in high demand and this convergence of businesses toward technology makes it easier for employees to change jobs. Many have done so.

回顾去年，“美国三分之一的员工换了工作；其中45%的人改变了行业，”行业分析师乔希·伯辛（Josh Bersin）表示。“公司之间、行业之间的流动性急剧上升。” 这一趋势部分源于远程办公的可能性，也因为员工更容易转移技能。反过来，员工的技能转移使得公司更难吸引和留住人才，因为员工可以轻松地从银行业转到科技业，再转到电信业。

Looking at last year, “a third of employees changed jobs in the United States; 45 percent of them changed industries,” Josh Bersin, the industry analyst, said. “The amount of mobility between companies, between industries, skyrocketed.” This trend is partially driven by remote work possibilities but also because workers can more easily transfer their skills. Employee skill transfer, in turn, makes it harder for companies to attract and retain talent when their employees can easily move from banking to tech to telecommunications.

Eightfold 的人工智能帮助雇主扭转这一趋势：它承诺根据求职者和员工的技能进行职位匹配，并找到能够学习一些新技能的员工，帮助他们在未来的工作中做好万全准备，或者顺利进入新的工作岗位，这个过程被称为“技能提升”。技能再培训和技能提升是人力资源领域最新的热门词汇，但技能瞬息万变，工作岗位的变化速度也比以往任何时候都快。

Eightfold’s AI helps employers push against this trend: it promises to match applicants and employees to jobs on the basis of their skills and to find employees who could learn a couple new skills, which could help them futureproof their jobs or slide into new jobs, a process called “upskilling.” Reskilling and upskilling are some of the latest HR buzzwords, but skills are changing rapidly and jobs are changing faster than ever before.

根据 2020 年世界经济论坛的《未来就业报告》，到 2025 年，40% 的劳动者的核心技能将发生变化，50% 的劳动者需要重新学习或提升技能。3

According to the 2020 World Economic Forum’s Future of Jobs Report, core skills will change for 40 percent of all workers by 2025, and 50 percent of all employees will need reskilling or upskilling.3

沃达丰计划招聘至少7000名软件开发人员，但由于公开就业市场上缺乏足够多具备这些新技能的人才，该公司正转向内部培养员工。或者更确切地说，是那些想要学习的员工，Starfield说道。他将员工大致分为三类：“一类员工将转向我们需要的新技能和新行为。一类员工仍在犹豫。还有一类员工永远不会。”

Vodafone wants to hire at least seven thousand software developers, but because there are not enough people with these new skills on the open job market, it is turning inward to develop its own employees. Or more specifically, the ones who want to learn, Starfield said. He categorizes employees into roughly three groups: “One group will make the shift to the new skills and behaviors we need. One group is still deciding. One group will never.”

通过这项人力资源计划，他试图激活中层仍在犹豫的群体。他将这项举措描述为“民主化”，让每个人都有机会“在我们的组织中成长”。他希望员工们愿意留在沃达丰，并通过获得这种个性化的职业建议感受到被重视。Starfield 表示，Eightfold 工具的另一个好处是，沃达丰可以为其员工制定长期规划，这在大数据出现之前几乎是不可能做到的。

With this HR initiative, he is trying to activate the middle still-deciding group. He describes the initiative as “democratization” and giving everybody a chance to “grow in our organization.” He hopes that employees will want to stay with Vodafone and will feel valued by getting this personalized career advice. Another upside of Eightfold’s tool is that Vodafone can make long-term plans for its workforce, something that has been nearly impossible to do before the advent of big data, Starfield said.

人工智能作为职业教练

AI AS CAREER COACH

Marc Starfield 和他的团队研究了市场，并决定在 2021 年选择 Eightfold 作为他们的供应商。该工具于 2022 年 1 月上线。

Marc Starfield and his team studied the market and decided on Eightfold as their vendor in 2021. The tool went live in January 2022.

Eightfold 的业务遍及 140 多个国家，拥有超过 20 亿员工数据集，约占全球劳动力的一半。Eightfold 前总裁、最近转行担任顾问的卡迈勒·阿卢瓦利亚 (Kamal Ahluwalia) 表示，该软件能够以 90% 的准确率预测员工未来五年内将要从事的两个职位。（目前尚未对这些说法进行独立测试，因此如此高的准确率难以验证。）

Eightfold operates in over 140 countries and has more than two billion data sets of employees, about half of the world’s workforce. The software can predict with 90 percent accuracy the next two roles of an employee over the next five years, said Kamal Ahluwalia, Eightfold’s former president, who recently transitioned to an advisor role. (There has been no independent testing done on these claims, so this high accuracy number is difficult to verify.)

该系统还可以预测个人获得新技能的潜力，这让高管们心跳加速，因为许多人都希望员工敏捷。

The system can also predict an individual’s potential to acquire new skills, something that makes executives’ hearts beat faster because many want agile employees.

Eightfold 的 AI 引擎从海量数据中学习到，懂 Python 的员工通常也懂其他一些人们可能不会在个人资料中列出的编程语言。根据其他人的简历推断技能，可以帮助那些比较谦虚的简历撰写者（她们大多是女性）不落伍——AI 只是将这些假定的技能添加到简历中。

Eightfold’s AI engine learned from the sea of data that employees who know Python often also know other programming languages that people might not list on their profiles. Inferring skills based on other people’s résumés helps more modest résumé writers, who are mostly women, not fall behind—the AI just adds these presumed skills.

“我们曾经遇到过这样的人，他们被雇佣时，验证的技能只有一项，然后推断出的技能有十一项，而这个人最终还是被雇佣了。”Ahluwalia 说道。推断技能帮助 Eightfold 合作的公司（例如美光公司）提升了多元化。“他们在 Eightfold 雇佣了更多女性、更多非裔美国人、更多退伍军人和更多残障人士。”

“We’ve had people who got hired where their validated skill was one, then there were eleven inferred skills, and that person got hired,” Ahluwalia said. Inferred skills have helped the companies Eightfold works with, such as Micron, to increase diversity. “They’ve hired more women, more Black Americans, more veterans, more people with disabilities with Eightfold.”

Ahluwalia 表示，由于许多求职者无法理解职位描述，Eightfold 的人工智能也帮助了 80% 申请错误职位的求职者。由于招聘经理不断在现有职位描述中添加越来越多的要求，职位描述可能过长，包含过多的优先技能和能力要求。Ahluwalia 表示，招聘经理还可能添加一些对求职者来说毫无意义的内部职位分类，导致大量求职者申请了错误的职位。

Because many applicants can’t decipher job descriptions, Eightfold’s AI also helps the 80 percent of workers who apply to the wrong job, according to Ahluwalia. Job descriptions may be too long and include too many preferred skills and capabilities because hiring managers keep adding more and more requirements to existing job descriptions. Hiring managers may also include internal job classifications that make no sense to applicants, hence the high number of applicants applying for the wrong opportunities, according to Ahluwalia.

当职位描述过长且涵盖的技能过多时，Eightfold 会向招聘经理揭示人才库的有限性。“它显示的是，如果这就是你的需求，那么人才库的现状就是这样的：12 个人，其中 1 名女性，其他均为男性，”Ahluwalia 举了一个假设的例子。这种透明度有助于管理者采取行动。“我们帮助客户了解真正需要什么，因为现在你可以看到这对你的人才库的影响。什么是人才输送管道？哪些是比较好的？多少经验才合理？所以，所有这些因素，你都可以实时看到其影响。”

When job descriptions become too long and include too many skills, Eightfold reveals to hiring managers the limited talent pool. “What it shows is, if this is what you’re asking for, this is what the talent pool looks like right there: twelve people, one woman, all others men,” Ahluwalia said in a hypothetical example. This transparency helps managers to act. “What we help customers do is see what is really required, because now you can see the impact on your talent pool. What’s the pipeline? What is nice to have? How much experience makes sense? So each of these things you start to see in real time what the impact is.”

在所谓的能力矩阵上，人工智能不仅向员工展示了经理所寻求的技能，还展示了哪些员工可以在三到六个月内学习到所需的技能，这有助于经理在内部找到合适的人才来进行培训。

On a so-called capability matrix, the AI shows the employees with the skills that a manager is looking for, but it also shows the employees who could learn the required skills in three to six months, which helps managers find the right people internally to train for the opportunity.

有了这些见解，管理者通常会选择降低期望值，重新关注工作的核心技能，而不是要求提供一长串的技能和能力。

With these insights, managers often opt to lower their expectations and refocus on just the core skills of the job instead of asking for a laundry list of skills and capabilities.

另一个有用的 Eightfold 功能是建议技能邻接——例如例如，人工智能建议，Invisalign 的一位帮助建立保持器的平面设计师可能也是一家游戏公司的优秀平面设计师。

Another helpful Eightfold feature is suggested skills adjacencies—for example, the AI suggests that a graphic designer at Invisalign who helps with building retainers might be a good graphic designer for a gaming company.

当我与求职门户网站 CareerBuilder 的前首席执行官 Irina Novoselsky 交谈时，她解释说，基于技能相似度的招聘将成为招聘的新常态，因为最抢手的职位空缺实在太少。几年前，CareerBuilder 重新调整了算法，将重点放在技能上。现在，它的人工智能会根据求职者的可迁移技能组合来匹配工作。“我想说，重要的不是你做过什么，而是你能做到吗？” Novoselsky 说。

When I spoke with the former CEO of the job portal CareerBuilder, Irina Novoselsky, she explained that hiring based on skills adjacencies will become the new normal in hiring because there are too few people for the most sought-after jobs. CareerBuilder rejiggered its algorithm a few years back to focus on skills. Its AI now matches people to jobs on the basis of their transferable skill set. “I like to say, it’s not what you’ve done, but can you do it?” Novoselsky said.

一切都关乎潜力，以及将技能从一个行业转移到另一个行业。新冠疫情期间，许多空乘人员失业，但他们的技能非常适合客户服务岗位：“他们善于处理问题，拥有良好的沟通能力，是物流处理员，也是项目经理，所以，从他们高客户满意度和客户互动技能来看，他们是完美的匹配对象。” 诺沃塞尔斯基说道。

It’s all about potential and transferring a skill set from one industry to another. During COVID, many flight attendants were out of a job, but their skills were suitable for customer service roles: “They are dealing with problems, their communication skills, they are logistic handlers, they are project managers, and so when you look at that high customer satisfaction and customer interaction skill set, they were a perfect match,” Novoselsky said.

由于全球对银行柜员的需求减少，他们或许也能填补客服部门的空缺。但有些技能的匹配度比其他技能更令人意外。

As the world needs fewer bank tellers, they might be a good fit for the empty seats in customer support, too. But some skill matches are more surprising than others.

“从基础技能来看，狱警和兽医技师非常契合。他们具备同理心、沟通能力、坚强的意志力，能够应对各种棘手的情况，”诺沃塞尔斯基说道。“害虫防治和抄表员也非常契合。”

“Prison guards, when you look at their underlying skill sets, are a huge match for veterinary technicians. Empathy, communication, strength, being able to manage difficult situations,” Novoselsky said. “Pest control has a really huge match with meter readers.”

她还表示，这种基于技能的招聘方式是提升多元化的​​秘诀。“这样做的副产品就是提升多元化，因为你现在不再寻找之前一直寻找的拥有相同经验的同一类型的人才。你扩大了招聘范围，能够找到完全不同类型的人才来担任这个职位。”我们已经看到，我们的客户能够利用我们的工具获得更加多样化的技能。”

She also said this skills-based hiring approach is the secret sauce to increasing diversity. “The by-product of this is increased diversity, because you are now not looking for the same type of person that you have been looking for that has that experience. You are widening your net and you are able to get a very different type of person into that role. We have seen that play out where our clients have been able to get a much more diverse skill set using our tools.”

另一个副作用是，公司可能会找到一些没有大学学位但拥有合适工作技能的人。专家表示，公司往往要求应聘者拥有大学学位，这使得大约60%没有学士学位但可能拥有合适技能的美国劳动者被排除在外。

Another by-product is that companies may find people who don’t have a college degree but have the right skills for the job. Too often, experts say, companies require college degrees, which excludes about 60 percent of working Americans who don’t have a bachelor’s degree but might have the right skill set.

海量数据使其他类型的分析成为可能。Ahluwalia 估计，Eightfold 可能拥有 70% 到 80% 的知识型员工的数据：“这很简单，就是他们在说什么，用什么词语，在什么情况下使用什么技能。” 这些数据带有“时间戳”，显示了人们在职业生涯的某些阶段做了什么以及他们的下一步计划，这实际上提供了一条职业发展路径。人工智能工具可以识别这些信息并将其推荐给其他人。

Large sets of data make other kinds of analysis possible. Ahluwalia estimated that Eightfold probably has data on 70 to 80 percent of all knowledge workers: “It’s simply a matter of what they’re saying, what words they’re using, what skill they’re using in what context.” The data is “time stamped,” showing what people did at certain points in their career and what their next steps were, which essentially provides a career path. The AI tool can recognize this and recommend it to others.

八倍工具还能向管理者展示某位员工的晋升速度是否比组织内其他人更快。“这也表明此人一直非常努力，并且比同事进步更快，”阿卢瓦利亚说道。

The Eightfold tool also shows managers if an employee is climbing up the career ladder faster than others in the organization. “That’s also a mark that this person has been working really hard and progressing faster than their peers,” Ahluwalia said.

这可能是一个信号。但我们都知道，晋升并不一定取决于员工是否尽职尽责。对于那些发展速度较慢的员工，例如那些为了照顾子女或年迈亲人而请假或兼职的员工（坦白说，她们大多是女性），或者那些身患残疾或患有慢性疾病的员工，这意味着什么呢？

It could be a signal. But we all know that promotions are not necessarily based on folks doing their best work. And what does this mean for employees who are on a slower trajectory, for example, employees (let’s face it, mostly women) who take time off or work part-time to care for their children or elderly relatives? Or those who have a disability or are struggling with a chronic illness?

这是模式识别的另一面。人工智能会记录什么是“正常的”，这意味着那些不遵循正常路径的人可能会受到惩罚或被标记为异常——尽管他们可能有充分的理由解释为什么他们的路径不同。我问问问阿卢瓦利亚。如果有人被标记为职业晋升非常缓慢，会发生什么？

This is the other side of pattern recognition. The AI notes what’s “normal,” which means that individuals who don’t follow one of the normal paths might be penalized or flagged as unusual—although they may have perfectly fine reasons for why their path is different. I asked Ahluwalia about this. What happens when someone is flagged as very slow moving up the career ladder?

“我们的做法是透明，而且是双向的，”他说。“雇主看到什么，我们也向员工展示同样的信息。”

“What we do is transparency and it’s both ways,” he said. “Whatever the employer is seeing, show the same information to the person as well.”

但我不确定这如何解决问题，因为它没有留下背景或解释的空间，但至少员工知道经理看到了关于他们的哪些信息。

But I’m not sure how that solves the problem, since it doesn’t leave room for context or explanations, but at least the employee knows what information managers are seeing about them.

员工合规

EMPLOYEE COMPLIANCE

令人惊讶的是，许多人力资源团队面临的最大挑战并非新技术是否有效或是否会产生偏见（尽管这应该是优先事项），而是员工对其的接受程度。员工接受度是评估人力资源投资的常用指标，而且很难衡量。员工会使用这个系统吗？我们很多人讨厌学习新技术程序，尤其是在不清楚它们如何让我们受益的情况下。

What’s surprising is that the biggest challenge for many HR teams is not whether the new technology works or creates bias (although this should be a priority) but its adoption among employees. Employee uptake is a metric often used to evaluate HR investments and it’s a tricky one. Will employees use the system? Many of us hate learning new technology programs, especially if it’s unclear how they benefit us.

Eightfold 在沃达丰和其他公司拥有很高的采用率，原因在于：它能为员工提供清晰的职业发展方向。许多人不擅长制定长期的战略性职业规划，而 Eightfold 则能通过展示其他人的职业发展历程，告诉人们自己的职业发展方向。它并非仅仅是一个职业阶梯，更像是一个展现不同选择的网格；例如，一个软件开发人员可以如何晋升为高级软件开发人员，然后是总监，最后是技术副总裁。

Eightfold has a high adoption rate at Vodafone and other companies for a reason: it’s pretty clear what’s in it for employees. Many people are pretty bad at long-term, strategic career planning, and Eightfold tells people where their career could go by showing where others have gone. It’s not necessarily a career ladder but more like a lattice that reveals different options; for example, how a software developer could become senior software developer, then director, then vice president of technology.

该平台帮助员工了解他们目前拥有的技能，以及他们渴望从事的不同职位所需的技能。该工具还会向员工展示他们目前所在公司中符合条件或即将申请的职位。至关重要的是，Eightfold 不仅向员工展示他们未来职位所需的技能，还向他们展示如何获得这些技能——并链接到 LinkedIn Learning 或 Udemy 等学习库。

The platform helps employees understand which skills they have today and which skills are required for different roles they aspire to. The tool also shows employees roles within their current employer that they are qualified for or are almost ready to apply for. And crucially, Eightfold shows employees not only which skills they need for the next role but also how to obtain them—linking to learning libraries like LinkedIn Learning or Udemy.

“我有时会开玩笑说要打造一个‘沃达丰我’的品牌，这意味着我清楚地知道自己在职业生涯中处于什么位置，”马克·斯塔菲尔德说道。他描述了Eightfold如何帮助沃达丰员工。一旦员工上传简历，“它就会立即显示‘你非常适合这些职位’。我认为这会让人们有信心说，‘让我去看看这个职位’，并想，‘哇，我之前没想到这一点，如果我只有这两三个方面，我就可以走上不同的职业道路了。’”

“I sometimes joke about having a ‘Vodafone Me’ brand, which is saying I know exactly where I am in my career,” Marc Starfield said. He described how Eightfold can help Vodafone employees. Once an individual uploads their résumé, “It immediately then gives them this ‘You are a strong match for these roles.’ I think that gives people confidence to say, ‘Let me go and have a look at that role,’ and think, ‘Wow, I didn’t realize that, and if I only had these two or three things, I could go into a different career path.’”

公司和员工使用这种技能提升系统的动机是一致的：有助于员工底线的同时也有助于公司的底线。

The incentives for the company and the employees to use this upskilling system are aligned: what helps an employee’s bottom line also helps the company’s bottom line.

马克·斯塔菲尔德面临的下一个挑战是如何利用员工的抱负来满足沃达丰的需求，尤其是在需求与期望相悖的情况下。比如说，假设他想成为一名学者；从表面上看，这对沃达丰没有帮助。“组织能否说，‘好吧，这很有意思，我们真的想获得更多数据洞察。你不是数据科学家，但你对研究的兴趣恰好将两者结合起来。’”斯塔菲尔德推测道，并试图为沃达丰构建一个用例。

The next challenge for Marc Starfield is to figure out how the ambitions of his employees might be harvested for Vodafone’s wants and needs, especially if they are at odds. For example, say he wanted to become an academic; on its face, that wouldn’t help Vodafone. “Can the organization say, ‘Okay, that’s interesting, we really want to get much more data insights. You are not a data scientist, but your interest in research kind of combines those two things,’” Starfield speculated, trying to build a use case for Vodafone.

然而，员工们不应该误会——这个工具提供的建议可能非常有用，但员工使用它的方式也会被记录下来。人工智能可能会注意到你没有参与任何学习机会（这是否意味着你不够敏捷，不够积极进取？），并且它会指出用户在公司中晋升的速度是否比其他人慢。

However, employees should make no mistake—the advice this tool gives can be incredibly helpful, but the way employees use it is also recorded. The AI might notice that you don’t engage in any of the learning opportunities (might that mean that you are not agile and not a go-getter?) and it points out if users are slower to move up the ranks in a company than others.

（最近，领英问我是否还在纽约大学担任新闻学助理教授。这是我在纽约大学工作的第六年，助理教授通常在第六年就会晋升为终身教授。但当时我正在休产假，疫情爆发时，我收到了（我可能在终身教职的轨道上待了更久。但也许领英的算法注意到大多数助理教授在第六年就升入副教授了，所以现在把我归类为“慢”？又或许大多数人在这么多年后都会换工作？我可能永远也不会知道这个自动提问究竟传递了什么信号。）

(Recently, LinkedIn asked if I was still an assistant professor of journalism at New York University. This is the sixth year I have worked at NYU, and usually in their sixth year, assistant professors go up for tenure. But I was on maternity leave, and when the pandemic hit, I received more time on tenure track. But maybe LinkedIn’s algorithm noticed that most assistant professors become associate professors in year six and has now categorized me as “slow”? Or maybe most people switch jobs after so many years? I will probably never know what signal was derived from this automated question.)

一些批评人士认为，让人工智能依赖简历并非良策。“我们认为简历是所有问题的根源，”招聘评估公司 Criteria Corporation 的首席执行官 Josh Millet 表示。“招聘是一项重要的预测业务。我们都在尝试以各种方式预测结果，而我们试图预测的结果就是工作绩效。” 他表示，供应商需要使用最具预测性的数据，而不是像简历这样最容易获得的数据。

Some critics believe that allowing AI to rely on résumés is not a great idea. “We believe the résumé is the root of the whole problem,” said Josh Millet, the CEO of Criteria Corporation, a hiring assessment firm. “Hiring is a big prediction business. We’re all trying to predict outcomes, one way or another, and the outcomes we’re trying to predict are job performance.” Vendors need to use the most predictive data, not the easiest available data, like résumés, he said.

对我们来说，这就像“垃圾进，垃圾出”。简历本质上能提供两点信息：一是教育背景信息，二是相关经验信息。所有科学研究都表明，就预测工作结果而言，这两项信息相当微弱。

“For us, it’s sort of a garbage in, garbage out scenario. What you’re getting from a résumé essentially is two things: you are getting some sense of the educational background and then you are getting some sense of the amount of relevant experience. All the science shows that those two things are pretty weak signals in terms of predicting job outcomes.”

信号微弱，噪音很大。米勒问道：“17年的销售经验能比8年的销售经验更能预测成功吗？根本不是。” 谁知道一个拥有17年销售经验的人是否真的擅长销售？他们或许在那些年里一直在努力，不断换工作。

Weak signal, lots of noise. Millet asked, “Is seventeen years in sales predictive of greater success than eight years? It’s not at all.” Who knows if someone who has seventeen years of experience in sales is really good at it? They may have struggled for those years, going from one job to another.

基于简历分析的人工智能技能匹配工具无法判断一个人是否真的擅长自己的工作。它唯一能获得的信息就是这个人是否有过这样或那样的经历。

An AI skills-matching tool that is based on analyzing résumés won’t understand whether someone is really good at their job. The only information it gets is that the person had this or that experience.

米勒说：“我们知道，除了经验和教育背景之外，还有更好的信号：职业道德、解决问题的能力、批判性思维——我们知道这些都与结果密切相关。”

“We know there are better signals out there that aren’t based on experience and educational background: work ethic, problem-solving, critical thinking—those we know are highly linked to outcomes,” Millet said.

其他批评技能匹配技术（例如 Eightfold）的人认为，这种匹配技术过于基础。他们认为，这些人工智能工具将人类的思维简化到简历上的几个关键词，无法理解潜在的人才。尽管如此，随着技能匹配技术的改进，它有望成为那些希望职业发展的员工的宝贵资产。

Other critics of skills-matching technologies à la Eightfold find the matching too basic. They believe that these AI tools reduce humans to just a few keywords on a résumé, that the tools don’t understand potential. Still, with improvements, skills matching promises to be a powerful asset for employees who want to move up in their careers.

沃达丰只允许员工将个人资料与公司内部职位进行匹配。而像联合利华这样的公司则将这项技术更进一步。他们开设了一个内部市场，员工可以申请公司内部的不同项目——为不同的团队工作，每周花几个小时学习新技能，同时继续在原有岗位工作。员工可以学习新技能，并在公司内部结识新同事。有些人最终找到了新工作。

Vodafone only lets employees match their profiles to in-house jobs. Companies like Unilever have taken this technology one step further. They have opened an internal marketplace where employees can apply to different projects within the company—working for different teams and learning new skills a few hours a week while still working in their old jobs. Employees learn new skills and get to meet new colleagues inside the company. Some are eventually able to find new jobs.

如果运作良好，这些市场可以为公司节省大量资金，因为他们无需聘请外部员工；相反，管理人员可以在内部寻找所需人才。联合利华使用了以色列公司Gloat开发的人工智能系统。在一次财报电话会议上，联合利华前首席执行官Alan Jope对该工具大加赞赏：“我们还将30万小时的人力投入到我们的内部数字人才市场……它的作用是将有能力的员工与项目和机会匹配起来，让他们从事有趣的新工作。”

If done well, these marketplaces can save companies real money because they don’t have to hire outside workers; instead, managers find the talent they need internally. Unilever used the AI system built by the Israeli company Gloat. In an earnings call, the former Unilever CEO Alan Jope praised the tool: “We’ve also unlocked 300,000 hours of people’s time to our internal digital talent marketplace…. And what that does is it matches employees who have capacity with projects and opportunities to do interesting new types of work.”

对于一家大公司来说，三十万小时可能意味着节省数百万美元。

Three hundred thousand hours probably equals millions of dollars in savings for a large corporation.

衡量倦怠和离职风险

MEASURING BURNOUT AND FLIGHT RISK

但员工数据也有许多其他用途。供应商收集各种“人员数据”，包括福利、年度评估、电子邮件、日历、联系人、简历等等，以了解哪些人明年有可能离职，哪些人正在“悄悄离职”。（即只做他们被要求做的事情），以及谁有倦怠的风险。

But data from employees can be used in many other ways as well. Vendors take in all kinds of “people data” from benefits, annual reviews, emails, calendars, contacts, résumés, and so forth, to understand who is at risk of leaving the company in the next year, who is “quiet quitting” (that is, just doing what they are being asked to do), and who is at risk for burnout.

2022 年秋季，员工辞职率仍处于历史最高水平，许多公司担心现有员工的离职风险，因此预测分析在 11 月的 HR Tech 上风靡一时。

In the fall of 2022, workers were still resigning at an all-time high and many companies worried about the flight risk of their current employees, so predictive analytics was all the rage at HR Tech in November.

百事公司资深人力资源经理尼迪亚·塞尔纳（Nydia Serna）分享了一个最有趣的观点。她当时是驻纽约的人力资源运营总监，她的工作弥合了人力资源和IT之间的鸿沟。她进入人力资源行业的方式有些曲折：“我刚开始攻读计算机科学学位，但我并不喜欢它。我的编程水平可能是你见过的最差的，但我了解这个系统。所以到了实习的时候，我对人力资源非常感兴趣，”她在会议的一个小组讨论中说道。

One of the most interesting perspectives was shared by Nydia Serna, a veteran HR manager at PepsiCo. At the time she was the head HR operations director based in New York and her work bridged the gap between HR and IT. She’d come to HR in a roundabout way: “I started my computer science degree and I didn’t like it. I was the worst coder you’ll ever meet, but I understood the system. So when it was time to take an internship, I was very interested in HR,” she said on a panel at the conference.

对她来说，数据为管理者在决策时提供了更坚实的基础；过去，大多数管理者依赖直觉或不完整的数据，而现在他们能够基于人员数据做出更复杂的业务决策。这正是她从IT部门带到人力资源部门的优势。

To her, data gives managers a much better grounding when making decisions; whereas before most managers relied on intuition or incomplete data, now they can make more complex business decisions based on people data. This is the strength she brings from IT to HR.

“我们所做的最有力的事情之一就是引入分析，因为它可以让整个组织看到我们在数据质量方面存在的差距，我们需要加大力度，将这些数据转化为实际信息，从而改变我们的工作方式，”她说。

“One of the most powerful things we’ve done is introduce analytics, because it surfaces up to the entire organization where we have gaps in data quality, where we need to push more and transform this data into actual information that’s going to change the way we work,” she said.

对于管理者来说，通过仪表板轻松访问这些数据并进行交互，对于了解自己的员工至关重要：“我们非常希望了解员工流失情况，并尽早发现哪些地方可能出现悄然离职的情况。性别差异在哪里？”

For managers, easy dashboard access to interact with this data is important in understanding their own employees: “We’re very interested in understanding attrition, identifying very early where we might be experiencing quiet quitting. Where do we have those gender gaps?”

但如果输入的数据不正确，这类系统可能会造成危害。“我们需要非常谨慎地对待我们的工作、我们将数据发送到哪里以及数据的准确性。有时数据并不像人们希望的那样准确。我会亲自审查这一点，”她说。当塞尔纳检查系统后，她在未来十二个月内戒烟的可能性为 3%。

But these kinds of systems can cause harm if the data fed into them is incorrect. “We need to be very careful about what we do, where do we send the data and how accurate it is. And sometimes it is not as accurate as one hopes. I review this on my very own self,” she said. When Serna checked the system, she had a 3 percent chance of quitting in the next twelve months.

百事公司也曾发起一项活动，鼓励员工自我认同，塞尔纳发现自己被错误地归类了。她最初在百事公司墨西哥分公司工作，那里没有人自称是拉丁裔。当她搬到美国，在公司担任其他职位时，她被错误地归类为白人/高加索人/非西班牙裔。

PepsiCo had also started a campaign for employees to self-identify and Serna found out she was misclassified. She started at PepsiCo in Mexico, where no one describes themselves as Latina. When she moved to the United States to take another position with the company, she was misclassified as white/Caucasian/non-Hispanic.

“所以当我去修改这些信息后，百事公司对待我（不是作为人力资源运营总监，而是作为公司员工）的整个沟通方式都开始改变，”她回忆道。“我收到了更多针对我的性别、种族、职业发展的通知，所以我明白了公司掌握正确信息的重要性。”

“So when I went in and changed that information, the entire communications approach that PepsiCo has towards me, not as a HR operations director, but as the employee of the company, started changing,” she recalled. “I had more notifications about targeting my gender, targeting my ethnicity, targeting my development, and so I can see how it’s important for the company to have the right information.”

百事公司刚刚开始使用 Visier 来满足其预测分析需求。Serna 迫切想知道人工智能能发现什么——例如，她的团队成员中哪些人可能是“安静离职者”。

For their predictive analytics needs, PepsiCo just started using Visier. Serna was eager to find out what the AI would uncover—for example, which of her team members might be quiet quitters.

Visier 是一家像凤凰涅槃一样浴火重生的初创公司。2022 年，它从高盛资产管理公司获得了 1.25 亿美元的融资，估值达到 10 亿美元。Visier的客户包括美国三大信用报告机构之一的益博睿 (Experian)、优步 (Uber)、Adobe 以及 Snapchat 的母公司 Snap。

Visier is a start-up that has risen like a phoenix out of the ashes. In 2022 it raised $125 million with Goldman Sachs Asset Management, which valued the company at $1 billion.4 Visier’s customers include Experian, one of the three leading credit reporting agencies in the United States; Uber; Adobe; and Snap, the parent company of Snapchat.

我采访了研究与战略副总裁伊恩·库克 (Ian Cook)，他也向我演示了这款工具。他说，Visier 的预测分析解答了 Eightfold 留下的很多问题。

I spoke with the vice president of research and strategy, Ian Cook, who also demonstrated the tool for me. He said Visier’s predictive analytics answers a lot of the questions that Eightfold leaves open.

Eightfold 解决了一个非常具体的问题，那就是为公司内部或外部人员匹配工作。它的人工智能无法解决的是：“那又怎么样？”库克说。“他们只是说，‘伊恩可以做这件事，这项工作需要完成——我们会帮助伊恩和这项工作完美契合。’”库克说道。Visier 的人工智能可以了解“Ian”是否在新工作中取得成功以及他对新工作的感受。

Eightfold solves a very specific problem, which is matching people to work, either internally or externally. What its AI doesn’t solve for is this: “So what?” Cook said. “They just said, ‘Ian can do this and the job needs to get done—we will help Ian and the job get together.’” Cook says with Visier’s AI he can find out if “Ian” succeeded at the new job and how he feels about the new job.

Visier 致力于收集公司尽可能多的数据——从业务数据到人员数据。如果可能的话，Visier 还会收集员工绩效数据、问卷调查中的参与度数据，以及基于人工智能的情绪分析，将电子邮件和其他书面沟通内容评为积极、消极或中性。

Visier tries to intake as much data as companies have—from business data to people data. If possible, Visier will also take performance data from employees, engagement data from surveys, and AI-based sentiment analysis, which rates email and other written communication as positive, negative, or neutral.

库克认为，被动监控所有电子邮件比每年通过调查询问员工一两次他们的感受更能准确地了解员工的感受。

Cook thinks that passively monitoring all emails gives a more accurate picture of employees’ feelings than asking someone once or twice a year via survey how they are feeling does.

“人们并不总是擅长表达自己的感受。他们通常不知道。而且，他们的感受会因人而异，可能是刚喝完咖啡，也可能是刚和老板进行了一次不愉快的谈话。被动地从沟通的语气和风格中感知员工的情绪，能让你更清楚地了解正在发生的事情，”他说道。他强调，情绪调查只在群体或团队层面进行，而不是从个人层面，以确保无法识别人员身份。

“People aren’t always really good at telling you how they feel. They don’t often know. And it varies depending on if they just had a coffee or if they had just had a bad conversation with their boss. Detecting [employees’ sentiments] passively from the tone of communication, style of communication gives you a cleaner signal around what’s happening,” he said. He emphasized that sentiment is only sampled at a group or team level, not from individuals, to ensure people cannot be identified.

与此同时，Visier 从员工那里获得的数据越精细、越个性化，预测就越准确。“数据量和流量都非常惊人，非常庞大，”库克说道。他估计，Visier 每位员工处理的信号大约有一万个。

At the same time, the more granular and individualized data from employees that Visier gets, the better the predictions. “The volume and the flow of data is quite extraordinary. Massive,” Cook said. He estimates that Visier processes about ten thousand signals per employee.

那么，一旦 Visier 拥有了庞大的数据湖，它能从中获得哪些洞察呢？库克表示，大多数公司都会问同样的问题。“我的人才够用吗？我的人才合适吗？我为现有员工支付的薪水是否过高？当我们拥有更成熟的客户时，他们开始思考：‘我们的管理层是否能够帮助员工保持专注并取得良好业绩？’他们开始从‘我们是否能够帮助员工高效工作？’的角度来思考这个问题。”

So once Visier has a massive data lake, what insights can it draw from it? Cook said most companies ask the same question. “Do I have enough heads? Do I have the right heads? Am I paying too much for the people I have? When we get more sophisticated clients, that starts to go to, ‘Do we have management that is helping people be committed and perform well?’ They start to look at that next layer in terms of ‘Are we helping people work?’”

库克举了一个例子来说明 Visier 的工具可能的优势：如果一家公司将一名员工提拔到新职位，Visier 可以查明该人是否继续留在该职位，以及这一变动是否对业务有帮助。

Cook gave an example where Visier’s tool might excel: if a company promotes an employee to a new position, Visier can find out whether the person has stayed in that position and whether this move has helped the business.

对库克来说，一切都归结于公司的商业决策，这也是他推销Visier的原因。这款软件可以帮助留住员工，从而节省招聘成本。但其他好处则体现在两个方面：如果你能帮助员工避免倦怠，那么你也能节省成本。

For Cook, everything goes back to business decisions for companies and that’s how he pitches Visier. The software can help with employee retention, which saves money in hiring. But other benefits are a two-step process: if you help employees not burn out, then you also save money.

“我们有充分的证据表明，利用数据可以做出更好的决策。更好的决策可以带来更好的回报。”库克说道。没错，前提是数据有意义，能够推动深思熟虑的决策。

“We’ve got a decent amount of proof that using data makes better decisions. Better decisions make better returns,” Cook said. True, that is, if the data is meaningful and drives thoughtful decision-making.

我们已进行背景调查，结果表明，我们的客户拥有更多数据并提供给更多用户，其盈利能力和资产回报率均优于同行。人力资源数据的精细化使用与业务成果之间存在关联。虽然两者之间的因果关系尚未得到最终证实，但这种关联正变得越来越清晰。

“We’ve done the background that says those of our clients who have more data being given to more users outperform their peers on profitability and return on assets. There is an association between sophisticated use of people data and business outcomes. It’s not finally proven without a doubt in terms of causation, but the association is becoming clearer.”

因此，它尚未得到证实，但它符合常识：更多数据等于更好的决策。

So it’s not proven yet, but it appeals to common sense: more data equals better decisions.

然后，伊恩·库克向我展示了公司如何使用 Visier 来解读自己的数据：“我可以导入员工人数。我可以导入求职者比例，看看有多少女性申请了某些职位。我可以综合查看所有成本构成，”他说道。“我们可以直接告诉你性别薪酬差距。”

Then Ian Cook showed me how companies can make sense of their own data with Visier: “I can bring in headcount. I can bring in applicant ratios for how many women are applying for certain jobs. I can look at cost components all together,” he said. “We can tell you your gender pay gap straight away.”

管理人员可以深入到个人层面，核实数据是否适用于其团队成员。该工具还会对特定团队的所有员工进行人脉分析。“它可以显示他们正在与谁交谈，”库克说道。该软件还会根据其他人的数据提供建议：“我看到你正在和简说话。和简说话的人也和布莱恩说话。你有没有想过联系布莱恩？”

Managers can drill down to the individual level and fact-check whether the data is correct for members on their teams. The tool also does a network analysis of all the employees on a given team. “It can show them who they are talking with,” Cook said. The software also delivers recommendations based on other people’s data: “I see you talking to Jane. People who talk to Jane also talk to Brian. Have you thought about connecting with Brian?”

该软件可以通过记录员工行为的任何变化来检测潜在的倦怠，例如，有人回复不频繁并且速度和以前一样快。他指出，对于那些曾经超负荷工作、每天工作十二个小时、到处发信息、现在却选择默默辞职的人来说，算法会检测到这种工作模式的变化，并显示该员工存在倦怠风险。

The software can detect potential burnout over time by recording any changes in employee behavior; for example, someone not responding as often and as fast as they used to. He suggests that for someone who used to go above and beyond, work twelve-hour days, fire off messages left and right and who is now in quiet quitting mode, the algorithm would detect this work pattern change and this employee would show up as being at risk of burnout.

Visier 发现许多医院集团存在倦怠问题，这些数据帮助护理部门和财务部门批准了更多招聘。一家医院最终没有增加任何支出，但改进了流程，缺勤率也降低了。Cook 表示，这些数据对推动形势发展至关重要：“当你不知道真相时，你只会争论人们的看法和走廊里有人说了什么。当你掌握了数据，你就可以把它当作一个实质性的业务问题来处理并解决它。”

Visier identified burnout in numerous hospital groups and the data helped the nursing and finance departments greenlight more hires. One hospital ended up not spending any more money but improved the process and had fewer absences. Cook said the data made the difference in moving the needle: “When you don’t know, you’re just arguing about people’s perceptions and what somebody said in the corridor. When you have the data, you can address it as a material business problem and solve it.”

他认为，Visier 的算法还可以通过计算离职风险评分，在一定程度上预测哪些员工会在未来 12 个月内离职。该算法基于离职员工的数据进行训练，试图找到离职员工的共同模式，并预测哪些现有员工具有类似的风险模式。

He argues that Visier’s algorithm can also predict, to a certain degree, which employee will leave in the next twelve months by calculating a flight risk score. The algorithm is trained on the data of employees who left. The algorithm tries to find patterns that people who left have in common and predicts which current employees have similar risk patterns.

据人力资源组织 SHRM 称，这种离职风险软件通常会衡量员工敬业度、缺勤率、绩效评估评级变化、上次晋升后的时间，甚至通勤时间和 LinkedIn 上的活动等数据。

This kind of flight risk software typically measures such factors as engagement level, absenteeism, changes in performance review ratings, time since last promotion, and even data like commute time and activity on LinkedIn, according to the HR organization SHRM.

库克表示，预测谁会离开并不是一门精确的科学，因为人类的行为千差万别：“你可以让一枚太空火箭撞上一千一百万英里外的小行星；这比预测某人是否会离开要容易得多。”在一家公司，维西尔预测了十六名高管中的九名会辞职，并最终获得了合同。

Cook said that calculating who will leave is not an exact science because human behavior can vary so much: “You can make a space rocket hit an asteroid eleven million miles away; that’s easier than predicting if someone’s going to leave.” At one company, Visier predicted nine out of sixteen resignations of senior-level executives and got the contract.

其他人，例如大型跨国房地产公司高纬环球（Cushman & Wakefield）前全球人才分析与规划主管林恩培（Enpei Lam），也分析了员工离职的原因。林恩培和他的团队从零开始构建了高纬环球的算法。

Other people, such as Enpei Lam, the former global head of people analytics and planning at Cushman & Wakefield, a large multinational real estate firm, have also analyzed why employees are leaving. Lam and his team built the algorithm at Cushman & Wakefield from scratch.

2021年，他刚进公司时，大辞职潮正如火如荼地展开，公司里人来人往。“他们想知道‘为什么有人要离开？’仅仅是因为工资吗？是因为对老板不满意吗？是因为对工作不满意吗？到底是怎么回事？”林先生说。他的老板们也想知道如何才能阻止员工辞职。高管们认为林先生和他的团队可以准确地预测员工何时会离开。“他们看着我们就像看着通灵师一样。”

When he started at the company in 2021, the great resignation was in full swing and the company was losing people left and right. “They want to figure out ‘why are people leaving?’ Is this just because of the pay? Is it because they’re not happy with their bosses? Is it because they’re not happy with their work? What is going on?” Lam said. His bosses also wanted to know how they could stop the resignations. The executives thought that Lam and his team could tell them exactly when someone would leave. “They look at us like we are psychic.”

Lam 和他的团队将 2020 年和 2021 年的 130 多个员工属性纳入他们的模型中，包括人口统计数据（性别、种族、残疾）、晋升、绩效、经理的性别和种族、任期和报销、基本工资增长、通勤时间、敬业度调查数据、工作场所分析数据（每日工作时间、每日专注时间、每日会议次数、外部网络联系百分比）等，以了解导致员工离职的最重要因素。

Lam and his team incorporated over 130 attributes about employees, including demographic data (gender, ethnicity, disability), promotion, performance, manager’s gender and ethnicity, tenure and reimbursement, base pay increases, commute time, engagement survey data, workplace analytics data (daily working hours, daily focus hours, number of daily meetings, percentage of external network contacts), and many more from 2020 and 2021 into their model to understand the most important factors driving people out the door.

拉姆表示，该模型在非常广泛的群体层面上的准确率达到80%到90%。“我们无法真正预测到个体层面，”他说。“这正是模型开始失效的地方。” 该模型对个体的准确率可能低于50%，这意味着它的预测能力比抛硬币还要差。

Lam said the model was 80 percent to 90 percent accurate on a very broad group level: “We can’t really predict down to the individual level,” he said. “That’s where the model starts to fall apart.” The accuracy of the mode for individuals can fall below 50 percent, which means it is less predictive than a coin toss.

Lam和他的团队发现，与员工离职相关的五个最重要的因素是内部流动性、每日会议次数、薪酬、绩效和经理任期。“内部流动性仍然是员工离职的首要原因，”Lam说道。“如果一个人连续两年都做着同一件事，那么他离职的可能性会比过去两年内转换过职位的人更高——高得多。”

Lam and his team found the five most important factors connected with people leaving the organization were internal mobility, the number of daily meetings, pay, performance, and manager tenure. “Internal mobility continues to show up as the number one reason why people are leaving,” Lam said. “If a person has continued to do the same thing for two years, that person’s likelihood to leave is going to be higher—a lot higher—than those who have switched roles during the past two years.”

对我来说，这些发现并不意外。那些在工作中停滞不前、被忽视晋升和加薪机会的人肯定会感到不开心。但这或许正是数据科学的魅力所在。它能帮助我们通过定性分析，找到我们一直以来怀疑或已知的事实的确凿证据。

To me, these findings were hardly surprising. People who have been stagnant at a job and overlooked for promotions and better pay would be unhappy. But maybe that is the beauty of data science. It helps us find solid evidence for things we suspected or knew through qualitative analysis all along.

该团队的分析基于他们输入模型的130个属性。由于缺乏数据，团队没有调查员工离职的其他原因。在调查和研究中，各种类型公司的员工都表示，他们离职的原因是不良的工作文化或“糟糕的管理者”。

The team’s analysis was based on the 130 attributes they fed into the model. What the team didn’t investigate were the other reasons why employees may leave because there wasn’t any data available. In surveys and studies, employees at all different kinds of companies have expressed that they left because of a toxic work culture or “bad managers.”

“糟糕的管理者”是一个模糊的数据点，可能在官方数据集中找不到，但林恩培告诉我，其他指标，包括管理者的任职年限、管理者的绩效评级、与管理者的关系以及管理者的性别，都被输入到了模型中。“我们的员工与管理者的关系相当好，”他说。“结果表明，管理者在职时间越长，员工的幸福感就越高。”

“Bad managers” is an amorphous data point and probably not available in an official data set, but Enpei Lam told me that other proxies, including manager tenure, manager performance rating, relationship with manager, and manager gender, were fed into the model. “Our employees have a pretty good relationship with their managers,” he said. “What came up is that the longer a manager is in a job, the happier employees are.”

我一直想知道，一旦公司获得了个别员工或特定团队的离职风险评分，他们会如何处理这些信息。他们会立即给员工升职吗？还是会开始对他们进行更密切的监控？

I always wondered what companies do with the information once they have flight risk scores for individual employees or specific teams. Do they give folks instant promotions? Start monitoring them more closely?

Visier 的 Ian Cook 表示，许多经理首先会问的是被标记的员工是高绩效员工还是低绩效员工。“名单上可能有人排在最前面：‘哦，谢天谢地，我之前关于他们贡献不足的沟通一直很有效。他们决定自己辞职了。太棒了。’这是一个合理的策略，”Cook 说。如果此人绩效高，经理和人力资源部门很可能会讨论如何留住这名员工。

Ian Cook from Visier said the first question many managers ask is if the person flagged is a high or low performer. “There could be people on the top of the list: ‘Oh, thank goodness, my communication about their lack of contribution has been working. They’ve decided to take themselves out. Excellent.’ That is a legitimate strategy,” Cook said. If the person is a high performer, managers and HR will in all likelihood discuss options on what they could offer to retain this employee.

但有人质疑离职风险预测是​​否真的有效。Thomas Otter 曾是人力资源领域的产品经理，现在一位风险投资家。他对离职风险预测工具深感担忧，认为它们往好了说是无稽之谈，往坏了说是带有歧视性。他认为，离职风险预测往往不准确，因为它们缺乏坚实的科学依据，而且输入的数据也存在错误。

But some question whether flight risk predictions work at all. Thomas Otter is a former product manager in the HR space and now works as a venture capitalist. He is deeply troubled by flight risk predictors and thinks they are at best nonsense, at worst discriminatory. He believes that flight risk predictions are often incorrect because they are not based on solid science and they have the wrong input data.

奥特说：“如果你真的能够衡量那些决定逃离风险的因素，那么衡量它其实并不公平，”因为很多工作以外的因素都会影响人们的决策。如果有人在照顾父母，他们的逃离风险就会降低。如果有人拥有信托基金并且经济独立，他们的逃离风险就会更高。如果有人处于异地恋，他们的逃离风险也会更高。

“If you could really measure the things that determine flight risk, it wouldn’t be really fair to be measuring it,” because a lot of factors outside of work play a role in people’s decision-making, Otter said. If someone is taking care of their parents, their flight risk is reduced. If someone has a trust fund and is independently wealthy, their flight risk is higher. If someone is in a long-distance relationship, their flight risk is higher.

他说：“对离职风险影响最大的因素是人力资源部门在道德层面上应该持有的数据集之外的因素。” 因此，基于现有数据做出的离职风险预测往往比较模糊，而且价值通常不高。

“The biggest impact on flight risk are things that are outside the data sets that HR departments should ethically be holding,” he said. So, flight risk predictions made on the existing data are vague and often of low value.

另一个问题是公司如何利用员工离职风险预测。一些管理者可能会为员工离职做好准备，限制其晋升、培训机会和薪酬，并奖励团队中可能留下的员工。“管理者永远不可能不知道或视而不见这些信息，”研究和咨询公司Gartner驻巴黎的副总裁兼HCM技术分析师Helen Poitevin向SHRM.org表示。“现在掌握这些信息会影响他们与被认为存在离职风险的员工的每一个决定或互动吗？” 5

Another problem is how companies use the flight risk predictions. Some managers might prepare for the exit of an employee and limit that person’s promotions, training opportunities, and compensation and reward people on the team who are likely to stay. “A manager can never unknow that information or unsee it,” said Helen Poitevin, a Paris-based vice president and analyst who covers HCM technologies for research and advisory firm Gartner, to SHRM.org. “Will having that information now influence every decision or interaction they have with employees who are deemed flight risks?”5

其他经理可能会决定向系统认为有离职风险的人员支付更多钱以吸引他们留下来，但由于大多数经理的资金有限，团队中的其他人会因为错误的原因而获得较少的报酬。

Other managers might decide to pay someone that the system said is at risk of flight more money to entice them to stay, but because most managers have limited funds, other people on the team would get less compensation for the wrong reasons.

“年轻单身白人男性的逃亡风险比已婚女性更高，”奥特说。“如果你要正确地从从企业角度来看，从个人层面来看，这显然是歧视性的。”

“Young, single white males have a higher flight risk than married females,” Otter said. “If you’re going to do flight risk correctly from a corporate perspective, at an individual level, it’s going to be, by definition, discriminatory.”

华盛顿特区咨询公司美世（Mercer）劳动力战略与分析业务合伙人兼联合负责人马修·史蒂文森（Matthew Stevenson）表示，那些不考虑外部数据、只分析内部数据的离职风险评分也存在问题。“许多数据集只包含员工内部情况的信息，却没有提及竞争对手的情况、类似职位的市场薪酬水平，以及失业率等外部劳动力市场数据。” 6

Flight risk scores that do not take into account external data but analyze only internal data are also problematic, said Matthew Stevenson, a partner and coleader of the workforce strategy and analytics practice at the consulting firm Mercer in Washington, DC. “Many of the data sets only contain information about what’s happening internally with employees and say nothing about what the competition is doing, what the market pay rates are for similar jobs or external labor market data like the unemployment rate.”6

在尼迪亚·塞尔纳的案例中，辞职风险预测器出错了。2022年，当她用该系统进行自我测试时，系统预测她在未来12个月内戒烟的概率为0.03。2023年初，她离开了百事可乐。

In Nydia Serna’s case, the flight risk predictor was wrong. In 2022, when she tested it against herself the system predicted that she had a 0.03 chance of quitting in the next twelve months. In early 2023, she left PepsiCo.

有毒团队

TOXIC TEAMS

在我们的谈话中，我问伊恩·库克，这款软件是否可以用来识别“有毒”团队和“有毒”经理。“有毒”经理难道不会导致大量员工离职吗？库克说是的，但这些数据也能告诉我们，一位经理因为其他原因导致大量员工离职。“说‘经理A有毒’风险很大。不，经理A招聘的是A级人才，而这些人才最终会去公司其他地方。”

In our conversation, I asked Ian Cook whether the software could be used to find toxic teams and toxic managers. Wouldn’t a toxic manager have a high number of employees leaving?
