Cook said yes, but that data can also show us that one manager has a high number of people leaving for a different reason. “There’s a huge risk to say, ‘Manager A is toxic.’ No, Manager A is hiring A-class talent, which then is going somewhere else in the business.”

他从一位客户那里得知，他们公司某个部门的离职率最高。深入调查后，他们发现了一些令人惊讶的事情：该部门经理的工作做得非常出色。许多人加入该部门后，六七个月内就跳槽到了其他部门，因为该经理开放的转会政策。这是一位非常出色的教练，尽管乍一看数据可能显示并非如此。

He learned from a client that one particular department at their organization had the highest resignation rate. When they looked deeper, they found something surprising: The manager was doing an amazing job. Many folks joined their department and then got a job in a different department within six to seven months because the manager had an open transfer policy. This was an excellent manager, although the data at first glance might have suggested otherwise.

对库克来说，这就是为什么人工智能只是谜题的一部分：“所以很难说事情发生只有一个原因，这对人们来说绝对是一个痛苦，因为他们实际上只是希望你解决问题，”他说。“如果没有所有这些额外的背景信息，我就无法解决问题。”

To Cook, this is why AI is only one part of the puzzle: “So it’s very hard to say there is one reason why things are happening, which is an absolute pain to people, because they really just want you to solve the problem,” he said. “I can’t solve the problem without all of this additional context.”

当管理者只关注数据而不再进行批判性思考时，决策可能会变得不公平，因为他们没有考虑背景。

When managers only take in the data and stop thinking critically, this is where decisions might become unfair, because they’re not considering the context.

不幸的是，上下文信息经常被遗漏。在2022年的HR Tech大会上，我遇到了一家类似的服务提供商SplashBI。我与首席执行官Naveen Miglani进行了交谈，他告诉我，SplashBI收集了员工的诸多数据点，包括他们的个人生活（例如，福利数据，可以显示员工是否在医疗保健计划中添加或删除了配偶，或者是否有孩子）、绩效评估、薪资等级，以及（有趣的是）通勤距离。

And, unfortunately, context often gets lost. At HR Tech in 2022 I met a similar service provider, SplashBI. I talked to the CEO Naveen Miglani and he told me that SplashBI pulls in many data points on employees, including about their personal life (for example, benefits data, which shows if someone added or dropped a spouse from their healthcare plan or had a child), performance reviews, pay grade, and, interestingly enough, commuting distance.

我问他如何确保数据不会导致偏见，例如，由于历史上的红线政策，通勤距离与美国的种族和社会经济地位高度相关。他告诉我，他信任他的数据人员，但通勤时间甚至被纳入数据集这一事实，表明他们可能缺乏批判性分析。

I asked him how he makes sure that the data is not leading to bias, for example, because commuting distance is highly correlated with race and socioeconomic status in the United States as a result of historical redlining. He told me that he trusts his data people, but the fact that commuting time is even part of the data set shows me that there may be a lack of critical analysis.

正如我们之前所见，对数据科学家的信任不足以根除人工智能中的偏见，尤其是当这项技术最常在普通员工不知情的情况下使用时。

As we have seen before, trust in data scientists is not enough to root out bias in AI, especially when this technology is most often used on rank-and-file employees without their knowledge.

第八章

CHAPTER 8

我们正在观察（和测量）

We Are Watching (and Measuring)

关于工作场所监控

On Surveillance at Work

埃米莉·史密斯是一位四十多岁的金发女子。她和年幼的儿子住在纽约州奥尔巴尼北部，是一名医疗编码员。2​​020年5月疫情爆发之初，她被解雇了。四个月后，她在一家保险公司找到了一份新的医疗编码员职位，可以完全远程工作，而这份工作正是她喜欢的。

Emily Smith is a blonde woman in her late thirties. She lives north of Albany in New York with her young son and works as a medical coder. She was laid off at the start of the pandemic in May 2020, and four months later she found a new medical coder position at an insurance company working fully remote, which she preferred.

她的工作是分析病人病历、抄写医疗代码以及添加医保报销单。她并非直接为保险公司工作，而是在一家人力资源中介公司工作，这家公司把她“借”到一家医院，这意味着她几乎没有福利，没有带薪休假，第一年没有假期，没有带薪假日，还要受到大量的监控，这让她心神不宁。

Her job was to analyze patient charts, copy medical codes, and add Medicare reimbursements. She didn’t work directly for the insurance company; she worked for a staffing agency that “lent” her to a hospital, which meant almost no benefits, no paid time off, no vacation time for the first year, no paid holidays, and lots of surveillance, which left her shaken.

新公司对监控的事情直言不讳，当然也没有隐瞒。第二天她就得到了全面的介绍：她被告知主管会检查她阅读了多少图表，以确保她达到了每小时至少阅读五张图表的目标。

The new company didn’t beat around the bush about the surveillance and certainly didn’t keep it a secret. She got a full introduction on day two: she was told that her supervisors checked how many charts she read to make sure she was meeting her goal of at least five charts per hour.

除此之外，她还了解到该系统还能跟踪她的电脑状态并向主管发送报告：“它显示工作时间、电脑锁定时间以及空闲时间，”她说。

On top of that, she learned that the system also tracked the status of her computer and sent reports to her supervisors: “It shows how much time is work time, how much time the computer is locked, and then how much time is idle time,” she said.

如果她六十秒内没有移动鼠标或者敲击键盘上的键，空闲时间时钟就会开始运行。

If she didn’t move her mouse for sixty seconds or tap a key on her keyboard, the clock for idle time started running.

“经理们会检查。主管们每天都会检查。如果你的工作、锁定和闲置比例不符合他们的要求，你就会收到‘嘿，怎么了？’”史密斯说。

“The managers check it. Supervisors check it every day. And if your ratio of work to lock to idle is not where they want it to be, you get a, ‘Hey, what’s up?’” Smith said.

有一次，她在15分钟（无薪）休息时忘记锁电脑了。她的主管联系了她，想知道她的电脑为什么闲置了这么久。她解释说自己忘了锁电脑，主管表示理解，但要求她确保以后不会再发生这种事。

One time she forgot to lock her computer when she went on a fifteen-minute (unpaid) break. Her supervisor pinged her wanting to know why her computer was idle for so long. When she explained that she had forgotten to lock her computer, they were understanding but asked her to make sure it wouldn’t happen again.

即使在做高效工作，比如读图表的时候，她也必须不停地敲击键盘或移动鼠标，以免系统记录她处于闲置状态。“这就像，如果我正在设定目标，那么读图表的时候鼠标不动又有什么关系呢？但我必须这么做。我必须在读图表的时候移动鼠标，这样才不会被记录下来，”她说。

Even while she was doing productive work, like reading a chart, she had to do busywork of hitting keys on her keyboard or moving her mouse so the system wouldn’t record her as idle. “It’s like, well, if I’m making my goals, what does it matter if my mouse isn’t moving while I read a chart? But that’s what I had to do. I had to just move my mouse while I was reading so that I didn’t get dinged,” she said.

该公司还追踪她访问的每个网站，并在每日报告中标记她访问的未经授权的网站。

The company also tracked every website she visited and flagged in daily reports if she visited an unauthorized site.

她上厕所时设置了一个两分钟的计时器，这样她的电脑就不会闲置太久，也不会超过她总共三十分钟的休息时间。

She’d set a timer for two minutes when she went to the bathroom so she wouldn’t have her computer sit on idle for too long and wouldn’t exceed her total thirty-minute break time.

艾米丽形容监测过程极其紧张：“我害怕去洗手间。那要花几分钟？之后我能自己做点零食吗？或者如果我感觉不舒服怎么办？”

Emily described the monitoring as extremely stressful: “I was afraid to go to the bathroom. How many minutes is that going to take? Am I going to be able to make myself a snack after? Or what if I am not feeling good?”

但软件的编程并没有考虑到人类的需求，比如可能需要稍微延长一下上厕所的时间。除了监控她每分钟的工作之外，她的主管每天还会发邮件，把她团队里二十多名员工从“效率最高”到“效率最低”进行排名。

But the software wasn’t programmed to care that humans have human needs and may need a slightly longer bathroom break. On top of monitoring every minute of her work, each day her supervisors sent out an email ranking the more than twenty workers on her team from “most productive” to “least productive.”

“感觉很丢脸，”史密斯说。但她仍然每天查看，确保自己至少没有被列为最差的。

“It felt demeaning,” Smith said. She still checked every day to make sure she was at least not listed as the worst.

随着时间的推移，她学会了一些简单的技巧来欺骗系统。她的主管告诉她，如果她的图表长达八千页，而她显然无法每小时至少分析五张图表，那么她应该回头看看其他日期的较短图表，这样可以提高当天的小时计数，让她的工作量看起来更平衡。

And over time, she learned simple hacks to trick the system. Her supervisor told her that if she had a chart that was eight thousand pages and she obviously wouldn’t be able to analyze at least five charts per hour because of it, she should go back to shorter charts from other days to bring up her hourly count for that day and make her load look more balanced.

即使在没有分配给她图表的日子里，她也必须摇动鼠标八个小时才能获得报酬。

And even on days when no charts were assigned to her, she had to jiggle her mouse for eight hours to get a paycheck.

尽管感觉她的一举一动都被追踪，但仍有报告需要完成：“除此之外，我们还必须在一天结束时填写一份表格：我们花在休息上的时间、花在图表上的时间，以及花在会议上的时间。”

Despite feeling like every one of her moves was tracked, there were reports to complete: “On top of that, we had to fill out a form at the end of the day: the amount of time we spend on break, the amount of time you spend in charts, and then the amount of time spent in meetings.”

她在公司工作期间，继母突然去世，她没有带薪休假，这让她心碎不已，不得不盘算着自己可以请多少天无薪假来帮助父亲。结果，她可以请三天假。

While she was working at the company, her stepmother died suddenly, and it was heartbreaking to her that she didn’t get any paid leave and had to calculate how many days she could afford to take off unpaid to help her dad. She could afford three days off.

艾米丽·史密斯 (Emily Smith) 在这份受到严格监控的工作上干了一年多，并于 2021 年底找到了一份新工作。

Emily Smith lasted a little over a year in the heavily surveilled job and found a new one in late 2021.

但这次经历让她患上了自我诊断的“监视创伤后应激障碍”。

But the experience left her with self-diagnosed “surveillance PTSD.”

在新工作中，史密斯不再受到监控，而是被要求自行记录工作时间。她说，她的老板为人很亲切，没有任何事无巨细的管理倾向。

In her new job, there is no surveillance and Smith is asked to track her own hours. She said her boss is a human without any micromanaging tendencies.

有一次，史密斯的一位同事在新工作中因为上班迟到了两分钟而感到压力很大，经理却毫不在意。事实上，这位主管说她根本不需要知道别人什么时候去洗手间。“她说，‘你是个成年人了——只要你把工作做完，我不在乎你去几次。’”

Once, when a coworker of Smith stressed over clocking in two minutes late at her new job, their manager didn’t care at all. In fact, their supervisor said she didn’t need to know when someone was going to take a bathroom break. “She says stuff like, ‘You’re an adult—as long as you get your work done, I don’t care how many times you go.’”

没有监控，又有真人上司，这让她的新工作比以前的工作好上百倍：“这里轻松多了，我也不担心。而且我说话他们也会听。”

The lack of monitoring and a human boss made her new job a hundred times better than her old one: “It’s so much more chill and I’m not worried. And they listen to me when I say something.”

秘密特工的监视级别

SECRET AGENT LEVELS OF SURVEILLANCE

上一章我们探讨了公司如何监控员工，以评估其能力和未来晋升潜力。本章我们将探讨公司监控员工的总体方式，这是一个更广泛的范畴。这些趋势揭示了一个潜在的隐患。

In the last chapter we covered how companies are surveilling employees to measure abilities and potential for future promotion. In this chapter we cover the broader category of how companies monitor employees in general. The trends reveal a potentially troubling future.

在实体办公室工作一直以来的一个好处是，管理者可以确保员工在工作。但办公室的监控有限。员工可能坐在办公桌前，却选择什么也不做，或者上网，或者在图表上涂鸦。但我们正在进入一个新的监控时代。

One benefit of working in a physical office has always been that managers can make sure employees are working. But surveillance at the office was limited. Workers might be sitting at their desks but choosing to do nothing or to surf the web or to doodle in charts. But we are entering a new era of monitoring.

“这简直就是秘密特工级别的监控，”前就业律师、民主与技术中心高级政策顾问马修·谢勒 (Matthew Scherer) 说。“以前，雇主让一个主管时刻盯着你，监视你的一举一动，这从来都不现实。” 但这是本质上就是这些监控程序的作用。它们也适用于远程工作者。

“This is secret agent levels of surveillance,” said Matthew Scherer, the former employment lawyer and senior policy counsel at the Center for Democracy and Technology. “It’s never been practical before for an employer to have a physical supervisor attached to your hip every second of every day monitoring what you are doing.” But that is essentially what these surveillance programs are doing. They are also used for remote workers.

谢勒说：“这确实是一种不同程度的侵扰，我们在工作场所从未见过，至少在绝大多数工作场所从未见过。”

“It really is a different level of intrusiveness that we haven’t seen in workplaces, at least the vast, vast majority of workplaces before,” Scherer said.

数据支持他的观点：“美国 10 家最大的私营雇主中有 8 家追踪个体员工的生产效率指标，其中很多都是实时追踪的。”据《纽约时报》调查显示。1

The numbers back him up: “Eight of the 10 largest private U.S. employers track the productivity metrics of individual workers, many in real time,” according to an examination by the New York Times.1

2020年，正值新冠疫情最严重之际，《纽约时报》记者采访了在佛罗里达州朱庇特经营一家营销公司的克里斯·休伊特（Chris Heuwetter）。休伊特告诉记者，自从他的20名员工开始居家办公后，工作时间大幅缩短，有些员工直到早上10点才回复信息。他还面临着销售额下降和客户响应速度变慢的问题。

In 2020, at the height of the COVID-19 pandemic, a Times reporter spoke with Chris Heuwetter, who was running a marketing company in Jupiter, Florida.2 Heuwetter told the reporter that work hours had collapsed after his twenty employees started working from home, with some not responding to messages until ten o’clock in the morning. He was also facing a drop in sales, and customer response times had slowed.

他开始使用一种名为 Hubstaff 的监控工具，员工的工作效率水平“立即”提高了，Heuwetter 说。

He began using a surveillance tool called Hubstaff, and employees’ productivity levels rose “immediately,” Heuwetter said.

我实在忍不住联系了一家公司，想在我的电脑上安装一个生产力追踪工具。我用了几个星期。它真的追踪了我在电脑上的每一秒。它记录了我访问的每个网站，并将它们分为高效和低效两类，每个管理员都可以调整。知道自己做的每一件事都被记录下来，感觉有点奇怪。

I couldn’t resist and contacted a company to get a productivity tracking tool on my computer. I used it for a few weeks. It literally tracked how I spent every second on my computer. It recorded every website I visited and classified them as productive and unproductive, which could be adjusted by individual managers. It felt kind of weird to know that everything I did was being recorded.

当然，这款工具并没有记录我所有任务，因为我在纸上写的提纲、打电话的时间以及其他非电脑任务都没有记录，而且我找不到手动输入的方法。但如果雇主使用这种监控软件，它可能会促使我改变自己的习惯：开始在电脑上列提纲，用电脑上的应用程序打电话，打电话时不断移动鼠标来产生活动。

The tool didn’t record the full scope of my tasks, of course, because outlines I wrote on paper, time spent on phone calls, and other noncomputer tasks weren’t recorded and I couldn’t find a way to manually input them. But if an employer was using this kind of monitoring software, it would probably lead me to adapt my habits: start making outlines on my computer, use an app on my computer to make calls, keep moving my mouse while on the phone to generate activity.

马修·谢勒 (Matthew Scherer) 等人表示，这种全方位的监视，尤其是当员工因休息时间过长或完成任务不够快而受到训斥时，会对我们的身心健康产生负面影响。

Matthew Scherer and others say that this kind of all-out surveillance, especially if employees are reprimanded for taking breaks that are too long or not doing tasks fast enough, has negative effects on our mental and physical health.

而且，监控可能不会在工作时间停止。最近，微软申请了一项专利，用于追踪员工是否在指定工作时间以外工作。申请文件指出，该应用程序可以用来追踪哪些人在下班后工作，以便公司可以制止这种情况。但这样的记录也可以帮助雇主了解哪些人为公司投入了大量时间。

And surveillance may not always stop during work hours. Recently, Microsoft filed for a patent to track whether employees are working outside their designated working hours. The filing states that the app can be used to track who is working after hours so companies can put a stop to that. But a log like this could also help employers understand who is putting a lot of time in for the company.

监视值得吗？

IS SURVEILLANCE WORTH IT?

多年来，司机、仓库工人和呼叫中心员工一直受到监控，现在这项技术正在进入白领职业，包括合同律师、医疗保健工作者、银行家和在家工作的员工。

For years, drivers, warehouse workers, and call center employees have been monitored and now the technology is moving into white-collar professions, including for contract lawyers, healthcare workers, bankers, and employees working from home.

但对雇主来说，这或许是值得的。我与密歇根州立大学人力资源与劳动关系学院的教授塔拉·贝伦德（Tara Behrend）就此进行了探讨。她教授管理心理学，也是职场科技应用方面的专家。

But maybe it’s worth it for employers. I spoke about this with Tara Behrend, a professor at Michigan State University’s School of Human Resources and Labor Relations. She teaches management psychology and is an expert in technology used in the workplace.

她和她的团队调查了员工对工作中被监控的态度。他们还分析了76项涵盖数字绩效监控的研究。元分析中的研究涵盖了超过2.1万名参与者。

She and her team surveyed workers about their attitudes toward being monitored at work. They also analyzed seventy-six studies that covered digital performance monitoring. The studies in the meta-analysis included more than twenty-one thousand participants.

工作场所监控的增幅惊人。贝伦德表示，监控数量增加了600%以上。“这是因为所有突然被归类为远程工作者的人，他们的老板都不知道该如何远程管理他们的绩效，所以他们过度依赖“这些监​​控工具让我很担心，”她说，“他们认为，‘如果我看不到员工的工作，就无法给他们有效的反馈，所以我需要某种技术解决方案，以便在我不在场的情况下了解他们在做什么。’”

The increase in monitoring at work was striking. Behrend said that surveillance has gone up by over 600 percent. “It’s because everyone who has suddenly been classified as a remote worker, their bosses don’t know how to manage their performance remotely, and so they lean too heavily on these surveillance tools,” she said. “They think, ‘If I can’t see the person working, I cannot give them effective feedback, and so I need some sort of technological solution to find out what they’re doing when I’m not physically present.’”

主管可以选择多种技术，包括追踪和分析员工的声音，或通过 GPS 进行位置监控。管理人员还可以远程访问计算机，记录员工的每一次按键操作并拍照。监控甚至可以使用生理传感器来追踪员工的心率和眼球运动。

Supervisors can choose from many different technologies, including tracking and analyzing someone’s voice or location monitoring through GPS. Managers can also remotely access computers and record every keystroke and take photos of workers. Surveillance can even involve physiological sensors that track heart rate and eye movements.

在调查中，贝伦德惊讶地发现，员工对工作监控的看法截然不同。“他们并非断然拒绝，也并非完全接受。他们只是表示，根据目的和具体情况，监控有时是可以接受的，而且他们的态度很大程度上取决于所使用的技术，”贝伦德说道。“像追踪心率这样的技术，人们普遍认为它不应该作为工作绩效的一部分。”

In her survey, Behrend was surprised to find a very nuanced take of what workers think of monitoring at work. “They’re not categorically rejecting this. They’re not categorically accepting it. They’re saying that it is sometimes acceptable depending on the purpose, depending on the context, and that their attitudes are very based on the technology involved,” Behrend said. “A technology like tracking your heart rate, generally people feel that that is not warranted as a part of work performance.”

但是，使用监测身体机能来保证工人安全的情况（例如，监测辐射暴露或跟踪卡车司机眼睛并在他们入睡时发出警告的摄像头）通常更容易被接受。

But cases in which monitoring bodily functions is used to keep workers safe—for example, monitoring radiation exposure or cameras that track truck drivers’ eyes and warn them when they are falling asleep—are generally more accepted.

许多员工认为，追踪从公司计算机网络下载的文件的监控行为，要么总是可以接受，要么有时是可以接受的。“理由是，这可能涉及公司安全，或者显然与工作相关。所以这是可以接受的，”贝伦德说。一般来说，“当人们能够同意、明确与工作相关、并且目标是针对行为时，监控是可以接受的。”

Many workers judged surveillance that tracked which files were downloaded from the company’s computer network to be either always or sometimes acceptable. “The rationale is that this might involve security for the company or it’s clearly work-related. And so it’s acceptable,” Behrend said. Generally, “people find monitoring acceptable when they can give consent, when it’s clearly job relevant, and when the target is about behavior.”

如果监控未经员工同意，可能会成为严重的压力源。许多员工会开始试图利用系统以最大限度地提高其性能评级。一个完整的利基行业迎合了这一需求：市面上有各种设备可以帮助人们保持电脑处于“活跃”状态——从鼠标摇杆到模拟运动的U盘。在TikTok视频中，人们将电脑鼠标连接到了机器人吸尘器和其他设备上。

If monitoring happens without employees’ consent, it can become a serious source of stress. Many employees will start trying to game the system to maximize their performance rating. A whole niche industry caters to them: there are devices for sale that help folks keep their computer on “active” status—from mouse wigglers to USB sticks that simulate movement. In TikTok videos, people have connected their computer mouse to a robot vacuum cleaner and other devices.

但贝伦德表示，这些监控指向一个令人担忧的趋势。“除非受到监管和保护，否则员工隐私很快就会成为一种奢侈品——而在美国，这种情况根本不存在。” 美国公司基本上可以在自己拥有的电脑上为所欲为，也可以在员工使用的电脑上为所欲为。

But the surveillance points to a worrisome trend, Behrend said. “Worker privacy is already well on its way to becoming a luxury good unless it’s regulated and protected—and in the US, it is not at all.” US companies can basically do whatever they want on computers they own and give to employees.

欧洲，尤其是德国和奥地利，监管更为严格。只要公司拥有五名员工，员工就可以投票选举一个工会，即一个内部员工代表团体。德国工会法第87条第6款规定，工会必须同意使用监控员工行为或绩效的技术。

There is more regulation in Europe and especially in Germany and Austria. As soon as a company has five workers, the employees can vote for a works council, an internal employee representation group. In paragraph 87, number 6, of the German works council law, it states that the works council has to agree to technologies that monitor the behavior or performance of employees.

正是由于法律中的这一句话，德国的工会才得以迫使世界上一些最大的科技公司阻止或废除个人监控和生产率监控。在工人监控领域，德国是一个未知领域。

Works councils in Germany have been able to force some of the largest tech companies in the world to prevent or abolish individual surveillance and productivity rates, thanks to this one sentence in the law. In the world of worker surveillance, Germany is terra incognita.

监视能提高绩效吗？

DOES SURVEILLANCE INCREASE PERFORMANCE?

塔拉·贝伦德（Tara Behrend）和她的团队对76项研究进行了元分析，试图解答“监督是否能提高绩效”这个问题。他们发现，监督的效果与许多高管的期望截然相反。

Tara Behrend and her team tried to answer the question of whether surveillance increases performance in their meta-analysis of seventy-six studies. They found that surveillance has the opposite effect of what many executives hope it accomplishes.

“绩效监控确实会增加你的压力，增加你的消极态度，但这并不能达到它原本的目标，即提高你的绩效，”贝伦德说道。事实上，监控越严格，绩效下降得越厉害。监控还会导致更高的倦怠率，像艾米丽·史密斯这样的人最终会辞职。

“Being monitored for your performance does increase your stress, does increase your negative attitudes, but it doesn’t accomplish the goal that it is meant to accomplish, which is to improve your performance,” Behrend said. In fact, the more intense the monitoring, the more performance goes down. Monitoring also leads to higher burnout rates and people like Emily Smith leaving their jobs.

更令人难以置信的是，监控工具的供应商自己都说监控工人会产生负面影响，但他们仍然提供这些工具。

What’s even more mind-boggling is that the vendors of surveillance tools themselves say that monitoring workers has negative effects, but they still offer the tools.

微软于 2022 年 9 月发布了一份报告，该报告“调查了 11 个国家/地区的 20,000 人，并分析了数万亿个 Microsoft 365 生产力信号”。3该报告的作者发现，追踪“生产力”适得其反：“由于一些组织使用技术来追踪活动而不是影响，员工缺乏关于他们被追踪的方式和原因的背景信息，这可能会破坏信任。”

Microsoft released a report in September 2022 that “surveyed 20,000 people in 11 countries and analyzed trillions of Microsoft 365 productivity signals.”3 The authors of the report found that tracking “productivity” was counterproductive: “As some organizations use technology to track activity rather than impact, employees lack context on how and why they’re being tracked, which can undermine trust.”

这也会导致“生产力剧场”，这意味着一些员工做的事情的唯一目的就是向老板发出信号，表明他们正在工作，包括移动鼠标（或使用自动鼠标“抖动器”），向同事发送电子邮件，使他们的状态灯呈绿色或活动状态，提早签到 Slack 以表明他们在早上工作，甚至出席与他们的工作无关的会议，只是为了表明他们在场。

It also leads to “productivity theater,” which means that some workers are doing things for the sole purpose of signaling to their boss that they are working, including moving their mouse (or using an automatic mouse “jiggler”), emailing coworkers so their status light is green or active, checking in early on Slack to show they’re working at early hours, or even showing up to meetings that have nothing to do with their work just to show they are present.

微软报告中的员工表示，他们每天要花大约一个小时的时间进行这种恶作剧，而这个小时本来可以用来完成实际工作。

Workers in the Microsoft report said they spent about an hour each day on such shenanigans, an hour that could have been used to get actual work done.

一名受到监视的员工向《华盛顿邮报》透露：“人们根本不关心（工作）。”微软一再表示，追踪活动并不是了解员工是否有效率的好方法。

“People just stopped caring [about the job],” one surveilled employee shared with the Washington Post.4 Microsoft has said again and again that tracking activity is not a good way to understand whether workers are productive.

“在微软，我们认为利用技术监视员工的工作并非解决之道，我们的技术并非为此目的而设计。用鼠标移动来衡量生产力就像把日晷当秒表一样。监控不仅会导致不良数据，还会破坏信任，而信任是组织成功的关键因素，一旦失去，就难以重建，”微软现代办公副总裁贾里德·斯帕塔罗 (Jared Spataro) 在2022 年 9 月发表于《财富》杂志的一篇专栏文章中说道。5

“At Microsoft, we believe that using technology to spy on people at work is not the answer and our technology is not designed for that purpose. Measuring productivity with mouse movements is like using a sundial as a stopwatch. And surveillance doesn’t just lead to bad data—it undermines trust, a critical factor in organizational success that, once lost, is incredibly difficult to regain,” said Microsoft’s Jared Spataro, the corporate vice president of modern work, in an op-ed piece in Fortune in September 2022.5

有趣而讽刺的是，报告中的部分数据来自微软自己的软件工具，这是一个庞大的生态系统，涵盖了Microsoft Teams会议、Outlook电子邮件、Word、Excel、PowerPoint以及许多其他应用程序，这些应用程序追踪员工如何使用这些工具。在产品描述中，微软声称“这些数据涵盖了员工如何在微软所有应用程序和服务中沟通、协作和管理时间。” 6

What’s interesting and ironic is that part of the data in the report came from Microsoft’s own software tools, a vast ecosystem from Microsoft Teams meetings, emails in Outlook, Word, Excel, PowerPoint, and many other applications, which track how employees use these tools. In product descriptions, Microsoft states that “the data covers how workers communicate, collaborate, and manage their time across all the applications and services in Microsoft.”6

尽管斯帕塔罗认为雇主应该限制监控，但微软过去几年向其他公司销售的软件已经涉足员工监控领域。企业似乎对这些工具内置的功能保持沉默，因为一旦信息泄露，就会引发公众的强烈抗议。

Although Spataro believes employers should restrain their surveillance, the software Microsoft has been selling to other companies over the past few years has pushed into the employee monitoring space. It seems that companies want to keep quiet about the capabilities that are built into these tools, because when something leaks out, there have been public outcries.

2020年，Zoom 在视频通话中引入了“注意力追踪”功能，可以向管理人员显示参与者是否正在打开其他标签页，或者是否只关注 Zoom 会议。在公众强烈反对后，Zoom 停用了该功能。7

In 2020, Zoom introduced “attention tracking” during video calls, which showed managers if participants were opening other tabs or were solely looking at the Zoom meeting. After a public backlash, Zoom deactivated the feature.7

微软在 2019 年公布生产力评分时遭到了公众的反对。8该软件跟踪了个人员工在微软应用程序中的活动水平，并为每位员工提供了总体生产力评分。

Microsoft encountered public pushback when it unveiled a productivity score in 2019.8 The software tracked individual employees’ activity levels in Microsoft applications and gave every worker an overall productivity score.

甚至连“生产力得分”这个词在这里都显得有些奇怪，因为该工具只追踪微软工具中的活动，而且并未公开良好生产力的基准。也许有人正在阅读报告，但并非在使用微软工具时。也许他们在 Gmail 中写了一封电子邮件，或者使用了其他非微软应用程序来完成工作，或者打了个电话？又或者他们正在参加一个面对面的会议？

Even the term “productivity score” seems odd here because the tool only tracked activity in Microsoft tools and the benchmark for good productivity was undisclosed. Maybe someone was reading a report, but not while using a Microsoft tool. Maybe they wrote an email in Gmail or used another non-Microsoft application to get work done or made a phone call? Or they were in an in-person meeting?

生产力得分是一个严格的基准，因为公司很难清楚地知道哪些可追踪的任务能让员工高效工作或表现优异：是发送大量电子邮件？参加每一次会议？还是几乎不参加会议？是进行深度思考（可能产生的数据很少）时效率高？还是进行长时间的面对面会议时效率高？这可能因工作和个人而异。由于我们并不真正了解这些数据的含义，这些生产力或绩效得分是任意的，因为任何特定工作都没有既定的生产力指标基准，但如果员工得分不够高，可能会给他们带来麻烦。

Productivity scores are a tough benchmark, because it’s hard for companies to clearly know which tasks that can be tracked make an employee productive or high performing: Is it when they send out a ton of emails? Go to every meeting? Or attend almost no meetings? Are they productive when they do some deep thinking, which would probably generate very little data? Or when they have long in-person meetings? This probably changes from job to job and from individual to individual. Since we don’t really know what most of this data means, these kinds of productivity or performance scores are arbitrary because there are no established benchmarks for productivity markers in any given job, but they could potentially get workers in trouble if people don’t score high enough.

在公众的强烈抗议之后，微软在 2020 年底改变了主意，表示生产力分数将不再作为衡量个人生产力的标准，而仅显示组织层面对微软工具的采用情况，而不再提供个人的分数和活动水平。

After a public outcry, in late 2020, Microsoft backpedaled and said that the productivity score would not be available as a measure of individual productivity anymore but only show the adoption of Microsoft tools at an organizational level, which doesn’t make individuals’ scores and activity levels available anymore.

Jared Spataro 在一篇博客文章中写道：“未来，生产力评分中的沟通、会议、内容协作、团队合作和移动性指标将仅在组织层面汇总数据，从而清晰地衡量组织层面对关键功能的采用情况。” 9 “组织中的任何人都无法使用生产力评分来访问有关个人用户如何使用 Microsoft 365 中的应用和服务的数据。”

“Going forward, the communications, meetings, content collaboration, teamwork, and mobility measures in Productivity Score will only aggregate data at the organization level—providing a clear measure of organization-level adoption of key features,” Jared Spataro wrote in a blog post.9 “No one in the organization will be able to use Productivity Score to access data about how an individual user is using apps and services in Microsoft 365.”

自 2020 年起，生产力评分功能（现称为采用评分）已被禁用，数据分析只能在团队级别进行。

Since 2020, the productivity score function, which is now called adoption score, was disabled and data analysis should be available only on a team level.

但事实证明，如果公司选择这些功能，在微软应用程序中进行监控仍然是可能的——至少对于调查人员、人力资源、法务和其他管理人员来说是这样。2022年秋天，我在YouTube上深入挖掘了微软的“兔子洞”，观看了微软工程师解释公司如何追踪员工以及潜在威胁来自何处的视频。

But it turns out that monitoring in Microsoft applications is still possible if a company chooses those functions—at least for investigators, HR, legal, and other administrators. In the fall of 2022, I went down the Microsoft rabbit hole on YouTube and watched videos in which Microsoft engineers explain how companies can track employees and where potential threats come from.

在一段视频中，微软的主持人甚至提出这样的论点：鉴于2022年近50%的员工计划在未来一年内跳槽，公司应该认真考虑任何员工对组织的威胁。“内部风险管理应该成为‘零信任’方法的一部分，以保护数据和通信，”微软内部风险解决方案首席项目经理Talhah Mir说道。“我们习惯于考虑由网络攻击等外部威胁或恶意管理员等内部威胁造成的数据泄露，但很少考虑日常员工带来的内部风险。这是一个日益严重的问题，大多数组织都对此感到担忧。” 10

In one video, the Microsoft hosts even make the argument that, because nearly 50 percent of employees in 2022 were looking to change jobs over the next year, companies should really consider any of their workers a threat to the organization. “Insider risk management should really be part of a ‘zero trust’ approach for the protection of your data and communications,” says Talhah Mir, the principal project manager of Insider Risk Solutions at Microsoft. “We’re used to thinking about data exposure caused by external threats from cyber attacks or insider threats from rogue admins, but less so about insider risks introduced by everyday employees. And this is an expanding problem that most organizations are worried about.”10

然后，视频出现了一个奇怪的转折，“内部攻击”突然变得无所不包，延伸到所有员工沟通。“当你观察像倦怠这样的问题时，你会发现，倦怠是人们离开组织的根本原因，这与人们在沟通平台上发泄情绪有着直接的联系，而这反过来又会导致不健康或有害的工作环境。或者更糟的是——可能导致职场骚扰，”米尔说。

Then the video takes a bizarre turn and suddenly “insider attacks” become all-encompassing and extend to all employee communications. “When you look at things like burnout, which is an underlying reason why somebody leaves an organization, what you find is that there’s a direct correlation to somebody’s venting in the communication platform, which then in turn leads to things like an unhealthy or toxic workplace. Or worse—can lead to workplace harassment,” Mir says.

请注意这里用来证明监视合理性的扭曲逻辑：有倦怠风险的人应该受到监控，因为他们更有可能离开，也更有可能在内部信息中发泄，而发泄可能导致有害的工作场所或职场骚扰。请记住，微软也曾报告称，个人监控可能会造成压力大或有害的工作环境。该公司向公众表示，监控个别员工并无益处，但向 IT（和人力资源）团队声称，微软产品可以监控所有通信，并据称可以检测信息中的骚扰、亵渎和歧视内容。

Notice the twisted logic used here to justify surveillance: people at risk of burnout should be monitored because they are more likely to leave and more likely to vent in internal messages, and venting can lead to a toxic workplace or workplace harassment. Remember that Microsoft also reported that individual monitoring can create a stressful or toxic work environment. To the public at large the company says it’s not helpful to monitor individual workers, but to IT (and HR) teams it claims Microsoft products can monitor all communications and allegedly detect harassment, profanity, and discrimination in messages.

有任何数据或科学依据支持这一观点吗？我确信倦怠风险和发泄情绪之间存在某种关联，但这又是如何导致工作环境恶化，甚至引发骚扰的呢？

Is there any data or science backing this up? I am sure there is a correlation somewhere between burnout risk and venting, but how does that lead to a toxic work environment and even to harassment?

在我看来，倦怠风险，甚至员工离职，很可能也与有害或糟糕的管理者有关。既然我们知道很多员工离职都是因为糟糕的管理者，那么我们现在是否应该监控所有管理者，找出那些有害的管理者呢？视频中的两位微软员工并没有提到这一点，但他们解释了公司为什么应该监控所有沟通内容：“这可能在你维护健康工作环境的整体战略中发挥关键作用，”米尔说道。

In my opinion, it is likely that burnout risk or even people leaving an organization is also correlated with toxic or bad managers. Because we know for a fact that many employees leave because of terrible managers, should we now monitor all managers and find the toxic ones? The two Microsoft employees in the video don’t address this, but they are addressing why companies should monitor all communications: “This could play a key part in your overall strategy to maintain a healthy work environment,” Mir says.

该软件会扫描个人用户行为，包括复制到U盘的文件和发送到公司外部的电子邮件。在视频中，微软员工强调数据是匿名的。但在该软件中，任何“风险信号”都与“关键事件”相关，例如员工辞职。此时，几乎任何人都能辨别出哪些员工正在被监视——在大多数公司，一天内不会有成千上万的人辞职。

The software scans individual user behavior, including files copied to USB drives and emails sent outside the organization. In the videos, Microsoft employees emphasize that the data is anonymized. But in the software, any “risk signals” are connected to “pivotal events,” such as an employee’s resignation. At this point, most anyone would be able to decipher which employee is being surveilled—in most companies, there aren’t thousands of people resigning on a given day.

无论如何，实际上，这些数据根本没有真正匿名化。事实上，整个系统可以设置为某些管理员可以随时查看所有员工姓名。管理员可以看到算法声称发现的针对性骚扰、亵渎和歧视的信息数量。该软件能够扫描每一条通信。微软表示，Purview 建立在隐私优先的原则之上，融入多重隐私保护措施，确保客户能够有效降低内部风险，同时又不损害用户隐私。可审计记录确保任何内部风险事件信息（包括员工姓名和相关内容）的访问均被记录并可追踪。

Anyway, in reality, the data isn’t really anonymized at all. In fact, the whole system can be set up so that certain admins can see all employee names at all times. The admins can see the number of messages with targeted harassment, profanity, and discrimination the algorithm claimed it found. The software is capable of scanning every piece of communication. Microsoft said that Purview is built on a privacy-first approach, incorporating multiple privacy protections to ensure customers can effectively mitigate insider risk without compromising users’ privacy. Auditable records ensure that any access of insider risk incident information (including an employee’s name and underlying content) is logged and trackable.

发现这些漏洞的不止我一个人。一些网站不仅向雇主提供如何监控员工的技巧，还介绍了使用 Microsoft Teams 监控员工的方法，并在这些教程中提供了该工具中各个选项的具体截图。

I am not alone in finding these loopholes. Websites that give employers tips on how to surveil their workers also describe ways to monitor employees using Microsoft Teams, and in these tutorials, they include exact screenshots on what options to set up in the tool.

微软似乎并未限制雇主使用这些审计和分析程序的方式。在美国，许多员工无需被告知他们正在使用这项技术。（我确信微软的隐私政策中明确告知员工，该软件可以访问和处理所有数据，但当我开始一份新工作时，我别无选择，只能同意公司和软件的隐私政策，因为我很可能不得不使用公司服务器和某些软件产品来工作。）

Microsoft does not seem to limit how employers can use these auditing and analytics programs. In the United States, many workers don’t need to be informed that the technology is being used on them. (Deep in Microsoft’s privacy policy, I am sure employees are informed that the software can access and process all data, but when I start a new job, I don’t really have a choice but to agree to a company’s and a software’s privacy policy because I will most likely have to use company servers and certain software products for work.)

算法生产力评分的问题

THE PROBLEM WITH ALGORITHMIC PRODUCTIVITY SCORES

如果您是一名员工，我建议您假设您的雇主对其员工采取“零信任”政策并且正在监控一切。

If you are an employee, I would recommend that you assume your employer has a “zero trust” policy toward their workers and is monitoring everything.

由于公司正在追踪我们的行为，一些员工可能会决定改变自己的行为，试图操纵指标：“没有人阻止员工设置自动发送电子邮件给自己，或者与志同道合的同事安排‘虚假’会议，以提高他们的绩效统计数据，”英国非营利组织“隐私国际”在一份关于微软能力的报告中写道。11

Because companies are tracking our behavior, some employees might decide to change their behavior to try to rig the metrics: “No one is stopping a worker from setting up automatic emails to themselves or setting up ‘fake’ meetings with like-minded colleagues in order to increase their performance statistics,” writes Privacy International, a nonprofit based in the United Kingdom, in a report on Microsoft’s capabilities.11

这可能会使生产力信号变得毫无意义，但该领域的专家称生产力信号基本上毫无意义。

This would probably render the productivity signals meaningless, but experts in the field have called productivity signals largely meaningless anyway.

微软前职场智能副总裁瑞安·富勒 (Ryan Fuller) 表示，尤其是在知识型工作中，生产力和绩效都没有明确的定义。“你如何评估营销团队、法律团队、研发团队的产出？这不是技术问题，而是人的问题。我们真的不知道，”富勒说道。“知识型工作是团队的；它不止一个人。它是一种集体努力，关乎个人，关乎他们如何与团队合作，以及团队如何有效地协调实现目标。它涉及很多维度，”他说道。算法并不能涵盖所有这些维度。

Particularly in knowledge work, there’s no definition of productivity, there’s no definition of performance, said Ryan Fuller, the former vice president for workplace intelligence at Microsoft. “How do you evaluate the output of a marketing team? A legal team, an R&D team? That’s not a technology problem, it’s a human problem. We just don’t really know,” Fuller said. “Knowledge work is the team; it’s more than one person. It’s a collective effort and it’s something about the individuals and how they function with the team and how well the team is aligned against goals. There are just so many dimensions to it,” he said. Not all of these dimensions can be covered by an algorithm.

虽然我们正处于算法统治我们生活的时代的开端，但这其中也有一些历史。十多年前，纽约市、休斯顿和佛罗里达州的学区曾使用算法来评估教师的绩效。教师的薪酬和晋升可能会受到其绩效分数的影响，一些教师甚至因为评分系统而被解雇。然而，这些隐秘的算法却遭遇了诸多阻力。

Although we are at the beginning of a time of algorithms ruling our lives, there is some history here. More than a decade ago, school districts in New York City, Houston, and Florida used algorithms to score teacher performance. A teacher’s pay and promotions could be affected by their performance scores, and some teachers were fired based on the scoring system. But the secretive algorithms received a lot of pushback.

2014年，休斯顿教师联合会对休斯顿独立学区使用的算法提起诉讼。《华盛顿邮报》写道：“教师们提出的指控包括：他们接受的评估是基于一些考试成绩，而这些考试并不评估他们应该教授的课程；这些公式难以理解；而且，由于教师无法质疑结果，宪法赋予他们的正当程序权利受到了侵犯。 ” 12

In 2014, the Houston Federation of Teachers filed a lawsuit against the algorithm used by the Houston Independent School District. “The teachers say, among other allegations, that they are being evaluated on the scores of tests that do not assess the curriculum they are supposed to teach, that the formulas are incomprehensible, and that their Constitutional rights to due process are being violated because teachers cannot challenge the results,” wrote the Washington Post.12

涉案教师之一安德鲁·杜威（Andrew Dewey）有一年被评为“最有效率”的教师。第二年，他却被评为“对学生的教育没有明显改善”。

One of the teachers in the lawsuit, Andrew Dewey, was scored as the “most effective” teacher one year. The next year, he was scored as making “no detectable difference” in his students’ education.

教师评估算法并没有使用基于深度神经网络的人工智能，但其背后的理念与今天的人工智能相同：算法将帮助雇主找到员工的“客观表现”。至少这是人们的希望。

The teacher evaluation algorithms did not use AI based on deep neural networks, but the idea behind them was the same as today’s AI: the algorithm will help employers find an employee’s “objective performance.” That was at least the hope.

休斯顿教师联合会主席盖尔·法伦表示，该算法并不准确，而且缺乏透明度，这对教师造成了伤害：“考试成绩被放入一个黑匣子中，没有老师能够计算或试图反驳那个能表明他们是否是好老师的数字。”

Gayle Fallon, president of the Houston Federation of Teachers, said that the algorithm wasn’t accurate and that the lack of transparency was hurting teachers: “The test scores are plugged into a black box where no teacher can either calculate or try and refute the number that comes out that tells if they are a good teacher.”

在相关诉讼中，法院经常站在教师一边。一位法官称纽约州教师评级制度“武断”且“反复无常”。

In the related lawsuits, the courts often sided with the teachers. One judge called the New York State teacher rating system “arbitrary” and “capricious.”

2017年，休斯顿独立学区解决了诉讼，并同意停止使用备受争议的教师评估系统。

In 2017, the Houston Independent School District settled the lawsuit and agreed to stop using the controversial teacher evaluation system.

自这些具有里程碑意义的决策以来，这类教师绩效算法已经不再受欢迎，但这并不意味着私营公司不再试图衡量员工的绩效。

Since those landmark decisions, these kinds of teacher performance algorithms have fallen out of favor, but that doesn’t mean that private companies are steering away from trying to measure their employees’ performance.

保护工会权利

PROTECTING THE RIGHT TO UNIONIZE

埃森哲公司前任董事总经理、负责人力资源的布莱恩·克罗普 (Brian Kropp) 表示，公司收集的数据可能无法用于生产力评分，但一旦获得数据，就很容易被滥用。

The data that companies collect may not work for productivity scoring, but once data is available, it can easily be misused, said Brian Kropp, former managing director at Accenture, where he covers human resources.

他曾合作过的一家公司使用刷卡数据（员工打卡上班的时间）来根据员工在办公桌前花费的时间来识别高绩效员工，但这并不能很好地代表生产力，因为有些人可能坐在办公桌前，效率不高，浪费时间。

One company he worked with used swipe-in data (when employees clocked in) to identify high performers based on the hours they spent at their desk—a poor proxy for productivity because some people might sit at their desk and not be productive, running down the hours.

当同一家公司在疫情期间面临裁员时，高管们试图使用同样的数据，据称确定高绩效员工，以确定低绩效员工并解雇这些员工。

When the same company was faced with layoffs during the pandemic, executives tried to use the same data that supposedly identified high performers to identify low performers and lay off those employees.

“我们获取了大量数据、信息和分析，但在某些情况下，我们基于这些数据做出的决策却令人质疑，”克罗普说道。“在很多情况下，在管理员工方面，技术的发展速度已经超越了我们对如何使用技术的知识。”

“We get a lot of data, we get a lot of information, we get a lot of analysis, but what decisions we’re making with that are really questionable in some cases,” Kropp said. “The technology is outpacing our knowledge on how to use the technology, in a lot of cases, when it comes to managing our employees.”

但很快，企业可能会面临政府机构全面监控的阻力。2022年秋季，美国国家劳工关系委员会总法律顾问詹妮弗·阿布鲁佐（Jennifer Abruzzo）撰写了一份执法备忘录，称她将对那些使用监控手段可能侵犯员工工会权利的雇主提起诉讼。这实际上可能意味着监控的全面停止，因为许多员工沟通，甚至社交媒体信息都可能包含工会活动。

But soon companies might face pushback on all-out surveillance from a government agency. In the fall of 2022, the general counsel of the National Labor Relations Board, Jennifer Abruzzo, wrote an enforcement memo saying that she will litigate against employers who use surveillance in cases where it could interfere with their employees’ rights to unionize. This could actually mean a broad stop to surveillance, because many kinds of employee communication and even social media feeds might include unionizing efforts.

阿布鲁佐写道：“通过电子手段进行密切、持续的监视和管理威胁到员工行使权利的基本能力。”

“Close, constant surveillance and management through electronic means threaten employees’ basic ability to exercise their rights,” Abruzzo wrote.

有充分的证据表明，雇主越来越多地使用新技术来密切监控和管理员工。例如，在仓库中，一些雇主会记录员工的谈话，并使用可穿戴设备、安全摄像头和射频识别徽章追踪他们的行踪。在路上，一些雇主会使用 GPS 跟踪设备和摄像头监视司机。还有一些雇主会全天监控使用电脑工作的员工——无论是在呼叫中心、办公室还是在家——使用键盘记录器和截屏、网络摄像头拍照或录音的软件。电子监控和自动化管理并不总是局限于工作时间。工作结束后，一些雇主会继续使用雇主发放的手机或可穿戴设备，或安装在员工自带设备上的应用程序，追踪员工的行踪和通讯记录。甚至在雇佣关系开始之前，一些雇主就通过性格测试和审查求职者的社交媒体账户来窥探求职者的私生活。13

It is well documented that employers are increasingly using new technologies to closely monitor and manage employees. In warehouses, for example, some employers record workers’ conversations and track their movements using wearable devices, security cameras, and radio-frequency identification badges. On the road, some employers keep tabs on drivers using GPS tracking devices and cameras. And some employers monitor employees who work on computers—whether in call centers, offices, or at home—using keyloggers and software that takes screenshots, webcam photos, or audio recordings throughout the day. Electronic monitoring and automated management are not always limited to working time. After the workday ends, some employers continue to track employees’ whereabouts and communications using employer-issued phones or wearable devices, or apps installed on workers’ own devices. And even before the employment relationship begins, some employers pry into job applicants’ private lives by conducting personality tests and scrutinizing applicants’ social media accounts.13

阿布鲁佐认为，这种无处不在的监控可能会干扰合法的工会活动，因为员工被允许共同组建工会，而工作场所的监控可能会揭露这些活动。她表示，她希望国家劳工关系委员会强制雇主事先披露他们参与的监控活动以及数据的使用方式，以便员工能够判断监控是否干扰了他们的组织工会权利。

Abruzzo believes that this kind of omnipresent surveillance could interfere with lawful union activity because employees are allowed to work together to build a union and workplace surveillance may uncover those activities. She said that she wants the NLRB to force employers to disclose what surveillance they engage in and how the data is used beforehand so employees can then decide whether it interferes with their rights to organize.

如果这些新措施能够实施（如果雇主提起诉讼，可能需要数年时间才能通过司法系统），那么一个全新的透明时代或许能够帮助员工了解自己受到了哪些监控。如果被迫透明化，许多公司可能会避免使用最激进的技术，因为高管们或许明白，了解员工在工作时间和下班后受到的监控程度会让员工感到不安。

If these new steps can be implemented, which would probably take years to wind through the court system if employers sue, a new era of transparency could help employees understand what surveillance they are subjected to. Forced to be transparent, many companies would likely shy away from using the most aggressive technologies because executives probably understand that finding out how much surveillance goes on during and after work hours would upset their employees.

但这可能只是一份备忘录里写的白日梦。

But this might just be a pipe dream written in a memo.

第九章

CHAPTER 9

我们随时准备提供帮助

We’re Ready to Help

关于工作中的健康数据

On Our Health Data at Work

T新冠疫情使心理健康问题成为焦点，尤其是在职场中。“全身心投入工作”之类的流行语，恰恰体现了我们人性中存在的种种弊端。如今，许多公司正在努力帮助员工保持身心健康。

The COVID-19 pandemic brought mental health struggles to the forefront, especially at work. Buzz phrases like “bring your whole self to work” acknowledge all of the human messiness that we bring to the table. And many companies are now trying to help their employees with their physical and mental health.

这正触动着另一股文化力量：提升和优化自我也是时代精神的一部分，引起了许多人的共鸣，尤其是白领人士。我读过很多关于如何提高工作效率和抽出更多时间锻炼的文章。我也认识一些人会追踪自己的睡眠模式和步数。有些人甚至会追踪自己的大脑活动。我们喜欢优化自己，所以这或许就是为什么我们中的许多人都乐于接受雇主在这方面的帮助。

That is hitting another cultural force: improving and optimizing ourselves is also part of the zeitgeist, which resonates with many folks, especially those in white-collar professions. I have read many articles on how I can bolster my productivity and find more time to work out. I also know folks who track their sleep patterns and number of steps. Some even track their brain activity. We love to optimize ourselves, so that’s probably why many of us are open to employers helping us in this endeavor.

但许多人没有意识到的是，帮助我们过上更健康、更高效生活的技术很可能包含内置的监视元素，可能会被用来对付我们。

But what many are not aware of is that the technology being used to help us live healthier and more productive lives in all likelihood includes a built-in surveillance element that could be used against us.

在本章中，我们将重点关注人工智能如何用于我们的身心健康。

In this chapter, we will focus on how AI is used regarding our physical and mental health.

身体健康

PHYSICAL HEALTH

几年前，健康数据技术在职场中的兴起始于健身追踪器，许多人都乐意将它戴在手腕上。许多公司注意到了这一趋势，并开始为员工提供健身、步行会议或步数追踪等报销服务。

The rise of health data technology at work started a few years back with fitness trackers, which many of us willingly put on our wrists. A lot of companies noted this trend and started giving employees reimbursements when they went to the gym, held walking meetings, or tracked their steps.

其基本理念是，健康的公司由健康的员工组成，员工需要自己掌控自己的健康（雇主也需要给予一些鼓励）。此外，雇主还可以节省医疗保险费用。

The underlying idea is that healthy companies are made of healthy employees and employees need to take their health into their own hands (with a little nudge from their employer). There is the added benefit that employers might save money on health insurance premiums.

韦恩·戈诺（Wayne Gono）是一位健身追踪爱好者。他是家族企业Regal Plastics Supply的首席网络官，曾任首席执行官。Regal Plastics Supply位于德克萨斯州，拥有约115名员工。

Wayne Gono is a fitness tracking devotee. He is the chief networking officer and former CEO of his family-owned company, Regal Plastics Supply, in Texas, which has about 115 employees.

几年前，该公司的健康保险供应商联合健康保险 (United Healthcare) 找到了 Regal Plastics，询问他们是否愿意为员工提供健身追踪器。激励措施是，如果员工达到了健身目标，他们可以从健康保险中获得一笔不小的返还。

A few years back, the company’s health insurance supplier, United Healthcare, approached them. Would Regal Plastics want to offer fitness trackers to employees? The incentive was that, if employees met their fitness goals, they could get back modest amounts of money from their health insurance.

Regal Plastics 的领导团队 Wayne Gono 和他的家人毫不犹豫地说道：“我们很喜欢这个想法，因为它能激励员工锻炼身体。” Gono 补充道，他的家人非常关心他们的员工。

Wayne Gono and his family, the leadership team at Regal Plastics, didn’t hesitate: “We like the idea of what it would do as far as challenging our staff to exercise,” Gono said. He added that his family cares deeply about their employees.

在 Regal Plastics，报名是自愿的。大约有五十名员工开始追踪他们的健康状况，其中包括喜欢友好竞争的 Gono。“作为公司里年纪最大的员工，我总是想成为一天中步数最多的人。然后我会向别人挑战：‘克雷格，你知道吗，我的年龄是你的两倍，我每天走一万八千步，而你才勉强走五步。’”

At Regal Plastics, signing up was voluntary. About fifty employees started tracking their fitness, including Gono, who loves friendly competition. “Being the oldest one in the company, I always wanted to be the one that had the most steps in the day. And then I would challenge people: ‘Well, you know what, Craig, I’m twice your age, I am getting eighteen thousand steps a day, you are barely getting in five.’”

有一天，戈诺查看了数据，然后打电话给克里斯·祖布科。祖布科是一名员工，心脏病发作，做了三次搭桥手术，三周后刚刚回来。戈诺祝贺他的进步：“伙计！我注意到你的步数又增加了，”戈诺说。1 “你以前不到2000步，现在超过6000步了。这周你锻炼了两次。太棒了！” 2

One day, Gono checked the stats and called Chris Zubko, an employee who had just returned three weeks after a heart attack and triple bypass surgery. Gono congratulated him on his progress: “Man! I noticed your steps have picked up,” Gono said.1 “You used to be under 2,000, now you’re over 6,000. Two times you worked out this week. Good!”2

克里斯·祖布科很感激老板的鼓励，尽管如果我是他，个人会觉得有点冒犯。但完全透明是Regal Plastics使命的核心：“我们提升公司内部的竞争力，因为我们每个办公室都配备了平板电视，而且遍布整个办公室。他们能实时获得销售数据，以及实时预测。一切都是实时的，”戈诺在接受我的采访时说道。

Chris Zubko appreciated his boss cheering him on, although if I were in his place, it would personally have felt a bit invasive. But total transparency is central to Regal Plastics’ mission: “We drive competitiveness within the company, because we have flat-screen TVs in every one of our offices, and they’re all over our offices. They just got real-time sales numbers. And real-time projections. Everything is real time,” Gono said in an interview with me.

他说，他的员工也很喜欢这种模式，因为领导层不会惩罚排名垫底的人。“我们以人为本，利润至上，”他说。“我们不在意学历，也不看重出身。我们只看他们是否认同我们的价值观。如果他们认同我们的核心价值观，我们就能教他们塑料行业。”

His employees loved it as well, he said, because leadership didn’t penalize people at the bottom of the list. “We are people before profits,” he said. “We’re not worried about degrees. We are not looking at pedigree. All we look at is, do they line up with our values? If they line up with our core values, they can get taught the plastics business.”

在Glassdoor上，该公司有44条评论，平均评分为4.4分（满分5分）。人们称赞该公司的企业文化以及员工之间的良好关系：“再合适不过了！自主性极佳。无与伦比的公司文化。他们给予你成功的自由！”一位匿名评论者写道。3

On Glassdoor, the company has forty-four reviews and an average rating of 4.4 out of 5. People praise the company’s culture and the relationship employees have with their colleagues: “Could Not be better fit! Amazing Autonomy. Unmatched Company Culture. They give you the freedom to succeed!” wrote one anonymous reviewer.3

该公司推出健身追踪服务已有数年。在最近的一次采访中，韦恩·戈诺表示，他仍然很享受每天从健康保险公司获得最高三美元的返还，以达到自己的健身目标。但该公司的健康保险费却只涨不降。

It’s been a few years since the company started fitness tracking. In a recent conversation, Wayne Gono said he still loves getting a maximum of three dollars back per day from his health insurance company for reaching his goals, but the company’s health premiums have only gone up, not down.

一些公司以善意的方式使用这种监控数据，包括 Regal Plastics，但一旦收集到数据，就很容易被滥用：例如，使用员工刷卡数据来寻找“高”绩效员工进行晋升的公司也想使用相同的数据来解雇“低”绩效员工。

Some companies use this kind of surveillance data in benevolent ways, including Regal Plastics, but once the data is collected, it could easily be misused: for example, the company that used employee swipe card data to find “high” performers for promotions also wanted to use the same data to fire “low” performers.

当公司不得不裁员时，一些高管可能会想解雇那些 Fitbit 数据最低的员工，因为他们可能会被视为“懒惰”或“超重”，而且公司还需要支付医疗保险费。就像我说的，数据一旦收集起来，就很难再放回原处，也无法确保它不被滥用。4

When a company has to do layoffs, some executives might want to fire the employees with the lowest Fitbit numbers since they might be perceived as “lazy” or “overweight” and will cost the company money in health insurance premiums. Like I said, once data is collected, it’s hard to put it back in the box and make sure it’s not being misused.4

我收集与健身或身体机能相关的数据来追踪自己的健康状况，与雇主要求我这样做时的感觉完全不同。几年前，《华尔街日报》报道，一家供应商的软件试图根据停止服用避孕药的女性的保险索赔来预测怀孕情况。5这让人感觉很具侵犯性，而且可能会带来意想不到的后果。该软件可能会预测一定比例的女性员工很快就会怀孕，因此，如果经理担心女性员工会休产假，他们可能不会提拔女性员工担任领导职务。

Me collecting data related to my fitness or bodily functions to track my health feels completely different from when my employer wants me to do it. A few years back, the Wall Street Journal reported that one vendor’s software tried to predict pregnancies on the basis of the insurance claims of women who stopped filling birth control prescriptions.5 That feels invasive and could have unintended consequences. The software might predict that a certain percentage of female employees will get pregnant soon, so a manager might not put female employees up for leadership positions if they are worried that the women will go on maternity leave.

许多员工可能不知道，在美国，他们的雇主可以自由出售他们的数据：“通过可穿戴技术作为工作场所绩效计划的一部分收集的所有数据都可以在未经员工知情或同意的情况下出售。”

Many employees may not know that in the United States their employers are free to sell their data: “All the data that’s being collected as part of workplace performance programs through wearable tech,” professor of law Ifeoma Ajunwa said, “can be sold without the knowledge or consent of the worker.”

健身追踪器和其他检查心率等重要统计数据的健康设备也可能会无意中向雇主透露员工有残疾，而根据《美国残疾人法案》，这可能是违法的。

A fitness tracker and other wellness devices that check vital statistics such as heart rate could also inadvertently disclose to an employer that an employee has a disability, which might be illegal under the Americans with Disabilities Act.

对于一些隐私学者来说，执法部门未经法院命令不得搜查我们的电子邮件或健康保险索赔，但在工作场所却不存在此类保护，这是一个巨大的讽刺。

For some privacy scholars, it’s a great irony that law enforcement can’t search our emails or health insurance claims without a court order, but no such protections exist in the workplace.

预测健康

PREDICTING HEALTH

令人惊讶的是，我们中的许多人经常与雇主分享数据，却可以预测我们的行为。

It’s surprising what can be predicted about us from the data many of us share routinely with our employers.

2022 年秋季，在拉斯维加斯举行的全球最大的人力资源技术会议之一上，我偶然发现了一家名为 Alight 的公司，该公司根据基本的就业和福利数据推断员工可能正在经历的事情：例如，员工将配偶从健康保险计划中剔除表明该员工离婚，并且可能需要心理健康服务。

At one of the largest HR tech conferences in the world in Las Vegas in the fall of 2022, I stumbled upon a company called Alight, which draws conclusions about what employees might be going through from basic employment and benefits data: for example, an employee dropping a spouse from their health insurance plan indicates a divorce and possibly a need for mental health services.

Alight 的宣传是，其软件可以个性化福利，帮助员工找到合适的福利，从而提升个人幸福感。这听起来是个很棒的主意。

Alight’s pitch is that its software personalizes benefits and helps employees find the right benefits to improve personal well-being. Sounds like a great idea on paper.

克雷格·罗森伯格是一位五十多岁的白人，担任 Alight 的健康解决方案副总裁。他告诉我，许多公司提供了很多福利，但“人们并不知道。即使他们知道，在需要的时候也记不住，因此很难与他们互动。”

Craig Rosenberg, a white man in his fifties who is the vice president of health solutions at Alight, told me that many companies offer a lot of benefits, but that “people don’t know about them. And even if they do know about them, they don’t remember them when they need them and then it’s hard to engage with them.”

Alight 表示，其个性化工具已被约一千家客户使用，其中包括 70% 的《财富》100 强企业，该工具有助于在正确的时间向员工提供正确的信息。因为当员工正处于危机之中，他们不想去研究并了解公司提供的所有好处。

Alight says that its personalization tool, which is used by around one thousand clients, including 70 percent of the Fortune 100, helps to get the right information to employees at the right time. Because when an employee is in a crisis, they don’t want to do research and wade through all the benefits a company offers.

在演示开始时，罗森伯格向我展示了几个不同的虚构员工以及 Alight Workforce 工具如何帮助他们。

At the beginning of the demo, Rosenberg showed me a few different fictional employees and how the Alight Workforce tool could help them.

他的第一个案例是一位名叫“艾登”的中年男子。Alight 软件“知道”艾登最近离婚了，因为他把配偶从健康保险中取消了。“我们从人力资源系统看到，他已经六个月没有休假了，我们在 401(k) 账户上看到，他在过去一年里借了两笔 401(k) 贷款，”罗森伯格说。“他正在处理一些事情。”

His first example was a middle-aged man named “Aiden.” The Alight software “knew” that Aiden was recently divorced because he’d dropped his spouse from his health insurance. “We see from the HR system that he hasn’t taken any vacation in six months and we see on the 401(k) side that he took two 401(k) loans out in the past year,” Rosenberg said. “There’s something going on here that he is dealing with.”

然后，该工具会为艾登提供个性化建议。“它会优先考虑心理健康。他的情绪健康是我们最想让他参与的事情。其次可能是财务方面——帮他联系一位财务顾问。”

The tool then makes personalized recommendations for Aiden. “It’s going to prioritize mental health. Emotional well-being for him is the top thing we want to engage him on. And then maybe the second priority is financial—connect him to a financial advisor.”

他告诉我这些的时候，我的耳朵嗡嗡响。感觉有点毛骨悚然。如果我的雇主允许第三方公司访问我的个人福利数据，让他们能够预测我生活中诸如离婚之类的私密细节——即使是为了帮助我——我也会觉得很奇怪。

My ears were ringing as he was telling me this. It felt kind of creepy. I would absolutely feel weird if my employer gave a third-party company access to my personal benefits data, which might put them in a position to predict such intimate details about my life as a divorce—even if it’s to help me.

在一次我必须注册才能观看的网络研讨会上，一位 Alight 员工甚至承认了这一点：“我们必须不断在带来价值的个性化与令人毛骨悚然的感觉之间找到平衡，”信息技术副总裁 Kellee Eavenson 说。

In a webinar, which I had to sign up to watch, one Alight employee even acknowledged this: “We have to constantly walk the line between the personalization that will bring that value versus feeling creepy,” said Kellee Eavenson, vice president of information technology.

克雷格·罗森伯格分享的下一个例子也很快变得令人毛骨悚然。“艾伦”是一位虚构的女员工，系统学习到她刚刚做完膝盖手术和核磁共振成像，AI工具预测她即将成为一位新生儿父母。“想象一下，有人刚刚在医疗计划中加入了孩子。这就会触发我们说：‘嘿，这些都是我们可以提供帮助的。’”

The next example that Craig Rosenberg shared also became creepy fast. “Ellen” is a fictional female employee who, the system learned, just had knee surgery and an MRI, and the AI tools predict that she is a new parent. “Think about someone where they just added a baby to their medical plan. Well, that’s a trigger for us to say ‘Hey, here are all the things that we can help with.’”

我相信雇主支付的托儿服务选项会很有帮助。但罗森伯格承诺，该工具还能做更多事情，包括为艾伦推荐最好的医生。

I am sure options for childcare paid for by the employer would be helpful. But the tool can do much more, including suggesting the best doctors for Ellen to see, promised Rosenberg.

但在一场面向人力资源经理的 Alight 网络研讨会上，我了解到的情况略有不同。网络主持人表示，所有医疗建议都针对护理质量和成本进行了优化。罗森伯格在与我演示时表示，Alight 会向员工推荐最合适的医生。但他没有提到成本是推荐标准之一。（Alight 表示，医疗建议首先针对质量进行优化，然后才是成本优化。）

But in an Alight webinar geared toward HR managers, I learned something slightly different. The web presenters said that all the medical recommendations were optimized for care quality and cost. In Rosenberg’s demo with me, he said that Alight suggests the best doctors to employees. He didn’t mention that costs are a criterion in the recommendations. (Alight said that the medical recommendations are optimized first for quality and then for cost.)

Alight 在产品中内置了一个反馈回路，如果员工使用了推荐的医疗服务提供商，软件就会自动更新。“艾伦膝盖有点问题，”罗森伯格说，“我向艾伦推荐了一位医疗服务提供商。我可以判断她是否点击了我们的推广信息。然后，我可以从这位服务提供商那里获取数据，并判断她是否使用了他们的服务？”

Alight built a feedback loop into the product that automatically updates the software if an employee uses the recommended health providers. “Ellen had a knee issue,” Rosenberg said. “I promote [a health care provider] to Ellen. I can tell whether she clicked on our promos or not. And then I can get data back from [the provider] and say, did she use [them] or not?”

我问罗森伯格，Alight 是从哪里得到艾伦做过膝盖手术和核磁共振成像的信息的。Alight 怎么会知道这么具体的医疗数据？这些数据是直接从她的医疗保险中提取的吗？“我们可以提取健康理赔数据；我们可以提取财富数据；我们可以提取人力资源系统的数据，”他说道。此外，该公司还从他们的平台上提取搜索数据。

I asked Rosenberg where Alight got the information that Ellen had knee surgery and an MRI. How could Alight know such specific medical data? Was this pulled directly from her health insurance? “We can pull in health claims data; we can pull in wealth data; we can pull in data from the HR system,” he said. Plus the company pulls in search data from their platform.

演示结束后，我再次联系他，并具体询问 Alight 是否可以访问员工的医疗记录：“我们从健康保险公司、公共和商业来源获取健康和提供者数据，并通过专有算法运行。”

After the demo, I reached out to him again and asked specifically whether Alight has access to employees’ medical records: “We obtain health and provider data from a combination of health insurance carriers, public and commercial sources, and run it through proprietary algorithms.”

不知何故，医疗保险数据正在公司之间交易。我想知道，如果该工具“得知”一名员工有性传播疾病？或者有人堕过胎？这个工具会给出什么建议？

Somehow health insurance data is being traded among companies. I wonder what might happen if the tool “learns” that an employee has a sexually transmitted disease? Or someone had an abortion? What would the tool suggest?

我们与医疗服务提供者分享一些最私密的健康信息。事实上，1996 年的《健康保险流通与责任法案》（HIPAA）是一项联邦法律，旨在保护患者的敏感健康信息，防止其在未经患者同意或知情的情况下被泄露。我一直以为这意味着我的健康数据将保持私密，但我想我错了。

We share some of our most intimate health details with our providers. In fact, the Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act of 1996 (HIPAA) is a federal law that protects sensitive patient health information from being disclosed without the patient’s consent or knowledge. I have always assumed this meant that my health data would stay private, but I guess I was wrong.

我对隐私的期望在美国并非现实。雇主可以共享数据，而且显然存在着完整的数据湖。“我们拥有一个专有数据集，其中包含一亿美国人的数据，超过330亿个数据点，”罗森伯格说。该公司还与大约3600万人“互动”，而Alight正是直接服务于这些人。这些互动每年会产生数亿个数据点。

My expectation of privacy is not the reality in the United States. Employers can share data, and apparently there are whole data lakes out there. “We have a proprietary data set that has data on a hundred million Americans, over thirty-three billion data points,” Rosenberg said. The company also “interacts” with about thirty-six million people, which Alight caters to directly. These interactions generate hundreds of millions of more data points per year.

罗森伯格坚称，访问所有这些数据并不成问题，因为 Alight 不会透露其活动所针对员工的姓名：“我们确实保护隐私。你作为人力资源人员，永远不可能知道艾伦有什么问题，”罗森伯格说。“所以，你会知道我们接触了 50 名患有肌肉骨骼问题的员工，以及他们是否使用了（特定医疗服务提供者的）帮助，但显然你无法知道‘艾伦’是否做过核磁共振成像。”

Rosenberg insisted that having access to all this data was not a problem because Alight wouldn’t disclose the names of employees targeted by Alight’s campaigns: “We do protect privacy. You, as an HR person, would never be able to see that Ellen has an issue,” Rosenberg said. “So you would know that we have engaged fifty people who have musculoskeletal issues and they used [a specific provider] to help or not, but obviously you wouldn’t be able to see that ‘Ellen’ had an MRI.”

但 Alight 的安全漏洞可能会发生，而且我们从其他研究中得知，即使是匿名数据也可能轻易被去匿名化。

But security breaches at Alight could happen, and we know from other research that even anonymized data can easily be de-anonymized.

在供应商和雇主之间共享数据方面，缺乏伦理考量。我相信，对一些人力资源经理来说，其中一些产品似乎是必需品。他们没有考虑所有这些数据可能意味着什么，以及这些数据公开后可能带来的后果。（Alight 表示，客户可以决定公司希望为其员工提供何种程度的个性化服务。

There is a lack of ethical considerations in regard to data sharing among vendors and employers. To some HR managers, I am sure some of these products seem like must-haves. They don’t think about what all that data might mean and the downstream consequences of having all this data out there. (Alight said that clients can determine which level of personalization the companies would like for their employees.)

当我问罗森伯格，是否有员工对 Alight 的服务感到毛骨悚然时，他说大多数人永远不会发现 Alight 掌握了他们多少信息，因为该软件的信息传递非常隐蔽。“你可以把它们想象成提醒。你永远不会看到这样的话：‘嘿，我看到你离婚了，我们可以帮你解决心理健康问题。’你可能会看到这样的信息：‘哇，有时候生活很艰难，我们可以帮忙。’”

When I asked Rosenberg if some employees were creeped out by Alight’s services, he said that most would never find out how much information Alight has on them because the software’s messaging is subtle. “Think of these as nudges. You’ll never see something like, ‘Hey, I saw you got divorced and we can help you with mental health issues.’ You might see a message of, ‘Wow, sometimes life is hard, we can help.’”

罗森伯格代表员工表示，这些推荐的便利性胜过了隐私问题。他还补充说，人们已经习惯了Netflix、Hulu和Spotify等推荐系统。

The convenience of these recommendations trumps privacy concerns, Rosenberg said, speaking for employees. He added that folks are already used to recommendation systems like Netflix, Hulu, and Spotify.

（我并不确信 Netflix 的模式对我来说真的有效。但那只是关于电视节目的消费——风险很低，而且数据是关于我看电视的情况，而不是我是否患有慢性病。）

(I am not convinced Netflix’s model works all that well for me. But that is about the consumption of TV shows—the stakes are very low and that data is about me watching TV, not if I have a chronic illness.)

Alight 用于这些推荐的是我的个人数据。我不希望这些数据被交易、出售或被第三方供应商使用，以至于任何人都可以拼凑出我的医疗和心理健康问题。我希望相信我的雇主和与我雇主签约的医疗保健公司不会与任何可能将其出售给 Alight 和其他公司的第三方供应商共享这些私人健康数据。我们已经看到太多数据和安全漏洞。同样令人愤怒的是，无论我多么努力地保护我的在线信息，我工作的公司或我的医疗保健提供者都可能将这些私密数据与 Alight 这样的第三方供应商共享。

What Alight uses for these recommendations is my personal data. I wouldn’t want that data to be traded, sold, or used by third-party vendors so that just anyone can piece together my medical and mental health challenges. I want to trust my employer and the healthcare company my employer has contracted with to not share this private health data with any third-party vendor that might sell it to Alight and other companies. We have seen too many data and security breaches. It’s also infuriating that, no matter how hard I try to safeguard my information online, the company I work for or my health care provider might just share this intimate data with third-party vendors like Alight.

事实上，多起针对 Alight 的网络安全漏洞诉讼仍在审理中，美国劳工部也已展开调查。（Alight 表示，其“坚定致力于为客户提供所需的信心，确保其员工的资产和信息受到保护”，并且“对于一个组织来说，这很常见”。Alight 的规模和复杂性足以管理一系列索赔和诉讼。”)

In fact, a number of lawsuits against Alight alleging cybersecurity breaches are pending and the Department of Labor has opened an investigation. (Alight said it is “steadfastly committed to providing our clients with the confidence they need to ensure their employee’s assets and information are protected,” and that it is “typical for an organization of the size and complexity of Alight to manage a range of claims and litigation.”)

该公司继续推销其服务，称其正在改变员工对雇主的看法：“这不仅仅是‘我通过他们获得医疗保险或人寿保险’。而是‘这个雇主真的在支持我’，”罗森伯格说。

The company continues to pitch its services, saying it is changing how employees see their employers: “It’s not just, ‘I have my medical insurance through them or life insurance.’ It’s like, ‘This employer is really supporting me,’” Rosenberg said.

Alight 决心利用这些数据更早地预测医疗问题：“我们将继续大力拓展分析领域，”罗森伯格说道。“在索赔中发现问题之前，我们就能预测哪些人有肌肉骨骼[问题]的风险？或者，在心理健康风险出现之前，哪些事件可能发生在一个人身上？所以我们可能会说，‘嘿，我们观察了十万个像你这样的人，发现这是一种模式。这意味着你可能有风险。’”

Alight is determined to do more with the data to predict medical issues earlier: “We’re going to be continuing to push really hard into the analytics space,” Rosenberg said. “Who’s at risk of musculoskeletal [problems] before we even see it in a claim? Or what events could happen to someone that is a mental health risk before it even happens? So we might say something like, ‘Hey, we looked at a hundred thousand people like you and this is a pattern. This means that you might be at risk.’”

但公司的健康计划很容易出问题，一些员工可能会认为公司只是敷衍了事，因为他们没有解决公司内部可能导致员工问题的更广泛的、潜在的问题。行业分析师乔希·伯辛表示：“如果你不把公司管理得健康，那么你不可能通过为员工开设瑜伽课来扭转这种局面。”

But company wellness programs could easily fall short and some employees might think that their company is just putting lipstick on a pig, since they are not tackling broader, underlying problems at companies that may contribute to employees’ problems. “If you are not managing the company to be healthy, you’re not going to be able to undo that by giving people a yoga class,” Josh Bersin, the industry analyst, said.

一家公司竟然关心员工的心理健康，这简直令人难以置信，毕竟它自己才是造成问题的关键，比如不处理不称职的经理或有害的工作环境。乔希·伯辛说，超过40%的美国工人害怕上班。

It’s just not believable that a company cares about its employees’ mental health when it creates the problem in the first place, for example, by not dealing with incompetent managers or a toxic work environment. Over 40 percent of American workers are afraid to go to work, said Josh Bersin.

数据分析、个性化和监控软件可以检查员工的健康问题以及他们是否正在使用推荐的服务，这感觉就像工作家长式作风：雇主确保员工健康高效，但却是以一种新的、极具侵略性的方式。

Data analysis, personalization, and surveillance software that checks for employee health issues and whether they are using the recommended services feels like work paternalism: an employer making sure their employees are healthy and productive, but in a new and very invasive way.

在某种程度上，雇主一直试图控制员工：工业革命后，一些雇主建造了工厂城镇，以便监督员工的实际行踪。一些雇主要求员工去教堂，过着“道德生活”。还有一些工厂城镇设立了私立学校，教育孩子们持有有利于工厂主的观点。

To a certain degree, employers have always tried to control their employees: After the Industrial Revolution, some employers built factory towns so they had oversight over their employees’ physical whereabouts. Some required their employees to go to church and live a “moral life.” Other factory towns had private schools that educated children to have viewpoints favorable to the factory owners.

在这些城镇，慷慨的慈善行为和依赖一家公司作为救星的现象十分常见。雇主可能会向城镇捐赠图书馆、溜冰场或住房，以赢得居民的支持。19世纪末，人们对所谓的“强盗资本家”的普遍批评是，他们想用捐赠来换取民众的赞赏，并建造他们认为重要的东西。如果他们想改善生活，本可以给员工更高的工资，但他们选择不这么做。

Generous philanthropy and dependency on one company as a savior was common in those towns. The employer might have donated a library, an ice rink, or housing to the town in order to win favor with residents. A common critique of the so-called robber barons at the end of the nineteenth century was that, with their donations, they wanted to buy people’s appreciation and build what they deemed important. If they wanted to improve lives, they could have paid their employees more, but chose not to.

或许有点夸张，但感觉如今的公司也在做类似的事情。疫情爆发前，Meta 和其他大型科技公司基本上在园区里建起了新的企业城：为员工提供免费的理发、健身房、按摩、干洗、餐饮和理疗服务。就像几个世纪前工业化的工厂城一样，一切都集中在一个地方。

Maybe it’s a stretch, but it feels like companies today are doing similar things. Before the pandemic, Meta and other large tech companies basically built new company towns on their campuses: giving employees free access to hair stylists, gyms, massages, dry cleaners, food, and therapists. Like the industrial factory towns from earlier centuries, everything is in one place.

如今许多人居家办公，这些福利就没那么重要了。但财务和健康方面的福利可以通过个性化平台提供，还能确保员工在生活中做出雇主期望的“正确”选择。

Now that many people are working from home, these perks are less meaningful. But financial and health perks and benefits can be delivered through personalization platforms and they can also make sure employees are making the “right” choices in life that employers want them to make.

提供心理健康帮助

OFFERING MENTAL HEALTH HELP

包括谷歌在内的一些公司会直接向员工提供心理健康服务（除了医疗保险福利之外），员工可以立即获得帮助，无需支付共付额和其他保险费用。但这适得其反，并造成了谷歌前员工切尔西·格拉森（Chelsey Glasson）表示，她对此很感兴趣。她曾担任用户研究员，目睹了谷歌对她主管的一名孕妇的歧视行为。根据公司规定，她向人力资源部举报了这些指控。格拉森表示，报复行为始于她投诉之后，直到她怀孕后仍在继续。她向人力资源部表达了自己的担忧，人力资源部建议她咨询谷歌聘请的第三方咨询师。

Some companies, including Google, offer mental health services to employees directly (in addition to health insurance benefits), and employees can get help right away and do not have to pay co-pays and other insurance fees. But this has backfired and created conflicts of interest, said former Google employee Chelsey Glasson. She used to work as a user researcher and witnessed discriminatory behavior against a pregnant person who she was supervising at Google. According to company policy, she reported the allegations to HR. Glasson said that the retaliation started after she made the complaint and continued when she herself got pregnant. She brought her concerns to HR and they suggested she speak to a third-party counselor paid for by Google.

“这真是个好资源，我当然要好好利用，”格拉森对《纽约时报》说。 “我当时真心庆幸，至少有一位EAP（员工援助计划）的顾问，我可以畅所欲言。”

“What a great resource, of course I’m going to take advantage of this,” Glasson said to the New York Times. “I was naively grateful that the EAP [Employee Assistance Program] counselor was at least one person I could talk to freely.”

一年后，格拉森对谷歌提起诉讼。她的治疗师告诉她，在法律团队要求提供两人会面的记录后，她与格拉森见面时“非常紧张和不自在”。此后，她的治疗师再也没有联系过她，格拉森感到自己被抛弃了。“我相信她担心与我合作会损害她与谷歌的关系，”格拉森写道。6她认为，当雇主直接支付服务费用时，这些心理健康咨询服务的核心存在利益冲突。

When Glasson filed a lawsuit against Google a year later, her therapist told her that she was “really nervous and uncomfortable” meeting with Glasson after her legal team asked for the records of their sessions together. Her therapist hadn’t been in touch with her since, and Glasson felt abandoned. “I believe she was worried that affiliating with me would compromise her relationship with Google,” Glasson wrote.6 She believes there is a conflict of interest at the heart of these mental health counseling services when employers directly pay for the services.

根据她的经验，她主张制定新的法律，并在公司建议员工通过员工援助计划 (EAP) 寻求咨询时强制透明：“除非立法通过，对 EAP 进行监管和监督，并且相关政府机构调查谷歌等公司如何使用 EAP，以及它们是否会对工作场所不当行为的受害者造成进一步伤害，否则这些事情都不可能发生。” 她还担心，许多人力资源经理可能会建议投诉歧视的员工参加咨询会议，这可能会传达出这样的信息：问题出在员工身上，而没有人关注更广泛的系统性问题。

Based on her experience, she is advocating for new laws and mandatory transparency when companies suggest employees see counselors through their employee assistance programs (EAPs): “None of these things will likely happen until legislation is passed to regulate and monitor EAPs, and the appropriate government agencies investigate how companies like Google use EAPs, and whether they cause further harm to victims of workplace misconduct.” She is also worried that many HR managers might suggest counseling sessions to employees who complain about discrimination, which can send the message that the employee is the problem, and that no one is taking a look at the wider systemic problem.

格拉森去年与谷歌达成和解。她的经历或许能为使用这些服务的员工敲响警钟。

Glasson settled her lawsuit with Google last year. Her experience may be a cautionary tale for employees using these services.

与此同时，雇主们也开始质疑员工健康计划的实际作用：“这需要投入巨资，首席执行官们也知道必须解决这个问题，”全球保险公司安盛（AXA）亚洲和非洲区首席执行官戈登·沃森（Gordon Watson）表示。“但这就像一条滑溜溜的鱼，我们抓不住。市面上有冥想应用程序和改善睡眠的应用程序，但却没有真正的整合方法。我们做得好吗？我们不知道。我们如何衡量进展？如何与竞争对手进行比较？所以我们萌生了让这些变得看得见、摸得着的想法。” 7

At the same time, employers are also starting to question how helpful employee health programs really are: “This costs a massive amount, and CEOs know this needs to be tackled,” said Gordon Watson, the CEO of Asia and Africa for the global insurance company AXA. “But it’s like a slippery fish that we can’t get our hands around. You have meditation apps and apps to sleep better, but no real integrated approach. Are we doing well? We don’t know. How do we measure progress? How are we compared to our competitors? So we had the idea to make that visible and tangible.”7

包括美国银行和安盛保险在内的大型雇主已成立非营利组织“OneMind at Work”，旨在评估组织心理健康项目的有效性。这些项目的数据共享和伦理考量不在该非营利组织的议程上。8

Large employers, including Bank of America and AXA, have formed the nonprofit OneMind at Work that will score the effectiveness of an organization’s mental health programs. Data sharing and ethical considerations around these programs are not on the nonprofit’s agenda.8

以安全为名的监控

SURVEILLANCE IN THE NAME OF SAFETY

安全预防是健康监测蓬勃发展的一个争议较少的领域。

A less contested area in which health surveillance is thriving is safety precautions.

一些组织甚至比 Alight 走得更远：一些公司不再像 Fitbits 和步行会议那样提供个性化福利和追踪我们的运动，而是直接从源头追踪我们的大脑。

Some organizations go even further than Alight: instead of personalizing benefits and tracking our movements à la Fitbits and walking meetings, some companies are now going directly to the source—tracking our brains.

在教育、工作和医疗保健领域，人们正在进行一项深入研究的运动，在我们自己意识到之前，了解是什么在推动着我们、驱使我们前进。

In education, at work, and in health care, there is a movement to get under the hood, to know what moves us and drives us before we ourselves might be aware of it.

一个重要的推动力是追踪大脑以确保安全。例如，澳大利亚的SmartCap公司制造了一种帽子，可以通过脑电图（通常称为EEG）记录大脑活动。该公司表示，这款工具可以追踪卡车司机的警觉性和疲劳程度。当帽子检测到疲劳时，它会发送一个向驾驶员发出视觉和音频信号，防止他们在驾驶时睡着。该公司还宣传了这款适用于矿工的帽子。每个工人的脑电波都存储在云端，SmartCap 声称这可以让使用该工具的公司更容易地进行合规和审计。

One big push is tracking brains for safety. For example, SmartCap in Australia built a cap that records brain activity via electroencephalogram (commonly called EEG). The company says its tool can track truck drivers’ alertness and fatigue. When the cap detects fatigue, it sends a visual and audio signal to the driver to prevent them from falling asleep at the wheel. The company also advertises the cap for miners. Every worker’s brain waves are stored in the cloud, which SmartCap claims makes compliance and auditing easier for the company using the tool.

据《南华早报》报道，在中国，脑电波检测工具已应用于工厂和交通运输领域：“这些轻巧的无线传感器隐藏在普通安全帽或制服帽中，持续监测佩戴者的脑电波，并将数据传输到使用人工智能算法检测抑郁、焦虑或愤怒等情绪波动的计算机。这项技术在世界各地广泛应用，但中国在工厂、公共交通、国有企业和军队中应用的规模空前，旨在提升制造业的竞争力并维护社会稳定。” 9

In China, brain wave detection tools are used in factories and in transportation, reports the South China Morning Post: “Concealed in regular safety helmets or uniform hats, these lightweight, wireless sensors constantly monitor the wearer’s brainwaves and stream the data to computers that use artificial intelligence algorithms to detect emotional spikes such as depression, anxiety or rage. The technology is in widespread use around the world, but China has applied it on an unprecedented scale in factories, public transport, state-owned companies and the military to increase the competitiveness of its manufacturing industry and to maintain social stability.”9

据《华尔街日报》的一段视频报道，中国也正在为学生佩戴脑电波感应头带，以测试他们在上课时的注意力水平。这些数据和排名会与老师、家长以及研究头带的科学家分享。10

Also in China, brain wave–sensing headbands are being used on schoolchildren to check their attention levels during instruction time, according to a video report in the Wall Street Journal. The data and a ranking of the kids are then shared with teachers, parents, and the scientists studying the headbands.10

在美国和欧洲，基于脑电图的头带作为一种消费技术，直接面向那些希望在冥想和睡眠期间追踪和优化大脑功能的用户。一些头带制造商还宣传他们的技术可以增强佩戴者的注意力和心理韧性。

In the United States and Europe, EEG-based headbands as a consumer technology are marketed directly to users who want to track and optimize their brain function during meditation and sleep. Some headband makers also advertise that their technology can strengthen the wearer’s focus and mental resilience.

供应商也在打造耳机，例如一款名为 MN8 的耳机，它具备脑电图功能，可供企业员工使用：“传感器可以检测大脑不同区域的电活动，这些活动的模式可以与不同的感觉或生理反应（例如压力、专注力或对外部刺激的反应）广泛关联。这些数据可以用来提高员工的效率，并且，IEEE（电气和电子工程师协会）报告称，“这项技术的支持者认为，这能让他们更快乐。当公司使用 MN8 系统时，员工可以深入了解他们个人的专注度和压力水平，而管理人员则可以获得有关其团队的汇总匿名数据。” 11

Vendors are also building headphones, such as one called MN8, with EEG capabilities for companies to use on their workers: “Sensors detect electrical activity across different areas of the brain, and the patterns in that activity can be broadly correlated with different feelings or physiological responses, such as stress, focus, or a reaction to external stimuli. These data can be exploited to make workers more efficient—and, proponents of the technology say, to make them happier,” the IEEE (Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers) reported. “When a company uses the MN8 system, workers get insight into their individual levels of focus and stress, and managers get aggregated and anonymous data about their teams.”11

有了这些新技术，我相信我们的大脑数据将被存储，并被开发人员用来训练新的模型，甚至可能以其他方式使用。这项技术目前正在使用，尽管几乎没有证据表明这些产品确实有效。

With all of this new technology, I’m sure our brain data will be stored and used by developers to train new models and it may also be used in other ways. This technology is in use now, although there is scant evidence the products actually work.

通过我们的声音检测心理健康问题

DETECTING MENTAL HEALTH PROBLEMS IN OUR VOICES

另一种改善心理健康、深入了解大脑内部活动的方法是一项新兴技术，它几乎可以应用于任何地方，包括大学和工作场所。这项技术被称为声音生物标记。事实上，它已经在美国至少一所大学投入使用，任何拥有智能手机的人都可以使用它。

Another way to try to improve our mental health and find out more about what is happening inside our brains is an emerging technology that could be applied almost everywhere, including in colleges and in the workplace, called vocal biomarkers. In fact, it was already used in at least one college in the United States and is accessible to anyone with a smartphone.

声音生物标记工具基于这样一种理念：人工智能可以从我们的声音中发现心理健康问题的信号。例如，无需精神科医生诊断某人是否患有躁郁症、抑郁症或焦虑症，人工智能应用程序只需分析该人的一部分声音即可完成诊断。

Vocal biomarker tools are based on the idea that AI can find signals of mental health problems in our voices. For example, instead of a psychiatrist diagnosing whether someone is bipolar, depressed, or anxious, an AI app can do it just by analyzing a snippet of that person’s voice.

这项技术主要不分析患者的言语，而是通过分析声音中潜在的生物成分，来判断一个人是否焦虑或抑郁。由于我们每天都在使用声音，这项技术的应用范围非常广泛：它可以用于分析Zoom会议、电话会议，甚至与Alexa等智能音箱的交流。

The technology mostly doesn’t analyze the words patients say, but the underlying biological components of the voice tell an algorithm if someone is anxious or depressed. And because we use our voices every day, this technology has potentially wide applications: it could be used to analyze participants in Zoom meetings, on phone calls, or even in communication with smart speakers like Alexa.

这项技术的发明者表示，如果成功，它将减轻许多痛苦：“在美国，五分之一的人患有抑郁症、焦虑症，甚至药物滥用障碍，而全球许多国家的比例甚至更高。” 总部位于波士顿的声音生物标记初创公司 Sonde Health 的首席执行官 David Liu 表示。“在某些情况下，青少年群体中，这一比例甚至上升到 33% 甚至更高。我们非常关注这个问题，因为每个人都在应对它。” 即使在发达国家，心理健康服务提供者的数量也不足以满足需求。

If the technology works, its inventors say, it could alleviate a lot of suffering: “One out of five people in this country [the US], and in many countries around the world that ratio is even higher, suffer from symptoms of depression, anxiety, or even substance abuse disorder,” said David Liu, CEO of Sonde Health, a vocal biomarker start-up based in Boston. “Those numbers have gone up in some cases to 33 percent or even higher in our adolescent population. It’s an issue that we feel very passionate about because everyone is dealing with it.” Even in developed countries, there aren’t enough mental health providers to meet the need.

刘大卫将心理健康状况不佳描述为“无声杀手”。患有心理健康问题的人可能不会出现直接的身体症状，但抑郁症和其他精神疾病的影响可能是灾难性的。

David Liu described poor mental health as a silent killer. Someone who’s suffering from mental health issues may not be having direct physical symptoms, but the effects of depression and other mental illnesses can be catastrophic.

疫情期间，心理健康问题成为焦点，尤其是在高校和职场。当时，一家名为Ellipsis Health的生物标记初创公司与门洛学院接洽，提出在学生身上测试这项技术的想法。门洛学院是一所小型私立学校，位于加利福尼亚州阿瑟顿，该镇是美国人均收入最高的城市之一。

During the pandemic, mental health struggles came to the forefront, especially at colleges and universities but also in the workplace.
