At that time, a vocal biomarker start-up called Ellipsis Health approached Menlo College with the idea to test this kind of technology on the students. Menlo College is a small, private school based in Atherton, California, a town with one of the highest per capita incomes in the United States.

工商管理专业的学生 Lina Lakoczky-Torres 当时是学生会的健康代表，并被邀请参与管理人员与 Ellipsis Health 的对话，讨论合作和推广事宜。

Lina Lakoczky-Torres, a business management major, was the wellness representative of the student government at the time and was brought into the conversations that administrators had with Ellipsis Health to discuss the collaboration and rollout.

拉科斯基-托雷斯说，即使在疫情爆发之前，硅谷和门洛学院也并非易事。“这真的让人不知所措，刚从高中毕业，就想着，‘好吧，现在我们处在一个21岁的年轻人创立独角兽企业的境地。你该怎么办？’ 感觉就像，我只是想弄清楚如何以我自己的身份生存下去。”

Even before the pandemic, Silicon Valley and Menlo College were not easy places to be, Lakoczky-Torres said. “It is really overwhelming, fresh out of high school, going, ‘Okay, now we’re in a situation where twenty-one-year-olds have built unicorns. What are you going to do?’ And it’s like, I’m just trying to figure out how to exist as my own person.”

作为健康代表，她最初希望帮助学生在门洛学院找到面对面的治疗师，并在校园内建立一个食品储藏室，但疫情爆发之初，所有人都被遣返回国。拉科茨基-托雷斯回到拉斯维加斯与母亲同住。

As the wellness representative, she initially hoped to help students find in-person therapists at Menlo and to build an on-campus food pantry, but at the beginning of the pandemic, everyone was sent home. Lakoczky-Torres went back to live with her mother in Las Vegas.

“一切都是线上的。你如何帮助线上的所有人？”拉科斯基-托雷斯问道。她需要改变目标，并希望确保学生们能够获得线上帮助。除此之外，她还面临着与家人一起生活的压力。“很多事情接踵而至。你和家人在一起。家庭问题。你无法逃避。你沉浸在自己的思绪中，却没有意识到自己有多么怀念社交互动，”她说。

“It was all online. How do you help everybody online?” Lakoczky-Torres asked. She needed to change goals and wanted to make sure that students could access virtual help. On top of that, she was struggling living back home with her family. “A lot of things come up. You’re with your family. Family issues. You can’t get away from it. You’re with your mind, you don’t realize how much you miss your social interactions,” she said.

许多人都需要心理治疗。此外，疫情还带来了一些独特的挑战：在疫情爆发前，Lakoczky-Torres 曾通过门洛学院的一个免费项目与一位正在接受培训的研究生治疗师合作过，但搬出加州意味着她与治疗师的联系被切断，因为他们只能在加州工作。“我当时心烦意乱。说实话，我感觉就像和我的治疗师分手了，”她说。“这种感觉真的很突然，尤其是在你最需要的时候。”

Therapy was needed by many people. Additionally, the pandemic brought unique challenges: Lakoczky-Torres had worked with a graduate student therapist in training via a free program at Menlo College before the pandemic started, but relocating out of state meant cutting the cord with her therapist because they were only allowed to work in California. “I was distraught. I’ll be honest. I felt like I was breaking up with my therapist,” she said. “It felt really abrupt, especially in the time that you need it the most.”

负责学生成功和战略规划的副校长安吉拉·施米德 (Angela Schmiede) 表示，拉科斯基-托雷斯并非唯一一个陷入困境的学生。与拉科斯基-托雷斯一样，门洛学院大约一半的学生并非来自加州，在心理健康服务需求比以往任何时候都更大的时候，他们却突然无法获得学院提供的心理健康服务：“我们确实看到心理健康需求有所增加，我认为这不仅仅是门洛学院的情况，全国各地的高校都存在这种情况，”施米德说道。

Lakoczky-Torres wasn’t the only student who was struggling, said the vice president for student success and strategic planning, Angela Schmiede. Just like Lakoczky-Torres, about half of the student body of Menlo College is not from California and all of a sudden couldn’t access the college’s mental health services when the need was greater than ever: “We did see an increase in mental health needs, and I think that’s not true just at Menlo College but at colleges and universities around the country,” Schmiede said.

大约在这个时候，Ellipsis Health 联系了门洛学院。该公司向该学院推销了一款人工智能工具，声称该工具可以评估学生不同程度的焦虑和抑郁，并帮助他们管理情绪。门洛学院无需为学生使用该应用支付一分钱。

At around this time, Ellipsis Health approached Menlo. The company pitched the college an AI tool that it said could assess different levels of anxi­ety and depression in students and prompt them to manage their feelings. Menlo College wouldn’t have to pay a penny for students to use the app.

对于安吉拉·施米德来说，Ellipsis软件是另一个帮助学生的工具。“如果说过去两年我对学生及其心理健康有什么了解的话，那就是没有一个放之四海而皆准的解决方案，”她说。“你可以提供面对面的咨询，但有些学生就是不会利用。但如果你能提供一种让学生自主访问、实时参与且没有任何障碍的方案，那么有些学生就会愿意接受。”

For Angela Schmiede, the Ellipsis software was another tool to help students. “If I’ve learned anything about students and their mental health over the last two years, it’s that there’s not a one-size-fits-all solution,” she said. “You can offer face-to-face counseling and some students just won’t take advantage of that. But if you can offer something where students are accessing it on their own and they can do it in real time and there’s not a barrier associated with it, then some students will access that.”

该工具于2020年末向门洛学院约800名学生推出。选择使用该应用程序的学生被要求每天留下至少30秒的语音留言，回答各种问题。Ellipsis还使用了临床常用的标准化抑郁和焦虑问卷。

The tool was rolled out to the roughly eight hundred students at Menlo College in late 2020. Students who chose to use the app were asked to leave daily voice messages that were at least thirty seconds long in which they answered various questions. Ellipsis also utilized standardized depression and anxiety questionnaires that are used regularly in clinical settings.

Lina Lakoczky-Torres 使用这个工具回答了诸如“‘家里一切都好吗？’”之类的问题。然后我会花 30 到 45 秒的时间说：“嘿，你知道，最近情况很艰难。我压力很大。我感觉不知所措，感觉快要窒息了，”等等。然后它会切换到提示我，“你最近感觉怎么样，或者学校怎么样？”她说。

Lina Lakoczky-Torres used the tool and answered questions such as: “‘How’s everything going at home?’ And then I go for thirty to forty-five seconds: ‘Hey, you know, things have been tough. I’m really stressed out. I’m feeling overwhelmed, I’m feeling like I’m being smothered,’ etcetera. And then it would switch over to prompt me, ‘How are you feeling lately or how is school going?’” she said.

“Ellipsis Health 所做的，”该公司首席执行官 Mainul Mondal 说道，“就是我们创造了声音生物标记，以便能够了解不同严重程度的压力、焦虑和抑郁，从而帮助医疗服务提供者和患者拥有更健康的生活。” 他说，口语为我们打开了一扇了解心灵的窗户。

“What Ellipsis Health has done,” said Mainul Mondal, the CEO of the company, “is we’ve created vocal biomarkers to be able to understand stress, anxiety, depression at different severity levels so we can help providers and patients to have healthier lives.” Spoken language provides that window into the mind, he said.

Sonde Health 首席执行官 David Liu 表示：“我们所做的就是分析人类的声音，并从分析中得出健康见解。”

“What we do is we analyze human voices and deliver health insights from that analysis,” said David Liu, CEO of Sonde Health.

这个想法是，人工智能可以从我们的声音中发现隐藏的抑郁和焦虑信息，甚至还能判断我们是否患有帕金森症或其他疾病。其基本原理是，我们的声音与大脑直接相连，因此，通过声音生物标记，我们可以记录声音并逆向分析大脑中发生的事情。

The idea is that AI can find hidden information on depression and anxiety in our voice, and also if we suffer from Parkinson’s or other diseases. The basic claim is that our voice is directly connected to the brain, and so with vocal biomarkers we can record the voice and reverse engineer what’s going on in the brain.

这是一项大胆的尝试，因为生物标志物通常是客观的医学体征，存在于血液、唾液、尿液或医学影像中，可以指示某种疾病或健康状况。例如，血液中铅含量高可能表明肾脏或大脑受损。特定细胞的成像可以提示某人患有癌症。“声音生物标志物”技术仍处于起步阶段。

This is a bold endeavor, because biomarkers are usually objective medical signs, something in our blood, spit, urine, or medical imaging that indicates a disease or medical condition. For example, high lead levels in blood can indicate kidney or brain damage. Or imaging of specific cells can suggest that someone has cancer. “Vocal biomarker” technology is still in its infancy.

该领域的公司表示，通过分析语音记录，他们可以客观地监测患者，例如，判断患者是否正在陷入抑郁或焦虑。他们还表示，他们的工具最终将能够诊断精神疾病，并指导人们自助，这可能会带来巨大的帮助，因为目前没有足够的心理健康服务提供者来照顾所有遭受痛苦的人们。

Companies in the space say that, through analyzing voice recordings, they can objectively monitor patients, for example, if someone is sliding into depression or anxiety. They also say that their tools will eventually be able to diagnose mental illnesses and coach people to help themselves, which could be immensely helpful because there aren’t enough mental health providers for all the people suffering.

“我们正在尝试寻找一种相当于血压和心率监测器的仪器，用于精神病学。”梅努尔·蒙达尔说道。

“We are trying to find an equivalent of a blood pressure and heart rate monitor, the same kind of thing for psychiatry,” Mainul Mondal said.

这项技术在智能手机上易于访问，可以帮助解决传统医生诊断过程中出现的诸多问题。医护人员可能会做出错误的诊断，而人工智能大概不会。又或者，抑郁症患者可能没有意识到自己的病情，或者因为羞耻感而不愿寻求帮助，导致无法得到诊断和治疗。而有了应用程序，尤其是在后台运行人工智能工具的情况下，他们就可以开始评估和自我帮助。这类人工智能工具还可以为全球许多无力支付心理健康咨询费用的用户提供诊断和治疗。

A technology like this, easily accessible on smartphones, could help solve several problems that occur in the traditional process of a doctor diagnosing a patient. A care provider might get the diagnosis wrong; presumably, the AI would not. Or folks who are depressed may not be aware of it or don’t want to seek help because of shame, so they don’t get diagnosed and treated, whereas with an app, especially with an AI tool running in the background, they could begin to assess and help themselves. These kinds of AI tools could also open diagnosis and treatments to many users around the world who don’t have the means to pay for mental health consultations.

但由于该软件使用起来非常方便，它可能会未经个人许可就被使用，从而暴露出他们可能想要隐藏的心理健康问题。它也可能在工作场所被使用和滥用。例如，声音生物标记工具可以用于会议录音，并且无需员工同意，公司就能发现焦虑或抑郁的员工。他们可以及早干预，以便员工获得帮助并保持高效工作（这符合公司的利益）。或者，他们也可以解雇被认定为焦虑或抑郁的员工——所有这些都基于声音生物标记的评估，而这些评估尚未在大型研究中得到彻底验证。

But because it’s so easy to use, the software could be utilized without a person’s permission, revealing mental health problems they might want to keep hidden. It could also be used and abused in workplaces. Vocal biomarker tools could be run on recordings of meetings, for example, and without employees’ consent, companies could find employees who are anxious or depressed. They could intervene early so individuals can get help and stay productive (which is in the interest of the company). Or they could lay off people identified as anxious or depressed—all based on assessments by vocal biomarkers that have not been thoroughly validated in large studies.

一些为这些算法提供信息基础的研究人员决定隐瞒一些相关信息：“我做过预测抑郁症的研究，我故意没有举例说明当时用过哪些词，因为那样的话，就会有空想的医生说，‘哦，好吧，他们经常用‘布洛芬’这个词，我听说‘布洛芬’是抑郁症的征兆。’所以现在我会以这种方式对这个人产生偏见，”人工智能公司 Hugging Face 的首席伦理科学家玛格丽特·米切尔 (Margaret Mitchell) 说，她对这项技术没有任何商业利益。她曾在俄勒冈健康与科学大学从事声音生物标记物的开发工作。“即使只是谈论这件事，也有点令人担忧，但让人们了解正在发生的事情很重要，”她说。

A few researchers who contributed to the information these algorithms are grounded in decided to withhold some pertinent information: “I’ve done work on predicting depression and I intentionally did not include examples of the kinds of words that were used because then you have armchair clinicians like, ‘Oh, well, they’re using the word ibuprofen a lot and I heard ibuprofen was a signal of depression.’ So now I’m going to be biased against this person in that way,” said Margaret Mitchell, chief ethical scientist at AI firm Hugging Face, who has no commercial interests in the technology. She worked on developing vocal biomarkers at Oregon Health and Science University. “Even talking about this, it’s a little bit worrying, but it is important for people to understand what’s happening,” she said.

米切尔的亲身经历解释了为什么这类信息很容易使从业者产生偏见。她的一位同事去听了一场关于抑郁症信号的讲座后，米切尔感到有些沮丧，并发出了一声叹息。同事立刻问道：“你抑郁了吗？抑郁的人经常叹气！”米切尔说，了解到这些信息后，同事对世界的印象发生了根本性的改变。“现在，她在抑郁症患者身上看到了一些她以前不会注意到的迹象。”

Her own experience makes a case for why this kind of information can easily bias practitioners. After one of her colleagues went to a talk about signals of depression, Mitchell was frustrated about something and audibly sighed. Her colleague immediately asked: “Are you depressed? Depressed people sigh a lot!” Knowing this information, her colleague’s impression of the world is fundamentally altered, Mitchell said. “Right now, she sees depression in people that she wouldn’t have otherwise seen.”

如果有人抑郁，他们可能会用一种单调的声音说话。但如果你用的是单调的声音，并不意味着你抑郁了。“理解因果关系——如果这样，那么那样——真的很重要，但很多人却搞砸了，”她说。“尤其是如果它最终影响到人们，以及在招聘等场合对人们的印象，那就非常值得关注了。”

If someone is depressed, they might use a monotone voice. But if you are using a monotone voice, it doesn’t mean you are depressed. “Understanding causality flow—if this, then that—is really critical and something that a lot of people mess up,” she said. “Particularly if it ends up influencing people and people’s impressions in situations like hiring, then it’s a very serious concern.”

另一方面，人工智能工具不会仅仅依赖单一指标。“它需要6到30秒的人声，然后，我们的算法和模型（这些算法和模型已经在美国和亚洲的数万人身上进行了训练）会分析你声音的原子层面，”Sonde Health 首席执行官 David Liu 说道。“我们会分析你正在经历的声音，告诉我们你一天的情况，或者告诉我们你在这30秒内的感受，然后将其转化为声音特征分数，”刘解释说。例如，Sonde 工具还会测量停顿时长。“我们观察的是从你嘴里呼出空气到检测到声音之间的时间差。因此，我们可以测量这个非常短的时间段。”

AI tools, on the other hand, wouldn’t just jump on one indicator. “It takes in six to thirty seconds of human voice and, from there, our algorithms and models, which have been trained on tens of thousands of people, both in the US and in Asia, are analyzing what I call the atomic level of your voice,” said David Liu, CEO of Sonde Health. “We are analyzing the sound as you are going through and telling us about your day or telling us about how you feel in those thirty seconds and that’s what’s translated into these vocal feature scores,” Liu described. The Sonde tool, for example, also measures pause duration. “What we look at is the time difference between when air is being pushed out of your mouth to when sound and voice are being detected. And so that time period, which is quite short, we can measure that.”

除了停顿时间，该工具还记录说话者声音的流畅度、声带肌肉的控制、声音的活泼度、能量范围、清晰度、清脆度和语速。

In addition to pause durations, the tool also records the smoothness of the speaker’s voice, control of vocal muscles, liveliness of the voice, energy range, clarity, crispness, and speech rate.

我采访的四家初创公司对这项技术目前取得的成果说法不一。有些公司声称，他们可以根据一个简短的语音样本测量某人的抑郁和焦虑评分。而像 Sonde Health 这样的公司则更加谨慎。

Claims about what the technology currently accomplishes differ according to the four start-ups that I talked to. Some say they can measure someone’s depression and anxiety scores based on one short voice sample. Others, like Sonde Health, are more careful.

“这项技术已经发展到可以让我们开始理解那些不正常的事情的程度，”刘说道。一段时间后，这款应用程序可以检测到变化。他承认，每个人都有状态不佳的时候，所以评估不能仅仅基于单一的语音分析。

“The technology is at a point where we can now begin to understand things that are off-kilter,” Liu said. Over a period of time the app can detect changes. He acknowledged that everyone has an off day, so an assessment can’t be based on one voice analysis alone.

David Liu 希望声音生物标记技术能帮助我们更好地了解自身的心理健康问题：“我们很多人都默默地忍受着痛苦，不是吗？所以，这其中一部分原因在于意识的提升，我很喜欢可穿戴设备在生理生物标记方面为我们带来的改变。我们甚至对睡眠周期也更加了解了，而十五年前，谁知道这些呢？但现在，这已经成为我们日常谈论的一部分了。”

David Liu hopes that vocal biomarker technology can help us become more aware of our mental health issues: “Many of us are walking around suffering silently, right? And so part of this is the awareness, and I love what wearables have done for us, on the physical biomarker side of things. We just become more cognizant about even sleep cycles, whereas fifteen years ago, who the heck knew about any of this stuff? But now it’s part of the common vernacular that we talk about,” he said.

他希望，有一天，通过这些声音生物标志物评分来追踪我们自身的心理健康状况将成为常态。Sonde Health 计划将这项技术被动地融入到手机和可穿戴设备中，这样，当生物标志物技术还只是“监听”状态时，你只需和妈妈说话就能评估声音生物标志物。

One day, he hopes, tracking our own mental health via these vocal biomarker scores will become the norm. Sonde Health is planning to build the technology passively into phones and wearable devices so that vocal biomarkers can be assessed from just speaking to your mom, say, when the biomarker technology is just “listening in.”

David Liu 向我保证，Sonde Health 计划让用户选择加入这项技术，并且分析不会在未经用户同意的情况下在后台被动运行。

David Liu assured me that Sonde Health plans to have users opt in to this technology and the analysis will not be passively running in the background without user consent.

只是说说

JUST TALKING

门洛学院的行政人员安吉拉·施米德尝试了省略号工具：“这有点尴尬，因为你只是坐在那里说话，却没有和任何人说话。所以这有点像自言自语，你会想，谁会真正听这些？”

Angela Schmiede, the administrator at Menlo College, tried the Ellipsis tool: “It’s a little bit awkward because you’re just sitting there and you’re talking and you’re not talking to anyone. So it’s a little bit like talking to yourself and you do wonder, who’s really going to listen to this?”

我尝试了 Sonde Health 的一个类似工具，把它下载到手机上。我每个月都会多次录制自己的声音，每次三十秒。虽然跟某个人谈论自己感觉很奇怪，但奇怪的是，录完之后我总感觉好一些。

I tried out a similar tool from Sonde Health, which I downloaded on my phone. I recorded myself for thirty seconds multiple times a month. It was weird talking about myself to no one specific, but in a strange way, I always felt a little better after I recorded my messages.

我并不是唯一一个注意到这一点的人：“光是聊天就有治疗作用。我确实发现了这一点。”施米德说道。

I wasn’t the only one who noticed that: “There is something therapeutic about just talking. I did find that to be the case,” Schmiede said.

Lina Lakoczky-Torres 和其他学生开始使用这个工具。每次使用时，他们都会得到评分。根据分数范围，该工具会为学生提供建议——从呼吸练习到为处于严重困境的学生提供的危机求助热线号码。

Lina Lakoczky-Torres and the other students started using the tool. Every time they used it, they were scored. Based on the range the score fell into, the tool gave students recommendations—from breathing exercises to a crisis helpline number for students in acute distress.

一位学生告诉安吉拉·施米德，她觉得这个工具让她更有力量，因为她可以随时使用它，而且不必依赖治疗师的安排。但对拉科茨基-托雷斯来说，这个工具给她的建议并没有太大帮助。当她感到压力很大时，她无法做平静的呼吸练习。她主要用这个工具来向妈妈展示她在家里生活的压力有多大：“看，这是真的。这就是我的感受。你看得见……数据就在那里，”她说。

One student shared with Angela Schmiede that she felt empowered by the tool because she could use it anytime she wanted to and she didn’t have to rely on a therapist’s schedule. For Lakoczky-Torres, the suggestions the tool gave her weren’t too helpful. When she was stressed out, she couldn’t do the calming breathing exercises. She mostly used the tool to show her mom how stressed she was living at home: “Look, it’s real. This is how I feel. You could see it…. There’s data right there,” she said.

安吉拉·施密德 (Angela Schmiede) 注意到，学生们并不太关心该工具的准确性：“他们对技术的信任程度可能比老一辈人更高，”她说。

Angela Schmiede noticed that the students weren’t very concerned about the tool’s accuracy: “They have a greater faith in technology than perhaps older generations do,” she said.

在推出该工具之前，Menlo 团队和 Ellipsis 还讨论了与大学健康中心分享危机评分的问题，但为了保护学生的隐私，他们决定不这样做。

Before rolling out the tool, the Menlo team and Ellipsis also discussed sharing crisis scores with the wellness center at the university but decided against it to protect students’ privacy.

几个月后，试验逐渐结束，门罗中心的结果也好坏参半。“我们研究了近60名参与者，其中一些人只使用了一次，而另一些人则使用了多次，”施米德说。大约75%的用户是女性。

The trial petered out after a few months and the results at Menlo were mixed. “We had close to sixty participants in the study and some of them only used it once. Others used it multiple times,” Schmiede said. About 75 percent of the users were female.

回顾试点项目，Lakoczky-Torres 对整个过程非常满意：“我觉得这家公司关心我们的数据、关心我们的感受，这很酷。而且，我们的感受也能反映出他们如何改进。” 她喜欢能够追踪自己一段时间内的分数，更好地了解自己的情绪：“如果我在期末考试高峰期使用这个工具，我的分数和春假期间相比会怎样？” 她问自己。她认为，这个工具“并非万能的，但它无疑是朝着某个目标迈出的一步。”

Reflecting on the pilot program, Lakoczky-Torres was happy with the process: “I thought it was pretty cool that this company cares about our data, how we were feeling. But also how we were feeling can reflect back on how they can improve it.” She liked that she could track her scores over time and get a better feel for her mood: “If I take this during the peak of finals, what are my scores versus when I’m on spring break?” she asked herself. The tool, she thought, “is not the end all, be all, but it’s definitely a step towards something.”

Ellipsis Health 将如何使用该工具收集的数据？Lakoczky-Torres 回忆道，当时并没有太多担忧。她只是假设，除了那些努力确保工具正常运行的工程师之外，Ellipsis 的任何人都无法访问这些数据。

How was the data the tool collected going to be used by Ellipsis Health? There wasn’t a ton of concern, recalled Lakoczky-Torres. She just assumed that, apart from the engineers who tried to make sure the tool worked, no one from Ellipsis would have access to the data.

即使他们真的这么做了，她也不担心。“隐私真的不复存在了，”她说。对她这一代人来说，分享感受无论如何都更重要：“如果你有某种感受，你会在社交媒体上公开，你会告诉你的“朋友们。这不是你真正想保密的事情，”她说。她称这个项目是一项很好的社会实验。当我与拉科茨基-托雷斯交谈时，她已经无法使用该工具了。

Even if they did, she wasn’t concerned. “Privacy doesn’t really exist anymore,” she said. For her generation, sharing feelings was more important anyway: “If you feel some type of way, you’re going to go onto your social media and put it on blast, you’re going to tell your friends. It’s not something you really want to keep to yourself,” she said. She called the program a good social experiment. When I talked with Lakoczky-Torres, she didn’t have access to the tool anymore.

我一度怀疑这一切努力是否值得。Lakoczky-Torres 认为值得，尤其是考虑到另一种选择：“省略号最终在其中发挥了非常重要的作用，至少让你感觉自己做了一些事情，完成了一些事情，”她说。她还表示，这个工具还将心理健康放在了首位。

I wondered if this whole endeavor had been worthwhile. Lakoczky-Torres thought it was, especially given the alternative: “Ellipsis ended up being a really big part of that, to at least feel like you’ve done something, accomplished something,” she said. The tool also brought mental health to the forefront, she said.

她或许有所发现：Ellipsis 应用的使用促使门洛学院重新思考学院的所有心理健康服务。施米德说，他们正在努力让学生获得更直接的帮助，并提供更广泛的服务。

She might be onto something here: Using the Ellipsis app prompted Menlo to rethink all of the college’s mental health services. They are working on giving students access to more immediate help and providing a wider range of services, Schmiede said.

科学

THE SCIENCE

我们无法知道这项技术是否有效或效果如何，因为没有一家公司进行过双盲安慰剂对照研究（这是测试医疗产品和设备的黄金标准），也没有任何工具获得 FDA 批准。

There is no way to know if or how well this technology works because no company has done a double-blind, placebo-controlled study, which is the gold standard in testing medical products and devices, and no tool has gotten FDA approval.

业内人士向我保证，声音生物标记是存在的，而且可以诊断健康状况，但实际情况要复杂一些。

Industry players assured me that vocal biomarkers exist and that they can diagnose health conditions, but the reality is a bit more complicated.

我们或许仍处于这项技术的炒作高峰期，其实际效果尚不确定。虽然这项技术正在逐渐进入市场，但对于用于此类测试的人员，几乎没有任何保障措施。

We may still be in the peak hype phase of this technology, and it’s a bit uncertain how good it really is. While the technology is breaking into the market, there are very few safeguards for humans whose voices are used in this kind of testing.

这些工具实用性的另一个威胁是，人工智能驱动的语音工具可能很快就能实时改变我们的声音，使它们听起来更单调或更快乐，这是声音生物标记社区以及人力资源部门必须应对的问题。经理们会询问求职者是否使用该技术让自己的声音听起来更“乐观”。

Another threat to practicality of these tools is that AI-driven voice tools might soon enough be able to change our voices in real time, making them sound more monotone or happier, something the vocal biomarker community will have to grapple with as well as possibly HR managers if job applicants use the technology to make their voices sound more “upbeat.”

在医疗保健环境中，错误的声音生物标记可能会导致误诊。或者，这些工具在某些数据集上可能运行良好，但在实际应用中却可能失效。这类问题以前也发生过，并且可能危及生命。

In healthcare settings faulty vocal biomarkers could lead to misdiagnosis. Or the tools could work well on some data sets but not in the wild. These kinds of problems have happened before and could have life-threatening consequences.

美国大型医疗软件提供商 Epic 构建了专有的败血症预测模型，该模型已被美国一百多家医院采用。败血症是人体对感染的极端反应，可危及生命。事实上，根据美国疾病控制与预防中心的数据，每年约有 170 万美国人患有败血症，约有 35 万美国成年人死于败血症。败血症是美国医院内的主要死亡原因，因此医生和护士及早发现有败血症风险的患者至关重要。

Epic, a large healthcare software provider in the United States, built a proprietary Sepsis Prediction Model, which was used in over one hundred US hospitals. Sepsis is the body’s extreme reaction to infection and is life-threatening. In fact, about 1.7 million Americans develop sepsis and around 350,000 adults in the United States die of sepsis in a given year, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention. Sepsis is the leading cause of death in US hospitals, so it’s of vital importance that doctors and nurses find the patients at risk of sepsis early.

一项科学分析表明，Epic 算法的表现不如宣传的那样。它的整体准确率为 63%，比抛硬币好不了多少。12该研究发表后，许多医疗保健机构对此进行了更深入的研究。

A scientific analysis showed that the Epic algorithm performed worse than advertised. It had an overall accuracy rate of 63 percent—a little better than a coin toss.12 After the study was published, many healthcare providers took a closer look.

那么，我们应该开发和使用这样的新技术吗？我们当然应该努力帮助护士和医生找到病人，让他们的生活更轻松，但我们承担不起在医疗保健中使用有缺陷的技术的后果，因为病人可能会因此丧命。

So, should we build and use such new technology? We should of course try to help nurses and doctors find sick patients and make their lives easier, but we can’t afford to use faulty technology in health care because patients could die.

相比之下，声音生物标记物是一项难以测试的技术。没有具体的“基本事实”来检验算法，就像败血症案例中那样——患者要么发展成败血症，要么没有，因此算法可以进行事实核查。但很难核实，例如，Ellipsis Health 针对学生抑郁和焦虑的声音生物标记物测量结果是否表明这些学生确实患有抑郁和焦虑，因为这些学生并没有接受专业评估。心理健康从业人员的评分可以与人工智能评分进行核对，但无论如何，精神障碍经常被误诊。

In comparison, vocal biomarkers are a tricky technology to test. There is no concrete “ground truth” to check the algorithms against, like there is in the sepsis case—patients either developed sepsis or not, so the algorithm could be fact-checked. But it’s difficult to check whether, for example, the Ellipsis Health vocal biomarker measure of depression and anxiety in students showed that these students actually had depression and anxiety because the students were not also evaluated by professional mental health practitioners whose scores the AI scores could have been checked against, and mental disorders are often misdiagnosed anyway.

为了了解声音生物标记物科学的进展及其局限性，我采访了伦敦帝国理工学院的人工智能教授比约恩·舒勒 (Bjoern Schuller)。他表示，声音生物标记物最容易应用于医生用听诊器听诊的情况——主要用于呼吸系统疾病，因为这些疾病会导致声音、呼吸和咳嗽出现可听见的变化。其他疾病，例如咽喉癌和颈癌，也会改变声音，可以通过技术手段发现。

To understand how far the science of vocal biomarkers has come and what its limitations are, I spoke to Bjoern Schuller, a professor of artificial intelligence at Imperial College London. He said that vocal biomarkers can most easily be used where doctors listen with a stethoscope—mainly in respiratory illnesses because these diseases cause audible changes in voice, breath, and cough. Other illnesses—for example, throat and neck cancer—change the voice as well and can be picked up by technology.

比约恩·舒勒表示，声音生物标记技术“源于人们的倾听，并越来越多地转向‘好吧，让我们想想是什么导致了你的声音发生变化’。声音的变化关乎你对言语产生的认知，关乎你的生理机能，关乎你的运动系统。如果这些受到了影响，我们应该能够察觉到。” 他表示，检测我们言语的声音生物标记已经能够准确地预测一个人的身高，甚至可以通过声音预测他们的心率。

Bjoern Schuller said vocal biomarker technology “came from where people have been listened to and moved more and more into, ‘Okay, let’s think about what would make a change to your voice.’ It’s your cognition for speech production, it’s your physiology, it’s your motor system. If that is somehow affected, we should be able to hear it.” He said that vocal biomarkers examining our speech can already accurately predict a person’s height and even their heart rate from their voice.

但愿景远不止于此。舒勒希望有一天，声音生物标记能够帮助早期诊断自闭症和其他疾病。“我们的想法是，你可以拥有一部具有智能功能的婴儿电话，可以识别自闭症等神经发育障碍的早期预警信号。然后，你可以说，‘请去看专科医生’，然后确认诊断结果，因为父母在五七个月大的时候可能还不会注意到，但婴儿电话会知道。”

But the vision is much larger than that. Schuller hopes that one day vocal biomarkers can help diagnose autism and other diseases very early on. “The idea is that you can have a baby phone with some smart ability that recognizes early warning signs of neurodevelopmental disorders like autism. Then one could say, ‘Please go to a specialist,’ and then have this [diagnosis] confirmed because the parents wouldn’t notice that at month five or seven, but the baby phone would know.”

声音生物标记技术也能在医疗资源匮乏的国家发挥巨大作用。人们不再像几十年前那样打电话报时，而是可以拨打一个电话号码，留下语音样本，然后电脑就能判断他们是否患有痴呆症、喉癌、颈癌或其他疾病。

Vocal biomarker technology could also make a huge difference in countries where medical care is hard to access. Instead of calling for the time, like people did decades ago, they could call a phone number, leave a voice sample, and the computer could tell them if they have dementia, throat or neck cancer, or another illness.

但今天的现实是，用声音来诊断健康状况舒勒说，生物标志物比许多人想象的要混乱和复杂得多。

But the reality today is that diagnosing health conditions using vocal biomarkers is more muddled and complicated than many players make it out to be, Schuller said.

由于几乎所有声音生物标记物都是由深度神经网络训练的，因此算法检测的内容并不总是清晰的。例如，对于COVID-19咳嗽样本，深度神经网络会提取咳嗽者的音频样本，并标注咳嗽者是否感染COVID-19。然后，该软件会自行找出COVID咳嗽和非COVID咳嗽之间的差异。舒勒表示，希望计算机能够检测到这些咳嗽类型之间的差异，但这并非总是如此。这项技术之前也曾失败过。

Because almost all vocal biomarkers are trained by deep neural networks, it’s not always clear what the algorithm is detecting. For example, with COVID-19 coughing samples, a deep neural network would ingest the audio samples of people coughing and labels stating whether the coughing persons had COVID-19 or not. The software would then figure out on its own the differences between the COVID and non-COVID coughs. The hope is that the computer can detect differences between these types of coughs, but that’s not always the case, Schuller said. The technology has misfired before.

舒勒解释说：“如果你把重症监护室（ICU）里所有感染新冠肺炎的人和街上所有非感染新冠肺炎的人都收集起来，我们收集的不是是否感染新冠肺炎，而是重症监护室和街道的声学效果。” 这样的算法毫无用处，因为它只是拾取不同的背景声音。

“If you collect all the COVID people in the ICU and all the non-COVID people in the street, we’re not picking up COVID or not, but the acoustics of ICU versus street,” Schuller explained. An algorithm like that would be useless because it’s just picking up different background sounds.

“很多人没有完全公开他们的测试方法，”舒勒说。科学家有时会对自己的方法产生偏见，这就是为什么比约恩·舒勒和他的博士生哈里·科波克想要复制他人的实验，以确保其有效性。“对于研究小组来说，发布他们训练好的模型以及复制这些研究所需的代码非常重要，”科波克说。

“There’s a lot of people not fully revealing their test methods,” Schuller said. Sometimes scientists can be biased to their own methods, and that’s why Bjoern Schuller and his PhD student, Harry Coppock, want to replicate others’ experiments to make sure they work. “It’s so important for research groups to release their trained models and the code required to replicate these studies,” Coppock said.

但这种情况并非总是如此，尤其是在声学机器学习领域。如果算法的训练数据包含语音样本，那么这些数据就属于个人数据，在某些情况下无法公开发布。有时，研究人员和公司希望将他们的算法隐藏起来，不让公众知晓，因为他们将其视为商业机密。

But that doesn’t always happen, especially in the acoustic machine learning space. If an algorithm’s training data consists of voice samples, that’s personal data that in some cases can’t be publicly released. And sometimes researchers and companies want to keep their algorithms shielded from the public because they regard them as their trade secrets.

但有些研究在发布时并没有提供基础数据，科学家被要求只相信作者。正因如此，舒勒并不热衷于将声音生物标记技术发布给公众。由于这些产品尚未经过独立验证，因此尚未公开。他担心声音生物标记的“蛇油”和对该技术的炒作会让人们对其敬而远之。（补充：Bjoern Schuller 主动告诉我，他确实拥有一家商业语音情绪检测公司，主要向游戏公司销售产品。该公司并不试图诊断健康问题。）

But some studies are released without the underlying data, and scientists are asked to just believe the authors. That’s why Schuller isn’t a huge fan of companies releasing vocal biomarker technologies to the public yet, because the products have not been independently validated. He is afraid that vocal biomarker snake oil and the hype of the technology will make people turn away from it. (Full disclosure: Bjoern Schuller told me without prompting that he does own a commercial voice emotion detection company that sells to gaming companies. It does not try to diagnose health issues.)

这是一项前景光明的技术，但大多数语音生物标记应用尚未经过独立验证或获得FDA批准。需要更多研究来证明这项技术有效，而这并非易事，因为精神疾病的诊断结果并不总是像其他许多疾病的血液检测那样客观。研究人员必须进行大规模双盲试验才能确定这些技术是否有效，但这些测试和试验成本高昂。

It’s a promising technology, but most voice biomarker applications have been not been independently validated or approved by the FDA. Many more studies are needed to prove that the technology works, and that’s not easy because the ground truth for mental illnesses is not always objective like a blood test for many other illnesses is. Researchers must run large double-blind trials to find out if these technologies make a difference, but those tests and trials cost a lot of money.

无论这项技术是否有效，人们都可能以意想不到的方式利用它：任何人都可以对求职者的样本运行语音算法，从而拒绝聘用那些被标记为焦虑、抑郁、精神分裂症或帕金森症的申请人。事实上，我播放了YouTube上随机人群通过Sonde Health的移动应用程序说话的视频，并获得了他们的“心理健康评分”（该公司称之为）。

Regardless of whether the technology works, people could utilize it in unintended ways: anyone could run a voice algorithm over samples of job seekers and not hire the applicants who are labeled anxious or depressed or as having schizophrenia or Parkinson’s. In fact, I ran YouTube videos of random people speaking through Sonde Health’s mobile app and got their “mental fitness scores,” as the company calls them.

我思考了一些以前从未考虑过的伦理问题：如果像 Alexa 这样的智能音箱从我的语音数据中检测到我正在陷入抑郁，亚马逊是否有义务告知我？或者，如果 Alexa 发现我们的孩子患有焦虑症，亚马逊应该告知我作为家长吗？如果 Alexa 记录了家庭暴力事件，科技公司是否有义务报警或联系儿童保护服务机构？

I wondered about other ethical questions I had never considered before: If a smart speaker like Alexa detects in my voice data that I am sliding into depression, should Amazon be obliged to tell me? Or what if Alexa discovers that our toddler has anxiety? Should Amazon tell me, the parent? If Alexa records an episode of domestic violence, are tech companies obligated to call the police or Child Protective Services?

这种技术也可以用于人们申请残疾保险。公司可以利用这类测试来检查一个人是否健康、焦虑或抑郁的人，都可以批准或拒绝承保。这不公平，但这并不意味着没有人考虑使用它。

This type of technology could also be used when people apply for disability insurance. Companies could use such tests to check whether a person is healthy or anxious or depressed to greenlight or deny coverage. This wouldn’t be fair, but it doesn’t mean that someone isn’t contemplating using it.

美国一些执法机构正在使用一种类似的技术，称为计算机语音压力分析仪，供应商声称，该技术可以通过分析嫌疑人声音中的压力水平来判断嫌疑人是否在说谎。

Some law enforcement agencies across the United States are using a similar technology called Computer Voice Stress Analyzer, which, the vendor claims, can determine whether a suspect is lying by analyzing the stress levels in their voice.

我采访了一家名为Cogito的公司，该公司分析呼叫中心的对话，并向客服人员提供实时反馈，告知他们需要改进的地方。该公司表示，它可以检测客户声音中的焦虑和沮丧情绪。2022年末，摩根大通申请了一项类似的人工智能技术专利，该技术可以预测“不满情绪”。

I spoke to a company called Cogito, which analyzes conversations in call centers and gives real-time feedback to agents on what they need to change. The company said it can detect agitation and frustration in customers’ voices. In late 2022, JPMorgan Chase filed a patent on a similar AI technology that can predict “dissatisfaction.”

新世界中的隐私

OUR PRIVACY IN THIS NEW WORLD

声音生物标志物只是我们的隐私受到威胁的一个领域：在工作中，隐私对许多员工来说正成为一种奢侈品。

Vocal biomarkers are just one area where our privacy is threatened: at work, privacy is becoming a luxury good for many employees.

长期以来，仓库和送货工人的行动一直受到监视，但现在像亚马逊这样的公司正在将监视提升到一个新的水平。2021 年，该公司要求为亚马逊工作的送货司机签署一份同意书，承认他们的行动以及生物特征数据可能会被跟踪和存储。据Vice报道，亚马逊送货车内的新摄像头可以感知打哈欠和分心驾驶，并监控司机的身体和面部动作。13据汤森路透报道，司机担心这些记录也可能被共享给“第三方服务提供商”。14倡导组织“监控技术监督项目”的执行董事 Albert Fox Cahn 表示，亚马逊可以“用这些数据做任何他们想做的事情” 。15

Warehouse and delivery workers have been subjected to surveillance of their movements for a long time, but now companies like Amazon are pushing the monitoring to the next level. In 2021, the company required delivery drivers working for Amazon to sign a consent form acknowledging that their movements, but also their biometric data, could be tracked and stored. New cameras inside the Amazon delivery vans can sense yawning and distracted driving and monitor drivers’ body and facial movements, according to Vice.13 Drivers fear that the recordings can also be shared with “third-party service providers,” according to Thomson Reuters.14 Albert Fox Cahn, the executive director of the Surveillance Technology Oversight Project, an advocacy group, said that Amazon can “do just about anything they want with this data.”15

我们正在进入一个新时代，大量信息，包括精神疾病的指标，都可以从我们的社交媒体、面部表情和声音中提取出来，并用于工作和教育领域。如果对学生进行持续监控，预测哪些学生会陷入抑郁，以便医生能够尽快干预，这难道不会让大学管理者、学生和家长感到更安心吗？学生会同意这种监控吗？我们会同意这种监控吗？

We are entering a new era where a lot of information, including indicators of mental illnesses, can be pulled out of our social media, our facial expressions, and our voices and could be used in work and educational settings. Wouldn’t it make university administrators, students, and parents feel better if students were monitored constantly to predict which ones were falling into depression so a doctor could intervene ASAP? Would students consent to this kind of monitoring? Would we consent to this kind of monitoring?

此外，我们的面部表情和声音都是独一无二的，与面部识别技术类似，我们几乎无法控制任何人如何使用这些非常私人的信息。

Also, our facial expressions and voices are unique to us and, similar to facial recognition technology, we have very little control over how anyone uses this very personal information.

如果公司开始使用这类技术，它们可能会彻底改变工作和生活中的权力平衡。它们收集和预测的信息可能会被用来对付我们。当然，这些技术可能效果不佳，但这并不意味着它不会被利用。

If companies start using these kinds of technologies, they could completely change the power balance at work and in our lives. The information they collect and predict upon could be used against us. And, of course, the technology might not work well at all, but that doesn’t mean it won’t get used.

科技供应商也在试图洞察人们的内心。一些背景调查公司现在宣称，他们可以通过社交媒体账户推断出人们是否有暴力倾向或自残倾向。我采访过的律师认为，这种做法可能是违法的，因为自残可能意味着精神疾病，而公司在提供工作机会之前是不允许询问这类问题的。

Tech vendors are also trying to look into people’s minds. Some background-checking companies now advertise that they can deduce from social media accounts whether people are prone to violence or self-harm. Lawyers I have spoken with believe this might be illegal because self-harm could point to a mental illness, something a company is not allowed to inquire about before making a job offer.

随着神经科学的快速发展，能够记录脑电活动、测量注意力或走神程度的工具也将不断涌现。《2022年科技趋势报告》指出：“科学家们已经发现了入耳式脑电图的各种应用，包括在办公室环境中测量员工的注意力。” 麻省理工学院媒体实验室开发的另一款名为AlterEgo的设备可以“大声说出”佩戴者脑海中的想法。

And as neuroscience swiftly progresses, so will tools that can record the electrical activity in our brain and measure focus or mind wandering. “Scientists have found various applications of in-ear EEG, including measuring employee attention in office settings,” according to the 2022 Tech Trends Report. Another device, called AlterEgo, which was developed at the MIT Media Lab, can “speak out loud” the thoughts the headset’s wearer is voicing in their head.

公司正越来越接近窥探我们大脑运作的奥秘。对于杜克大学哲学与法学教授妮塔·法拉哈尼来说，这仅仅是我们能够从大脑中提取信息的开端。“我们可以开始解码一些非常简单的事情，比如简单的数字、单词、人们听到的声音、注意力集中的位置以及困倦程度。”

Companies are getting closer and closer to peeking into what is going on in our brains. To Nita Farahany, philosophy and law professor at Duke University, this is just the beginning of the information we can pull from our brains. “We can start to decode simple, simple things like simple numbers, words, things that a person is hearing, where their attention is focused, drowsiness.”

她担心，随着科技的进步，闸门将会打开：“随着我们在神经科学、人工智能和机器学习领域能力的不断增强，我们可能很快就会对人脑的运作方式有更深入的了解，”她说道。“但大脑难道不是你以为能让你获得精神喘息的空间，是自由的最后堡垒，是你以为可以拥有想法和创造力、幻想某些事物、产生荒诞想法或绝妙创意的地方吗？难道你以为大脑是唯一一个永远安全的空间吗？”法拉哈尼问道。

She is worried that as the technology advances, the floodgates will open: “With our growing capabilities in neuroscience, artificial intelligence, and machine learning, we may soon know a lot more of what’s happening in the human brain,” she said. “But wasn’t the brain the one area that you thought that you had some mental reprieve, the last bastion of freedom, the place that you thought you could have ideas and creativity, fantasize about something, have an absurd idea, have a brilliant idea. Is that the one space that you thought would always be secure?” Farahany asked.

感觉我们可能都成了我们生活这个巨大数据实验室里的实验对象。一旦企业（和政府）能够读取我们的想法，我们所熟知的隐私和民主就将终结。除非我们现在就着手制定必要的法律来规范这些技术的使用。

It feels like we might all become guinea pigs in this gigantic data laboratory that is our lives. And once corporations (and governments) can read our thoughts, that will be the end of privacy and democracy as we know them. That is, unless we work now to write the laws needed to regulate use of these technologies.

第十章

CHAPTER 10

被算法解雇

Fired by an Algorithm

寻找问题员工

On Trying to Find Problem Employees

R还记得序章里的Lizzie *吗？她是一位年轻的化妆师，在新冠疫情爆发时，在英国一家MAC彩妆专柜工作。她先是被暂时休假，然后公司又宣布裁员。最终的裁员决定是基于之前的表现、销售指标以及HireVue视频面试的结果。

Remember Lizzie* from the Prologue? She is the young makeup artist who worked at a MAC makeup counter in the UK when the COVID-19 pandemic hit. First she was furloughed and then the company announced layoffs. The termination decisions were based on previous performance, sales metrics, and a HireVue video interview.

当莉齐因为在 HireVue 评估中得分低而被解雇时，她感到愤怒、悲伤和沮丧。她​​和另外两名被解雇的化妆师一起，找到了无偿劳动律师，对裁定提出质疑。

When she was laid off because of her low scores in the HireVue assessment, Lizzie was livid, sad, and frustrated. Together with two other laid-off makeup artists, she found pro bono employment lawyers and challenged the decisions.

“我们都认为我们失去了工作，这很不公平，”莉齐说。在法律诉讼期间，当莉齐查看了她所有的数据时，她在 HireVue 结果中发现，根据前雇主对她的评估，她的得分在 0 到 33 分之间（满分 100 分）。但“评级”和“推荐”部分留空，“状态”下显示“进一步审核”。

“We all believe that we’d lost our jobs unfairly,” Lizzie said. And during the legal proceedings, when Lizzie got to review all the data her former employer had on her, she found on her HireVue results, she scored between 0 and 33 points out of 100. But the Rating and Recommendation sections were left blank, and under “Status,” it said “further review.”

对莉齐来说，“进一步审核”意味着发生了技术错误，人力资源部门需要重新审核面试，甚至可能让她重做。她认为她的经理误解了 HireVue 的结果，并将其解读为她的技能需要进一步审核。她不明白为什么“评分”和“推荐”部分是空白的，这表明出了问题。

To Lizzie, the “further review” meant that a technical error had occurred and the HR folks needed to take a second look at the interview and maybe have her redo it. She believes her managers misunderstood HireVue’s results and interpreted it as her skills needed further review. She wonders why the Rating and Recommendation sections were blank, which indicated that something went wrong.

当她看到 HireVue 的结果单时，她松了一口气。毕竟，她是一位能力出众的化妆师：“我的直觉告诉我，情况有些不对劲，但最终得到确认，这真让我感到欣慰。”

When she saw the HireVue result sheet, she felt relieved. She was a capable makeup artist after all: “It was refreshing to get the reassurance that my gut feeling about it was that something wasn’t right with the situation.”

她认为，公开谈论人工智能技术是如何在她身上被利用的至关重要。“它如何评估员工以及它如何影响人们，这令人担忧，尤其是在我们无法完全了解其使用方式的情况下，”莉齐说道。（HireVue 的评估旨在作为招聘流程的一部分。HireVue 不建议在有实际在职绩效数据的情况下使用这些客观评估。）

She believes it’s important for her to speak out about how AI technology was used on her. “How it reviews and how it’s affecting people is quite scary, especially when we’re not getting full transparency of how it’s being used,” Lizzie said. (HireVue’s assessments are designed to be used as part of the hiring process. HireVue does not recommend use of these objective assessments when actual on-the-job performance data is available.)

人力资源部门如何利用人工智能工具来确定哪些人将被解雇或裁员，是最后一章关于人工智能监控的主题。无论我们乐意与否，裁员和解雇都是生活中的现实。正如莉齐的例子所示，随着越来越多的人工智能工具渗透到人力资源领域，人工智能如今在解雇决策中扮演着重要的角色。

How HR departments are using AI tools to determine who is being fired or laid off is the subject of this last chapter on AI surveillance. Whether we like it or not, layoffs and terminations are a fact of life. As Lizzie’s example shows, AI is now playing a part in firings as more and more artificial intelligence-based tools penetrate the HR field.

Brian Westfall 是技术评论和研究公司 Capterra 的分析师。他调查了 300 多位主要来自中型企业的人力资源主管，其中 98% 的人表示，他们会如果他们需要在 2023 年做出裁员决定，就必须依赖算法、人力资源软件和人工智能。

Brian Westfall is an analyst at Capterra, a technology review and research company. He surveyed more than three hundred HR leaders in mostly midsize companies, and 98 percent of them said that they would rely on algorithms, HR software, and AI if they needed to make layoff decisions in 2023.

韦斯特福尔说：“有证据表明，企业越来越依赖算法工具来做出这些关键决策。”

“Here is some evidence that companies out there are relying more and more on algorithmic tools to make these critical decisions,” Westfall said.

但与此同时，许多受访的人力资源经理表示，尽管他们会利用科技手段做出裁员决策，但他们并不信任这些算法。只有50%的受访者“完全相信”算法或人力资源软件能够给出公正的建议。

But at the same time, many of the HR managers surveyed said that, although they will use tech to make layoff decisions, they don’t trust these algorithms. Only 50 percent of the people surveyed were “completely confident” that algorithms or HR software would make unbiased recommendations.

这种态度与哈佛商学院教授乔·富勒在上一章讨论的公司高管调查中发现的类似：他的团队调查的高管和经理绝大多数在招聘中使用算法，即使这些技术筛选会淘汰合格的候选人，他们仍然依赖算法。同样如此：许多人力资源经理不信任算法，但几乎所有人力资源经理都会使用算法来做出裁员决策。

These are similar attitudes to what Joe Fuller, the Harvard business professor, found in his survey of company executives discussed in an earlier chapter: the executives and managers his team surveyed overwhelmingly use algorithms in hiring, and even though these tech screens are cutting qualified candidates, they still rely on them. Same here: many HR managers don’t trust algorithms, but almost all of them would use them to make layoff decisions.

专家表示，领导者在使用技术手段决定解雇员工时应谨慎行事。“显然，这其中存在很多风险。如果公司不熟悉这些工具，使用不良数据或带有偏见的数据，而算法无法考虑到这些数据，最终会做出非常糟糕的决策，”韦斯特福尔说道。“就像任何工具一样，如果你不知道自己在做什么，或者不知道它是如何运作的，就会发生糟糕的事情。但如果你了解该工具的工作原理，并且知道自己在做什么，它就能帮助你完成工作。”

Experts say leaders should exercise caution when using technology to decide who gets a pink slip. “There is a lot of danger there, obviously. If companies are not familiar with these tools and they are using bad data or they are using biased data and algorithms aren’t going to be able to take that into account—they are going to end up making really poor decisions,” Westfall said. “Like any tool, if you don’t know what you’re doing or you don’t know how that works, something bad is going to happen. But if you do know how that tool works and you do know what you’re doing, it can help you do your job.”

目前尚不清楚公司是否有将非量化数据纳入裁员审核流程的流程。例如，一位模范员工可能在某一年表现不佳，或者一位员工可能经常帮助他人，从而造福许多人，但这可能不会反映在该员工的绩效数据中。

It’s not clear whether companies have a process for incorporating nonquantitative data into the layoff review procedure. For example, an exemplary employee might have an off year or an employee may constantly help others, which benefits many, but that may not be reflected in the employee’s performance data.

寻找低绩效者

THE HUNT FOR LOW PERFORMERS

多年来，专家们一直预测人类工作者将被机器和人工智能取代——人类将基本上被淘汰。有些工作已经实现自动化，有些工作将因 ChatGPT 和其他大型语言模型而发生改变，但许多新的工作正在被创造出来，需要人类工作者。

For years, experts have predicted that human workers will be replaced by machines and artificial intelligence—humans will basically be put out to pasture. Some jobs have been automated, some jobs will change because of ChatGPT and other large language models, but many new jobs are being created that use human workers.

算法不会很快取代我们，但正在发生的变化是，算法和基于人工智能的工具正在成为越来越多员工的“老板”。它们负责检查所有任务是否完成，评估员工的工作效率，挑选员工进行领导力培训，以及在极少甚至完全无人监督的情况下雇佣和解雇员工。1

Algorithms are not going to replace us anytime soon, but what is changing is that algorithms and artificial intelligence–based tools are becoming the “bosses” of more and more workers. They check to make sure all tasks are done, rate employees’ productivity, select employees for leadership training, and hire and fire people with very little or no human oversight.1

仓库工人和送货司机处于工作场所监控和算法追踪的前沿。事实上，他们就像煤矿里的金丝雀，向我们展示了其他行业工人未来可能面临的危险。

Warehouse workers and delivery drivers were on the forefront of workplace surveillance and algorithmic tracking. In fact, they are the canaries in the coal mine and show us what might lie ahead for workers in other industries.

其中一位送货司机是克莱尔·格罗夫，一位年近五十的白人女性。她住在英国伍斯特，是一位单身母亲，有一个成年的自闭症儿子。她十七岁参军，后来成为一名飞行员，就是为了表明自己的立场。“有人告诉我，‘你不能这么做，因为你是个女孩。’”她说。“我想这就是我这么做的原因，只是为了给我爸爸留下个好印象。”

One of these delivery drivers is Claire Grove, a white woman in her late forties. She lives in Worcester, England, and is the single mother of an adult autistic son. She joined the military at seventeen and became a pilot to make a point. “I was told, ‘You can’t do that because you are a girl,’” she said. “I think that’s why I did it, just to impress my dad.”

她辞职结婚，离婚后加入了预备役。2005年，格罗夫在她所在的团滑雪时遭遇了一场事故。由于伤势严重，她无法长时间坐着，因此无法继续工作，于是她于2006年从预备役的全职工作中退休。“从那以后，我就一直很失落，”她说。

She resigned to get married, and after her divorce, she joined the reserves. In 2005, Grove had a skiing accident with her regiment. Her injury prevented her from carrying out her work, because she has a hard time sitting down for long, so she retired from her full-time job in the military reserves in 2006: “I’ve been very much a lost soul since then,” she said.

2017年，在购买了几处出租房产并忙于偿还抵押贷款后，她需要额外的收入来源。就在那时，她决定注册亚马逊Flex。除了他们常用的货车外除了车队承包商之外，亚马逊还与自由职业司机合作。他们报名轮班，用私家车运送超额包裹。

In 2017, she needed an additional income stream after buying several rental properties and scrambling to pay the mortgages. That’s when she decided to sign up with Amazon Flex. In addition to their regular van fleet contractors, Amazon also works with freelance drivers. They sign up for shifts and deliver overflow parcels in their private cars.

格罗夫经常在晚上接班，在她家附近送包裹，这样她的一位房客——一位老师——就可以帮她照看儿子了。她说，一开始她不太好意思接这份工作，因为自己资历太高了。但后来她发现她真的很喜欢这份工作。“我会送货到农场，抚摸狗狗，人们会说，‘哇，你平安夜送货’，或者‘你人真好’。这真的很有趣，”她说。

Grove regularly picked up shifts in the evenings delivering packages near her home while one of her lodgers, who was a teacher, could watch her son. She was embarrassed to take the job at first, she said, because she was overqualified. But it turned out she really liked it. “I would deliver to the farms and stroke the dogs and people would be like, ‘Wow, you are delivering on Christmas Eve,’ or ‘You are so nice.’ It was really enjoyable,” she said.

格罗夫每天都会查看亚马逊的应用程序，寻找适合她日程安排的轮班。她所在地区的大多数轮班时间为四小时，工资固定为44至54英镑（约合54至66美元），包括她的人工和汽车使用费。格罗夫估计她每月的收入约为800英镑（约合991美元）。

Over the course of the day, Grove would check Amazon’s app for shifts that suited her schedule. Most of the shifts in her area were for four hours and paid between 44 and 54 pounds (roughly $54 to $66) flat fee for her labor and the use of her car. Grove estimates she made about 800 pounds ($991) per month.

报名轮班后，她必须至少在开始时间前15分钟到达仓库，签到、领取包裹，然后开始送货。她的包裹信息可以通过应用程序追踪。

After she signed up for a shift, she had to get to the depot at least fifteen minutes before the start time, sign in, collect her parcels, and start her route. Her deliveries were tracked by an app.

只要条件允许，她就会带一个朋友一起去，在不得不并排停车时，给他们一些零钱让他们帮忙看车。有时，交通督导员会质疑她是不是在送货，因为她的车看起来不像送货车。她回忆说，开车的时候，她和朋友会把音乐开大，一起唱歌。

When possible, she took a friend with her and paid them pocket change to guard her car when she had to double park. On occasion, traffic wardens would question whether she was making deliveries because her car didn’t look like a delivery van. While driving, she and her friend would turn up the music and sing along, she recalled.

格罗夫的收入足以维持收支平衡，因此她决定购买一辆电动汽车，并用亚马逊 Flex 送货的收入支付每月的还款。

Grove was earning enough to make ends meet, so she decided to buy an electric car and make the monthly payments with her income from her Amazon Flex deliveries.

她对这份工作最不喜欢的，大多都与算法管理有关。司机必须跟着亚马逊的GPS导航，有几次，系统竟然要求她开车过河，而河里根本就没有桥，或者拐进根本不存在的街道。

The things she didn’t like about the job were most all related to management by algorithms. The drivers had to follow Amazon’s GPS, and a few times, the system asked her to drive across rivers that had no bridge in sight or turn down nonexistent streets.

GPS 还意味着包裹扫描只能在系统指定的一个精确位置进行。在大型住宅区，这可能会使事情变得复杂，因为邮件室或单个建筑的位置与应用程序指示司机前往的位置并不完全一致。格罗夫记得，当她站在顾客面前试图递上包裹时，应用程序却不允许她扫描，她感到很尴尬。

The GPS also meant that scanning packages was only possible in one exact spot, which the system designated. That could make things complicated in larger residential developments where mail rooms or individual buildings weren’t exactly where the app told drivers to go. Grove remembered feeling embarrassed when she would be standing in front of a customer trying to hand over the package, but the app wouldn’t let her scan it.

“你会说，‘抱歉，我不能把包裹给你。我只需要打电话确认一下地址，这样他们就能把那个点移到正确的地方。’”格罗夫说。在等待的过程中，有些顾客会不耐烦，这让格罗夫很担心他们会把包裹评为不满意，这会对她的记录产生不良影响。这也意味着她会浪费宝贵的时间。

“You say, ‘Sorry, I can’t give you your parcel. I just need to ring up and say this is definitely the right address so they can move that dot to the correct place,’” Grove said. While they had to wait, some customers would get impatient, which made Grove nervous that they would rate the delivery as unsatisfactory, which would reflect poorly on her record. It also meant that she would lose precious time.

另一个痛点是当仓库迟到时，司机无法准时上班。亚马逊 Flex 司机担心，如果他们没有按时刷卡，算法会将他们记录为“缺席”，这会损害他们的声誉。“每个人都下车说，‘我需要刷卡，我迟到了。’每个人都在问，甚至有人开始按喇叭，”格罗夫回忆道。

Another pain point was when the depot was running late, and drivers couldn’t report to work on time. Amazon Flex drivers were afraid that the algorithm would register them as no-shows if they didn’t scan in on time and this would hurt their standing. “Everyone’s getting out of the car saying, ‘I need to scan in, I am late.’ And everyone’s asking and people start piping their horns,” Grove recalled.

还有一次，她爆胎了，担心自己的工资会受到影响。她拼命地试图联系公司的人，甚至把轮胎和救援车辆的照片都发了过来，以免亚马逊在她迟到签到时怪罪她。“你拼命地想去那里告诉别人，结果，已经太晚了。你错过了你的时间段，”格罗夫说。

Another time, she worried about her rating when she had a flat tire. She frantically tried to reach someone at the company, even sending photos of the tire and the recovery vehicle so Amazon wouldn’t hold it against her when she was late to sign in for her shift. “You are desperately trying to get there and tell someone and then, well, it’s too late. You missed your block,” Grove said.

她说，她在 Amazon Flex 的许多同事都是来自印度、巴基斯坦和东欧的新移民。有些人英语说得不好，而且几乎所有人都无法承受失去这份工作。格罗夫有点特殊。她敢于为自己和他人发声，维护自己的权益。

Many of her Amazon Flex colleagues were recent immigrants from India, Pakistan, and Eastern Europe, she said. Some struggled with speaking English and almost all of them couldn’t afford to lose this gig. Grove was a bit of an outlier. She had no problem speaking up and advocating for herself and others.

例如，在轮班快结束时，格罗夫距离仓库还有半小时的路程，而她还有很多包裹要送，她会停下来，开车回到仓库，并在规定的四小时内把包裹送回。仓库的工作人员对此很不满意。有时他们会告诉她，电脑显示她可以在轮班期间送完所有包裹，所以她应该可以。

For example, toward the end of a shift, when Grove was half an hour away from the depot and she still had a lot of packages to deliver, she would stop, drive back to the depot, and return parcels within the four hours allotted to her. The workers at the depot didn’t like that. Sometimes they told her that the computer said that she could deliver all the packages within her shift, so she should have been able to.

还有一次，一名工人告诉她：“有时候你工作三个小时，拿四个小时的工资。所以其他时候你应该工作五个小时，拿四个小时的工资。我说，‘不，对不起，这是剥削。’然后他们就说，‘好吧，如果你带回来的包裹超过这么多，就会被威胁终止合同。’”她回忆道。

Another time a worker told her: “Sometimes you’ll work for three hours and you’ll get paid for four. So the other times you should work for five hours and get paid for four. And I said, ‘No, sorry, that’s exploitation.’ And they went, well, if you bring more than so many parcels back, you would get a threat to have your contract terminated,” she recalled.

她不知道哪些事情在她记录上留下了污点。有些事情她收到了一条自动消息：

She doesn’t know which occurrences left a black mark on her record. For some incidents she received an automated message:

你好，克莱尔，

Hello Claire,

我们的记录显示，您并未在 2020 年 2 月 3 日完成所有指定的递送。我们希望您尝试递送您领取的每一个包裹。

Our records indicate that you did not complete all of your assigned deliveries on 3 February 2020. We expect you to attempt every package you pick up.

我们理解，在极少数情况下，可能无法尝试寄送您包裹中的所有包裹。如果您未能寄送所有分配的包裹，且该问题持续存在，则不会影响您使用 Amazon Flex 的资格。

On rare occasions, we understand that attempting every package in your block might not be possible. Failing to attempt all your assigned packages will only affect your eligibility for Amazon Flex if it is a consistent problem.

如果出现意外情况导致您无法尝试所有套餐，请回复此电子邮件并提供更多信息。

If something unexpected prevented you from attempting all of your packages, please reply to this email with further information.

您的反馈正在帮助我们打造地球上最以客户为中心的公司。

Your feedback is helping us build Earth’s Most Customer-Centric Company.

致以最诚挚的问候，

Warmest regards,

英国亚马逊

Amazon.co.uk

格罗夫回信说，当天早些时候，一位司机已经尝试过派送包裹，但没能成功，可能是因为在伍斯特的中央商务区很难找到停车位。当天晚些时候，她也找不到停车位，而且她无法步行派送较大的包裹，所以她把几个包裹退回了仓库。

Grove wrote back that a driver earlier in the day had already tried to deliver the parcels but wasn’t able to, probably because it was really hard to find parking in the central business district of Worcester. She hadn’t been able to find parking later in the day either, and she wasn’t able to deliver the bigger packages on foot, so she returned several to the depot.

根据经验，她怀疑亚马逊的员工不会阅读她解释退货原因的电子邮件，否则她会收到罚单。她对高度自动化的系统的不满在邮件中显露无遗：“根据经验，我估计你根本不会看这封邮件，”她写道。

She suspected from experience that no Amazon worker would read her email explanation of why she had to return packages and that she would get dinged. Her frustrations with the largely automated systems shone through in her message: “I also expect from experience that you will not even read this email,” she typed.

2020年2月13日，格罗夫收到亚马逊的一封自动邮件，邮件中记录了她2020年2月2日至2月8日的一周活动，其中包括她必须退回大量包裹的当天。邮件显示，她的记录仍然显示可靠率为100%，投递尝试率为99%，准时投递/尝试率为100%。

On February 13, 2020, Grove received an automated email from Amazon with her week’s activity covering February 2 to February 8, 2020, which included the day she had to return lots of packages. According to the message, her record still showed a 100 percent reliability rate, a 99 percent delivery attempt rate, and a 100 percent on-time delivery/attempt rate.

三天后，也就是2020年2月16日，格罗夫通过电子邮件被亚马逊解雇。邮件主题为“服务终止通知”，称呼她只是“你好”：

Three days later, on February 16, 2020, Grove was fired from Amazon via email. The message with the subject line “Notice of Service Termination” addressed her simply as “Hello”:

你好，

Hello,

我们的记录显示，您多次未完成所有指定的递送任务。每次出现这种情况时，您都应该收到一封电子邮件提醒。

Our records indicate that, on multiple occasions, you did not attempt all assigned deliveries. You should have received an e-mail alert for each of these occurrences.

由于这些违规行为，我们将终止与您的协议。您的账户已被停用，您将无法再参与 Amazon Flex 计划。

Due to these violations, we are terminating our agreement with you. Your account has been deactivated and you will no longer be able to participate in the Amazon Flex program.

格罗夫认为她是在算法的帮助下被解雇的。

Grove believes that she was terminated with the help of an algorithm.

读到邮件时，她很沮丧，担心自己付不起车贷。她开始怀疑自己，想知道如果自己没接那一班，这种情况会不会发生，或者想想自己是不是应该加班。“你后悔了，”格罗夫说。她试图对这个决定提出上诉，但没有成功。（亚马逊表示，他们不使用自动化系统或算法来解雇配送员。该公司表示，所有解雇决定均由团队中的人工决定，并调查所有司机的申诉。）

She was upset when she read the email and worried that she wouldn’t be able to make her car payments. She second-guessed herself, wondering if this would have happened if she didn’t pick up that one shift or thinking maybe she should have worked extra hours. “You have this regret,” Grove said. She tried to appeal the decision, but no luck. (Amazon said that it does not use automated systems or algorithms to fire delivery partners. The company said that humans on their teams determine all termination decisions and investigate all driver appeals.)

直到今天，她仍然不知道自己被亚马逊解雇的确切原因。“你永远没法通过电话和人沟通。你永远没法和亚马逊的人力资源部门进行口头交流。”

To this day, she doesn’t know the exact reason why she was fired from Amazon. “You can’t speak to a person over the phone ever. You never have a verbal conversation ever with Amazon HR.”

疫情刚开始，格罗夫就被解雇了，这让她陷入了经济困境，尤其是她的一个房客竟然停止支付房租。“我意识到我根本赚不到足够的钱来支付信用卡、抵押贷款等等，”她说。“我离无家可归只有一个月了。”

Grove was terminated just as the pandemic started, which put her in a tough spot financially, especially when one of her tenants stopped paying rent. “I basically realized that I wasn’t going to be able to make enough money to pay credit cards and mortgages and everything,” she said. “I’m one month away from being homeless.”

她停止了支付任何与生存无关的费用。她仍然欠着房贷、车贷和信用卡的钱。“所以我现在负债累累。我的信用评级很差，但我认为在这个经济形势下，我不是唯一一个处于这种境地的人，而且我还活着，”她说。

She stopped paying anything that she didn’t need to pay to survive. She still owes money for her mortgage, her car, and her credit cards. “So I’m now in debt. My credit rating is shit, but I don’t think I’m the only one in this economy that’s in that position and I’m still alive,” she said.

她说得对：克莱尔·格罗夫并不孤单。至少她不是唯一一个被亚马逊解雇的人。维姬·格雷厄姆，一位二十五六岁、留着红色脏辫的黑人女性，也曾是亚马逊 Flex 的司机，她认为自己是被自动化系统解雇的。

She’s right: Claire Grove is not alone. At least not alone getting terminated by Amazon. Vicky Graham, a Black woman in her mid-twenties with red dreadlocks, is also a former Amazon Flex driver and believes she was fired by an automated system.

2020年，疫情最严重的时候，她大学毕业，获得了表演专业的美术学士学位。“我当时真的很想找一份灵活的工作，这样我就能安排自己的时间，同时还能随时寻找其他职位，并在需要的时候参加试镜。”

In 2020, during the height of the pandemic, she graduated college with a BFA in acting. “I was really looking for jobs that were flexible, that I was able to kind of create my own schedule while I was able to still look for other positions and audition whenever I needed to.”

安全是另一个担忧，所以Uber和Lyft根本不可能。“我年轻的时候，不太放心车里载别人。我更愿意载东西，而不是载人，”她说。

Safety was another concern, so Uber and Lyft were out of the question. “I didn’t feel comfortable having other people in my car as a young female. I would much rather transport things instead of people,” she said.

她开始使用 Postmates 等送餐应用程序，然后是 DoorDash，但没有稳定的收入，而且必须依赖陌生人，而陌生人当天可能想要也可能不想要送餐，这让她感到压力很大。

She started with food delivery apps like Postmates, then DoorDash, but it was stressful not having a consistent income and being dependent on strangers who may or may not want food delivered that day.

后来她听说了亚马逊 Flex：“而在亚马逊，总是有班次，总是有包裹。即使包裹不够，你仍然有机会拿到钱。” 在她之前位于马里兰州哥伦比亚市（巴尔的摩和华盛顿特区之间）的家附近，亚马逊每小时支付 18 至 21 美元的包裹递送费。

Then she heard about Amazon Flex: “Whereas Amazon, there were always shifts, there were always packages. Even if there weren’t enough packages, you still had the opportunity to get paid anyway.” Amazon paid between $18 and $21 per hour for package delivery near her former home in Columbia, Maryland, which is between Baltimore and Washington, DC.

“我当时有点犹豫要不要申请，一方面是因为我内心不想成为杰夫·贝佐斯赚更多钱的原因之一，但另一方面，我当时也拿到了工资，而且工作时间和待遇都很好。” 与在外卖应用上工作相比，在亚马逊工作，她能用更少的时间赚到更多的钱。她尝试过每周为 Amazon Flex 工作大约 25 个小时。

“I was a little hesitant to apply and do it, because part of me was, I don’t want to be part of the reason why Jeff Bezos gets even more money, but also I was getting paid and the hours and the pay were really good.” She would make more money in less time working for Amazon than for food delivery apps. She tried to work around twenty-five hours per week for Amazon Flex.

Amazon Flex 司机与亚马逊的所有连接都通过一个应用程序进行，格雷厄姆表示，这个应用程序从第一天起就存在问题。她说，她花了大约一周时间才注册。即使注册后，该应用程序仍然出现故障。在应用程序几次将她引导到根本不存在的道路后，她决定同时运行谷歌地图和亚马逊应用程序。

Every connection an Amazon Flex driver has with Amazon is routed through one app, which Graham described as buggy from day one. She said it took her about a week to sign up. Even after she signed up, the app continued to malfunction. After the app directed her a few times to roads that didn’t exist, she decided to run Google Maps simultaneously with the Amazon app.

总的来说，她很喜欢送包裹：“我从小就喜欢看HGTV（家居与园艺电视节目）。所以我很喜欢开车穿过不同的街区，看看不同的房子，”格雷厄姆说。

In general, she enjoyed delivering packages: “I’m the kind of person who always watched HGTV [Home & Garden Television] since I was a child. So I really like driving through different neighborhoods and seeing different houses,” Graham said.

最让人恼火的是取货点的签到流程。她几乎每次去取货都要等上四十分钟。她曾在不同的亚马逊配送中心注册过包裹。那段时间是无偿的。

A frustrating part was the sign-in process at the pickup locations. It took about forty minutes of waiting almost every time she wanted to pick up packages at the different Amazon fulfillment centers she had signed up to. That time was unpaid.

另一方面，调度应用程序中的算法缺陷有时对她有利。大约每五次取货中，亚马逊就会安排过多的 Flex 司机，导致她要么只收到几个包裹，要么一个包裹都没有，但仍然可以拿到整个街区的货款。

On the flipside, sometimes the algorithmic flaws in the scheduling app worked in her favor. About every fifth pickup, Amazon scheduled too many Flex drivers and she either got only a couple of packages or none at all but would still be paid for her whole block.

她认为她的评分很高，因为她在完成工作时从未遇到任何问题。

She believes her ratings were high because she never had any issues with getting the job done.

但维姬·格雷厄姆认为，正是这个存在漏洞的应用程序导致她在为亚马逊 Flex 开车一年多后被“神秘解雇”。当时她正试图在亚马逊取包裹，她以为自己已经通过应用程序登录了，但却收到了上班迟到的通知。她与几位经理进行了沟通，他们也尝试帮她登录，并向她保证已经登录了。

But Vicky Graham thinks the buggy app caused her “mysterious termination” over a year after she started driving for Amazon Flex. She was trying to pick up packages at Amazon and she thought she had signed in via the app but got a notification that she was late to her shift. She spoke with different managers, who also tried to sign her in and assured her they had done so.

几天后，她就无法再使用该应用程序了。

A few days later she lost access to the app.

“我以为是技术问题，或者我需要更新应用程序，或者我需要删除它并重新下载。我试了好几次。我只是以为是技术故障，因为那主要是我对这个应用程序感到沮丧。我不认为我做错了什么，”她说。

“I was thinking it was a technical issue or I needed to update the app or I needed to delete it and redownload it. I did all of that multiple times. I was just expecting a technical error, because that was mostly my frustration with the app anyway. I didn’t think I did anything wrong,” she said.

她给技术支持发了邮件，却被告知要删除并重新下载应用程序，她说她已经这样做过很多次了。“我没法和真人通话。这才是我最终想要的。但所有的电话号码都是自动拨出的，我甚至连正确的号码都打不通，”格雷厄姆说。

She emailed technical support but was told to delete and redownload the app again, something she said she had done many times already. “I couldn’t talk to a real person. That’s ultimately what I wanted to do. But all of the phone numbers were automated and I couldn’t even press the right number to get to a real person,” Graham said.

绝望之下，她拨打了西雅图亚马逊的电话，但没人能帮她，这让她感到无助：“我对那些贪婪的公司感到沮丧，他们把一切都自动化了，因为他们唯一关心的就是赚钱。我觉得很多很多时候，真正的人际关系、同情心和同理心都会消失。”

Desperate, she called a phone number at Amazon in Seattle, but no one was able to help her and it made her feel helpless: “I just get frustrated with very greedy companies who automate everything because all they care about is the money that they’re making. I feel like a lot of the actual personal connection and compassion and empathy is lost a lot of the time.”

她发现自己被解雇了，是因为技术支持人员给她发了一封邮件，说他们不必透露解雇原因。直到今天，她仍然不知道自己在2021年2月被解雇的原因。之后，她陷入了经济困境，不得不再次使用DoorDash和其他外卖服务来支付账单。

She found out she was fired when tech support emailed her stating that they did not have to disclose why someone was terminated. To this day, she does not know why she was terminated in February 2021. Afterward, she struggled with money and went back to DoorDash and other delivery services to pay her bills.

我当时真的太惊讶了，完全不知道该怎么办。我几乎放弃了，因为很明显，这封邮件里装了个自动程序，只要听到这些关键词就会自动回复。所以我根本没法跟人沟通。

“I was just so surprised. I didn’t know what to do. I just kind of gave up on the situation as a whole, because it’s clear that there’s just some automated program in this email that’s just supposed to spit out these responses when they hear these keywords. So I’m not going to be able to talk to a person.”

她决定暂时停止从亚马逊购物。

She decided to stop buying from Amazon for a while.

（亚马逊表示，格雷厄姆和格罗夫被解雇是因为他们“屡次违反计划政策”。）

(Amazon stated that Graham and Grove were offboarded because they “repeatedly violated program policies.”)

内部人士的观点

THE INSIDER VIEW

康奈尔·考西（Cornell Causey）是一位四十多岁的特种部队老兵，也是一名承包商。2019年，他辞去了军事承包商的工作，因为他想留在美国，陪伴家人。他曾在亚马逊仓库担任主管，亲眼目睹了仓库管理的另一面——管理人员如何被要求使用算法和技术来追踪、训斥和解雇亚马逊仓库员工。

Cornell Causey is a Special Operations Forces veteran and a contractor in his forties. He left his job as a military contractor in 2019 because he wanted to stay stateside and spend time with his family. He worked as a supervisor in Amazon warehouses and got to see the other side—how managers were instructed to use algorithms and technology to keep track of, reprimand, and terminate Amazon warehouse workers.

他的梦想是为亚马逊工作，因为即使他先是作为一名士兵，后来又成为一名承包商，驻扎在阿富汗和尼日尔偏远危险的地区，亚马逊也总能给他寄送包裹：“你下单，它就到了，”考西说。“如果你看到一些在我们在阿富汗时的照片中，如果你看我们身后，你会看到堆积如山的亚马逊箱子，里面装着我们订购的东西。”

His dream was to work for Amazon because even when he was stationed in remote and hazardous areas in Afghanistan and Niger as a soldier and then as a contractor, Amazon was always able to send him packages: “When you ordered it, it came,” Causey said. “If you see some of the pictures of when we were in Afghanistan, if you look behind us, you’ll see mountains of Amazon boxes from stuff that we had ordered.”

考西是一位留着花白胡须的黑人男子，他将简历发布在领英上，几乎立刻就被亚马逊的招聘人员联系。该公司为他提供了8.5万美元的年薪，让他在迈阿密的亚马逊配送中心担任经理，负责监督员工从移动货架上挑选商品并将其装箱。

Causey, who is a Black man with a salt-and-pepper beard, put his résumé on LinkedIn and almost immediately was approached by an Amazon recruiter. The company offered him $85,000 for a job as a manager at an Amazon fulfillment center in Miami, where he oversaw associates who picked the merchandise from mobile shelves and put it in boxes.

他热爱这份工作，热爱迈阿密，也钦佩亚马逊严谨的运营方式。“亚马逊的一切，每一件事，都经过数字化追踪，”他说，“他们的工作效率，他们把所有东西准备好送货的速度，以及司机扫描包裹、装上货车、准备发货的速度。”

He loved the job, he loved Miami, and he admired how tightly Amazon ran the business. “Everything with Amazon is tracked digitally. Every single thing,” he said. “The rate people work. How fast they get everything ready to go for delivery. How fast it takes drivers to scan their packages and put them in their van and get ready to go.”

例如，所谓的“拣货员”的工作被分解成几个易于监控的任务：他们必须从移动货架上取下一件商品，确认无误后再放入货箱。每个拣货员每小时必须完成一定数量的此类任务（通常约为 300 到 350 个），才能达到“完成率” 。2

The work of so-called pickers, for example, is broken down into a few tasks that can be easily monitored: they have to pick an item off a mobile shelf, confirm that it’s the correct one, and place it in a bin. Every picker has to do a certain number of these tasks (usually around 300 to 350) per hour to “make rate.”2

在算法规则下工作基本上意味着人类变得更像机器人：他们的工作被分解成几个重复性的任务，这些任务由算法监督，算法根据生产力目标决定他们的命运。

Work under algorithmic rules basically means that humans have become more like robots: their work is broken down into just a few repetitive tasks that are overseen by algorithms that determine their fate based on productivity targets.

虽然有人工管理，但他们也必须遵守规则。考西说，追踪手下员工的状况让他苦不堪言。如果有人“没达到标准”，他就必须去找员工，了解情况，然后向他们宣读电脑生成的警告。

There were human managers, but they also had to abide by the rules. Tracking the associates working under him made Causey miserable, he said. When someone didn’t “make rate,” he had to go see the employee, find out what had happened, and read them a computer-generated warning.

即使有人“达到了标准”，但百分比却垫底，他也必须去指导他们。“说到底，这不是为了达到某个数字，”考西说。“他们只是希望你更加努力。”

Even when folks “made rate,” but they were in the bottom percentage points, he had to go coach them. “At the end of the day, it’s not about hitting a certain number,” Causey said. “They just want you to work harder.”

员工可能会因为工作效率、行为或工作质量问题而受到谴责。考西认为自动化决策并不总是正确的。“我确实看到很多事情让我感到不公平，人们受到了不人道的对待。”

Workers could be reprimanded for problems with their productivity, behavior, or quality of their work. Causey didn’t think that the automated decisions were always right. “I definitely saw a lot of things that I felt were unfair and people were treated less than human.”

考西说，有些人可能会感到惊讶的是，造成不公平待遇的往往不是人类，而是机器。

What may be surprising to some is that it wasn’t the humans that most often caused the unfair treatment, Causey said. It was the machines.

“上级经理别无选择；‘我知道你很努力，但电脑告诉我，我需要指导你。尽管我喜欢你，了解你，也看到你努力工作，但我不能违背这个原则。你今天不知怎么地跌到了倒数5%，我必须指导你，因为如果我不这样做，电脑就会说我没有做好我的工作。’”他回忆道。

“The managers who were over them had no choice; ‘I know you were trying, but the computer is telling me that I need to coach you. I can’t go against that as much as I like you and as much as I know you and I’ve seen you working hard. You somehow fell in the bottom 5 percent today and I have to coach you because if I don’t, the computer is going to say I’m not doing my job,’” he recalled.

康奈尔·考西唯一能做的就是加个注释，解释为什么有人当天表现不佳。“‘哦，你父亲今天去世了？我可以把这写进注释里，但我不知道谁会读到它。’”他说。

The only thing Cornell Causey was able to do was add a note that explained why someone may have underperformed that day. “‘Oh, your father died today? I can put that in my note, but I don’t know who’s reading it,’” he said.

如果工人收到的警告次数过多，最终会被解雇。“如果他们没有达到工资标准，他们基本上就会找个理由解雇，”考西说。他自己也因涉嫌违反安全规定而被解雇。

If workers accumulated too many warnings, they eventually would be let go. “If they weren’t hitting their rates, they would basically just find a reason to terminate,” Causey said. He himself was let go for an alleged safety violation he said.

自动发射

AUTOMATICALLY FIRED

亚马逊自己也承认，它一直在通过算法解雇仓库工人。在亚马逊因劳资纠纷向国家劳工关系委员会提交的文件中（该文件最先由The Verge发布），一位代表亚马逊的律师表示，公司解雇仓库工人并非因为工会活动，而是因为他们没有达到由算法设定的“生产率” 。3

Amazon itself admitted that it had been terminating warehouse workers via algorithm. In documents Amazon filed with the National Labor Relations Board because of a labor dispute, first published by The Verge, a lawyer working on behalf of Amazon stated that the company was firing warehouse workers not because of union activities but because they were not meeting their “productivity rates,” which are set by an algorithm.3

该律师还表示，这些解雇不是由人类管理人员发起的，而是由算法发起的：“收到与生产相关的通知的标准完全是客观的——生产系统自动生成所有与生产相关的警告和解雇通知，无需主管人员的输入。” 4

The lawyer also stated that the terminations were not initiated by human managers but by algorithms: “The criteria for receiving a production related notice is entirely objective—the production system generates all production related warning and termination notices automatically with no input from supervisors.”4

我想知道，用一刀切的方法来监控员工是否正确？难道我们每个人都不一样吗？难道有些人比其他人更强壮吗？有些人体型更大，有些人体型更小吗？也许有些人有健康问题。对每个人都一视同仁的方法公平吗，尤其是对残疾人来说？

I wonder if a one-size-fits-all method is the right way to monitor workers? Aren’t we all different? Aren’t some people stronger than others? Are some larger and some smaller? Maybe some folks have health conditions. Is a same-for-everyone approach fair, especially for people with disabilities?

“这些技术的使用不仅增强了雇主的权力，也降低了他们考虑个体差异、员工情况或工作场所不同情况发生原因的积极性。这鼓励他们采取这种僵化的、一刀切的方法来监控员工，”民主与技术中心高级政策顾问马修·谢勒（Matthew Scherer）表示。

“The use of these technologies is not only increasing employers’ power, but it’s decreasing their incentive to take into account individual variations and workers’ circumstances or the reasons that different things happen in the workplace. It encourages them to take this rigid, one-size-fits-all approach to monitoring their workforce,” said Matthew Scherer, senior policy counsel at the Center for Democracy and Technology.

除了生产率之外，亚马逊还会追踪员工未完成分配任务的时间——这被称为“任务停工时间”（TOT）。如果员工的TOT时间过长，可能会被解雇。除了算法追踪员工时间之外，让亚马逊许多仓库员工感到不满的是，即使TOT是由于机械故障导致员工无法继续工作，算法仍然会追踪TOT。5

In addition to the productivity rates, Amazon tracks how long employees are not doing their assigned tasks—it’s called time off task (TOT). If someone has too many TOTs, they can be terminated. What’s upsetting to many warehouse employees at Amazon besides algorithms tracking their time is that the algorithms still track TOT even when it’s caused by mechanical failures that do not allow them to continue to work.5

信息和数据存在不平衡。“雇主收集的关于工人的信息量远远超过工人掌握的关于雇主如何使用这些信息以及如何评估他们的信息量，”谢勒说。在许多仓库，工人不允许携带手机，所以即使他们想记录问题，也做不到。一些仓库工人每次传送带断裂或系统出现故障时，他们都会用纸笔记录下来，这样他们就可以反驳算法关于他们没有做出速率的说法。

There is an information and data imbalance. “The amount of information that employers collect about workers is dramatically greater than the information that workers have about how the employers are using that information and how they are being assessed,” Scherer said. In many warehouses, workers are not allowed to bring their cell phones, so even if they wanted to document problems, they can’t. Some warehouse workers document with pen and paper every time a conveyor belt breaks or a system is down so they can refute the algorithm’s claim that they didn’t make rate.

谢勒表示，即使人类经理参与其中，也很难违抗算法。所以，如果算法建议人力资源经理解雇某人，很难推翻该建议。“在这种情况下，对他们来说最容易的事情就是解雇这个人。与机器争论，试图说‘我要推翻它，让这个人继续在那里工作’，可不是件容易的事，”谢勒说。

And even if a human manager is in the loop, it’s hard to defy an algorithm, said Scherer. So, if an algorithm recommends that an HR manager fire someone, it’s hard to override the recommendation. “What’s going to be the easiest thing for them to do in that situation is to fire them. It’s not going to be easy to argue with the machine and try to say, ‘I’m going to override it and let this person keep working there,’” Scherer said.

“这些技术对工人的控制力可能无所不包。我认为危险在于，它们正在扼杀工人任何干预、投入或发挥能动性的机会。这与一百年前的感觉截然不同，”加州大学伯克利分校劳工中心技术与工作项目主任安妮特·伯恩哈特说道。（亚马逊表示，认为公司设定固定配额是一种普遍的误解。相反，亚马逊表示，其绩效评估基于安全且可实现的期望，这些期望基于时间和任期、同事绩效以及对安全工作规范的遵守情况。）

“These technologies are potentially so all-encompassing in terms of their control over workers. I think the danger is that they are shutting off any sense, any opportunities for intervention or input or agency by workers. And that feels very different than a hundred years ago,” said Annette Bernhardt, director of the Technology and Work Program at the University of California Berkeley Labor Center. (Amazon said that it is a common misconception that the company has fixed quotas. Instead, Amazon says that it assesses performance based on safe and achievable expectations that are based on time and tenure, peer performance, and adherence to safe work practices.)

持续的监控也会导致解雇。Sommer Ketron 是 Jumpstart:HR 的顾问。她与中小型公司合作，帮助他们满足人力资源需求。

The constant surveillance also plays a role in firings. Sommer Ketron is a consultant with Jumpstart:HR. She works with small to medium-size companies and helps them with their human resources needs.

她回忆说，在她担任公司内部人力资源主管期间，曾有几次监控员工电脑日志成为解雇员工的主要证据。从其中一份日志中，她了解到一名员工大部分工作日都在约会网站Plenty of Fish上度过。他因此被解雇。另一名负责监管未成年员工的员工在工作时观看色情内容，还被终止。所有这些都是在计算机日志中发现的，这些日志是通过算法记录员工在工作电脑上访问的每个网站而得出的。

She recalled that while she was working as in-house HR, there were a couple instances where monitoring the logs of employees’ computers became the main evidence in their termination. From one of these logs she learned that one employee spent most of their workdays on the dating website Plenty of Fish. They were terminated. Another employee, who supervised minor employees, was watching porn at work and was also terminated. All of this was uncovered in computer logs from algorithms that recorded every website employees visited on work computers.

算法统治

RULED BY ALGORITHMS

大多数员工并不知道算法是否参与了他们的招聘、晋升或解雇。安妮特·伯恩哈特认为，正因如此，这些人工智能工具才远不如社交媒体算法受到关注。“算法是如此隐形，目前，这些系统对员工和政策制定者来说都像个黑匣子，”她说道。

Most workers wouldn’t know if an algorithm was involved in their hiring, promotion, or firing. That’s why these AI tools have gotten way less attention than social media algorithms, Annette Bernhardt, believes. “It’s so invisible, and right now, these systems are a black box to workers and to policymakers alike,” she said.

研究人员必须进行侦查工作，才能查明雇主使用了哪些监控工具：“目前，我们基本上是在对这项技术对员工造成的危害进行逆向工程，”她说。而公众看到的只是冰山一角。“这实际上体现了监管或监督的缺失，”伯恩哈特说。

Researchers have to do detective work to find out which surveillance tools employers use: “We are at this point largely reverse engineering the tech from the harms to workers,” she said. And the public is seeing only the tip of the iceberg. “That is really an illustration of the lack of regulation or oversight,” Bernhardt said.

美国几乎没有法律禁止在工作场所使用监控技术。多年来，一些法律提案被提出，但面临严峻的障碍。6

There are few laws forbidding surveillance tech in the workplace in the United States. Some laws have been proposed over the years but have faced stiff hurdles.6

与此同时，正如我们所见，越来越多的公司正在使用监控系统：“我们正处于一个快速发展、快速升级的采用阶段，”伯恩哈特说道。“在我看来，现在正是我们开始认真讨论是否以及在多大程度上监管这项技术的关键时刻，因为如果我们等到十年后，就太晚了。现在这匹马已经跑出马厩了。”

Simultaneously, as we have seen, more and more companies are now using surveillance systems: “We are in for a very steep, quickly escalating adoption phase,” Bernhardt said. “In my mind, this is exactly the critical moment for us to start a robust discussion about whether and how much to regulate this technology, because if we wait till ten years from now, it’s too late. The horse is out of the barn.”

对安妮特·伯恩哈特来说，就我们目前掌握的知识而言，我们的未来一片黯淡。改变必须立即发生。

To Annette Bernhardt, our future looks dark with the knowledge we already have today. Change needs to happen now.

“这里的反乌托邦之路实际上是，工人基本上变成了有血有肉的机器人，几乎没有能力自己做决定，也没有能力质疑对他们做出的决定，无论是由“这可以由算法决定，也可以由雇主决定，或者两者共同决定，”伯恩哈特说。“这就是此刻的不同之处。”

“The dystopian path here is literally that workers become basically robots in the flesh with almost no ability to make their own decisions, to question the decisions that are being made about them, either by the algorithm or by the employer or the two working together,” Bernhardt said. “That is what feels different about this moment.”

她希望工人能够参与进来，与雇主共同决定在工作场所应该使用哪些技术。

She wants workers to be at the table, deciding together with employers what technologies should be used in the workplace.

*由于害怕遭到报复，莉齐要求隐去她的姓氏。

* Lizzie asked to have her last name withheld for fear of retribution.

结语

EPILOGUE

生活在一个有预测能力的社会

Living in a Predictive Society

我当我开始研究人工智能在职场中的应用时，我兴奋不已。“终于，”我心想，“找到一个解决人类招聘偏见的方案了。” 但当旅程结束时，我感到有些沮丧，因为我知道至少有一些个人和公司用来做出招聘决策的工具不起作用。至少有一些公司正在根据带有偏见的垃圾算法做出高风险的招聘决策，这些算法会造成真正的伤害，并阻碍合格人才获得工作。

I was so excited when I started this journey researching AI in the world of work. “Finally,” I thought, “a solution to biased human hiring.” But at the end of this journey, I feel a bit demoralized knowing that at least some of the tools people and companies use to make employment decisions do not work. At least some companies are basing high-stakes employment decisions on biased and junk algorithms, which cause real harm and prevent qualified people from getting jobs.

从人工智能供应商那里购买这些工具的公司必须更好地审查算法。“公司应该对此感到担忧，因为如果算法失效，他们就等于白白花了数百万美元，承受了不必要的复杂性和风险。从商业角度来看，这很不划算，”美国最大的人工智能招聘平台供应商之一 Modern Hire 的前执行副总裁 Eric Sydell 说道。Modern Hire 于 2023 年 5 月被 HireVue 收购。合并后，Sydell 离开了公司。

The corporations buying these tools from AI vendors must do a better job vetting the algorithms. “Companies should be concerned about that because when [the algorithms] don’t work, they’re paying millions of dollars for nothing, and complexity that they don’t need and risk that they don’t need. That’s no good from a business perspective,” said Eric Sydell, former executive vice president of Modern Hire, one of the largest AI hiring platform vendors in the United States. Modern Hire was bought by HireVue in May 2023. Sydell left the company after the merger.

正确地做到这一点并非易事。许多购买或监督这些系统的人缺乏足够的怀疑，没有提出正确的问题，也没有要求看到这些系统有效的证据，这可能是因为他们借助人工智能是为了让自己的生活更轻松，而不是更艰难。

Doing it the right way is hard work. Many people buying or overseeing these systems are not skeptical enough, are not asking the right questions, and are not demanding to see proof that these systems work probably because they are resorting to AI to make their lives easier, not harder.

真相被精心包装的营销语言所掩盖，很难被揭穿。但我们必须做得更好。人们的未来取决于此。

The truth is coated in beautifully crafted marketing language and it’s hard to break through that. But we have to do better. People’s futures depend on this.

“我的手机能用，因为我能看到它在用。我不需要一直查看它是否有效。它响了，我就知道它有效。但算法不是这样，”赛德尔说。检查算法很难，因为它们的计算通常是不可见的。许多人力资源工具会生成排名，从而降低申请人数量，这样看起来系统运行良好。但正如我们所见，事实可能并非如此。
