“My phone works because I can see that it works. I don’t have to check it all the time to see if it works. It rings and I know it works. But algorithms aren’t like that,” Sydell said. It’s hard to check algorithms because their calculations often are invisible. Many HR tools produce a ranking and decrease the applicant pool, so it looks like the system is doing well. But, as we have seen, that might not be the case.

“供应商当然希望你认为它在任何地方都有效，”他说。“不，它不是。劳动力的人口结构、求职者群体都在变化，良好绩效的衡量标准也在随着时间推移而变化，文化因素也在变化，人口结构和地理区域也各不相同，规范也各有不同；各种各样的因素都会影响算法的效果，使其变得更好或更差。”

“The vendor wants you to think that it works everywhere, of course,” he said. “No, it doesn’t. The demographics of the workforce, the applicant pool change, what good performance looks like changes over time, cultural things change, and demographics and geographical regions are different and have different norms; all kinds of things come into it and make algorithms work better or less well.”

这些技术的发展速度实际上超越了法规，许多供应商利用这些法规为所欲为。“在缺乏明确的指导方针、法规和规则的情况下，没有什么能让他们遵守任何完美、高标准的行事方式。如果你在偏见和隐私方面遵守规定——你应该这样做——显然，这并不意味着算法是好的，”Sydell 说。

The technologies are essentially outpacing regulations, which many vendors use as a carte blanche to do what they want. “In the absence of clear guidelines, regulations, rules, there’s nothing necessarily making them conform to any perfect, great high-standard way of doing things. If you are compliant in terms of bias and privacy, which you should be, obviously that doesn’t mean the algorithm is any good,” Sydell said.

雇主需要测试人工智能工具是否适用于公司中的特定岗位。“在使用之前，你需要在员工身上进行验证。你不能仅仅相信他们说的，就认为它在实际应用中是有效的。”“因为你们公司的软件工程师和那家公司的软件工程师做的工作不一样，所以你们会为另一家公司招聘软件工程师，”民主与技术中心高级政策顾问马修·谢勒 (Matthew Scherer) 表示。“我认为这些雇主经常忽略的一点是，他们没有尝试批判性地思考‘这项测试是否考察了那些让我在工作中取得成功的关键因素？’”

Employers need to test that the AI tools will work for specific roles in their companies. “Before you use it, you need to validate it on your workforce. You can’t just take their word for it that it’s valid when hiring software engineers for another company because your software engineers do different things than the software engineers at that other company,” said Matthew Scherer, senior policy counsel at the Center for Democracy and Technology. “The thing that I think is often missing for these employers is they don’t try to think critically about ‘is this test testing for the key things that make somebody successful at the job for which I’m using it?’”

在担任现职之前的三年多时间里，Matthew Scherer 一直在 Littler Mendelson 律师事务所担任律师，该事务所专攻劳动法。他的专长是算法招聘工具和数据分析。很多公司在准备与供应商签订合同时才找到他，这让他的工作更加困难，尤其是当他不得不告知对方该工具性能不佳时。“这些工具一直很差劲。它们在识别优秀候选人方面表现不佳，”他说道。

For over three years prior to his current position, Matthew Scherer was a lawyer at the firm Littler Mendelson, which specializes in labor and employment law. His expertise was in algorithmic hiring tools and data analytics. Companies often came to him late in the game when they were ready to sign a contract with a vendor, which made his job harder, especially when he had to break the news that the tool wasn’t very good. “Consistently, the tools were shitty. They weren’t doing a very good job of identifying good candidates,” he said.

当你真正尝试用这些工具来预测某个特定工作的成功时，它们的效果并不好；它的效果并不比随机从帽子里抽出一个候选人的名字好多少。它们之所以不太准确，是因为它们太过笼统和概括。

“These tools don’t work very well when you actually try to use them to predict success in a specific job; it’s not doing much better than randomly picking a candidate’s name out of a hat. They just aren’t very accurate because they are so generic and so generalized.”

因此，相信供应商会严格审核其产品并非良策。“我的经验是，你不能指望或依赖供应商一定会这样做，”Eric Sydell 说道。

So, trusting a vendor to critically audit its own product is not the answer. “What I’ve learned is you can’t expect or rely on the vendor to necessarily do that,” Eric Sydell said.

第一步可能是提出一些尖锐的问题：“什么数据？什么分析？你如何确保它仍然有效？它如何改进？你如何避免收集数据带来的隐私问题？” Sydell 说。如果我是人力资源经理，我会问：“供应商如何验证这个工具是否适用于我们正在招聘的职位？”

A first step could be to ask tough questions: “What data, what analytics? How are you making sure that it still works? How is it improving? How are you avoiding privacy concerns with the data you’re collecting?” Sydell said. And if I was an HR manager, I would ask the question, “How did the vendor validate this tool for the roles we are hiring for?”

但 Sydell 也承认，对于人力资源经理甚至大公司来说，审查算法非常困难。“这太难了，因为这些“算法太复杂了，没人能理解，”他说。“要真正核实这些供应商的说法，需要做很多工作。你必须查阅研究；你必须查看数据；你必须分析；你必须看看他们使用了哪些技术。研究设计好吗？你必须有多个拥有不同专业知识的博士参与才能真正做好这项工作。但谁有这个能力呢？没有人。”

But Sydell also acknowledged how difficult it is for HR managers and even large companies to vet algorithms. “It’s too hard because these algorithms are so complicated and nobody understands them,” he said. “To really vet what those vendors are saying, it’s a lot. You’ve got to look at studies; you’ve got to look at data; you’ve got to look at analytics; and you’ve got to see what techniques they used. Is the study design good? You have got to have multiple PhDs involved with different expertise to really do a good job. But who has that? Nobody.”

一种解决方案是监控算法的结果。结果公平吗？算法是否符合公平的招聘和工作惯例？使用一段时间后，它们是否仍然正常运行？“在我看来，所有这些问题的解决方案是更好的监控——持续的、更好的监控。这个行业不是这样设置的，”正在创办自己的审计公司的赛德尔说道。“招聘行业不希望这样。他们希望你相信他们提供给你的统计数据和你最终会经历的一样，因为他们不希望事情被持续监控。那样会增加更多的工作量，增加更多的成本。”

One solution is to monitor the results of the algorithms. Are the results fair? Are the algorithms complying with fair hiring and work practices? And are they still functioning properly after being in use for some time? “What the solution is for all these things, in my opinion, is better monitoring—continual, better monitoring. The industry is not set up that way,” said Sydell, who is in the process of starting his own auditing company. “The hiring industry, they don’t want that. They want you to take on faith that the statistics they throw at you are what you will experience too, because they don’t want things to be continually monitored. That’s more work, that’s more cost.”

有时，律师会建议雇主公司不要仔细研究这些人工智能工具或收集任何数据，因为在诉讼中，他们可能不得不披露他们的测试和数据。但另一方面，专家表示，不采取任何措施审查算法会造成危害。“如果你没有数据，也不去查看数据，那么你肯定会做错——肯定会。这其中存在偏见，而且缺乏有效性，”Sydell 说。监管可以通过强制第三方持续监控来提供帮助。

Sometimes, lawyers advise employer companies not to take a closer look at these AI tools or to collect any data because in a lawsuit they then might have to disclose their tests and their data. But, on the other hand, not doing anything to vet algorithms creates harm, experts say. “If you don’t have the data and you’re not looking at the data, guaranteed, you’re doing it wrong—guaranteed. There’s bias and lack of effectiveness,” Sydell said. Regulation could help here by mandating continual monitoring by a third party.

这些算法不会消失，研究人员和记者不应放弃从外部调查它们，以追究行业责任。我完全支持创新和新方法，但它们必须有效且公平。

These algorithms aren’t going away, and researchers and journalists should not give up trying to investigate them from the outside to keep the industry accountable. I am all for innovation and new approaches, but they have to work and be fair.

我希望科学能够进步，独立研究人员能够重现研究结果，法规能够确保我们受到保护。

I hope the science improves, independent researchers can reproduce the findings, and regulations ensure we are protected.

我们的未来会是什么样的？

WHAT DOES OUR FUTURE LOOK LIKE?

万宝盛华集团（ManpowerGroup）的管理心理学家兼首席创新官托马斯·查莫罗-普雷穆齐克（Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic）描绘了一幅人工智能主导的未来黯淡图景。他预测，我们的数据将越来越多地被上传到网上，算法将越来越擅长解读我们的“数据废气”，无论是我们在亚马逊上的购物模式、Nest 恒温器上的温度偏好、Spotify 上的音乐选择，还是我们的推特动态。一切都将成为算法的目标，而所有这些加在一起，将使人工智能更好地了解我们是谁。

Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic, the management psychologist and chief innovation officer at ManpowerGroup, paints a bleak picture of an AI-mediated future. He predicts that more and more of our data will be online and algorithms will get better at interpreting our “data exhaust,” whether it’s our buying patterns on Amazon, our temperature preferences on Nest thermostats, our music choices on Spotify, or our Twitter feeds. Everything will be fair game for the algorithm, and everything together will give AI a good sense of who we are.

“生活将会像一场永无止境的求职面试，”他说。“我们所做的一切都将被人工智能和算法监控，并用于计算职业潜力和工作潜力。” 查莫罗-普雷穆齐克说，最终我们甚至不需要申请工作。未来，算法将根据我们留下的数据尾气为我们匹配工作。

“Life will seem like a never-ending job interview,” he said. “Everything we do will be monitored by AI and algorithms and will be used to compute career potential and job potential.” Eventually, we won’t even need to apply for work, Chamorro-Premuzic said. In the future, algorithms will match us to jobs based on the data exhaust we leave behind.

那将是我们所熟知的隐私的终结。

And that would be the end of privacy as we know it.

我们正处于这个新时代的早期阶段，但一些雇主已经开始使用自动背景调查来剔除那些起诉过前雇主的求职者。还有一些雇主正在利用人工智能来寻找合适的求职者。

We are in the early stages of this new era, yet some employers are already using automatic background checks to weed out job applicants who have sued their former employers. And others are using AI to find the right personalities for a job.

供应商正在讨论将人们的技能验证和教育成就放在区块链服务器上，以便招聘人员和雇主轻松访问这些信息。

Vendors are discussing placing people’s skills verifications and educational achievements on a blockchain server, which would make them easily accessible to recruiters and employers.

其他公司，例如Dice.com，已经开发出一些产品，可以抓取社交媒体网站的数据，并从中构建人员的技能档案。根据一项针对该公司的集体诉讼，Dice 的算法抓取了数十个社交媒体网站，并创建了科技行业从业人员的就业档案。招聘人员随后向 Dice 付费以获取这些档案的访问权限。

Other companies, such as Dice.com, have developed products that scrape social media websites and build skills profiles of people from their data exhaust. According to a class action lawsuit against the company, Dice’s algorithm crawled dozens of social media sites and created employment profiles of people working in the tech industry. Recruiters then paid Dice for access to these profiles.

诉讼称，许多员工并不知道自己的信息已被录入数据库。伊恩·道格拉斯和其他科技开发者表示，该网站的个人信息有误。道格拉斯要求公司删除他的个人资料（他本人并未创建），但遭到了拒绝。2019年，Dice同意支付100万美元以和解这起集体诉讼，并大幅改变其商业惯例，允许消费者访问、请求更改甚至删除他们的Dice个人资料。1

Many workers didn’t know they were in the database, according to the lawsuit. Ian Douglas and other tech developers said that the website had incorrect information on them. When Douglas asked the company to delete his profile, which he hadn’t set up, Dice refused. In 2019, Dice agreed to pay $1 million to settle the class action lawsuit and to substantially change its business practices by allowing consumers to access, request changes to, and even delete their Dice profiles.1

另一家软件公司正试图将这个想法更进一步。在一次管理心理学会议上，一位企业家找到我，他正试图建立一个关于员工的技能评分系统，而不是为他们量身定制。就像现已停用的Klout评分系统（该系统根据人们的在线社交影响力进行评分）一样，他的公司也试图为每个人建立一个技能评分系统。他将其描述为一种信用评分，只是针对技能——他希望雇主愿意付费给他的初创公司，以查看潜在员工的技能评分。接受评估的员工不一定能获得这些分数。

Another software company is trying to take this idea one step further. At a management psychology conference, I was approached by an entrepreneur who is trying to build a skill score system about workers—not for them. Like the now-defunct Klout score, which gave folks a score based on their online social influence, his company is attempting to build a skill score for everyone. He pitched it like a credit score, just for skills—he hopes that employers will pay his start-up to see the skills scores on potential employees. The workers being judged wouldn’t necessarily have access to these scores.

我想知道技能或教育水平的变化会如何更新。我们的数据是否存储在这些数据库中，我们是否有发言权？

I wondered how changes in skills or education level would be updated. Will we have a say whether our data is stored in these databases?

诸如此类的技能评分制度，加上不靠谱的即时性格测试和通过社交媒体持续进行的背景调查，与中国备受诟病的社会信用评分相差无几。当然，两者的区别在于，中国政府会对自己的公民进行评分。某些违规行为——例如乱穿马路或不缴纳法院罚款——可能意味着政府会将一个人列入黑名单，并限制其参与社会活动的能力，例如购买飞机票或火车票。2

Ideas like this skill score system, plus dodgy instant personality tests and continuous background checks through our social feeds, are not far from China’s much-criticized social credit score. One difference, of course, is that the Chinese government will score its own citizens. Certain infractions—jaywalking or not paying a court fine—could mean that the government will essentially blacklist a person and curtail their ability to participate in society, such as buying airplane or train tickets.2

这在西方民主国家可能不太可能发生，尽管各国政府也在使用基于人工智能的监控工具来更好地了解本国民众。但很多权力掌握在私营企业手中，与民主选举产生的政府相比，其透明度明显较低。

That’s probably not in the cards in Western democracies, although governments are also using AI-based surveillance tools to learn more about their own people. But a lot of power rests with private corporations, which have significantly less transparency than democratically elected governments.

如果我犯了个小错误，比如在推特上对某人发火，或者在回复一条带有厌女情绪的推文时说了脏话，该怎么办？如果学生给我这个教授留下了负面评价，该怎么办？算法会拒绝我的工作机会吗？或者我的大学会解雇我吗？

What if I make a small mistake, like getting angry with someone on Twitter and answering a misogynist tweet with a swear word? What if a student leaves a negative review of me as their professor? Will an algorithm reject me for a job opportunity or will my university fire me?

尽管性格特征并不能很好地预测工作中的成功，但正如我们所见，雇主正在使用这些测试和人工智能从我们的数据中提取这些特征。

Although personality traits are not very predictive of success on the job, as we have seen, employers are using these tests and AI to pull those traits out of our data exhaust.

这个算法监控的新时代不仅威胁着我们的隐私，也威胁着我们对人类主权的认知。它可能会剥夺我们选择职业和人生目标的自主权和自由意志。

This new era of surveillance by algorithm not only threatens our privacy but also threatens our idea of human sovereignty. It may take away our agency and free will to choose our career and who we want to be.

我们真的应该相信公司会为求职者和员工构建一个充满人性的未来吗？还是我们需要开始向立法者施压，要求他们强制透明化并规范算法，确保算法能够像宣传的那样有效，帮助我们构建一个既能维护我们行动意志，又能将人性置于工作和社会中心的未来？

Should we really trust companies to build a human future for their job applicants and employees? Or do we need to start pressuring lawmakers to mandate transparency and regulate algorithms to make sure they work as advertised and help us build a future that preserves our will to act and keeps our humanity at the center of work and society?

我认为我们需要采取行动。测试这些工具可以发现某些技术存在诸多缺陷。我希望这能带来改变，让人们对供应商的说法产生更多质疑。

I believe we need to act. Testing these tools shows how flawed some of the technologies are. I hope it brings about change and greater skepticism of vendors’ claims.

写这本书让我明白，我们需要付出更多努力，抵御那些掌控我们生活、对我们做出高风险决策的恶意算法——很多时候我们甚至毫不知情。市场存在的问题在于，供应商几乎没有动力去改进产品或持续监控算法，因为成本高昂。

Writing this book has shown me that we need to do more to fight off bad algorithms ruling our lives and making high-stakes decisions about us—many times without us ever knowing. What’s problematic in the marketplace is that the vendors have very little incentive to make their products better or to monitor their algorithms over time because it would be costly.

初创企业面临着扩大规模、销售产品、被收购并向投资者支付回报的资金压力，这阻碍了很大一部分市场自我监管。这项技术过于复杂，大多数人难以理解。对供应商及其客户公司来说，大家对工具存在的问题保持沉默也有利。结果就是，许多人工智能工具买家和普通公众都不知道哪些工具好用，哪些工具是垃圾。

The monetary pressure for start-ups to scale, sell their products, and get bought to give investors a payout is strong, preventing large parts of the market from regulating itself. The technology is too complicated for most people to understand. It is also to the benefit of vendors and their client companies for everyone to keep quiet about problems with the tools. The result is that many AI tool buyers and the general public do not know which tools are decent and which are junk.

我在撰写本书的过程中萌生了一个想法，那就是减轻人工智能工具开发面临的资金压力。如果我们可以成立一个非营利组织，专门为公众利益测试和开发人工智能工具，会怎么样？我现在就正在为此努力。这样的项目将汇集研究人员、计算机科学家、社会科学家、记者、心理学家、项目经理、数据科学家、统计学家以及其他相关领域的专业人士，共同解决我们能够预见的人工智能相关问题。例如，我们可以尝试编写一个公正有效的简历筛选程序。我们会仔细记录每一次迭代，最终验证其可行性。所有这些研究都将面向所有人开放，希望这能给企业施加压力，促使他们选择合适的工具，而不是那些听起来最神奇的工具。聊天机器人、人工智能游戏和其他用于招聘的人工智能工具也是如此。我们可以测试和构建它们，并展示哪些方法有效，哪些无效。我们还可以测试它们是否方便残障人士使用，以及它们是否具有预测性。

One idea that came out of my journey writing this book is to take the monetary pressure off building AI tools. What if we could start a not-for-profit organization that will test and build AI tools in the public interest? I am working on that right now. Such a project would bring together researchers, computer scientists, social scientists, journalists, psychologists, project managers, data scientists, statisticians, and others to solve the problems with AI that we can foresee. For example, we could try to program a résumé screener that is unbiased and that works. We would carefully document every iteration and see at the end whether this is possible or not. All of that research would be available to anyone, and hopefully that would put pressure on companies to choose the right tools and not the ones that sound most magical. The same goes for chatbots, AI games, and other AI tools used for hiring. We could test and build them and show which methods are successful and which are not. We could also test whether they are accessible for people with disabilities and whether they are predictive.

如果可能的话，我们会进行纵向研究，了解评估如何预测候选人在工作中的成功。我们会获得雇主的认可和法律许可，以便对新员工群体进行两三年甚至更长时间的跟踪。

If possible, we would run longitudinal studies to understand how assessments might predict a candidate’s success on the job. We would obtain buy-in and legal clearance from employers in order to follow cohorts of new hires for two or three years or longer.

也许最终，基于这些证据，我们或许会得出这样的结论：即使是最好的人工智能工具也无法预测人类未来的行为，包括在新工作中取得成功。最近的一项研究表明，人工智能工具可能并不擅长预测未来。

And maybe at the end, looking at the evidence we may or may not conclude that even the best AI tools are unable to predict what humans will do in the future, including being successful at a new job. A recent study showed that AI tools may not be very good at predicting the future.

预测社会结果有用吗？

DOES PREDICTING SOCIAL OUTCOMES WORK?

事实证明，预测午餐吃什么（可能是羽衣甘蓝沙拉或三文鱼沙拉）很容易，因为我讨厌花时间做决定，总是点差不多的东西。然而，预测我是否会擅长一份工作却要难得多。

It turns out that predicting what I will have for lunch (probably some kind of salad with kale or salmon) is easy because I am the type of person who hates spending time on decision-making and just keeps ordering more or less the same thing. Predicting if I will be good at a job, however, is much harder to do.

几十年来，招聘人员一直在努力为合适的岗位找到合适的人才。从入职一年半后辞职或被解雇的人数来看，大约有50%的员工在入职一年半后就辞职或被解雇，这表明我们在人岗匹配方面仍然做得不够好。所以，或许我们应该给人工智能一个机会？但到目前为止，我所经历的人工智能应用体验并不乐观。

People in charge of hiring have been trying to find the right people for the right jobs for decades. Judging by the number of people who quit or are fired after starting a new job, which is about 50 percent of employees after a year and a half, we are still not very good at matching people to positions. So maybe we should give AI a chance? But so far, the experiences with AI that I have chronicled are not encouraging.

为什么预测一个人能否成功如此困难？在职场中，大多数公司只会雇佣一个人，而很少考虑招聘过程中的其他诸多变量。团队怎么样？老板是不是有毒？同事怎么样？公司文化如何？新员工的个人生活也会以各种方式影响他们的表现——也许他们突然需要照顾亲人，或者出现健康问题，又或者正在经历离婚。

Why is it so challenging to predict whether someone will be successful? In a work setting, most companies hire an individual and don’t often think about the many other variables that go into hiring. What’s the team like? Is the boss toxic? What are coworkers like? What is the company culture? And there are myriad ways a new employee’s personal life can impact their performance—maybe they suddenly have to take care of a loved one. Or they develop a health condition. Or they are going through a divorce.

预测未来的招聘和其他社会结果，包括预测前科犯是否会再次犯罪，极具挑战性，因为没有人确切知道未来会发生什么。人类至今仍未真正预测未来，但谈到人工智能，我们似乎相信，凭借数千个数据点，计算机可以做到这一点。

Predicting the future for hiring and other social outcomes, including forecasting whether a former convict will commit another crime, is very challenging because no one knows exactly what the future will hold. No human has been able to predict the future, but when it comes to artificial intelligence, we somehow believe that with access to thousands of data points a computer can do exactly that.

即使我们使用数千个数据点和机器学习算法，仍有证据表明预测未来可能不可靠。数十位科学家共同开展了一项大型研究，这项研究发表于2020年。他们邀请了457名研究人员（160个团队）预测美国四千多个家庭的个人社会结果。科学家们从一项正在进行的研究中获得了关于这些家庭的高质量数据，该研究记录了他们从孩子出生到十五年后的生活（该研究仍在进行中）。3

Even when we use thousands of data points and machine learning algorithms, there is evidence why predicting the future might be unreliable. Dozens of scientists worked together on a large study that was published in 2020. They asked 457 researchers (160 teams) to predict the individual social outcomes of more than four thousand families in the United States. The scientists had high-quality data on these families from an ongoing study that chronicled their lives from the time their children were born to fifteen years later (it’s ongoing).3

研究人员要求参与者预测家庭在六个方面面临的社会结果：GPA、毅力、物质困难、裁员、被驱逐和职业培训。他们提出的问题包括：孩子的家庭会面临物质困难吗？主要抚养人会被解雇吗？孩子的GPA是多少？孩子的家庭会被驱逐吗？孩子有毅力吗？主要抚养人会接受职业培训吗？研究人员并没有具体询问工作成功与否，但预测这类社会结果与预测某项工作的成功类似，而“毅力”这样的特质在职场上非常抢手。

The researchers asked participants to predict families’ social outcomes in six categories: GPA, grit, material hardship, layoff, eviction, and job training. They asked questions like: Will a child’s household face material hardship? Will the primary parent be laid off? What GPA will the child have? Will the child’s household be evicted? Will the child have grit? Will a primary caregiver receive job training? The researchers didn’t specifically ask about success at a job, but predicting these kinds of social outcomes is similar to predicting success in a given job, and traits like “grit” are in high demand in the workplace.

这项研究的伟大之处在于，科学家们已经掌握了研究结果，因此掌握了基本事实数据。预测结果可以与已知的社会结果进行核对。

The great thing about this study was that the scientists had access to the outcomes already, so there was ground truth data. The prediction could be checked against the known social outcomes.

为了解答这些问题，参与研究的团队收集了“脆弱家庭”研究*中全部4242个家庭的数据。该研究追踪了家庭从出生到九岁的整个过程。从出生到九岁的数据非常丰富，每个家庭有12942个变量，为数百万种可能性提供了可能。4

To answer the questions, the participating research teams received data for all 4,242 families in the Fragile Families study,* which tracked families from birth onward. The data from birth to nine years old is so rich that there were 12,942 variables per family, bringing the possible options to millions of possibilities.4

机器学习专家们渴望拥有如此海量的数据来预测招聘结果。该领域的大多数供应商都要求提供更多数据，认为这将提高准确性。

Such a mountain of data is something that machine learning folks would love to have to predict hiring outcomes. Most vendors in the space ask for more data, arguing it will increase accuracy.

除了家庭从孩子出生到九岁的数据外，研究人员还获得了一半家庭在孩子十五岁时的六项结果。因为他们知道如果一半家庭遭遇了这种情况，他们的算法能预测另一半家庭的结果吗？孩子十五岁左右时，他们的GPA会是多少？这个家庭是否经历过被驱逐？

In addition to the data of families from the birth to age nine of their child, the researchers were given access to the six outcomes for children at age fifteen for half of the families in the study. Because they knew what happened to half of the families, could their algorithms predict the outcomes of the other half? When a child was around fifteen, what would their GPA be? Had there been an eviction in the household?

这看起来像是一个简单的数据科学挑战。大量的数据和预测社会结果应该很简单——招聘和人员分析领域的人工智能供应商每天都在做这件事。

This seemed like a straightforward data science challenge. Lots of data and predicting social outcomes should be straightforward—AI vendors in hiring and people analytics do it every day.

事实证明，做出这些预测绝非易事。所有机器学习提交的预测准确率都极低。总共提交了160份预测，其中1.0分表示预测准确率100%。即使是最好的一份预测，在“物质困难”类别中也只有0.23分。GPA预测准确率为0.19，而针对勇气、驱逐、职业培训和裁员等问题的最佳算法，其预测未来结果的准确率为0.07。在统计学中，任何低于0.3的准确率都被认为是弱预测。

It turned out that making these predictions wasn’t easy at all. None of the machine learning submissions were rated very high for accuracy. There were 160 submissions, with a score of 1.0 indicating a 100 percent accurate prediction. Even the best submission scored only .23 in the category of Material Hardship. GPA prediction was at .19, and the best algorithms for grit, eviction, job training, and layoffs predicted future outcomes accurately at a .07 rate. Anything under .3 is considered a weak prediction in statistics.

“我们发现，即使是最好的预测也不太准确……尽管脆弱家庭的数据包含了数千个变量，以帮助科学家了解这些家庭的生活，但参与者仍然无法做出准确的预测，”研究人员写道。

“We discovered that even the best predictions were not very accurate…. Even though the Fragile Families data included thousands of variables collected to help scientists understand the lives of these families, participants were not able to make accurate predictions,” wrote the researchers.

令人震惊的是：在 160 份提交的数据中，即使是最好的机器学习算法也无法很好地预测这些孩子的未来将如何发展。

Here is what’s striking: out of the 160 submissions, even the best machine learning algorithms didn’t perform well in predicting how the futures of these children would unfold.

科学家们还想看看机器学习模型与传统预测模型的比较结果。他们与一位专家合作，在数千个数据点中只考虑了四个变量：母亲的种族/民族（一个值得怀疑的变量！）；孩子出生时父母的婚姻状况；教育水平；以及孩子九岁时的一个结果。5

The scientists also wanted to see how the machine learning models compared to traditional predictive models. They worked with an expert and considered only four variables out of the thousands of data points: race/ethnicity of the mother (a questionable variable!); marital status of the parents at the birth of the child; education level; and one result when the child was nine.5

事实证明，仅使用四个变量的传统预测模型几乎与最好的机器学习算法一样好。事实上，传统模型的表现甚至优于许多机器学习算法。算法。但这项研究仍然表明，机器学习算法和传统方法都不太擅长预测未来。

It turned out that the traditional predictive models that used only four variables were almost as good as the best machine learning algorithms. In fact, the traditional models outperformed many of the machine learning algorithms. But still, this study shows that neither machine learning algorithms nor traditional methods are very good at predicting the future.

在求职等应用场景中，这意味着数据科学家用来预测求职者成功率的机器学习算法可能与传统基准相比表现不佳。“在预测社交结果方面，人工智能并不比仅使用少数特征的人工评分好多少，”普林斯顿大学计算机科学教授阿尔温德·纳拉亚南 (Arvind Narayanan) 表示。6

In applied settings such as job searches, this means that the machine learning algorithms that data scientists use to predict job applicants’ success could be underperforming when compared to traditional benchmarks. “For predicting social outcomes, AI is not substantially better than manual scoring using just a few features,” said Arvind Narayanan, computer science professor at Princeton University.6

如果公司需要一种方法来筛选求职者，手动评分是更好的选择，因为用户可以选择特征。种族、性别或其他人口统计变量的替代变量可能存在偏见，而且在大型数据集中通常难以避免，可以根据用户的知识进行消除。这一点很重要，因为许多人工智能专家要求提供越来越多的数据来改进他们的预测。但正如这项研究表明的那样，如果数据被用来预测未来以及人类的行为，更多的数据可能并无帮助。但正如我们在本书中所看到的，即使是像邮政编码这样看似中立的标准，也可能导致算法中的种族歧视。

If companies need a method to select job applicants, manual scoring is preferable because the user can select features. Proxies for race, gender, or other demographic variables that might be biased and that are often hard to avoid in large data sets can be eliminated to the best of the users’ knowledge. This matters because many AI experts ask for more and more data to improve their predictions. But as this study shows, more data might not be helpful if the data is being used to predict the future and what humans will do, but as we have seen throughout this book even a neutral-looking criterion like zip codes can result in racial discrimination in algorithms.

此外，许多机器学习算法使用深度神经网络，因此其结果通常难以解释，甚至对开发人员来说也难以理解。独立审计人员和研究人员即使能够检查用于构建模型的训练数据，也很可能无法验证或重现这些结果。

Additionally, many machine learning algorithms use deep neural networks, so the findings are often hard to explain, which makes the algorithms opaque even to developers. Independent auditors and researchers most likely can’t verify or reproduce these findings even if they can examine the training data that was used to build the model.

想象一下这样的系统：“每次你被拦下，警察都会将你的数据输入电脑，而不是在驾照上扣分。大多数时候你都可以逍遥法外，但到了某个时候，黑匣子系统会告诉你，你不再被允许驾驶。 ” 7不幸的是，如今我们在很多领域都存在这种系统，”纳拉亚南说道。包括招聘。

Imagine a system like this: “Instead of points on a driver’s license, every time you get pulled over, the police officer enters your data into a computer. Most times you get to go free, but at some point, the black box system tells you you’re no longer allowed to drive.7 Unfortunately, we have this kind of system today in many domains,” Narayanan said. Including hiring.

正因如此，Narayanan 和其他专家建议供应商和数据科学家至少应该考虑使用传统方法，因为在这项大型研究中，传统方法的得分与人工智能方法相当甚至更高，但所需的数据量却很小。使用哪种数据也由供应商决定，供应商可以选择歧视性较小的变量，因此收集较少的数据通常可以减少隐私、法律和道德问题，并减少歧视。

That’s why Narayanan and other experts suggest that vendors and data scientists should at least contemplate using traditional methods because they scored on par or better than AI methods in this large study but needed only a fraction of the data. What kind of data is used is also decided by the vendor, who can choose less discriminatory variables, so collecting less data usually causes fewer privacy, legal, and ethical problems and less discrimination.

正如我在第一章中所述，用名字来预测工作成功显然是带有偏见且不道德的，应该被禁止。但由于人工智能招聘算法在很大程度上是保密的，因此很少有人发现这些机器内部出了什么问题。其他方法，例如使用推特信息或评估面部表情来预测性格，都是侵入性的，并且缺乏坚实的科学依据。

As I described in Chapter 1, using first names to predict success in a job is obviously biased and unethical and should be made illegal, but because AI hiring algorithms are kept largely secret, not many folks find out what goes wrong inside these machines. Other methods like using Twitter feeds or assessing facial expressions to predict personality are invasive and not based on solid science.

我们可以回去吗？

CAN WE GO BACK?

那么，为什么不干脆回到回归分析呢？对阿尔温德·纳拉亚南来说，这个想法的问题在于商业利益。供应商想要销售昂贵的人工智能产品，他们不断告诉我们需要使用机器学习和大量数据。但在大多数情况下，他说：“手动评分规则同样准确，而且更加透明，值得考虑。” 但有些规则需要更多劳动力，而且通常不如人工智能辅助决策那么快。

So, why not just go back to regression analysis? For Arvind Narayanan, the problem with that idea is commercial interests. Vendors want to sell expensive AI products and they keep telling us that we need to use machine learning and lots and lots of data. But in most cases, he said, “manual scoring rules are just as accurate, far more transparent, and worth considering.” But some are more labor intensive and often not as fast as AI-assisted decision-making.

纳拉亚南和他撰写的《脆弱家庭》算法研究的合著者并非唯一注意到这个问题的人。大卫·富特雷尔曾任沃尔玛的选拔和评估总监，沃尔玛是美国最大的私营雇主。他和他的团队运营着全球最大的招聘机器之一，每天评估数千名沃尔玛求职者。

Narayanan and his coauthors of the Fragile Family algorithm study are not the only ones who observed this problem. David Futrell was the director of selection and assessment at Walmart, which is the largest private employer in the United States. He and his team ran one of the largest hiring machines on the planet and assessed thousands of Walmart applicants every day.

他在2020年一次行业会议的小组讨论中分享了自己使用人工智能和机器学习工具的经验：“我第一次看到这些工具时就非常兴奋。多年来，我一直使用回归和相关技术进行一种传统的预测，而很多机器学习工具只是一种超快且复杂的方法，可以测试所有可能的组合。”

He shared his experience with AI and machine learning tools on a panel at an industry conference in 2020: “I was very excited by these tools whenever I first started seeing them. So I’ve been doing a kind of traditional prediction using regression and correlation techniques for many years and a lot of these machine learning tools are just superfast and sophisticated ways to test all of the possible combinations.”

由于 Futrell 的团队每天评估数千人，他手头上掌握着海量数据，避免了样本量过小等可能导致结果偏差的问题。他要求团队测试许多新的人工智能工具。结果他很失望：“我们在测试和实践中发现，机器学习的预测结果并没有比传统方法好多少。”

Because Futrell’s team assessed thousands of people a day, he had an abundance of data at his fingertips and didn’t run into such problems as small sample size, which could skew results. He asked his team to test a lot of the new AI tools. And he was disappointed: “When we tested this and in practice, we didn’t find the machine learning predictions to be substantially better than the old-fashioned way.”

因此，无论是在计算机实验室还是在应用环境中，人工智能的表现都没有超越传统的统计模型。而且两种方法都没有实现太多的统计相关性。

So, neither in computer labs nor in applied settings did AI outperform traditional statistical models. And neither method achieved much statistical relevance.

“这些问题很难解决，因为我们无法预测未来，”阿尔温德·纳拉亚南说道。“这应该是常识。但当涉及到人工智能时，我们似乎决定将常识搁置一旁。”

“These problems are hard because we can’t predict the future,” Arvind Narayanan said. “That should be common sense. But we seem to have decided to suspend common sense when AI is involved.”

人类无法预测其他人未来的行为，统计学和数据科学也一样。在招聘中，了解某人是否胜任工作的最佳方法之一是让他们亲自去做，但这意味着公司可能不得不在入职后不久就解雇他们，从而损失收入，因为这个过程成本高昂。虚拟环境下的工作试用或许能在不久的将来给我们带来更多预测性答案，但没有人能够预测外部因素对某人工作表现的影响。一些专家表示，在招聘过程中可以更多地考虑候选人的团队和经理。

Humans can’t predict how other humans will act in the future, nor can statistics or data science. In hiring, one of the best ways to understand whether someone is good at the job is to have them do the job, but that means companies might have to fire people shortly after hiring them, losing revenue in the process, since the process can be expensive. Job trials in virtual settings might give us more predictive answers in the near future, but no one can predict extraneous influences on someone’s job performance. Some experts say that more can be done to take into account the candidate’s team and managers during the hiring process.

此外，雇主使用多种评估方式来测试候选人可能会有所帮助；他们可以评估工作的不同方面了解候选人的技能要求，从而更好地了解他们。当然，这需要花费更多资金。公司还应该进行工作分析，以确定职位所需的技能，这又是一项额外的成本，而且经常被人工智能工具忽略。

Also, it might be helpful for employers to use more than one assessment to test candidates; they can assess on different aspects of the job requirements to get a better picture of the candidate. But, of course, that costs more money. Companies also should do a job analysis to find which skills are needed in a role, which is another extra cost and often gets shortchanged with AI tools.

对于阿尔温德·纳拉亚南 (Arvind Narayanan) 来说，招聘是使用机器学习算法最糟糕的领域之一，因为人工智能的预测并不明确：“在算法招聘中，没有明确的预测目标。我们对如何定义一个人是一名好员工意见不一，因此这些系统一开始就从一个定义不明确的任务开始。”

To Arvind Narayanan, hiring is one of the worst areas to use machine learning algorithms because what the AI is predicting is unclear: “In algorithmic hiring, there are no clear prediction targets. We don’t all agree on what it means for someone to be a good employee and so these systems are starting off with a very poorly defined task.”

公司希望聘用“高效”或“优秀”的员工，但这究竟意味着什么？又该如何衡量呢？雇主甚至不知道如何量化“高效”或“优秀”，如果预测的目标本身就模糊，他们又如何预测呢？“据我所知，这些公司并没有真正拿出证据，证明这些系统能够预测出一些可衡量的未来绩效，”纳拉亚南说道。

Companies want to hire “productive” or “good employees,” but what does that mean? And how can we measure it? Employers don’t even know how to quantify “productive” or “good,” so how can they predict anything if the target of the prediction is fuzzy? “As far as I’ve seen, these companies are not really producing evidence that these systems are predicting some measurable future performance,” Narayanan said.

这话虽然残酷，但却是事实。在测试了这么多工具之后，我也不确定很多公司究竟在用他们的AI招聘和生产力工具衡量什么。“我把它们称为精密的随机数生成器，我坚持这个说法。我认为它们除了削减成本之外，真的没什么用，”纳拉亚南说。

That’s harsh but true. After testing so many tools, I am also not sure what many companies are measuring exactly with their AI hiring and productivity tools. “I’ve called them elaborate random number generators and I’m sticking to that. I think they really accomplish nothing other than cost cutting,” Narayanan said.

许多公司使用人工智能工具来填补小时工职位，而人力资源经理在这个领域会收到大量申请，并且经常需要招聘大量员工。“公司经常用人工智能工具来填补那些被低估的职位，而且公司并不关心最终会雇佣谁，”纳拉亚南说道。“当务之急是让这个过程尽可能高效。所以，从这个角度来看，人工智能或许可以实现他们的目标，但随机数生成器也能实现。认为可以真正量化这些关于工作绩效的指标，然后进行预测——我认为这是不合理的。我认为这些系统根本没有做到这一点。”

Many companies use AI tools to fill hourly positions, an area where HR managers receive lots of applications and regularly have to hire lots of people. “Companies are often using them for positions that are undervalued, and companies don’t care about who they ultimately end up hiring,” Narayanan said. “The imperative is to really make that process as efficient as possible. And so maybe from that perspective, it achieves their goals, but so would a random number generator. The idea that you can really quantify these things about job performance and then predict them—that’s the part that I find incoherent. I think these systems are not really doing that at all.”

他并不是唯一一个这么想的人。

He is not the only one who thinks this.

由于销售产品的财务压力，确保工具有效（这需要时间）并非许多供应商的首要任务。“很容易就推出一些不太好的东西，作弊，破坏科学流程，”Modern Hire 前员工 Eric Sydell 说。“科学卖不出去。”

Because of financial pressures to sell products, making sure the tools work, which takes time, is not a priority for many vendors. “It’s too easy to put stuff out that’s not that great and to cheat and to short-circuit the scientific process,” said Eric Sydell, formerly of Modern Hire. “Science doesn’t sell.”

对阿尔温德·纳拉亚南来说，证明这些系统有效运行的举证责任应该落在供应商身上。供应商应该能够透明地展示他们的系统有效运行，并让其他人进行测试。

To Arvind Narayanan, the burden of proof that these systems work should be on the vendor. Vendors should be able to show transparently that their system works and let others test it.

那么，有什么更好的方法吗？在医学领域，医生和患者出于合理的考虑，倾向于优先尝试创伤较小的手术：损伤和损失较小，疼痛较轻，并发症也较少。我建议我们在招聘人工智能时也采用同样的策略：使用透明的算法，包括传统的回归分析，这些算法经过验证且公平公正，然后强制测试所有基于人工智能的算法。

So, what’s a better way? In medicine, doctors and patients tend to try less invasive surgeries first for logical reasons: there is less injury and loss, they cause less pain, and there are fewer complications. I suggest we use the same playbook for AI in hiring: let’s use transparent algorithms, including traditional regression analysis, that are validated and fair and then mandate to test all AI-based algorithms.

在医学领域，尤其是新药领域，制造商必须证明新药比安慰剂更有效。为此，公司会进行随机对照试验。“我认为这应该成为所有决策领域的标准，”纳拉亚南说。

In medicine and especially for new medications, manufacturers have to prove that a new medication works better than a placebo. To do that, companies run randomized controlled trials. “I think that needs to become standard in every domain of decision-making,” Narayanan said.

在招聘过程中，情况可能是这样的：公司首先会确定成功的定义。然后，他们会聘用那些通过第三方（例如非营利研究团队）在算法上被标记为“成功”或“不成功”的候选人。（因此，招聘公司并不知道候选人是如何被标记的。）

In hiring it could look like this: Companies first would decide what constitutes success. Then, they would hire candidates who have been algorithmically labeled “successful” or “unsuccessful” through a third party, a not-for-profit research team, for example. (So the hiring company doesn’t know how the candidates have been labeled.)

“所以，他们俩都受聘了，然后你比较他们三年后的表现，规模是几百人或几千人，”纳拉亚南说。如果被标记为“成功”的人确实比被标记为“不成功”的人在统计上更成功，那就证明这个算法是有效的。

“So both of them get hired and then you compare their performance three years down the line and at a scale of hundreds or thousands of people,” Narayanan said. If the folks labeled “successful” are truly more successful by a large statistical margin than the folks labeled “unsuccessful,” it would prove that the algorithm worked.

我们还可以通过与随机选择进行比较来测试AI工具。例如，如果一家公司正在招聘卡车司机，第三方或非营利组织可以使用AI工具来招聘该工具筛选出的最合格的人员。同时，他们也会招聘那些符合最低资格要求（例如商业驾驶执照）但随机选择的候选人。哪种招聘方法能在三年后培养出更多成功的员工？

We could also test AI tools by comparing them to random selections. For example, if a company is hiring truck drivers, a third party or nonprofit could use an AI tool to hire the most qualified folks the tool selects. At the same time, they would also hire candidates who have the minimum qualifications (like a commercial driver’s license) but who are chosen at random. Which hiring method produces more successful employees three years down the road?

当然，在招聘领域，这种做法闻所未闻，但这正是证明这些人工智能工具是否真正有效所必需的。“希望由此获得的知识能够在未来很长一段时间内造福数十亿求职者，”纳拉亚南说道。

It’s of course unheard of in hiring to do such a thing, but that’s what’s needed to prove whether these AI tools really work. “The knowledge that’s going to be gained out of this is hopefully going to benefit billions of job seekers for a long time to come,” Narayanan said.

与此同时，我希望立法者能够了解行业现状，并开始强制要求培训数据和技术报告的透明度。如果政府机构开始测试这类工具，甚至为警务、招聘、职场监控、信用评级和刑事判决等领域使用的高风险人工智能决策工具开发某种类似FDA的实体，那就太好了。

In the meantime, I hope lawmakers will get wise to what’s happening in the industry and start mandating transparency of training data and technical reports. It would be great if government agencies started testing these types of tools and even developed some sort of FDA-like entity for high-stakes AI decision tools used in such areas as policing, hiring, surveillance at work, credit rating, and criminal sentencing.

目前，纽约市、其他市政当局和各州正在努力强制销售招聘工具的供应商接受偏见审计。8这是一个值得称赞的目标。我深入研究了审计工作，发现两家聘请第三方公司审计其人工智能工具的供应商都得到了有争议的结果，但他们却利用审计来加强营销。简而言之：聘请自己的审计师会造成利益冲突，我们也看到过类似的系统崩溃。例如，在2008年金融危机爆发前，许多银行和投资公司付钱给第三方来“审计”和评估他们的投资工具。许多次级抵押贷款被捆绑在一起，并被评为AAA。

Right now, New York City, other municipalities, and states are working on making bias audits mandatory for vendors that sell hiring tools.8 That’s a laudable goal. I have dug deep into auditing and found that the two vendors that hired third-party companies to audit their AI tools both had controversial outcomes but used the audit to bolster their marketing. In short: hiring your own auditors creates conflicts of interest, and we have seen similar systems break down. In the lead-up to the financial crisis in 2008, for example, many banks and investment firms paid third parties to “audit” and rate their investment vehicles. Many subprime mortgages were bundled together and rated AAA.

纽约市目前已立法，将只关注偏见的审计系统，有望确保歧视性算法消失，但它不会解决利益冲突，也不会帮助公众了解这些算法是否真的能够挑选出最合格的申请人，或者只是精心设计的数字生成器。

An audit system that is solely focused on bias, which is now the law in New York City, would hopefully make sure that discriminatory algorithms disappear, but it wouldn’t solve conflicts of interest and it wouldn’t help the public understand if these algorithms actually work in picking the most qualified applicants or are just elaborate number generators.

更好的制度是由一个独立的政党或政府制定明确的透明度和有效性标准，并在这些工具上市前对其进行偏见和有效性测试。必须提供证据证明人工智能工具不存在歧视，包括歧视有色人种、残疾人和特定年龄段的人。这种透明度也有助于其他人，包括研究人员、记者和计算机科学家，独立测试这些系统。

A better system would be for an independent party or the government to set clear standards of transparency and effectiveness and test these tools for bias and validity before they are allowed on the market. Evidence that AI tools do not discriminate, including against people of color, people with disabilities, and people of a certain age, would have to be produced. This transparency would also help others, including researchers, journalists, and computer scientists, independently test these systems.

如果政府不愿意采取行动，非营利组织和民间社会利益相关者可能会介入并提供足够的资金来测试和构建符合公众利益的人工智能工具。

If the government is not willing to act, nonprofits and civil society stakeholders may be able to step in with enough funding to test and build AI tools in the public interest.

规范该行业的另一种方法是赋予员工更多权力，让现有员工有权决定在他们身上使用哪些技术以及使用哪些技术来招聘求职者，类似于德国和奥地利的工作委员会正在做的事情。

Another way to regulate the industry is giving employees more power and letting current employees have a say about which technologies are used on them and are used to hire applicants, similar to what works councils in Germany and Austria are doing.

这就是我们控制垃圾算法，确保它们不再造成进一步危害或至少将危害降至最低的方法。但还有一个领域需要我们关注：神经科学的发展将很快对招聘和工作产生深远的影响。科学家们正在接近研制出能够读取我们思想的工具，这将对职场技术以及我们人类自身产生深远的影响。

That’s how we could rein in junk algorithms and make sure they do no further or at least very little harm. But there is another area we need to watch: developments in neuroscience will soon have a profound impact on hiring and work. Scientists are getting closer to build tools that can read our thoughts, which has vast implications for technology used in the workplace and on us humans.

我们未来想法的隐私

THE PRIVACY OF OUR THOUGHTS IN THE FUTURE

神经科学正在以惊人的速度发展，我们正处于机器学习读取我们思想的早期阶段。

Neuroscience is advancing at an incredible speed and we are in the early days of machines learning to read our thoughts.

我不知道为什么，但当我想到我们可能正在进入这个黑暗的奥威尔式社会，人工智能算法和神经科学工具正在侵占我们的私人大脑空间时，我想起了我最喜欢的一首童年歌曲，它曾经给过我希望：Die Gedanken sind frei—— “思想是自由的”。

I don’t know why, but when I think of this dark Orwellian society we might be entering, with AI algorithms and neuroscience tools encroaching on our private brain space, I recall one of my favorite childhood songs that used to give me hope: Die Gedanken sind frei—“thoughts are free.”

这首歌出现于十八世纪，以早期版本为基础，反映了压迫统治下的生活。（我不知道为什么它引起了我的共鸣——1990年代，我十二岁的时候，绝对没有想过压迫政权。）

The song emerged sometime in the eighteenth century building on earlier versions, reflecting on life under oppressive rulers. (No idea why it resonated with me—I definitely wasn’t thinking about oppressive regimes back in the 1990s when I was twelve.)

Die Gedanken sind frei，我们可以理解，

Die Gedanken sind frei, wer kann sie erraten,

思想是自由的，谁能猜得透呢？

Thoughts are free, who can guess them?

Sie fliegen vorbei wie nächtliche Schatten。

Sie fliegen vorbei wie nächtliche Schatten.

它们像夜影一样飞过。

They fly by like nocturnal shadows.

没有人能知道，

Kein Mensch kann sie wissen,

没有人能够了解他们，

No person can know them,

kein Jäger sie schießen mit Pulver und Blei

kein Jäger sie schießen mit Pulver und Blei

没有猎人可以用火药和铅射击它们。

no hunter can shoot them with powder and lead.

思想是自由的！

Die Gedanken sind frei!

思想是自由的！

Thoughts are free!

“我的思绪自由流动。我的思绪赋予我力量，”皮特·西格（Pete Seeger）在其1966年的专辑《危险歌曲》（Dangerous Songs）中诠释了“思想自由”（Die Gedanken sind frei）。9尽管我们可能生活在一个压迫性的体制下，但这首歌表明，我们的私人思想是我们自己的。但如今，预测分析和神经科学正在挑战我们作为自主个体的这一概念。

“My thoughts freely flow. My thoughts give me power,” sang Pete Seeger in his interpretation of “Die Gedanken sind frei” for his album Dangerous Songs (1966).9 Even though we might live in an oppressive system, this song suggests our private thoughts are our own. But today, predictive analytics and neuroscience are challenging the very idea of us as autonomous individuals.

人工智能系统的开发者们相信，我们内心深处受模式驱动，而算法能够发现这些模式。我们仍然可以自由地思考我们想要思考的事情，但我们的想法、偏好和行为可以被人工智能预测。

Makers of AI-based systems believe that, deep down, we are driven by patterns and that algorithms can find these patterns. We are still free to think what we want, but our thoughts, preferences, and behaviors can be predicted by artificial intelligence.

随着预测算法逐渐深入我们生活中越来越敏感和私密的领域，其他基于脑机接口的算法现在可以真正读懂我们的思想和情感。

As predictive algorithms push into ever more sensitive and private aspects of our lives, other algorithms based on brain–computer interfaces now can literally read our thoughts and emotions.

这项技术的原型是存在的：这些神经科学工具可以从我们的大脑中提取简单的单词。10

A prototype of this technology exists: these neuroscience tools can extract simple words from our brains.10

管理心理学家托马斯·查莫罗-普雷穆齐克也认为，这描绘了一幅相当黯淡的景象。“我们要进行系统性的社会工程，把人们安排到他们该去的地方吗？我经常发现，尽管这些问题让我们感到恐惧，让人们感到震惊，而且它们看起来像奥威尔式的、像《1984》那样——但我们在很多方面都正朝着这个方向发展。”

Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic, the management psychologist, agrees that this paints a rather bleak scenario. “Are we going to engage in systematic social engineering and put people where they have to be? I often find that even though the questions scare us and shock people and they look very Orwellian and 1984—we are trending in many ways toward that.”

为可怕的未来做准备

PREPARING FOR A SCARY FUTURE

这是一个黑暗的前景——在这个系统中，算法定义了我们是谁，我们擅长什么，以及我们在哪里挣扎。这关系到我们的生活方式。如果算法出错了怎么办？

It’s a dark outlook—a system in which algorithms define who we are, where we excel, and where we struggle. What’s at stake is the way we live. What if the algorithms get it wrong?

如果算法消除了人为的差异性会怎样？一个由算法运行的招聘系统可能会阻止雇主找到能够改变组织的候选人，因为严格执行算法会将选拔限制在一个基于统计分析的狭窄、主流的范围内。

What if the algorithms take away human variability? A hiring system run by algorithms could prevent employers from finding candidates who can change the organization because a rigorous application of the algorithms keeps selection to a narrow, mainstream pool based on statistical analysis.

公司可以、或者应该要求我们做的事情的限度是什么？

And what are the limits of what companies could and maybe should ask us to do?

“我们能不能鼓励人们开始做一些事情，比如增强他们的大脑？我们能不能让他们服用一些‘聪明药’和‘聪明药’之类的东西？如果你开车时感到困倦，你应该服用一些类似“服用莫达非尼（一种兴奋剂药物）来提高清醒度？如果你是一名医生，需要值48小时的班，你应该服用清醒药吗？”杜克大学法学与哲学教授妮塔·法拉哈尼问道，她研究的是新兴技术的社会影响。

“Could we also encourage individuals to start doing things like enhancing their brains? Could we ask them to take things like smart pills and smart medications? If you’re drowsy while driving, should you take something like modafinil [a stimulant medication] in order to improve your wakefulness? If you’re on a forty-eight-hour shift as a physician, should you take a wakefulness drug?” asked Nita Farahany, professor of law and philosophy at Duke University, where she investigates the social implications of emerging technologies.

也许在不久的将来，工作场所会让注意力不集中或情绪激动的员工回家。

Maybe in the near future, workplaces will send workers home who show less than stellar concentration or emotional agitation.

例如，如果人工智能工具在工作或招聘过程中使用声音生物标记，推断出你患有早期痴呆症或认知能力下降，会怎么样？公司可能不会雇用你，可能会要求你提前退休，或者可能会因为你的薪酬太高而解雇你。

What if AI tools use vocal biomarkers at work or during the hiring process, for example, and infer that you have early dementia or cognitive decline? A company might not hire you, might ask you to retire early, or might fire you because you are too expensive to employ.

算法决定我们未来的想法，与我们人类能够在工作中或工作之外蓬勃发展、不断成长的理念相悖。难道我们不应该给予人类在工作职责和生活中成长的机会吗？

This idea of algorithms deciding our future counters the idea that we, as humans, can flourish and blossom and grow in a job, or outside of a job. What happened to giving humans a chance to grow with their job responsibilities and in their lives?

我相信，从招聘和预测分析开始，构建人类的未来仍然是可能的。事实证明，我们传统的招聘方式以及选拔晋升和领导职位的方式都充满了偏见，而且效果不佳。（我们不明白为什么我们会认为自动化一个糟糕的系统就能奇迹般地解决人类无法解决的问题。）

I believe that building a human future is still possible, starting with hiring and predictive analytics. It turns out that our traditional ways of hiring people and selecting them for promotions and leadership roles are riddled with bias and don’t work well, either. (No idea why we thought automating a bad system would miraculously fix the problem humans haven’t been able to solve.)

为了构建一个人人都有机会成功的未来，我们必须开始规范人工智能系统，确保神经科学工具不会被滥用来读取我们内心深处的想法。摆脱这些侵入性工具的束缚必须被视为一项人权。

To build a future in which we all have a chance to succeed, we have to start regulating AI systems and make sure the neuroscience tools cannot be abused to read our innermost thoughts. Being free from these invasive tools must be considered a human right.

我们还需要找到回归人性的道路。人类不仅仅是数量上的实体。我们可能超出预期，也可能低于预期。我们可以应对挑战，我们不仅仅是工作和技能。

We also need to find a way back to our humanity. Humans are more than quantitative entities. We can exceed or fall below expectations. We can rise to the occasion, and we are more than our jobs and our skills.

我相信，只要对工作世界发生的事情保持透明，并抵制公司和供应商的通过测试、审计和规范算法工具，人工智能可以帮助完成一些模式识别任务，从而构建以人类为中心的未来。

I believe that with transparency about what is happening in the world of work and by pushing back against companies’ and vendors’ power by testing, auditing, and regulating algorithmic tools, AI can be helpful with some pattern recognition tasks to build a future with humans at the center.

这个世界需要对我们人类敞开大门，接纳我们的思想和创造力。我们需要有机会在工作和生活中蓬勃发展，用我们的聪明才智为他人带来惊喜。但我们需要为此而奋斗。从现在开始。

This world needs to be open to us as humans, with our thoughts and creativity. We need to be given the chance to flourish and surprise others with our ingenuity—in our jobs and in our lives. But we need to fight for it. Starting now.

*自 2023 年 1 月起，该研究更名为“家庭和儿童福祉的未来研究”。

* Since January 2023, the study is now called The Future of Families and Child Wellbeing Study.

附录

APPENDIX

尝试找工作

Trying to Find a Job

我们已经在书中讨论过一些宏观问题，但在这里我想重点介绍一下在以下情况下可以使用的具体策略：(1) 在这个新的人工智能驱动的环境中找工作时；(2) 当你认为你的公司正在追踪你时。

We have dealt with the big-picture issues in the book, but here I would like to focus on specific strategies to use (1) when looking for a job in this new AI-driven environment and (2) when you think your company is tracking you.

求职技巧

JOB APPLICATION TIPS

•不要试图通过选择独特的设计或配色方案来脱颖而出，而要使您的简历可机读：没有图像，没有两列，没有特殊字符（如与号或波浪号） - 计算机可能无法正确获取这些信息。

•Instead of trying to stand out by choosing a unique design or color scheme, make your résumé machine-readable: no images, no two columns, no special characters such as ampersands or tildes—computers may not be able to correctly ingest that information.

•使用最常用的模板。求职平台 ZipRecruiter 的首席执行官伊恩·西格尔 (Ian Siegel) 建议，使用简短明了的句子：尽可能陈述并量化成就。（纽约大学瓦瑟曼职业发展中心执行主任格雷西·萨基西安 (Gracy Sarkissian) 建议，如果你不喜欢机器可读的版本，可以考虑准备一份面向人类的简历，以便带着它去面试。）

•Use the most common template. Use short, crisp sentences: be declarative and quantify achievements where possible, said Ian Siegel, CEO of the job platform ZipRecruiter. (If you don’t like the machine-readable version, consider having a second résumé geared toward humans that you can bring to job interviews, said Gracy Sarkissian, the executive director of the Wasserman Center for Career Development at NYU.)

•列出许可证，包括许可证号码和认证。

•List licenses, including license number and certifications.

•请勿列出您的地址或位置，尤其是当您不住在工作地点附近时。

•Do not list your address or location, especially if you do not live near the worksite.

•使用项目符号在单独的部分列出您的技能，以便机器可以轻松获取。

•List your skills in a separate section using bullet points so machines can easily ingest it.

•确保你的简历与职位描述中的关键词相匹配，并使用在线简历扫描工具（Jobscan 等）将你的简历与职位描述进行比较，看看你是否适合该职位。（匹配率最好控制在 60% 到 85% 之间，因为人工智能可能会过滤掉 100% 匹配的简历，认为它们只是职位描述的副本。）

•Make sure your résumé matches the keywords in the job description and compare your résumé to the job description using online résumé scanners (Jobscan and others) to see if you are a match for the role. (Aim for a 60–85 percent match because AI might filter out 100 percent matches, considering them a copy of the job description.)

•想要扩大求职者范围的公司可能会使用人工智能来推断您是否是女性和/或有色人种。推断通常是通过您在简历中留下的代词和其他信息进行的。例如，如果您写自己是美国西班牙裔精神病学协会的成员，人工智能很可能会推断您是拉丁裔。如果有人写自己是非裔美国房地产专业人士协会的成员，软件很可能会将其归类为非裔美国人。

•Companies that want to broaden their applicant pool may use AI to infer whether you are a woman and/or a person of color. Inferences are often made by pronouns and other breadcrumbs you leave in your résumé. For example, if you write that you are a member of the American Society of Hispanic Psychiatry, the AI will likely infer that you are Latinx. If someone lists that they are a member of African American Real Estate Professionals, the software would in all likelihood classify them as African American.

•尽量避免通过求职网站申请。招聘人员告诉我，他们最先查看的简历都是直接通过公司网站申请的；如果候选人库不够，他们才会考虑通过 Indeed、Monster、ZipRecruiter 等求职平台申请的候选人。

•Do not apply via job boards if you can avoid it. Recruiters have shared with me that the first résumés they check out are from candidates who applied directly via the company’s website; if the candidate pool is insufficient, only then will they turn to candidates who applied via job platforms like Indeed, Monster, ZipRecruiter, and others.

•如果可能，请在申请工作后通过 LinkedIn 联系招聘人员。

•If possible, contact recruiters via LinkedIn after applying for a job.

•在求职平台上与招聘人员互动。领英前产品管理副总裁约翰·杰辛 (John Jersin) 表示，这会向人工智能发出信号，表明你正在积极寻找工作，并会推荐你更多机会，因为大多数人工智能工具都经过优化，可以找到“可能申请的合格人员”。

•Engage with recruiters on job platforms. It will signal to the AI that you are actively looking for a job and will recommend you for more opportunities because most AI tools are optimized to find “qualified people likely to apply,” said John Jersin, former vice president of product management at LinkedIn.

•只要你符合职位描述中的部分条件，就可以申请那些需要更多经验的工作。“让算法来判断你是否合适，然后它会把你排在最上面或最下面，”伊恩·西格尔说道。这也可能暗示人工智能会向你推荐更高级的职位。

•Apply to jobs that require more experience than you have, as long as you meet some of the qualifications in the job description. “Let the algorithms decide whether or not you are a great match and they will sort you to the top or bottom,” Ian Siegel said. This may also signal the AI to show you more senior jobs.

•如果您在 LinkedIn 等求职平台上有个人资料，请务必列出您的所有技能，因为招聘人员通常会根据地点和技能来搜索候选人。

•If you have a profile on a job platform like LinkedIn, make sure to list all your skills because recruiters often search for candidates by location and skills.

•与您想进入的行业和公司的人员建立联系。

•Network with folks in the industry and at companies you want to land in.

•哈佛商学院教授乔·富勒 (Joe Fuller) 表示，对于入门级和管理类职位，可以考虑说明自己能够熟练使用 Microsoft Office Suite 应用程序，即使职位描述中没有这项技能。

•For entry-level and administrative jobs, consider stating that you are competent in Microsoft Office Suite applications, even if it’s not in the job description, said Harvard business professor Joe Fuller.

•现在许多求职者使用 ChatGPT 和其他大型语言模型来撰写或润色简历和求职信。请务必核实结果。您还可以让 ChatGPT 回答最常见的面试问题，并让它帮助您提前准备答案。

•Many job applicants now use ChatGPT and other large language models to write or polish their résumés and cover letters. Make sure you fact-check the results. You can also prompt ChatGPT for the most common interview questions and have it help you prepare answers in advance.

•最重要的是：不要灰心！许多其他求职者也发出了数百份申请。

•And, most importantly: don’t be discouraged! Many other job seekers are sending out hundreds of applications as well.

如果我被追踪了怎么办？

WHAT IF I AM BEING TRACKED?

由于工作场所监控的透明度很低，因此我向怀疑自己被跟踪的读者提出以下建议：

Because there is very little transparency in surveillance at work, here is what I recommend to readers who suspect they are being tracked:

•假设工作电脑、平板电脑和手机上的所有内容都受到监控。没有任何内容是私密的，即使是 Slack 或 Microsoft Teams 中的私人消息。雇主可以访问所有内容，包括已删除的消息。（据研究公司 Gartner 称，在疫情爆发前，约有 10% 的受访公司表示使用此类软件，但自疫情爆发以来，约有 30% 的公司购买了远程跟踪软件。《纽约时报》报道称，美国十大私营雇主中有 8 家使用生产力监控。）

•Assume that everything on a work computer, tablet, and phone is monitored. Nothing is private, even private messages in Slack or Microsoft Teams. Everything can be accessed by an employer, including deleted messages. (According to the research firm Gartner, before the pandemic, around 10 percent of companies surveyed said they used this type of software, but since the pandemic, about 30 percent of companies purchased remote tracking software. The New York Times reported that eight of the ten largest private US employers use productivity monitoring.)

•假设您从工作电脑上移走的每份打印件和每个文件也都会受到跟踪。

•Assume that every printout and every file you move off a work computer is tracked, as well.

•如果可以，请在工作时使用第二台个人电脑或个人电话来查看个人电子邮件或浏览网页。

•Use a second personal computer or your personal phone, if you can, to check your personal email or surf the web when you are at work.

•如果可以避免，请不要在手机上安装公司软件。

•If you can avoid it, do not install company software on your phone.

•检查邮件中的情绪。尽量保持邮件积极向上、专业化，因为越来越多的公司启用了“员工倾听”工具，可以追踪邮件中的情绪。该软件还可以追踪评论和推文等外部信号。

•Check your emails for sentiment. Try to keep them upbeat and professional, since more and more companies are enabling “employee listening” tools, which may track sentiment in messages. The software can also track external signals like reviews and tweets.

•保持 LinkedIn 上的更新稳定，不要一次性更新所有内容，因为这会增加您的离职风险评分。

•Keep your updates on LinkedIn steady and do not update everything at once because that can increase your flight risk score.

致谢

T谨以此书献给我的家人，尤其是我的女儿弗里达。她是我生命中的光芒。未来，我希望她和她的同伴们不再被贬低为一个数字，而是因其人性而得到认可。

This book is dedicated to my family and especially my daughter, Frieda. She is the light of my life. In the future, I hope that she and her peers will not be reduced to a number but will be recognized for their humanity.

首先，我要感谢所有我的消息来源。没有他们，这个项目就不可能实现。感谢你们挺身而出，与我分享你们的经历——我非常感谢你们对我的信任，也感谢你们给予我讲述你们故事的荣幸！

First and foremost, I want to thank all my sources. Without them this project would not have been possible. Thank you for coming forward and sharing your experiences with me—I am so grateful for the trust you all put into me and the privilege of telling your stories!

我还要感谢我的经纪人，Folio 的 Roger Freet。他不仅接听了一位首次写作的作家的电话，并在创作过程中给予了我很多帮助，而且他本人也是一位非常优秀的人。

From there, Dan Ambrosio and his excellent team took over and made sure this book is the best version it can be. I want to especially thank copy editor Christina Palaia, production editor Seán Moreau, proofreaders Susan VanHecke and Erica Lawrence, and indexer Sherri Linsenbach who helped shape the final manuscript into this book. I also want to thank Amanda Kain for the fabulous cover.

如果没有该领域值得信赖的专家的无限帮助，我不可能写出这本书，包括约翰·斯科特、马修·尼尔和弗雷德奥斯瓦尔德一次又一次地接听我的电话，并向我详细讲解工业和组织心理学研究的方方面面。

I couldn’t have written this book without limitless help from trusted experts in the field, including John Scott, Matthew Neale, and Fred Oswald, who again and again took my calls and walked me through the ins and outs of industrial and organizational psychology research.

特别感谢我的研究助理 Victoria Albert、Priyanka Vora、Noah Daly，尤其是 Clara McMichael。

A special thanks goes to my research assistants, Victoria Albert, Priyanka Vora, Noah Daly, and especially Clara McMichael.

此外，我还要感谢 Lowri Daniels 和 Alice Milliken 帮助我核实手稿。

Additionally, I want to thank Lowri Daniels and Alice Milliken for helping me fact-check the manuscript.

我感谢身边所有优秀的人，以及纽约大学的同事们，他们在百忙之中抽出时间为我提供建议，并帮助我完成这本书。在纽约大学和新闻系，我真正找到了新的思想家园，我每天都心怀感激，能与这些优秀的同事共事。

I am grateful to all the amazing people surrounding me and my colleagues at NYU who took time out of their busy schedules to advise me and help me with this book. I have truly found a new intellectual home at the university and in the journalism department and I am grateful every day to work with such wonderful colleagues.

我还要感谢 Mona Sloane 对这个项目和我所有其他工作的坚定支持。

I also want to thank Mona Sloane for her unwavering support of this project and all of my other work.

我感谢我的朋友和同事Rachel Swarns、Meredith Broussard、Sally Herships、Sayash Kapoor、Jennifer Strong、Mickey Maudlin和Emma Cillekens对我工作的支持。还要感谢我的长期导师Jim Mintz和Sheila Coronel，他们总是能给我很多有益的建议。我还要感谢所有曾在不同出版物共事过的编辑们。你们的意见和批评反馈至关重要！

I thank my friends and colleagues Rachel Swarns, Meredith Broussard, Sally Herships, Sayash Kapoor, Jennifer Strong, Mickey Maudlin, and Emma Cillekens for their support of my work. And my long-term mentors Jim Mintz and Sheila Coronel, who always have helpful advice. I also want to thank all the editors I have worked with at different publications. Your input and critical feedback were incredibly important!

我非常感谢我的搭档马特。他一直告诉我这本书有多重要，并确保我有足够的额外时间来写作。谢谢你！

I owe a lot of gratitude to my partner, Matt. He kept telling me how important this book is and made sure I had all the extra time that I needed to write it. Thank you!

我还要感谢许多机构慷慨提供的奖学金、资助和宝贵支持：麻省理工学院奈特科学新闻奖学金项目的黛博拉·布鲁姆和阿什利·斯马特；纽约大学人文中心的莫莉·罗杰斯；以及帕特里克·J·麦戈文基金会的维拉斯·达尔和梅根·英格利什，感谢他们对我工作的支持。感谢纽约大学新闻风险投资基金，该基金由一位真正慷慨的同事斯蒂芬·所罗门创立。

I am also grateful for the fellowships and grants and invaluable support many organizations so generously provided: Deborah Blum and Ashley Smart at the MIT Knight Science Journalism Fellowship; Molly Rogers with the NYU Center for the Humanities; and Vilas Dhar and Meaghan English at the Patrick J. McGovern Foundation for throwing their support behind my work. Thank you to the Journalism Venture Capital Fund at NYU, which was started by Stephen Solomon—a truly generous colleague.

我还要感谢 Marina Walker Guevara、Boyoung Lim、他们的整个团队以及普利策中心人工智能问责网络的其他研究员，他们都鼓励我继续前进并在每一步都给予我帮助。

I also want to thank Marina Walker Guevara, Boyoung Lim, their whole team, and the other fellows at the Pulitzer Center AI Accountability Network, who all encouraged me to keep going and helped me every step of the way.

如果没有你们的支持，我就不可能完成这项工作！

I could not have done this work without all of your support!

并感谢一路上为我加油并在多方面帮助我的所有人！

And thanks to everyone else along the way who cheered me on and helped me in many ways!
